<html><head><title>Womankind Worldwide - Newsletter</title></head><body bgcolor="bdfbc0" text="000000" link="9306a9" vlink="502c88"><h1 align=center><img src="newsletter_logo.jpg" ></h1><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../wk_info.html">Womankind Worldwide</a></i><hr><h1 align=center>Emergency Scheme in Ghana</h1><font size=+1>Update on the emergency scheme to assist the 700 rural women supported by WOMANKIND in northern Ghana. </font><p>For over four years, WOMANKIND  has worked in partnership with the Bawku East Women's Development Association ( BEWDA ) in Northern Ghana. When heavy rains and flooding threatened widespread hunger last year, WOMANKIND made an appeal to the ODA's Emergency Aid Department to assist the 700 BEWDA members until the next harvest. The appeal was successful and the first bowls of subsidised grain were distributed in March.<p>The scheme has been very successful, distributing 10 bowls of grain fortnightly to each member during the hungriest period. One of the main aims of the scheme was to ensure that the women were not forced to sell their goods and livestock in order to buy food before the next harvest came in. Being able to buy grain at nearly half the inflated market price has meant that the women have not lost the productive assets they worked so hard to acquire. One family spoke of the relief they felt that they would not have to sell their last remaining plough bullock, their main source of income.   <p>By July, BEWDA members were harvesting their early staple crop and no longer needed to rely on the subsidised grain. Furthermore, having had food throughout the hungry season, the women are now in good enough physical shape to plant the Autumn crops. It is important that the assistance this year is viewed as an emergency measure only. Already, the women are thinking about what actions they need to take to help themselves in the next hungry season. We support the determination of the BEWDA members to find their own solutions that will lead to the long term and sustainable development of their communities.<p><b><a href="index.html">Contents Page</a></b><p><hr><p>©Copyright:1996 Womankind Worldwide<hr></body></html>
