<html>

<header>

<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Austria

</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the

National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.

<br> 

<h5> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.

1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen

European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The

report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The

Hague, the Netherlands.

</h5>

<hr>

<h3>Contents:</h3>

<ul>

<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Austrian Development Cooperation</a>

<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>

<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>

<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>

<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

</ul><p>



<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Austrian Development Cooperation</h3>



Official Austrian development cooperation started in the mid 1970s, based on charitable church-related and a

voluntary tradition of assistance to post-war European countries and refugees. Attention and assistance

traditionally were more focused on the consequences of East - West conflicts than on North - South

relations. Its neutral position in international politics facilitated Austria's intermediary role in UN affairs.

North - South development cooperation received rather belatedly attention in Austrian politics. Although the

majority of the Austrian public has a positive attitude towards development cooperation, it does not yet

appear to be well informed on this point, and appears to overestimate current Austrian development efforts.

Development education activities are stepped up by the Government. 

<p>

Net official development assistance amounted to US $ 556 million in 1992, which was 0.30 per cent of

GNP. This percentage was 0.25 cent in 1990 and 0.34 in 1991. The Government has stated the intention to

reach the DAC average (1990) for ODA of 0.35 per cent of GNP and, later, the EU average for ODA of

0.51 per cent. In 1992 24 per cent of Austria's ODA was disbursed through multilateral channels.

Multilateral contributions increase faster than the bilateral component, and will continue to do so as a

consequence of Austria's EU membership. 

<p>

<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

<p>

The legislative basis for Austria's aid programme is the Development Cooperation Act of 1974 and

subsequent Acts in 1977, 1983 and 1989. Development cooperation is not the responsibility of one minister,

but is spread over several ministries. Till 1989 development cooperation was the responsibility of the

Federal Chancellor and thereafter the competence of the Minister of Foreign Affairs. Since 1991 a State

Secretary for Integration and Development Cooperation, who heads the Department for Development

Cooperation in the Federal Chancellery (BKA) is responsible. The State Secretary is responsible for:

bilateral technical aid, co-financing programmes, humanitarian and emergency aid and parts of the

multilateral financial assistance. The financial efforts in these areas however, amount to less than 30 per

cent of the bilateral programme in 1992. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs is responsible for multilateral aid.

The Ministry of Finance is responsible for financial aid (a.o. debt relief) and concessional official export

credits. The Ministry of the Interior is responsible for aid to refugees (in Austria), the Ministry of

Agriculture for food aid and the Ministry of Science and Research as well as the Ministry of Education are

both partly responsible for the scholarship programme. 

<p>

Since Austrian law does not allow the government to carry out its own programmes (principle of

subsidiarity), there is no governmental aid agency for the implementation of project. Implementation is

contracted out to private firms and NGOs or implemented by the federal L„nder and Municipalities.

<p>

The Secretary at the BKA is responsible for the overall coordination, programming and reporting on aid

policies, with the above mentioned extensive limitations. Policy planning is done by a Planning and

Programming which comes under the competence of the Department for Development Cooperation of the

BKA. During the coming re-organisation the number and expertise of the currently small number of staff in

the department will be enlarged and up-graded. 

<p>

To strengthen the coordination of the aid programme an Interministerial Committee for the Coordination of

Aid was established in 1992, including a dozen senior officials of the various ministries. The Committee is

chaired by the Director-General of the Department for Development Cooperation. The Committee can issue

non-binding recommendations only. 

<p>

<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>

<p>

In 1974 an Advisory Council on Development Cooperation (Beirat) was established in order to guarantee a

coordinated development policy and implementation. The Council could advise the Federal Chancellor on

these matters. The ca. 50 members of the Council are appointed by the Federal Chancellor and represent all

major sections in society, including Members of Parliament of the Standing Committee for Foreign Affairs,

representatives of NGOs, industry, and trade unions. It is chaired by the State Secretary for Integration and

Development Cooperation.

<p>

The Council meets three or four times a year. Meetings are held at the request of the State Secretary. The

Council does not write reports or recommendations. It is a panel for discussion with the State Secretary.

Discussions are considered as an input for policy formulation which is executed by the State Secretary and

the officials involved. The Council's main function is preserving the support for development cooperation in

Austrian society. It discusses amongst others: DAC reports, the negotiations with EU and the government's

Three-Year Programme for Development Cooperation. The operational criteria for Austrian development

cooperation were elaborated in 1979 and 1980 by a working group of the Council, based on the 1974 Law.

The Council appears to play a minor role since. The Council has no Secretariat. Members can be contacted

through the Federal Chancellery. The Council does not publish any documents of its discussions and its

present agenda is not known.

<p>

In order to improve its functioning working groups were established in 1992 on environmental questions and

on human rights. In the DAC Aid Review of 1992/93 the Austrian government is invited to reconsider the

role of the Advisory Council with regard to obtaining the necessary support of the population for an

enlarged and improved aid programme. In view of greater efficiency, a reduction of the number of Council

Members should be considered. 

<p>

Parliament has a Standing Sub-Committee on Development Policy (under the responsibility of the Standing

Committee for Foreign Affairs) which sets its own agenda. Parliament apparently does not show great

interest in questions of aid. Debates on government reports submitted to Parliament have been held

belatedly. In 1988 Parliament conducted an enquiry into the development assistance, but there has been no

active follow up reported.

<p>

<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>

<p>

There are many small, mainly church related NGOs and a number of large ones. In 1991/1992 sixty per

cent of the bilateral aid was channelled through fifty NGOs. Four NGOs accounted for two-thirds of funds

made available. The NGOs continuously urge the government to improve the performance of its aid

programme and to raise the volume of aid. Discussions with the government concentrate on the question

whether 

NGOs can be discussion partners for the government in development cooperation policy matters or whether

they are subcontractors for implementation of projects only. In 1993 the Government and NGOs entered into

serious negotiations in order to establish a long term cooperation programme between government and

NGOs. An umbrella organisation of several development NGOs, the Working Association for Development

Cooperation (AGEZ), is acknowledged by the Government as a discussion partner on issues such as the

quality of Austrian aid and the consequences of Austria's EU membership. 

<p>

The NGOs can be roughly divided into four categories: firstly, organisations for the care of foreign students

in Austria (which originated in the late 1950s at the universities); experts and volunteer sending

organisations, organised in the Institute for International Cooperation and in the Austrian Development

Service; third, NGOs that implement projects in developing countries and fourth, NGOs for information and

development education.

<p>

According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey 11 institutes qualify as Development Research and Training

Institutes. Several contribute to the debate on development policy and implementation, such as the Vienna

Institute for Development Cooperation, the Austrian Foundation for Development Cooperation and the

Austrian Research Foundation for Development Cooperation. The latter institute publishes an annual survey

and analyses of Austria's development cooperation.

<p>

<hr>

<H6></a>

