<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - British Government accused of 'playing race card'</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="#d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">[OneWorld News Service]<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>
<h2>British Government accused of playing 'race card'</h2><p>

Legislation to be introduced in Britain in the next year has outraged asylum-seeker and refugee support groups.<p>

It has been a longstanding aim of the governing Conservative Party to seek to tighten up controls on illegal immigrants and applications for asylum.<p>

While Prime Minister John Major claims that tighter rules will help streamline the processing of asylum-seekers, opposition parties claim that the Government - which is trailing in the opinion polls - is playing on racist fears in a bid for re-election.<p>

Most controversial is a proposal to establish a 'white list' of countries which are considered safe.  Claims of political asylum from people from these countries would be assumed to be unfounded.  Social security benefits for these applicants would also be stopped, leaving them with no means of support - they are prohibited from seeking work in the UK.<p>

Refugee support groups were outraged when leaked documents showed that countries on this 'white list' might include Turkey and Nigeria - both reknowned for human rights abuses.<p>

Nigeria has become an international pariah after <b><a href="news_top_africa.html#nigeria">executing</a></b>  nine pro-democracy activists on 10 November.  <b><a href="../amnesty/ai_press.html#east">Turkey</a></b> has been repeatedly criticised by Amnesty International for imprisoning journalists who criticise the war against Kurdish rebels.<p>

Human rights campaigners were shocked last week as Government figures showed that all but one of the 2,032 applications for asylum from Nigerians had been refused.  These included people who had been tortured for taking part in demonstrations against General Abacha's military government.<p>

"This is a country in which human rights abuses are going on on a massive scale and yet when they seek asylum in the UK more than 99 per cent are refused.  It is simply not credible that less than 1% of these people are genuine refugees," Nick Hardwick of the Refugee Council told British newspaper 'The Guardian'.<p>

Also controversial in the new legislation are measures to penalise companies that employ illegal immigrants.  Campaigners fear that this might lead to job applicants being refused or harassed because of their skin colour.<p>

Challenged in the House of Commons over the measures, Prime Minister John Major said: "I believe passionately in the equal rights of anyone in this country, whether they be black, brown, yellow or white.<p>

However, demonstrators splashed Conservative Party Chairman Brian Mawhinney with orange paint outside Parliament yesterday, to show their disapproval of the proposals.<p>

The Conservatives were further embarrassed at remarks made by a Party press officer, who acknowledged that fanning fears over immigration and race had been an electoral asset to the Government and had "played particularly well in the tabloids" in 1992.<p>
<ul>
 <br><b><li>See OneWorld Online's <a href="news_top_world.html#refugees">News Features on Refugees</a><li><a href="partner_news/wk46_refugee.html">Statement by the Refugee Council</a><br clear=left>
</ul>


<p>

