<a name="aid">

<br>

<h2>Aid and Debt</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../oda/publications/bod47/business.html">Microfinance is now big business:</a></b><br>
Expanding financial services for the poor has long been a development goal.  Now microcredit schemes are taking off across the world, and the <b>ODA</b> reveals why.<br>
<font size=2><b>From the ODA, featured on the OneWorld News Service 12 August 1996</b></font><br>
<p>



<li><b><a href="../oxfam/cfa/index.html">Leading development charities plead the case for aid:</a></b><br>
Alarmed by an unprecedented decline in aid budgets around the world, leading UK charities working overseas are pushing for a renewed commitment to the world's poor.  They stress that properly targeted aid can work, and that spending money now can help prevent conflict and environmental degradation in the future.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Oxfam, featured on OneWorld News Service 4 July 1996</b><br>
Image ©Copyright: Oxfam</font>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="../eurodad/is3_gb.htm">At least 32 countries suffer unsustainable debt burden:</a></b><br>
The European Network on Debt and Development is highly critical of the World Bank and IMF's assessment of many poorer countries' debt burden.  The problem is much worse than the these global financial institutions will admit, it says.<br>
<b><font size=2>From ECDPM, featured on OneWorld News Service 25 June 1996</font></b>
<p>

<li><b><a href="../christian_aid/waiving/waiv.html">Christian Aid - IMF should sell gold to cancel poor country debt:</a></b><br>
A short but in-depth report from <b>Christian Aid</b>, 'Not Waiving but Drowning', puts the case for a fundamental shift in global financial transfers.  For too many years, money has flowed out of the countries whose populations most need it and into the coffers of the IMF and rich country banks.<p>

<li><b><a href="../odi/odi_briefing196.html">ODI Paper - New sources of finance for development:</a></b><br>
This ODI Briefing Paper gives an in-depth look the international squeeze in aid budgets, and the renewed interest in new sources of finance.<p>


<li><b><a href="../oxfam/press_debt.html">Oxfam: Multilateral Debt reduction could save 21 million children</a></b><br>
A new Oxfam report highlights how debt repayments by some of the world's poorest countries threaten the lives of millions.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk41_gemini_aid.html">New criticisms of IMF aid emerge:</a></b><br>A report by a British development expert doubts the whole system of international aid.<p>

<li><b><a href="../odi/odi_debt.html">Poor Country Debt: a never-ending story?</a></b><br>
'Third World Debt' no longer makes the news, but the debt burden still crushes many low-income countries.  The ODI reviews the options for relieving this seemingly perpetual misery.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk40_gemini_privatization.html">Aid privatisation threatens a lifeline to the poor:</a> </b><br>
The World Bank's monetary policy has often been blamed for worsening the poor country debt burden.  Now, at last, there are signs of new thinking...<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_debt.html">Too early to celebrate new debt initiative:</a> </b><br>
The World Bank's soft loans agency, the IDA, is a lifeline to many poorer countries.  Now potentially disastrous cuts are threatened<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_oda.html">Weasel words usher in British aid cuts:</a> </b><br>
In order to stave off a near-certain election defeat, the British government is casting about for more money to use in tax cuts.  The overseas aid budget may be the first to get the chop...<p>

<li><b><a href="../odi/odi_agri2.html">Is there life after Structural Adjustment?</b></a><br>
The <b>ODI</b> examines how the public sector agricultural extension services in less developed countries are achieving a limited impact only. 
<p>

<li><a href="../odi/odi_aid.html"><b>Aid In Transition:</b></a>
<br>The US public may be suffering 'aid fatigue', but in Japan citizens are even volunteering the interest they earn on their postal accounts.  This <b>ODI</b> briefing paper reviews changes in the nature and purpose of overseas aid.
<p>
</ul>

<a name="biodiversity">
<hr width=40%>

<h2>Biodiversity and Conservation</h2>

<ul type=square>


<li type=square><b><a href="../oda/publications/bod47/wildlife.html">Could economics be the saviour of our wildlife?</a></b><br>
Recent studies in Kenya reveal that up to 44 per cent of wildlife may have disappeared over the last 20 years, around 30 per cent within protected areas. People are questioning whether present conservation techniques are really working, and the British Overseas Development magazine now sees sound economics as the best way to save the wildlife.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Overseas Development Administration, featured on the OneWorld News Service 7 August 1996</b></font><p>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/july/reef.html">It's sink or swim time for the world's coral reefs:</a></b><br>
The world's coral reefs are under severe threat from human activity. If they are to survive these 'undersea rainforests' now need to attract the sort of support that there cousins above ground have been getting. <br> 
<font size=2><b>From Gemini News Service, featured on OneWorld News Service 24 July 1996</b></font>
<p>



<li type=square><b><a href="../gemini/july/biodiversity.html">Global alert as alien invaders attack wildlife:</a></b><br>
'Biological pollution' is now as serious a problem as chemical pollution, scientists were told at a recent conference.  Alien species introduced by man to new areas have been devastating local ecosytems across the world.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Gemini News Service, featured on OneWorld News Service 10 July 1996</b></font>
<p>





<li><b><a href="../vso/orbit59/conlead.html">Conservation: Pandas before people?</a></b><br>
'He's Destroying His Own Rainforest.  To Stop Him, Do You Send In The Army Or An Anthropologist?' asked a recent WWF advert.  This reveals the insensitive and implicity anti-people attitude of some conservationists, says <b>Orbit magazine</b>.<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/earthtimes_wk46_species.html">Species becoming extinct at a record rate:</a></b><br>
Human activity is drastically reducing the biodiversity of the Earth, the World Biodiversity Convention has been told.  <b>The Earth Times</b> reports.
