<h2>Children's rights</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/august/children.html">Rescued prostitutes present theatre of life:</a></b><br>
As the <strong>World Congress Against the Sexual Exploitation of Children</strong> approaches, <b>Gemini News service</b> takes a look at the problem of child prostitution and at a play based on the real-life experiences of the rescued prostitutes who are its writers and its stars.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Gemini News Service, featured on the OneWorld News Service 13 August 1996</b></font><br>
<p>

<li><b><a href="reports/jul96_children.html">Britain to join campaign against child sex tourism:</a></b><br>
Britain has now joined thirteen other countries  by introducing laws that allow the prosecution in the UK of child molesterers who have committed sexual offences in other countries.<br> 
<font size=2><b>By the OneWorld News Service 25 July 1996</b></font><p>





<li><b><a href="partner_news/jun96_children.html">Guatemalan police convicted of murder of street children:</a></b><br>
On 24 September 1994, Ruben Garcia Gonzales (14) and Daniel Rosales (10) were trying to sleep in Zone 4 of Guatemala City.  Without warning two private policemen came up to the children and opened fire with shotguns.  Daniel died instantly, and Ruben died later in hospital.  Now, unprecedentedly for a case involving street children, the two policemen have been convicted of their murders and imprisoned.<br>
<b>From Bruce Harris, 13 June 1996</b><br>
<font size=2>Street children in Latin American cities are often seen as no better than vermin. ©Copyright: Casa Alianza</font><p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/may/children.html">Call for tougher battle to combat Sri Lankan child sex trade:</a></b><br>
For years child sex victims in Sri Lanka have been harshly punished, while their abusers have escaped with small fines.  New laws are being introduced to combat sex tourism, but a domestic cultural change may also be needed.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/may/unicef.html">Little Meena campaigns for sexual equality in South Asia:</a></b><br>
A crusading cartoon character is leading UNICEF's fight against the bias that condemns many South Asian girls to second-class citizenship.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/mar96_tourism.html">Bid to protect children as sex tourism spreads in India:</a></b><br>
Rich country paedophiles in search of child prostitutes are increasingly abandoning South-East Asia in favour of Indian resorts, reports <b>Gemini News Service</b>.<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/journjan_2.html">Killed like cockroaches- Central American street children:</a></b><br>
Viewed as little short of human vermin, Central American street children face cruelty and sudden death at the hands of police and security forces, reports <b>Amnesty International</b>.<p>


<li><b><a href="partner_news/dyingrooms_top.html">Special Report on 'The Return to the Dying Rooms':</a></b><br>
Huge controversy was aroused by the screening of a documentary film which claimed the Chinese authorities were deliberately exterminating orphaned children.  It accompanied a report by <b>Human Rights Watch/Asia</b>, which catalogued systematic neglect by state orphanages which often lead to the deaths of orphans.  This <b>OneWorld Special Report</b> has both sides of the story - as well as the transcript, a summary of the report, and several Facts Sheets from the <b>Chinese Government.</b><p>



<li><b><a href="../unicef/sowc/index.html">Launch of the State of the World's Children Report 1996:</a></b><br>
In the past decade some 2 million children have been killed in war and 12 million left homeless.  <b>UNICEF</b> launched its anti-war agenda on 11 December in London, with a parallel multimedia launch here on its <b>OneWorld</b> Web site - including movie clips, RealAudio features, a summary of the report and a special feature to mark <b>UNICEF</b>'s upcoming 50th Anniversary.<p><br clear=right>


<li><b><a href="../unicef/icdb/index.html">UNICEF's International Children's Day of Broadcasting:</a><br></b>
Sunday 10 December is the day when the kids take over television, radio - and this part of the Internet.  Last year's event had a potential audience of one billion people, from Liberia to Peru to Jordan.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk47_gemini_child.html">Cry of help for child victims of conflict:</a></b><br>
