<h2>Freedom of Expression and Censorship</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../cba/sept96/china.htm"> Growing concern about freedom of expression in Hong Kong after 1997:</a></b><br>
China has begun to impose its own limits on press freedom in Hong Kong. Editors have been urged to tone down stories that were not to China's liking, and there has been a significant increase in the number of journalists detained or harassed. The Hong Kong Journalists Association is still hoping that Beijing will respect the rights and freedom that Hong Kong's people currently enjoy.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Commonwealth Broadcasting Association, featured on the OneWorld News Service 8 August 1996</b></font><br>
<p>


<li><b><a href="partner_news/may96_hrw.html">Worldwide efforts to censor Internet expand:</a></b><br>
Freedom of expression on the Internet is in serious danger across the globe, says <b>Human Rights Watch</b>.  Governments across the globe are rushing to impose controls, using excuses such as protecting children and thwarting terrorists to justify their actions.<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/hrw/index.html">Silencing the Net - The Threat to Freedom of Expression Online:</a></b><br>
The full Human Rights Watch report - giving a worldwide breakdown of how freedom in cyberspace is threatened in different countries.  Censorship legislation is being enacted or considered by governments of all political colours - led, ironically, by the United States, birthplace of the Internet.<p>

<li><b><a href="../index_oc/9602/saudi.html">Censorship and control in the international Arab press:</a></b><br>
The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia - a country not reknowned for its political openness - owns 95% of the Arabic-lanugage media in Arab countries and abroad.  <b>Index on Censorsip</b> investigates.<p>

<li><b><a href="../index_oc/letter_mar15.html">Letter from Lagos - Unleashing the Furies:</a></b><br>
A performance of a play by the Nobel laureate Wole Soyinka gave the Nigerian authorities cause for concern recently, despite the fact that the same play is used in schoolbooks across the country.<p>


<li><b><a href="../index_oc/letter.html">Letter from Lagos:</a>
<br>Index on Censorship's</b> correspondent in Nigeria reports on the military dictatorship's abuse of the press, legal system and human rights in the country.  This report is <b>exclusive to Index's Web site</b>.<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_turkey_oct30.html">Legal changes leave repressive measures intact:</a> </b><br>
<b>Amnesty International</b> claims that minor changes to Turkey's Anti-Terror law will still lead to people being jailed for expressing non-violent opinions.<p>


<li><b><a href="../index_oc/news/albania6feb.html">Opposition press and politicians under fire in Albania:</b></a><br>
Albania's democratically-elected government has come under attack for passing repressive legislation to silence its critics.<p>


<li><b><b><a href="http://www.oneworld.org/index_oc/index_movs/wei.ram">Endangered Writers - the story of Wei Jingsheng:</a></font></b><br>


<li><b><a href="../index_oc/marlowe.html">Journalists targeted in civil war:</a><br>Index on Censorship</b> counts the ever-mounting cost of Algeria's bitter civil war. Journalists particularly have been hit: 35 have been assassinated by Islamic radicals in the last two years. 

As part of <b>Index on Censorship's</b> 'Endangered Writers' series, Frank Ortega tells the story of one Chinese journalist who suffered for his outspokenness. <br><font size=-1>Cartoon by  <a href="../index_oc/cartoon.html">Naji Al-ali</a> </font><p>

