<a name="economy">
<hr width=40%>

<h2>The Global Economy</h2>

<ul type=square>



<li type=square><b><a href="../ni/issue278/keynote.html">What's wrong with the global economy?</a></b><br>
Economic globalisation seems to have many benefits.  Produce is brought from faraway countries and the free market keeps prices low.  But what are the real costs?  Local producers are bankrupted, for a start.  And massive pollution results from unsustainable transport networks, which are needed to bring food thousands of miles from field to table.<br>
<font size=2><b>From New Internationalist, featured on OneWorld News Service 10 July 1996</b><br>
Image ©Copyright: New Internationalist</font>
<p>

<li><b><a href="reports/jun96_g7.html">Voices from below disrupt G7 meeting of the powerful:</a></b><br>
Whenever global power-brokers meet nowadays, they find the agenda they are pushing challenged by a growing grassroots movement.  Last week's G7 summit meeting in Lyon was no exception.  Economics author <b>Titus Alexander</b> reports on the colourful and vocal alternatives being offered to the plans of the "Gang of Seven".<br>
<font size=2><b>Report from Titus Alexander, featured on OneWorld News Service 1 July 1996</b></font><p>




<li><b><a href="reports/jun96_apartheid.html">West accused of practising 'global apartheid':</a></b><br>
Question: What does the current global financial and social system have in common with apartheid South Africa? Answer: Just about everything, says economics writer Titus Alexander.  The Majority World is exploited for its resources and labour, while the West puts up protectionist barriers and immigration controls to prevent a fairer wealth distribution.<br>
<font size=2><b>Report by the OneWorld News Service, 25 June 1996</b><br>
Image shows South African child in black township ©Copyright: Word-Pictures</font><p>


<li><b><a href="../vso/orbit60/fairtrad.html">Fair, square and at a retailer near you - the rise of fair trade:</a></b><br>
In a profit-making world, is there any such thing as fair trade?  <b>William Ang'awa</b> investigates the rise of the fair trade movement for <b>VSO's Orbit</b> magazine.<p>

<li><b><a href="../vso/orbit60/trade.html">Exploitation and poverty - the truth about free trade:</a></b><br>
'Free trade', 'globalisation' and 'liberalisation' are concepts promoted with great vigour by the international capitalist establishment.  With good reason.  Strong countries with big companies have much to gain from open access to other countries' markets and labour.<p>



<li><b><a href="../oxfam/press_20may.html">Oxfam launches worldwide campaign for clothes workers:</a></b><br>
Estela has worked Dominican garments factories for several years.  "I was sacked from one factory just because I was ill for a few days," she reports.  Hundreds of thousands of other people all over the world - mainly women - are working long hours for low pay in appalling conditions.  Why?  To produce clothes for Western consumers. <br>
<font size=2>Photo ©Copyright: Oxfam UK</font><p>

<br><li><b><a href="../oxfam/clothes/index.html">Oxfam's Clothes Code Campaign</a></b><br clear=left><br>

<li><li type=square><b><a href="../gemini/may/cuba.html">Cuban students swap Marx for markets:</a></b><br>
Socialist Cuba seems to be moving steadily towards the mixed economy.  Academic institutions are changing with the times - and offering courses in free-market economics rather than Marxist philosophy.<p>



<li><b><a href="../christian_aid/waiving/waiv.html">Christian Aid - IMF should sell gold to cancel poor country debt:</a></b><br>
A short but in-depth report from <b>Christian Aid</b>, 'Not Waiving but Drowning', puts the case for a fundamental shift in global financial transfers.  For too many years, money has flowed out of the countries whose populations most need it and into the coffers of the IMF and rich country banks.<br>
<font size=2>Water pump provided by the Society for Integrated Rural Development, 1km outside the village of Koolnaykampatti, Tamil Nadu, India  Photo ©Copyright: Christian Aid/D K Crevance</font>
<p>



<li><b><a href="../panos/gmpress.html">Gold Mining - weighing up the costs:</a></b><br>
As demand for gold hits an all-time high, more and more developing countries are opening their doors to mining companies.  This <b>Panos</b> report asks if the new benefits from gold could turn out to be as illusory as the fabled El Dorado.<p>

<li><b><a href="../oxfam/wb_sum.html">Oxfam - Summary paper on World Bank Inspection Panel:</a></b><br>
Oxfam's report on the World Bank's efforts to make itself more accountable to the people its policies are affecting.<p>

<li><b><a href="../com_fnd/path_supsup.html">Solomon Islands women turn seeds into money:</a></b><br>
Using the resources of credit unions, Sup Sup gardens are providing both additional food and income to families.<p>



<li><b><a href="reports/mcspotlight_launch.html">McDonald's vow to continue McLibel fight after McSpotlight launch:</a></b><br>
The McDonald's watchdog Internet site, McSpotlight, was launched from a laptop and mobile phone outside a McDonald's in London by the McLibel Two yesterday.<p>



<li><b><a href="reports/mcspotlight.html">McSpotlight Web site targets "arrogant" corporation McDonald's:</a></b><br>
Today sees the launch of a campaigning site by people determined to win "the fight against McDonald's global domination".  Dealing with issues ranging from animal welfare to tropical deforestation, this site intends to use the Internet to keep one step ahead of the corporation's lawyers.<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/teakwood.html">Teakwood exploitation and insurance scandal engulfs WWF:</a></b><br>
In the Netherlands the World Wide Fund for Nature has given its name to a financial scheme for teakwood exploitation which others denounce as "fraud".  The implications for global forest management could be huge.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk3_zimbabwe.html">Zimbabwe - controversy over state privatisation:</a></b><br>
In Zimbabwe many of the majority black population fear that IMF and World Bank-sponsored privatisation will result in the country handing back many of its assets to the better-off white population.<p>



<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk51_gemini_presents.html">No Christmas joy for exploited toy workers:</a></b><br>
While Western children enjoy their fluffy toys, multinational companies rake in the profits.  But workers in Asian factories are the real losers, reports <b>Gemini News Service.</b><p>


<li><b><a href="../pwblf/index.html">Launch of the Prince of Wales Business Leaders Forum site:</a></b><br>
Founded in 1990 as a personal initiative of HRH The Prince of Wales, the Forum works in partnership with business leaders to promote the values and practice of sustainable development in the corporate world.  Today sees the launch of the Forum's Internet site, as part of the OneWorld partnership.<p><br clear=right>

<li><b><a href="../christian_aid/gazza.html">Globe-trotting sports shoe exploits third world workers:</a></b><br>
Sports shoe companies spend millions hiring Western stars like Michael Jordan and Linford Christie to promote their products.  But the Asian labourers get almost nothing from the production process, says a new report from <b>Chrisitian Aid</b>. 
<p>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk47_gemini_oil.html">How oil sparked the Zapatista rebellion:</a></b><br>
Oil exploitation is in the news again after the executions of 9 Ogoni campaigners in Nigeria.  In Mexico too, a rebellion was sparked when a petroleum company ignored local concerns.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk41_gemini_consumers.html">Multinationals object to code of conduct:</a></b><br>Transnational corporations wield huge power in the global economy.  But efforts to make them behave responsibly are hampered by a lack of co-operation.<p>

<li><b><a href="../odi/odi_developing.html">Developing Countries in the World Trade Organisation:</a></b><br>
The <b>ODI</b> examines why trade reform matters to low-income countries, as they struggle to establish their postion in the changing world economic system.<p>

<li><b><a href="../ni/contents267.html">Wealth, not scarcity, makes people hungry:</a></b><br>
Alternative perspectives on the balance of wealth and poverty, as explored in the <b>New Internationalist</b> magazine.<p>

<li><b><a href="../christian_aid/caid_pressg7.html">Seven ways the G7 could help the poor:</a><br>
Christian Aid</b> lobbies for change at the G7 Summit, arguing for a fundamental review of the international financial system - keeping the developing world in mind.<p>

<li><a href="../christian_aid/caid_promises.html"><b>Waiting for the World Bank to practice what it preaches:</a>
<br>Christian Aid</b> challenges the World Bank to act on its own findings - that its policies are making poor people even poorer.
<p>

<li><a href="../odi/odi_political.html"><b>Political liberalisation and economic reform in developing countries:</b></a><br>
The last decade has seen unprecedented moves towards more liberal and democratic forms of political rule across the developing world.  The <b>ODI</b> reports.
<p>
</ul>

<a name="humanrights">
<hr width=40%>

<h2>Human Rights</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li type=square><b><a href="../amnesty/reports/kazakstan/index.html">Amnesty unveils brutality of Kazakstan prison system:</a></b><br>
Information gathered by <b>Amnesty International</b> suggests that a brutal penetentiary system prevails throughout the countries of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS). Kazakstan, a country with a shockingly high rate of executions, is the focus of an Amnesty report that demands widespread changes.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Amnesty International, featured on the OneWorld News Service 8 August 1996</b></font><p>





<li type=square><b><a href="../ippf/ppc961/china.html">Human rights and family planning in China:</a></b><br>
The human rights aspect of China's family planning programme is constantly under attack by Western media and politicians, as are the International Planned Parenthood Federation (IPPF) and the United Nations for providing support to Chinese family planning.  <b>Li Yang</b> and <b>Jeremy Hamand</b> explain how people's rights can be safeguarded.<br>
<font size=2><b>From IPPF, featured on OneWorld News Service 11 July 1996</b><br>
A grandmother and grandson in China ©Copyright: IPPF</font>
<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/china_july5.html">China executes a thousand in 'strike hard' anti-crime campaign:</a></b><br>
The death penalty was once banned in the People's Republic of China.  Now it is used unfairly and with increasing regularity, says <b>Amnesty International</b>.  Executions are often carried out within days of a suspect's arrest and torture may be used by police to extract confessions.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Amnesty International, featured on OneWorld News Service 10 July 1996</b></font>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="../amnesty/press/uk_june17.html">Amnesty condemns IRA and loyalist human rights violations:</a></b><br>
As well killing and injuring people by placing bombs in crowded British city centres, the IRA is blamed by <b>Amnesty</b> for punishment beatings and killings within Northern Ireland.  Similarly, loyalist paramilitaries have  been carrying out their own violent forms of arbitrary justice.<br>
<b><font size=2>From Amnesty International, featured on OneWorld News Service 21 June 1996</font></b>
<p>


<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/annreport_june18.html">World governments duck human rights responsibility, says Amnesty:</a></b><br>


The human rights group <b>Amnesty International</b>  documented human rights abuses in 146 countries in 1995. But responsibility doesn't just lie with those who pull the trigger or apply the electric shock, says Secretary General Pierre San&eacute;.  It lies with governments - including those of China, France, the USA and the UK - who export military and torture equipment to countries with repressive regimes.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Amnesty International, featured on OneWorld News Service 19 June 1996</b><br>
Image ©Copyright: Amnesty</font><p>


<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/usa_june12.html">US electro-shock belts could be used for torture, says Amnesty:</a></b><br>
The introduction of a remote-controlled electric belt for prisoners in the United States could amount to inhuman and degrading treatment, says the human rights body <b>Amnesty International</b>.  Belts are often activated accidentally, and can be used to torture detainees.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Amnesty International, featured on OneWorld News Service 18 June 1996</b></font><p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/health_may22.html">Support doctors who blow the whistle on torturers, says Amnesty:</a></b><br>
Doctors and nurses have been killed and imprisoned because they refused to cover up evidence of torture and human rights abuses.  In Iraq in 1994, doctors were required by law to amputate the ears of 'deserters' - those who refused were executed.<p>

 <li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/torture_may22.html">Amnesty International launches stop torture campaign:</a></b><br>
"Torture takes place every day on every continent.  It's happening to someone, somewhere in the world this minute," says <b>Amnesty International</b>.  Torture is endemic in more than 40 countries, yet is largely ignored by the international community. <p>

<h4>Five countries where torture is routine:</h4>



 <li><b><a href="../amnesty/torture/mexico.html">Mexico - tortured for standing up:</a></b><br>
<b>Julieta Flores Castillo</b>, aged 18, was raped and tortured in December 1995 after she joined a land rights protest.  She had electricity applied to her nipples and legs, had her head forced into a vat of water, had carbonated water forced up her nose and was beaten all over her body.<br clear=right><br>



 <li><b><a href="../amnesty/torture/kenya.html">Kenya - confess or 'disappear':</a></b><br>
<b>Raphael Wang'ondu Kariuki</b>, a lawyer, was arrested by Special Branch officers in September 1995 and forced to sign a fictitious 45-page statement.  When he initially refused to answer questions, he was beaten about the head and body with a plank of wood.  Later he was pushed into a pile of excrement and beaten about the genitals.<br clear=right><br>



 <li><b><a href="../amnesty/torture/israel.html">Israel - an immoderate death:</a></b><br>
<b>Abd al-Samad Harizat</b> was tortured to death - quite legally - in Israel.  He died of a brain haemorrhage after being violently shaken by Israeli interrogators.  Violent shaking of prisoners is officially permitted, as part of the "moderate physical pressure" police can use to extract confessions.<br clear=right><br>



 <li><b><a href="../amnesty/torture/turkey.html">Turkey - 'I meet my torturers every day':</a></b><br>
After 13 days in custody, <b>G&uuml;lbahar G&uuml;nd&uuml;z</b> had to be carried into court on a blanket - unable to walk and barely able to speak.  On the third day of interrogation, she was kicked hard in the back.  She fell down and found she could not stand up.  She has been in a wheelchair ever since.<p>

 <li><b><a href="../amnesty/torture/china.html">China - punished by torture:</a></b><br>
<b>Tang Yuanjuan</b> was one of a group of workers arrested in Changchun, Jilin Province, in June 1989.  When he refused to admit to being a "criminial" he was severely beaten and then stripped naked and given shocks to the head, neck, armpits, stomach and legs with a high-voltage electric baton.  <p>




</ul>

