<a name="internet">

<hr width=40%>


<h2>The Internet: information and development</h2>

<ul type=square>


<li><b><a href="partner_news/may96_hrw.html">Worldwide efforts to censor Internet expand:</a></b><br>
Freedom of expression on the Internet is in serious danger across the globe, says <b>Human Rights Watch</b>.  Governments across the globe are rushing to impose controls, using excuses such as protecting children and thwarting terrorists to justify their actions.<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/hrw/index.html">Silencing the Net - The Threat to Freedom of Expression Online:</a></b><br>
The full Human Rights Watch report - giving a worldwide breakdown of how freedom in cyberspace is threatened in different countries.  Censorship legislation is being enacted or considered by governments of all political colours - led, ironically, by the United States, birthplace of the Internet.<p>

<li><b><a href="../index_oc/issue196/flashpoints.html">Pornography claims aid Internet censorship:</a></b><br>
The USA recently passed a law to censor the Internet on the grounds of pornography being accessible to minors.  China and Indonesia may use the same excuse for political reasons.<p>


<li><b><a href="../index_oc/news/china5feb.html">Jiang points the way backwards for China's information economy:</b></a><br>
The mushrooming Internet is challenging China's state control of the media, where the provision of business information is a lucrative trade.<p>


<li><b><a href="../index_oc/spore.html">Censorship and the Internet: a Singaporean Perspective</a><br></b>
Technology and censorship are often seen as opposing forces in the information age.  Singapore wants to harness the new technologies for development whilst keeping censorship controls in place.<p>

<li><b><a href="../panos/panos_internet_south.html">Developing world faces new 'information poverty':</a><br></b>
A report released today by the <b>Panos Institute</b> is deeply critical of the way the 'information revolution' has bypassed the developing world.<p>
</ul>

<a name="labour"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Labour</h2>


<ul type=square>

picture


<li type=square><b><a href="../ni/issue281/keynote.html">Cancer of "class" has taken over world, says New Internationalist:</a></b><br>
In 1991 the board of directors of the company General Dynamics met to consider their salaries.  They worked out a way to enrich themselves by $18 million by cutting the jobs of 500 workers.  In effect, says <b>New Internationalist</b> magazine, the board members had pocketed the wages, self-respect and aspirations of 500 people.  And the US class system let them do it.<br>
<font size=2><b>From New Internationalist, featured on the OneWorld News Service 7 August 1996</b><br>
Image ©Copyright: New Internalionalist</font><p>


<li type=square><b><a href="../oxfam/news/home_june20.html">ILO members to sign convention protecting rights of homeworkers:</a></b><br>
<b>Oxfam</b> strongly welcomes the ILO's long-awaited decision to recognise and protect the rights of employees working from home worldwide.  At present many homeworkers have to endure extremely low pay and poor conditions.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Oxfam UK, featured on OneWorld News Service  21 June 1996</b></font>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="http://www.oneworld.org/euforic/courier/156e_pet.htm">The changing face of trade unionism in Africa:</a></b><br>
Trade unionists took a front-seat role in dismantling one-party regimes in African countries.  Today they face the challenge of safeguarding political pluralism and improving conditions for workers in the face of wider economic forces.<br>
<b><font size=2>From ECDPM, featured on OneWorld News Service  18 June 1996</font></b>
<p>

<li><b><a href="../vso/orbit60/trade.html">Exploitation and poverty - the truth about free trade:</a></b><br>
'Free trade', 'globalisation' and 'liberalisation' are concepts promoted with great vigour by the international capitalist establishment.  With good reason.  Strong countries with big companies have much to gain from open access to other countries' markets and labour.<p>



<li><b><a href="../oxfam/press_20may.html">Oxfam launches worldwide campaign for clothes workers:</a></b><br>
Estela has worked Dominican garments factories for several years.  "I was sacked from one factory just because I was ill for a few days," she reports.  Hundreds of thousands of other people all over the world - mainly women - are working long hours for low pay in appalling conditions.  Why?  To produce clothes for Western consumers. <br>
<font size=2>Photo ©Copyright: Oxfam UK</font><p>

<br><li><b><a href="../oxfam/clothes/index.html">Oxfam's Clothes Code Campaign</a></b><br clear=left><br>




<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk51_gemini_presents.html">No Christmas joy for exploited toy workers:</a></b><br>
While Western children enjoy their fluffy toys, multinational companies rake in the profits.  But workers in Asian factories are the real losers, reports <b>Gemini News Service.</b><p>

</ul>


<a name="landrights"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Land Rights</h2>

<ul type=square>



 <li><b><a href="land_action/may96_land.html">OneWorld Special Report - Land Rights in Brazil:</a></b><br>
Brazil's Decree 1775 amounts to genocide, say indigenous land rights campaigners.  This special report - including a RealAudio interview and detailed information - investigates land rights issues in Brazil and around the world.<br>
<font size=2>Kaiow&iacute; child ©Copyright: Steve Cox/Survival</font><p>


<li><b><a href="land_action/index.html">OneWorld Multimedia report - The Land is Ours:</a></b><br>
Hundreds of land rights campaigners have taken over a vacant industrial site in South London, and have started putting practical small-scale sustainable development into practice.  The report has RealAudio interviews with people there, video footage of the occupation and photos of the site and its inhabitants.<p>



<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/brazil_apr25.html">Amnesty: Investigation into Brazilian massacre of peasants seriously flawed:</a></b><br>
On 17 April at least 19 demonstrating peasants were killed by military police in the Brazilian region of Par.  An investigation is being carried out, but by the state authority whose own police force was responsible for the murders.<p>

<li><b><a href="land_action/index.html">Land rights movement occupies derelict London site:</a></b><br>
A group of land rights activists has taken over 13 acres of London wasteland and begun building a sustainable eco-village, which it aims to hand over to the homeless and local people.
<p>

<li><b><a href="../christian_aid/press/apr24.html">Landless peasants mown down by Brazilian police in the Amazon:</a></b><br>
At least 25 people were killed at a demonstration about land rights in Brazil, when 200 military police opened fire with machine guns into the crowd, reports <b>Christian Aid</b>.<p>

<li><b><a href="../odi/land_reform.html">Land Reform: New Seeds on Old Ground?</a></b><br>
A detailed paper by the <b>ODI</b>, investigating the meaning of land reform and looking at past attempts to achieve a fairer distribution of the most important natural resource of all.<p>


</ul>

<a name="nuclearweapons"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Nuclear Weapons and Testing</h2>

<ul type=square>




<li><b><a href="../world_court/press_jul8.html">World Court declares nuclear weapons threat and use illegal:</a></b><br>
In a landmark decision, the International Court of Justice in The Hague has declared that the threat or use of nuclear weapons is illegal in just about any circumstance.  "This places a duty on the military to review their whole attitude toward nuclear weapons, which are now effectively in the same category as chemical and biological weapons," says World Court Project UK Chair Robert Green.<br>
<font size=2><b>From the World Court Project UK, featured on OneWorld News Service 9 July 1996</b><br>
Illegal and immoral - nuclear weapons.  Image ©Copyright: US Govt</font>
<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/jul96_worldcourt.html">World Court delivers verdict on nuclear weapons:</a></b><br>
The World Court in the Hague has been deliberating on the legality of nuclear weapons.  Our partner The World Court Project has been campaigning to have nuclear weapons declared illegal in international law.  Today the verdict was delivered, and we are publishing extracts.  More information will be available as it comes in.<br>
<font size=2><b>From the World Court Project UK, featured on OneWorld News Service 8 July 1996</b><br>
Will nuclear weapons continue to haunt mankind? ©Copyright: US Govt</font>
<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/may96_nuclear.html">International petition launched to support nuclear test ban:</a></b><br>
Pressure is building on world leaders to sign a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and to begin moves towards completely eliminating nuclear weapons.  Now a new international campaigning group is combining old and new methods to give the world's citizens a voice.<p>


<li><b><a href="partner_news/nuclear.html">Unrepentant Chirac announces end to French nuclear tests:</a></b><br>
Following the sixth and largest nuclear explosion on Saturday, President Chirac has announced the successful conclusion of the testing programme, and pledged to work towards a global test ban treaty.<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/greenpeace.html">Radioactive leaks reported on Mururoa:</a></b><br>
The French government has confirmed that a leak of radioactive iodine 131 took place from Mururoa atoll during its nuclear testing programme in 1995.<p>

<li><b><a href="wk44_french_test.html">French stand firm as third nuclear blast reported:</a></b><br>Pacific countries went through the usual motions of condemnation, but Chirac is now convinced he can weather the diplomatic storm.<p>


<li><b><a href="../news/msf_report.html">The health of the population of French Polynesia and nuclear testing</a></b><br>
Tired of all the hot air surrounding the nuclear testing debate?  This report by Medicins Sans Frontieres gets to the heart of the matter, by using both political and scientific analysis.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk42_gemini_bomb1.html">The battle against the bomb -1:</a></b><br>Scientists opposed to nuclear arms are pessimistic about the chances of a total end to nuclear testing, even with a full test ban treaty.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk42_gemini_bomb2.html">The battle against the bomb - 2:</a></b><br>Anti-nuclear campaigners are hoping that a ruling in their favour at the World Court will bring global disarmament nearer.<p>

<li><b><a href="wk40_french_test.html">Second nuclear test among largest ever:</a> <br>
OneWorld Online reports</b> on the second French test in Polynesia, the seizure of Greenpeace's last ship and reported repression in Tahiti<p>

<li><b><a href="../world_court/world_court.html">World Court Project launches Internet bid to ban nuclear weapons:</a><br></b>
The <b>World Court Project</b> is operating an electronic form which will allow the Web community to participate in the fight against nuclear weapons.  Sign the form and your 'declaration of public conscience' will be taken as evidence by the World Court in the Hague.<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/wk40_flotilla.html">News from the peace flotilla at Moruroa:</a> <br> </b>
Updates and reports are now being sent direct to <b>OneWorld Online</b> from the South Pacific peace flotilla.  Bulletins include opinions and news of actions to stop nuclear testing<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/freedom_gabi_interview.html">Interview with peace activist Gabriel Tetiarahi:</a> <br> 
<a href="../com_fnd/path_piango.html">Gabi Tetiarahi</a></b>, co-ordinator of the Pacific Islands Association of NGOs, was recently accused of inciting riots and violence through his criticism of French nuclear testing.  Here he answers back...<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_tahiti_trade_unionists.html">Tahiti - inquiry urged into alleged French ill-treatment:</a></b><br>
<b>Amnesty International</b> report their worries that some of the 16 trade unionists arrested in Papeete may have been beaten.<p>

<b><li><a href="news_french_test.html">Chirac defiant despite worldwide condemnation:</b><br></a> As the nuclear blast shakes Moruroa, France vows to continue the tests.<p>

<b><li><a href="news_open_letter.html">Open letter from Hawai'i to Tahiti:</b><br></a> A Hawai'ian coalition offers support for the French Polynesians and condemns nuclear testing.<p>

<b><li><a href="french_president.html">Why we want to test the bomb:</a></b><br> An interview with the French President, Jacques Chirac's, spokesperson. <p>

<b><li><a href="news_saynon_page.html">View the controversial "Say Non" video:</a></b><br>'The Day of the Jacques' - how your boycott can stop the testing.<p>




<b><li><a href="../feedback/wk32_hiroshima.html">Hiroshima - a survivor's story:</a></b><br> The experience of Yoshiko Nishimoto, who was working in a factory only 2 kilometres away the blast.</a><p>


<li><b><a href="../gallery/hiroshima/hiroshima_top.html">The OneWorld gallery:</a></b><br> Hiroshima and Nagasaki exhibition of photographs.<p>

<b><li><a href="bloomfield.html">Why the atom bomb wasn't necessary to end the war:</a></b><br> A personal viewpoint, by CND Chair Janet Bloomfield.<p>

<b><li><a href="children_hirosh_book.html">Stories from the children of Hiroshima:</a></b><br>"...they had no hair
left and their burned faces were crimson with blood: they no longer appeared
human."<p>

<b><li><a href="news_japan.html">Hiroshima and the campaign against French nuclear testing:</a></b><br> The <b>OneWorld</b> news team reports on the lessons of history.<p></ul>



