<a name="refugees"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Refugees and Migration</h2>

<ul type=square>


<li><b><a href="reports/jul96_refugees.html">Refugees get 'kick in the teeth' from UK government:</a></b><br>
On 15 July, the British government passed new laws  re-introducing "unlawful" social security regulations, which will stop asylum-seekers from claiming welfare benefits. The Refugee Council's Chief Executive,<b> Nick Hardwick</b> has described the laws as "a kick in the teeth to some of the world's most vulnerable people". <br>
<font size=2><b>By the  OneWorld News Service 17 July 1996</b></font>
<p>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/april/refugees.html">New iron curtain keeps migrants out of 'Fortress Europe':</a></b><br>
The European Union has been pushing Eastern European countries to erect new barriers against poor migrants seeking a better life in the West.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_mozambique.html">Refugees from Mozambique in Zimbabwe</a> </b><br>
Refugees are normally despised in host countries.  But in Zimbabwe employers fear the loss of Mozambican refugees - who are their cheap labour reserve.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_germany.html">German churches help shelter deportees</a> </b><br>German churches are offering sanctuary to refugees the government wants to deport.  Gemini News Service reports.<p>



<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_hongkong.html">Vietnamese Boat People still face deportation</a> </b><br>
Twenty thousand Vietnames refugees - the so-called 'boat people' - are still languishing in foul conditions in Hong Kong's detention camps.  How long can the stalemate last?<p>

<b><li><a href="../gemini/wk38_gemini_bhutan.html">Refugee crisis as Nepalese are expelled:</a></b><br>In a little-known ethnic dispute, tens of thousands of people are being forced out of the Himalayan kingdom of Bhutan.<br>

<li><a href="../patp/pap_migration.html"><b>Migration today - the global challenge:</b></a>
<br>One in every 50 people in the world is forced to flee their native land.  Patrick Taran of the World Council of Churches believes injustice and war lie at the root of the problems. 

 <br><br><b>See OneWorld Online's <br><a href="../overviews/refugees/stalker_migration.html"> Overview on Refugees and Migration</a></b><br>
for in-depth analysis and the facts and figures of human migration flows worldwide. <p>

</ul>

<a name="transport">
<hr width=40%>

<h2>Transport</h2>

<ul type=square>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/july/mexico.html">Trans-Mexican road bridge threatens last great tropical forest:</a></b><br>
Plans to build a road bridge across Mexico to rival the Panama Canal and cash in on global trade are being welcomed by business interests. However, as Government officials gush about the dawn of a new 'Taiwancito', environmentalists warn that the bridge would be a death sentence to the country's last great tropical forest.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Gemini News Service, featured on the OneWorld News Service 6 August 1996</b></font><br>
<p>






<li><b><a href="reports/rts/index.html">Seven thousand at motorway party demand end to car culture:</a></b><br>
For one Saturday afternoon, traffic jams on London's M14 motorway were replaced with music and dancing as seven thousand people held an impromptu - and illegal - street festival.  Cars were prevented from entering the road, as protesters demonstrated their ideas for a sustainable future.<br>
<font size=2><b>By the OneWorld News Service 15 July 1996</b><br>
Thousands of people crowd onto the M14 in London to protest against increasing car use and pollution.  Image ©Copyright: Mark Lynas</font>
<p>


<li type=square><b><a href="../gemini/july/kenya.html">Kenyan taxi cyclists pedal from poverty</a></b><br>
With few cars and a bus system in near-collapse, enterprising cyclists are taking the commuter strain in Kisumu, Kenya's third-largest city.  Their service is cheap, non-polluting and reliable, and can earn the cycle operators a healthy income.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Gemini News Service, featured on OneWorld News Service 8 July 1996</b></font>
<p>



<li><b><a href="reports/jun96_criticalmass.html">Fuming cyclists take to the streets in protest at pollution:</a></b><br>
Cyclists the world over say they are sick of being treated as second-class road users.  As cheap, non-polluting transport, many feel that the future belongs to them.  Critical Mass - when cyclists club together to show cars who's boss - has become a world-wide expression of pedal-power.<br>
<font size=2>Critical Mass comes down the Cowley Road in Oxford, UK  ©Copyright: Helena Earnshaw</font><p>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/may/cars.html">Electric jolt for the car industry:</a></b><br>
All over the world, the growth in the use of the car as the principal means of transport has meant a huge increase in dangerous pollution from exhaust emissions.  Has the time come for the electric car?<p>


<li><b><a href="partner_news/apr96_newbury.html">Eviction of protesters finally ends at Newbury:</a></b><br>
The first stage of the British government's long-running battle with environmentalist anti-road campaigners at Newbury has ended, with the last protest camps being evicted by bailiffs.<p>



<li><b><a href="partner_news/newbury.html">One World News Service Multimedia Report: Newbury, UK</a></b><br>
The campaign against the new road at Newbury has been much  in the UK media recently. <b>OneWorld Online </b>visited the site of protest to find out why.<p>


</ul>


<a name="un">
<hr width=40%>

<h2>The United Nations</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li type=square><b><a href="../gemini/july/un.html">Struggle to fill the UN's seat of power:</a></b><br>
All eyes at the UN are on the increasingly bitter contest between Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and the US over Mr Boutros-Ghali's decision to run for a second term.  But behind the scenes a more important struggle is taking place over the real seat of UN power - the Security Council.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Gemini News Service, featured on OneWorld News Service 8 July 1996</b></font>
<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press_incourt.html">Why war criminals have nothing to fear:</a></b><br>Despite the fact that most war criminals are never punished, world leaders at the UN commemorations are planning to avoid taking concrete measures to establish a permanent International Criminal Court, reports <b>Amnesty International</b>.<p>

<li><b><a href="../vso/release.html">UN celebrates the work of volunteers around the world:</a></b><br>

Today is International Volunteer Day.  To mark this occasion, <b>Voluntary Service Overseas (VSO)</b> is paying tribute to volunteers working to help rebuild communities and infrastructure in areas of past conflict. 
<p>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk41_gemini_leaders.html">Leaders line up for 50-year photo opportunity:</a></b><br>The UN's 50th birthday is approaching.  But many countries haven't paid their contributions fully... <p>
<li><a href="../ni/NIissue262.html"><b>The UN at 50:</b></a>
<br>This special edition of the <b>New Internationalist</b> debates the past and the future of the United Nations.
<p></ul>


<a name="water">
<hr width=40%>

<h2>Water</h2>

<ul type=square>


<li><b><a href="partner_news/apr96_earthtimes2.html">Mexico City plans way out of water crisis:</a></b><br>
Mexico City's water supplies are running low, with wells in the surrounding valley rapidly becoming depleted.  To prevent a water and sanitation crisis, city authorities are looking at means to reduce demand and improve services. <br><b><font size=2>April 15 1996</font></b><p>


<li><b><a href="../wateraid/megaslums/index.html">Mega-Slums - The coming sanitary crisis:</a></b><br>
"After a generation or more of excessive water use and reckless discharge of municipal and industrial wastes, the situation of the world's major cities is appalling and getting worse," says a recent statement. <b>WaterAid</b> report investigates these crucial issues.<p>

<li><b><a href="../wateraid/thirsty/index.html">Thirsty Cities - Water, sanitation and the urban poor:</a></b><br>
A vital summary of the state of the world's water supplies and sanitary measures.  Will the growth of 'mega-slums' launch the world's urban poor into a massive sanitary crisis?<p> 

<li><b><a href="../gemini/mar96_water.html">Simmering disputes over water in Nile Valley:</a></b><br>
In a first step to averting possible future wars over scarce water supplies, the 10 countries of the Nile basin have been taking steps to sort out their demands.<p>

<li><b><a href="../patp/pap_victoria.html">An ecological disaster in the making:</a></b><br>The once clear, life-filled Lake Victoria is murky, smelly, and choking with algae.
<p>

<li><b><a href="../patp/pap_overview.html">Reversing the course of destruction:</a></b><br>
Anne E. Platt analyses the complex inter-relationship between human communities and inland water resouces.<p>

</ul>
