<html>

<header>

<title>Development Co-operation Review of Sweden</title>

</header>

<hr>

<H3><center><p></a>

Development Co-operation Review of Sweden<br>Summary and Conclusions<p>

<i>OECD Development Assistance Committee</i><p></h3>

<h5>June 1996<br>

For a copy of the full report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris Cedex 16, France

<br>

Home Page: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm" target="_top">http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm</a></h5>

</center><p>

<hr>

The OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) conducts periodic reviews to improve the individual and collective development co-operation efforts of its members.

<p>

The peer review is prepared by the Secretariat and involves staff from development agencies in other DAC member countries. A draft report of the team is prepared by the Secretariat and it forms the basis for a review meeting with the member.

<p>

Sweden's development cooperation programme is at a critical juncture.

New Swedish policies both contribute to and reflect evolving international

approaches to development. But at the same time, the organisational

structure is being overhauled and the historically high levels

of aid attained in 1992-93 are being sharply cut.

<P>

In its review of Sweden's programme on 5 June 1996, the Development

Assistance Committee (DAC) of the OECD concluded that changes

in the Swedish aid programme will influence the international

development community, where Sweden has been a leader and pacesetter.

Mr. James Michel, Chair of the DAC, summarised the findings of

the review based on these main points of policy, organisation

and aid volume.

<P>

Sweden's development cooperation programme aims to improve the

standard of living of the poorest people. Its established goals

include: growth of resources; economic and social equality; economic

and political autonomy; democratic development and society; and

a far-sighted utilisation of natural resources and concern for

the environment. The Parliament has recently approved the addition

of a sixth goal: equality between women and men.

<P>

In response to the recommendations of a Task Force on Poverty

Reduction, the Swedish International Development Cooperation Agency

(Sida) has prepared a poverty profile for each of its 21 main

co-operation countries and is working with its development partners

in those countries to prepare participatory country strategies.

The DAC welcomed this approach. It also commended Sweden's many

analytical contributions on aid policy issues more generally.

<P>

The Committee also welcomed Sweden's efforts in promoting the

reform of multilateral development institutions, both in the United

Nations and the multilateral development banks. Those efforts

include the identification of new and more reliable methods of

financing the multilateral development cooperation system. 

<P>

A new element in Sweden's multilateral programme is its contributions,

as a Member of the European Union since 1 January 1995, to the

development cooperation programme of the European Communities

(EC). Sweden is bringing to bear on the EC programme its long

experience in participatory development and cross-cutting social

areas, and is working to ensure greater coherence in EC policies

impacting on developing countries.

<P>

A sweeping reorganisation of Sweden's development co-operation

system has taken place. Five autonomous entities previously responsible

for development activities have been merged into a single Sida.

A reorganisation of the Swedish Ministry for Foreign Affairs,

also underway, will integrate country aid strategies and programming

into overall political and commercial relationships. These changes

hold the promise with strong effort and over time, of greater

coherence and effectiveness in the Swedish aid effort.

<P>

Sweden has traditionally been among the leaders in the DAC in

the volume of its official development assistance (ODA). In 1995,

however, ODA volume, at $2 billion, was down 3.3 per cent in real

terms from the previous year. The ODA/GNP ratio fell from 0.96

to 0.89 per cent. As a part of its effort to reduce its public

sector budget deficit, Sweden has temporarily abandoned its target

of 1 per cent of GNP for official development assistance and will

reduce the level of budgeted ODA to 0.7 per cent of GNP in 1997,

an estimated reduction of 11 per cent from the 1996 budget. The

level of ODA as a percentage of GNP is expected to remain constant

at 0.7 per cent through 1999. The Committee expressed its concern

at this reduction and its apprehension regarding future trends.

Sweden has stated its intention to regain the 1 per cent target

when economic circumstances permit. The Committee noted that rebuilding

aid levels is never an easy task and raising ODA as a per cent

of a growing GNP will require significant increases in the aid

budget.

<P>

The Summary and Conclusions as agreed by the Committee and the

Report prepared by the OECD Secretariat will be published in the

Development Co-operation Review Series of the DAC.

<P>

The Delegation of Sweden at the Peer Review Meeting was headed

by Mr. Jan Cedergren, Assistant UnderSecretary, Ministry for Foreign

Affairs. The examining Members were Japan and the Netherlands.

Mr. Michel chaired the review. 

<p> 

<HR>

<H6><i>Updated on August 8, 1996</i><p>

Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the Netscape browser. Please address comments to <a href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter

Ballantyne</a>, ECDPM</H6>

