<html><head><title>Crosslines: The other side of the street</title><!!keys: Crosslines+internet+media+e-mail+Geneva Internet Day></head><body><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="crosslines.html"> Crosslines Global Report</i></a><hr><h2>...the other side of the street</h2><p><i>Now we know. E-mail stands for excess mail, the additionalcommunications that seek you out and pour in on you immediatelyyou set up an electronic connection. Some is psychic junk mail:"Have a nice day" addressed to everyone in the organization;"What does arcom mean?" (I don't know). "Why are you nowhulm@itu.ch when you were hulm@itu.arcom.ch a few months ago?"(I don't know!). No wonder one of the commercial accessproviders goes by the name of panix.  By <b>Peter Hulm, </b>Managing Editor of Crosslines.</i><hr>The secrets of e-mail came out during a presentation at theGeneva Internet Day organized on 28 March by the InternationalTelecommunication Union (actually it proved so popular it wasscheduled for repetition on 29 March). Inayet Syed of ITU'sInformation Services Department (yet another mystery guest for<i>What's My Line</i>) revealed that 36,000 e-mail messages wereexchanged through ITU's system last month and its gopher menusystem recorded a peak of 180,000 accesses in one week. By myrough calculation that's one access every 3.5 seconds. So that'swhy I have such a hard time getting through some days.<p>Tony Rutkowski, Executive Director of the Internet Society, hadsome more mind-boggling statistics to offer the presentationsaudience: "World-Wide Web traffic growth is so stunning that ifit were to continue, in the year 1996 it will exceed the world'stelephone traffic." He also said that by the year 2000 therewould be 4,000 PetaBytes of traffic, enough to fill 10,000 1.2Gigabit/sec digital pipes.  And you know what that means (don'tyou?).<p>My point is: how much of the e-mail you receive would youotherwise get through the post? Syed explained: "If I don't readmy e-mail for a week it will take me half a day to process it.If you are on [an Internet news] list, that will add to it." YetITU has only 3,500 registered users, compared to the 20 millionhanging in the net at the moment and the 187 million internettedcomputers projected for 2000.<p>ITU, which started up a Web server last Friday (23 March 1995),prepared 18,000 pages for access through the new system. Syedlifted the corner on another much-hidden truth about W3 [=WorldWideWeb - Ed.] Thoughmuch of the formatting work was automated, "we did a handful ofpages [manually] to make it look nice. It took --," he said,sounding incredulous --"For two weeks I have been working onthis."<p>ITU is the home of engineers and PTT officials rather thanhackers. But you can't blame Michael Minges for pointing outthat 90% of Internet networks are in developed countries andthat the number of Internet users is overshadowed by the 600million telephone subscribers and more than one billion TV setsworldwide. Information consultant Michael Jensen noted that onlyAlgeria, Egypt, South Africa, Tunisia and Zambia havefull-powered lease lines to the Internet. Zambia's and Algeria'sconnections are only a few months old.<p>Some contrasts within international organizations are glaring:Tony Rutkowski passed on the estimate that 80% of all scientistswho have ever lived are now reachable on the Internet. But a fewweeks ago UNESCO Director General Federico Mayor circulated aReport by an eminent panel that the single most effective actionthat could be taken to enhance science today would be to ensurethat "all scientists everywhere had effective Internetconnectivity." The weird reality is that UNESCO itself has tocall on an outside University and commercial organization tohandle its electronic documents system because it lacks theskills and capacity to operate the system on its own, as Sayedpointed out.<p><hr>©Copyright: Crosslines Global Report April 1995<hr><a href="index.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo2.gif"> CROSSLINES Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
