<html><head><title>Womankind Worldwide - Newsletter</title></head><body bgcolor="bdfbc0" text="000000" link="9306a9" vlink="502c88"><h1 align=center><img src="newsletter_logo.jpg" ></h1><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../wk_info.html">Womankind Worldwide</a></i><hr><h1 align=center>Small Grants Programme: update</h1><font size=+1>Our small grants appeal in January raised nearly £25,000. The following reports are typical of the 90 small grants projects we were able to support last year thanks to generosity of our many supporters.</font><h3>Society for Community Development Project, Tamil Nadu, India</h3>Many of the voluntary organisations in the Salem District of Tamil Nadu are deeply concerned about the growing incidence of Female Infanticide in this area. The profound poverty of the people, increasing dowry demands and the poor social standing of women all contribute to the intense pressure and shame a family feels when a baby girl is born.<p>The Society for Community Development was set up in 1990 to support the rural poor of the Salem district. They applied to WOMANKIND for a small grant of £500 to run a campaign to combat the practice of Female Infanticide in their local area. Seminars and cultural programmes re-establishing the value of girls and women in society were held in three of the villages where the practice is traditionally most widespread. Issues such as dowry payments, education for girls and family planning were raised and thoroughly discussed. The parents of girl children were given gifts to promote the feeling that having a baby girl is a cause for celebration and not a source of shame and despair. Information pamphlets and posters were distributed to the surrounding area.<p>The campaign was widely welcomed and received considerable coverage in the local press. Nearly 1000 people attended the meetings and many signed a pledge promising to protect girl babies in their own families and villages from infanticide and neglect.<p><h3>Proyecto Independiente de Salud Indigena Lenca (PISIL), Honduras</h3>PISIL was set up 1993 to provide health training to the scattered communities of indigeneous people around San Jose. These communities are extremely poor and isolated. Indeed some of the villages are only accessible by foot. Over the last two years, PISIL has extended its work to include training in income generating activities such as pottery, embroidery, sewing, tile making. The aim of the training has been to build on the traditional skills of the villagers and to restore pride in their own rich culture and customs. <p>Many of the villagers are seasonal workers on the local coffee plantations. For much of the year, there is no work and the villagers have to survive on nothing more than a few tortillas to eat each day. The women wanted to use this time to make clothes for their families and to sell for a much needed income. WOMANKIND gave PISIL a small grant of £300 to buy a sewing machine, scissors, fabric, needles, thread etc to help them set up a sewing project.<p>The project has been a tremendous success. PISIL organised training for the women in cutting patterns, sewing, dressmaking and sewing machine maintenance. Three sewing groups were set up and with PISIL's two existing machines, each group now has its own sewing machine. The women meet once a week to work together and help each other out. This has the first opportunity for some of the women to earn an income of their own.<p> <h3>Madina Women's Development Programme, Sierra Leone</h3>Long periods of war and civil upheaval  have taken their toll on the poorest people of Sierra Leone. The Madina Women's Development Programme was formed by 100 rural women in the villages around Madina in central Sierra Leone. These women wanted a forum where they could come together to talk over their problems and offer each other mutual support.<p>More than three quarters of Sierra Leone's population do not have access to safe drinking water. A pressing concern expressed by many members of the Madina group was that their health and that of their families is badly affected by poor nutrition and  insanitary conditions. The programme agreed to organise workshops to train representatives from each of the villages in diet and nutrition, healthcare, safe drinking water and sanitation.<p>Many of the women have no means of earning money. The programme also set up a soap making project to enable their members to generate an income. Good quality soap is expensive and up until now has only been available in the urban areas some distance away. So the women were confident that there would be a market for their produce but the group needed training, materials and the basic tools necessary to start up their enterprise. <p>The Madina programme approached WOMANKIND for support and all this work has been made possible by a small grant for £792 to fund the healthcare workshops, training in soap making techniques and the purchase of materials and tools for their project. Already, some of the profit from selling the soap has started up a revolving fund which makes loans available to members who want to set up other small businesses.<p><h3>You can help other groups put their intitiatives into practice</h3><b>Our partners in developing countries have the courage and determination to improve their situation for themselves - what they often lack is funding to support their initiatives. Even small sums of money can make an enormous difference. If you would like to make a donation towards our small grants fund, please send it to us at 4 Albion Place, Galena Road, London W6 0LT.</b><p><b><a href="index.html">Contents Page</a></b><p><hr><p>©Copyright:1996 Womankind Worldwide<hr></body></html>
