<body>
<title>Poor in Health - Section 3</title> 
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="scf_info.html"> Save the Children Fund</i></a>
<p></center>
<hr>

<br>
<h2>3. ROUTES TO HEALTH</h2>
<p>

Clearly, health policy in 1996 exists in an environment radically different from that of 15 years ago. The changing economic climate and the new conditions caused by increasing global competition have brought benefits to some while impoverishing and marginalising many others.<p>


In 1981, in the belief that the world economy would continue to grow and governments of rich and poor countries would continue to make money available for health, the goal of universal health care by the year 2000 was approved by the Health Assembly reinstating the aims enshrined in the 1978 Alma Ata Declaration (<a href="../health/box4.html">see also "health for all"</a>)<p>


The 1980s turned out to be plagued by economic recession, declining terms of trade and falling aid. The decade crippled the economies of the poorest countries. Many faced the bitter pill of structural adjustment. Debt repayments swallowed up budgets. The market's dominance grew and the role of the state was increasingly reduced. Public sector health systems collapsed. In the global economic crisis, the most vulnerable suffered first - and worst.<p>
<p>


<h2>3.1 THE WORLD BANK MODEL</h2>

In this changed environment in 1993, the World Bank made its first major international policy statement on health in 15 years. It stated that:<p>



<ul type=disc>
<li>governments should provide the basic package of health care; but
<li>hospital-based health care should be charged for; and
<li> the free market and non-government organisations should supply other services.
</ul>

Firmly endorsing the belief in the competitive market as the arbiter of growth and social policy, it emphasised solutions which broadly imply a major contraction in the ambitions of state health systems and strongly support private sector health financing and provision:<p>


<i>"The challenge for most governments is to withdraw from areas of health care provision best left to the private sector while concentrating resources and attention on things that only government can do: responding to market failures (such as externalities associated with infectious disease control: ... and investing in health and education for the poor."</i><p>

<center>World Bank, World Development Report, 1993</center><p>


The basic premise of the new recipe for health was, and is, that money must be spent 'efficiently'. Cost effectiveness, measured by 'DALYs' (disability adjusted life years) per dollar, determined whether or not a treatment should be provided. Treating one child might save x years of impairment, while treating another may only improve a condition without sparing him/her the impairment - which according to the World Bank model is less cost effective. If a treatment is cost effective on these terms, it should be provided; otherwise it should not.<p>


In practice this means that in a poor country, resources would be available for, say, measles immunisation, which is effective and reasonably cheap, but treatment would not be available for a disabled child whose condition was not wholly remediable; nor for a child with HIV which led to secondary infections, because he or she would be bound to die anyway.<p>

<i>"Greater economic efficiency ... often brings with it greater inequity and inequality of opportunity".</i>
<center> World Health Organisation, Health in Social Development, Copenhagen 1995</center><p>
<p>


<a name="flaws"><h2>3.2 FLAWS IN THE MODEL</h2></a>

In 1996, The World Bank World Development Report 1993 remains the authority on health policy and is interpreted as the orthodoxy by many donors. While it welcomes the ports as an important contribution to the health policy debate, Save the Children opposes the model of health proposed in the report on the following grounds:<p>

<ul type=disc>
<li>It fails to acknowledge the absolute lack of resources available to the poorest countries to secure even minimum levels of quality in health care delivery to minimum numbers of people. It underestimates the real costs of effective health system.<p>

<li>It under-estimates the time needed to implement radical policy changes in environments that are poor. This will result in either no change or partial change with unforeseen consequences.<p>

<li>The cost-effectiveness model - as opposed to one which examines the cost of effectiveness - will fail the poorest and remove the notion of equity from health policy. It may lead to the further fragmentation of health services, inefficiency and waste through duplication and a failure to build strong health systems which are integrated and coordinated.<p>

<li>It repeats mistakes made by the World Bank in other sectors which have shown that if you standardise models of development across the world and impose solutions from above they will fail because of lack of ownership and failure to adapt to local circumstances (a href="../health/box5.html">see also "paying the price for health"</a>).<p>

<li>It assumes that private and NGO suppliers of health services are comparatively better on quality of care, access and coverage grounds than the government - an unproven assumption. It does not outline the role of government in regulating private provision to preserve standards of cost, quality, safety and coverage.<p>

<li>It relies too much on a US-style model of health services which has been shown to be inefficient overall and to exclude the poor. The US spends 13.8 per cent of its GDP (Gross Domestic Product) on health, a level of spending at which such a model may function. In poor countries, which spend less than one per cent of GP on health, the application of this model cannot work. <p>

</ul>
<p>
<p>

<a name="reforming"><h2>3.3 REFORMING THE MODEL</H2></a>

Since 1993, and in response to continual lobbying the health policy debate has begun to use a new language which supports Save the Children's own experience. Papers published  by the World Bank on health in Africa have acknowledged the lack of resources there, including insufficient levels of aid, and have proposed an annual increase in funds for health services in low-income and low health expenditure countries in Africa of $1.6 billion (Towards Better Health in Africa, 1995). It states that where governments of the poorest countries cannot afford to contribute to this, richer donor countries must.<p>

In further statements, the World Bank remains true to its mandate that growth is essential for poverty reduction but also stresses the need to look at the pattern and distribution of growth - who is losing and who is gaining. The world Bank's recent poverty assessments in Ghana for example, show the average rate of poverty has dropped; but that the gap between rich and poor has widened.<br> (Forthcoming paper, working title: Taking Action for Poverty Reduction in sub-Saharan Africa).<p>

Using language that echoes Save the Children's position, the World Bank describes a situation where African countries take charge of their own health; determine their own health policies, priorities and goals and build true consensus; assume responsibility for their health programmes; develop the ability to coordinate donor contributions; and make their own decisions - in the house, village and country. Thereby, donor countries and institutions work within the framework of national policies, reducing and eventually eliminating separate donor-financed and largely 'vertical' programmes. (Towards Better Health in Africa, 1995)<p>


The time is right to seize on these changes in emphasis and to reform the World Bank's recipe for health care. Unless we do, the goal of the universal right to health for all children will remain a pipe dream.<p>

<table border=6>
