<h1>Migrants and refugees</h1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2><li>The facts</h2>
<ul type=square>
 <li><b><a href="../guides/migration/index.html"><b>OneWorld Online:</b> Refugees - Facts and Statistics</a></b><br>
Peter Stalker gives you the facts you need to know.<br>
<li><a href="../overviews/refugees/stalker_foreign.html"><b>OneWorld Online Overview: Foreigners in OECD Countries - Facts and Statistics</a></b><br>
Who's living where? Peter Stalker finds out.<br>
<li type=square><b><a href="../overviews/refugees/stalker_asylum.html">OneWorld Online Overview: Asylum Seekers - Facts and Statistics</a></b><br>
Just how many people apply for asylum? <br>
<li><b><a href="../overviews/refugees/stalker_immigration_uk.html">OneWorld Online Overviews: Immigration to the United Kingdom</a></b><br>
Facts and figures on who makes up the British population and how this has changed.</ul>
<br clear=left><br>


<h2><li>The issues</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../gemini/april/refugees.html">Gemini News Service: 'New Iron Curtain' to Shut out Migrants</a></b><br>
The Euopean Union has been successfully pressing Hungary and some of its neighbours in east and central Europe to toughen immigration controls.  Western countries regard these eastern states as a vast transit camp for a growing army of poor migrants trying to flee poverty.<br>
<li><b><a href="../overviews/refugees/stalker_migration.html">OneWorld Online: Migrants and Refugees</a></b> <br>
As many as 100 million people are living outside their country of origin, that's one in every 50 of us. Why are so many people living away from home? Peter Stalker explains.
<li><b><a href="../overviews/refugees/stalker_emigration.html"><b>OneWorld Online Overview:</b> Emigration</a></b><br>
What is the impact of emigration on sender countries? Peter Stalker examines the issue.<br>
<li><b><a href="../overviews/refugees/stalker_language.html">OneWorld Online Overview: Language</a></b><br>
Immigrants often have to learn a new language to get work - Peter Stalker looks at the difficulties faced by people when they move to a different country.
<li><b><a href="../patp/pap_migration.html">People and the Planet: Migration Today - The Global Challenge</a></b><br>
What should be done to meet the problem?<br>
<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_mozambique.html">Gemini News Service: Repatriation Leaves Employers with Crops to Pick</a></b><br>
Successful refugee repatriation programmes are usually greeted with enthusiasm by all concerned but a group of farmers in Zimbabwe, faced with losing cheap labour, are less than happy ...</ul>




<h2><li>Environmental refugees</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../patp/pp_eco_refugees.html">People and the Planet: Environmental Refugees - a Crisis in the Making,</a></b><br>
Numbers of environmental refugees may increase alarmingly with the projected global warming.  Norman Myers reports on some of the key findings of a recent US report on the problem.<br>
<li><b><a href="../patp/pp_haiti.html">People and the Planet: Real Lives - Haiti</a></b><br>
"My land was tired - so I left". Haiti is an island of environmental refugees, over 1.3 million have left their homes, Catherine Maternowska reports.<p>
</ul>
<p>


<h2><li>Refugees by country</h2>
<ul type=square> 
<li><b>Bosnia: <a href="../news/europe/bosnia.html">OneWorld Reports on Bosnia</b></a><br>
Background information, news and feature stories, photographs and maps.
<p>


<li><b>Bhutan: <a href="../gemini/wk38_gemini_bhutan.html">Gemini News Service: Mountain Exodus As Cultures Collide</a></b><br>
Tens of thousands of people are leaving Bhutan - a majority being pushed out by a minority, a major but little known dispute.<br>
<b><a href="../gemini/mar96_bhutan.html">Gemini News Service: Marchers Defy Batons in Bid to Return Home</a></b><br>
Every week or two a fresh group of Bhutan refugees try to cross the Mechi Bridge from Nepal to India in an attempt to walk to their country of origin.   So far most have not made it past the Siliguri jail a few kilometres into India.<p>


<li><b>Germany:  <a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_germany.html">Gemini News Service: Churches Become Homes From Home</a></b><br>
German churches offering a safe haven to refugees are annoying their government.
<p>

<li><b>Iraq: 
<a href="../gemini/wk48_gemini_iraq.html">Gemini News Service: Hungry State Bleeds Youth and Talent</a></b><br>
As many as 4 million people have silently left Iraq seeking brighter futures elsewhere after crushing UN sanctions imposed after the Gulf War have dwindled opportunities for the educated.<p>

<li><b>Liberia: </b><br>
<ul type=circle>
<li><b><a href="../scf/press_apr12.html">SCF - Conflict and Background</a></b><br>
Liberia was thrown into conflict after the killing of Master Sergeant Doe in 1989. Since then the warring has continued and has recently escalated.  Find out the background to the conflict, the current situation, the effects of fighting on the local population, how the international community has reacted and what is in store for a nation divided by ethnicity and politics.<br>
<b><li><a href="../oxfam/news/liberia_june11.html">Oxfam: Oxfam Accuses Liberian Warlords of Diverting Aid to fuel their war</a></b><br>
Oxfam, along with 12 other aid agencies, reluctantly refuses to re-establish their aid operation to war-torn Liberia after looting of aid convoys.<br>
<b><li><a href="../scf/press/may14.html">SCF: Calls for Action to end Liberian Refugees' Misery</a></b><br>
SCF urge western African nations to make proper provisions for refugees fleeing the Liberian conflict.<br>
<li><b><a href="../scf/press/may7.html">SCF: Aid Agencies Appeal to Emergency Regional Summit on Liberia</a></b><br>
Aid agencies warn that Monrovia's population faces complete devastation if a solution is not found.<br>
<li><b><a href="../scf/press_apr9.html">SCF: Fighting will Create New Disaster for Civilians</a></b><br>
SCF warns that the fighting in Monroovia looks likely to create a new humanitarian disaster for civilians on top of an existing emergency resulting from six years of war.<br>
</ul><p>

<b><li>Mozambique:</b><br>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_mozambique.html">Gemini News Service: Refugees from Mozambique in Zmbabwe</a></b><br>
Refugees are normally despised in host countries.  But in Zimbabwe employers fear the loss of Mozambiquan refugees - who are their cheap labour reserve.</ul><p>



<li><b>Rwanda: </b><br>
<ul type=circle>
<b><li><a href="../news/africa/rwanda.html">OneWorld News Service reports on Rwanda</a></b><br>
Find out the latest from this troubled African nation, together with background information, news and feature stories, maps, photographs and video clips.<br>
<li><b><a href="../oda/ssch_headlines.html">ODA: Scots Teachers Pass On Soccer Skills to Refugees</a></b><br>
Two Scottish teachers flew out to Zaire to teach Rwandan children soccer.
</ul><p>

<b><li>Tibet: <a href="../ni/issue274/keynote.html">NI: The Great Escape</a></b><br>
What on earth is inducing ordinary Tibetans to cross - on foot and at night - the highest, bleakest, most perilous mountain paths in the world?  Vanessa Baird begins her investigations in Nepal.<p>


<li><b>Vietnam: <a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_hongkong.html">Gemini News Service: When Moving Back On Moving Back</a></b><br>
20,000 Vietmanese refugees are still facing deportation in Hong Kong detention camps twenty years after the end of the Vietnam War.  Gemini News Service looks at the controversy surrounding the asylum seekers.<p>

<b><li>Western Sahara: <a href="../guides/sahara/index.html">OneWorld Online Guide: Western Sahara web site</a></b><br>
Find out about the current situation, the history to the conflict, the Saharawi land and people, the refugee camps, schooling and a gallery of paintings by the children in the camps.<p>

 </ul></ul></ul>
<a name="people">


<center>[break][break][break]</center><br>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


<h1>People and places</h1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2><li>Afghanistan</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../amnesty/journjan_1.html">Amnesty International: The World's Guity Secret</a></b><br>
The world's governements have betrayed Afghanistan, playing out their rivalries on Afghan soil.</ul><br>

<h2><li>Brazil</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../oxfam/policy/brazil.html">Oxfam: A Mortal Blow to the Land Rights of Brazil's Indian</a></b><br>
Recent changes in procedures governing the legal and physical recognition of Indian lands will produce incalculable negative repercussions.</ul><br>

<h2><li>Burkina Faso</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../ni/268_heart.html">Chris Brazier returns to Bukina Faso</a></b>, ten years after his first visit which transformed the way he looked at the world. <br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/ni_pix/268_map_p9.gif">NI: Map of Sabtenga</a></b><br>
 A map of the village (gif 70k) 
<li><b><a href="../ni/268_heart.html">NI: A Decade In Burkina Faso: The Facts </a></b><br>
Chrs Brazier returns after ten years to the African village which transformed his way of looking at the world. Find out why.</ul><br>

<a name="burma">
<h2><li>Burma</h2>

<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue280/facts.html">New Internationalist: Burma - The Facts</a></b><br>
Human rights, business, refugees, resources...<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue280/simply.html">New Internationalist: A History of Burma</a></b><br>
The New Internationalist looks at the history, culture and struggle of the Burmese people.<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue280/interview.html">New Internationalist: Icon of Hope</a></b><br>
Aung San Suu Kyi, Burma's elected leader, is interviewed by John Pilger.<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue280/keynote.html">New Internationalist: A Cry for Freedom</a></b><br>
Burma has one of the worst human rights records in the world but the ruling junta is keen to present a new face to the world.  John Pilger discovers the terrible human price its people are paying for that new face.<br>
<i><font size=-1>(Image © New Internationalist)</i></font>
</ul><br>

<h2><li>China</h2> 
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../tvandradio/dyingrooms.html">OneWorld Online: Return to the Dying Rooms</a></b><br>
The full transcript of The Dying Rooms, the documentary that revealed the systemmatic and deliberate murder by starvation in Chinese orphanages, is available to read here. <br>
<b><li><a href="../gemini/gemini_childmurder.html">Gemini News Service: Where 'Quality Control' Leads to Child Murder</a></b><br>
China is reinforcing its one-child-family policy with an ever more controversial "child quality" law which will empower the authorities to impose sterilisation or abortion on couples found to have genetic, mental or infectious diseases.</ul><br clear=left><br>

 

<h2><li>Eritrea</h2> 

<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../gemini/wk2_gemini_bicycles.html">Gemini News Service: Mobilising Women in Fresh Liberation Drive</a></b><br>
As bicycle enthusiasts try to overcome sexual discrimination by encouraging women into the saddle in Eritrea the national cycle-racing team has been helping to put the recently-liberated country on the map.<br>

<font size=-1><i>(Image © ODA)</i></font><br clear=left><br></ul>


<h2><li>Ethiopia</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../cafod/weth-0.htm">CAFOD: Ethiopia: Working in Partnership</a></b><br>
Find out about the country that suffered thirty years of civil war and one of the most devastating famines in world history.</ul><br>
  
<h2><li>Kenya</h2> 
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../vso/overview.html">Wahome Mutachi charts the growth of Kenya from its bloody beginnings to today's fragile calm.</a></b><br>
East Africa's 'success story' still faces instability and tension, and multi-party democracy has not proved the panacea it was hoped.  Wahome Mutachi charts the growth of Kenya from its bloody beginnings to today's fragile calm.</ul><br>

<h2><li>India</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../ymcacare/street.html">YCARE: Street Life</a></b><br>
They eat from the dustbins and beg for a piece of bread or morsal of rice. Their tomorrows are enveloped in deep darkness. Visakhapatnam YMCA is helping street children experience life away from this reality and get them off the streets.<br>
<li><b><a href="../actionaid/actionaid_cdrom1.html">ACTIONAID: Discover India.</a></b>This new CD-ROM offers the opportunity to explore and discover the reality of life in India.</ul><br>

<h2><li>Mongolia</h2>

<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../vso/orbit/61/monglead.html">VSO: Mongolia - Glorious Past, Uncertain Future</a></b><br>
With the Soviet Union consigned to history along with Genghis Khan, the Mongolian people face the challenge of rebuilding their country along new lines.  J Enebat suggests that national pride will see them through.<br>
<b><li><a href="../vso/orbit/61/mongecol.html">VSO: Protecting the Wilderness</a></b><br>
Mongolia's unspoilt grasslands and unharmed ecosystems are now under threat - from economic development.<br>
<b><li><a href="../vso/orbit/61/monglaw.html">VSO: Reinventing the Law</a></b><br>
Genghis Khan may not be the best role model for law, order and justice, but Mongolia is invoking his example in an attempt to revitalise its legal system.<br>
<b><li><a href="../vso/orbit/61/mongkids.html">VSO: New Kids on the Block</a></b><br>
Increasing income inequality, street children have become a new feature in Mongolia's cities.  What forces drive them there and what is the government doing to care for them?<br>
<font size=-1><i>(Image © VSO)</i></font><br>
</ul>



<h2><li>Palestine</h2> 
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../ymcacare/rehab.html">YCARE: Rehabilitation in the West Bank</a></b><br>
Nidal Abu Zuluf, East Jerusalem YMCA, writes about the work of their Rehabilitation Programme which provides help and counselling to disabled people and their families.</ul><br>


<h2><li>Tanzania</h2>
<ul type=square> 
<li><b><a href="../unicef/nnud_contents.html">UNICEF: Tanzania Fact Files</a></b><br>
Fact files on history, geography, culture and even how to speak Swahili, bake cocunut biscuits and make a kanga.<br>
<li><b><a href="../oda/oda_tanzania.html">ODA fact file on the  East African country of Tanzania</a></b> - its climate, landscape, agriculture, trade, health and education and population. Statistics, photographs and text tell you all.
</ul><br>

<h2><li>Tibet</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue274/contents.html">NI: Issue 274: A Cause for Courage</a></b><br>
How big is Tibet? What is its history? The New Internationalist looks into these questions and examines the uneasy relationship that exists between China and Tibet.</ul><br>

<h2><li>Uganda</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="partners_pix/orbit59/overview.html">VSO: Rising from the Ashes</a></b><br>
Uganda's brutal past under the rule of Idi Amin has often overshadowed its present, but now the Pearl of Africa is looking to build afresh its future.<br>
<li><b><a href="../vso/orbit59/vsougan.html">VSO: Rediscovering the Pearl of Africa</a></b><br>
Sue Grant reviews VSO's involvement in Uganda.<br>
<li><b><a href="../vso/orbit59/radio.html">VSO: Freedom of the Airways</a></b><br>
Kalungi Kabuye reports on the radio revolution sweeping through Uganda's capital.<br>




<b><li><a href="../vso/orbit59/rags.html">VSO: From Rags to Riches</a></b><br>
Imported second hand clothes may be the only affordable option for most Ugandans, but the growth in this trade sells disaster for the country's resurgent cotton industry.<br>
<b><li><a href="../vso/orbit59/ugawomen.html">VSO: A Voice of One's Own</a></b><br>
The past decade has brought significnt progress in the lives of Uganda's women, both at the grassroots level and in high official positions.  Keturah Kamugasa Akiiki reports on recent successes and challenges for the future.<br>
<i><font size=-1>(Image © VSO)</i></font>
</ul>
<br clear=left><br>

<h2><li>Crime and Punishment</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue282/editor.html">New Internationalist: Editor's Letter</a></b><br>
How does crime and punishment compare between the relatively richer 'north' to the poorer 'south'?<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue282/facts.html">New Internationalist: The Facts</a></b><br>
Rates for serious violent crime are more or less stable but prison populations and the resources expended on the crime-control industry are both expanding rapidly.  Find out how much gets spent, who's commiting what type of crime where, and more.<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue282/keynote.html">New Internationalist: Rush to Punishment</a></b><br>
Richard Swift visits the jailers and the jailed - in a system that's become an end in itself.<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue282/learn.html">New Internationalist: What You Learn in Prison</a></b><br>
So prison life is supposed to rehabilitate the offender?  This is what Kevin Murray found after investigating prison life in Canada.<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue282/awayout.html">New Internationalist: A Way Out</a></b><br>
Richard Swift walks the mainstreet USA to find the alternatives that are being developed for an overburdened system of crime control.<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue282/simply.html">New Internationalist - Simply - The Punishment Machine</a></b><br>
Inequality and unemployment are on the increase like never before.  In the fear that this will result in a growing violent underclass, governments are investing in prisons and police in a new frenzied crime-control industry.<br>
<b><li><a href="../ni/issue282/action.html">New Internationalist - Take Action!</a></b><br>
Find out how you can get involved in the prison reform.</ul><p>





<h2><li>Racism</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../cafod/racism.htm">CAFOD Factsheet: Racism</a></b><br>
What is racism, how multi-cultural is Britain and what laws are there to protect people?
</ul>
<p>

<h2><li>Communications</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../vso/orbit/61/communic.html">VSO: Whose line is it anyway?</a></b><br>
Why should media ownership matter to people fighting for basic survival? Cees J Hamelink examines the global disparity in communication power and shows how lack of 'voice' can marginalise whole communities.<br>
<b><li><a href="../v">VSO: A Bad Press</a></b><br>
With the media providing less and less coerage of the developing world, it is small wonder that people in Britain have less and less understanding of the issues involved.  Daya kishan Thussu examines the growing trend towards excluding news from the South.<p>
</ul>



<h2><li>Dictators</b></h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue275/facts.html">NI: Dictators - the Facts.</a></b><br>
How many people live under military systems and where are the world's ten worst regimes?<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue275/where.html">NI: Where are they Now?</a></b><br>
Thinking of organizing a military coup or taking over your own country?  Would you end up in jail or could you be looking to a nice little villa in the sun? The New Internationalist looks at the some of the world's most notorious dictators and asks, where are they now?<br>
</b></ul><p>


