<h1>Homelessness</h1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue276/facts.html">NI: The Facts</a></b><br>
More than 1,600 million people worldwide live in life threatening and health-threatening circumstances - that's almost one third of the world's population.<br>
<b><li><A href="../ni/issue276/streettalk.html">NI: Street Talk</b></a><br>
Words from Thuli, Scott, Max and Alain in the wilderness of Johannesburg, Los Angeles, London and Paris.<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue276/caged.html">NI: Caged</a></b><br>
The Hong Kong economic miracle looks like a mirage when you're old, says Ho Hei Wah.<br>
<a name="caged">
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue276/simply.html">NI: Simply ... The Ideal Home</a></b><br>
For consumer societies the ideal home is the ultimate buy, but this 'ideal' creates more problems than it solves in an outside world that won't go away.<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue276/exclusive.html">NI: World Exclusive!<br></b></a>
Homeless people are making their presence felt on the streets, earning a living without having to beg.  The success story of the street papers.<br>
<font size=-1>©New Internationalist</font>

</ul><br><a name="cities">

<center>[break][break][break]</center><br>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


<h1>Cities</h1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2><li>Changing Cities</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><A href="../vso/orbit/61/forum.html">VSO: Tales of the City</a></b><br>
What's it like to be an urban dweller in a developing country?  Jenny Seabrook finds out and celebrates the achievements of the world's urban poor.<br>
<b><li><a href="../patp/vol6/livernas.html">People and the Planet: How Cities Grow</a></b><br>
People and the Planet look at how the smaller cities are changing in size and composition and reveal that change may not be as dramatic as first thought/.<br>
<b><li><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL962.html#transition">World Goodwill: The City in an Age of Transition</a></b><br>
Due to the population explosion and mass migration from rural areas beset by poverty Third World cities are growing at an alarming pace.  Every ten to fifteen minutes their population doubles.<br>
<b><li><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL962.html#auroville">World Goodwill: Habitat for Humanity</a></b><br>
Habitat for Humanity is an not-for-profit action group building homes for low income families.  World Goodwill looks at how the scheme works.<br>
<li><b><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL961.html#urban">World Goodwill: Becoming an Urban Species</a></b><br>
In 1900 just 14% of the worlds population lived in cities, now that figure is almost 50%.  In the words of Lester Brown of the Worldwatch Institute we have become "an urban species".<br>

<li><b><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL961.html#cities">World Goodwill: Cities Action on the Environment</a></b><br>
Agenda 21 of the Rio Earth Summit (1992) calls upon local municipalities to draw up their own programmes to make cities more environmentally friendly.<br>
</ul><p>




<h2><li>Sustainable cities</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../patp/vol6/pyesmith.html">People and the Planet: Building Green Islands in Bombay</a></b><br>
Bombay is the world's fifth most polluted city with a minimum of green spaces but two imaginative clean up projects hope to re-teach people about the value of open green spaces.<br>
<b><li><a href="../patp/vol6/charlesw.html">People and the Planet: Making Dreams Come True in Bangkok</a></b><br>
New hope has been brought to Bangkoks worst slum areas in a new government initiative.<br>
<b><li><a href="../patp/vol6/satterth.html">People and the Planet: Towards Healthy Cities</a></b><br>
There is no need for cities to be unhealthy, says David Satterthwaite.<br>
<b><li><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL962.html#sustainable">World Goodwill: Sustainable Community</a></b><br>
What are sustainable city networks and how people are working to change the cityscape in which they live?<br>
<b><li><a href="../patp/vol6/cavalcan.html">People and the Planet: Curitiba</a></b><br>
Christina Cavalcanti reports on the city's efforts to extend its succeses in the face of a growing population.<br>
<b><li><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL962.html#curitiba">World Goodwill: Curitiba</a></b><br>
Curitiba, Brazil's fifth largest city has experienced rapid growth in population since the 1960's fed by migration from the surrounding poor rural areas.  Even though around 80% of the population earns as little as $500 a year it is cited as a model of urban planning and environmentally sustainable development.  Find out why.<br>
<li><b><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL962.html#auroville">World Goodwill: Auroville - City of Human Unity</a></b><br>
Auroville, a pioneering experiment where people all over hte world have come together to create a model city, is situated on 2,600 acres in the Indian state of Tamil Nadu.  Find out how such a model city works.<br>
<li><b><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL961.html#sustainability">World Goodwill: Sustainability</a></b><br> 
Is the goal of a sustainable city really possible?<br>
<li><b><a href="../overviews/cities/girardet_urbanage.html">OneWorld Online Overview: The Urban Age</a></b><br>
Are sustainable cities in an urbanising world really possible? Herbert Girardet thinks so.<br>
<li><b><a href="../overviews/cities/girardet_urbanisation.html"><b>OneWorld Online Overview:</b> Urbanisation and the Growth of Cities</a></b><br>
How far does urbanisation, especially in the 'developing' world, threaten environmental sustainability?<br>
<b><li><a href="http://www.gn.apc.org/resurgence/villages.html">Resurgence: Villages with Vision</a></b><br>
Groups of people around the world are forming new villages to experiment with ecological and spiritual lifestyles.<br>
</ul><p>


<h2><li>Urban consumption and sanitation</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../patp/vol6/rees.html">People and the Planet: Ecological Footprints of the Future</a></b><br>
Can cities really be ecology friendly?  Dr. William Rees warns that unless a shift in consumption habits is essential.<br>
<li><b><a href="../wateraid/megaslums/summary.html">WaterAid: Mega-Slums - The Coming Sanitary Crisis</a></b><br>
By the turn of the century, half the 6.2 billion population of the planet will be urban.  At least half of the urban population will live in crowded tenement, shanty towns and slums.  WaterAid examines the impact of such growth on water supplies and waste disposal.<br>
<li><b><a href="../overviews/cities/girardet_table1.html">OneWorld Online Overview: London</a></b><br>
Find out how much the 7 million people of London produce and consume each year.<br>
<li><b><a href="../overviews/cities/girardet_composting.html">OneWorld Online Overview: Composting and Waste in Cities</a></b><br>
How can separating your rubbish help city life?<br><br>

<ul><a href="yes_schools_env.html#waste">Water and waste in cities</a></b><br>
</ul></ul>


<h2><li>Healthy cities movement</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../cities/cities_healthy.html">International Healthy Cities Foundation: What is the Healthy Cities Movement?</a></b><br>
Why is it important to be concerned about the state of our cities - the IHCF tells you why and what they're about.</ul><p>


<h2><li>Housing projects</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL961.html#squatter">World Goodwill: Squatter Settlements</a></b><br>
Squatter settlements are the inevitable result of high urban population growth, but new self-help schemes in some of the worst affected cities are easing the poverty experienced in "shanty towns".<br>
<li><b><a href="../cafod/cafmag6.htm">CAFOD: Stalin's Grandchildren</a></b><br>
Although the last political prisoners were released from Albania's labour camps in 1991, many are still living in cramped conditions in dormitories, corridors and bunkers.  A unique housing project has not only given new apartments to 94 families, it has created a new sense of purpose and hope amongst some of those who have suffered the most under the communist regime.</ul><p>

<h2><li>Roads and transport</h2>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="../news/reports/rts/index.html">OneWorld News Service: Motorway Party Demands End to Car Culture</a></b><br>
For one Saturday afternoon, traffic jams on London's M14 motorway were replaced with music and dancing as seven thousand people held an impromptu - and illegal - street festival.  Cars were prevented from entering the road as protestors demonstrated their ideas for a sustainable future.<br>
<li><b><a href="../news/partner_news/newbury.html"><b>OneWorld Online News Reports:</b> The Newbury Bypass </a></b><br>
Read all the reports on the Newbury Bypass scheme and why people are protesting.<br>
<b><li><a href="../news/reports/jun96_criticalmass.html">OneWorld News Service: Fuming Cyclists Take to the Streets in Protest at pollution</a></b><br>
Critical Mass hits Oxford, UK.<br>
<b><li><a href="../gemini/july/kenya.html">Gemini News Service: Kenyan Cyclists Pedal from Poverty</a></b><br>
With few cars and a bus system near collapse, enterprising cyclists are taking the commuter strain in Kismu, Kenya's third-largest city.<br>
<b><li><a href="../gemini/july/mexico.html">Gemini News Service: Trans-Mexican Road Bridge Threatens Last Great Tropical Forest</a></b><br>
Plans to build a road bridge across Mexico to rival the Panama Canal and cash in on global trade are being welcomed by business interests.  However, as Government officials gush about the dawn of a new 'Taiwancito', environmentalists warn that the bridge would be a death sentence to the country's last great tropical forest.<br>
<b><li><a href="../gemini/may/cars.html">Gemini News Service: Electric Jolt for the Car Industry</a></b><br>
All over the world, the huge growth in the use of the car as the principal means of transport has meant a huge increase in dangerous pollution from exhaust emissions.  Has the time come for the electric car.<br>
<li><b><a href="../patp/vol5/newsfile.html#roads">People and the Planet: Amazon Roads</a></b><br>
Concern is growing over plans by the Brazilian Government to build four major highways through the Amazon rainforest.<br>
<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk46_gemini_cars.html">Gemini News Service: Quest for Private Route Out of Transport Chaos</a></b><br>
A clash is looming in China - the kingdom of the bicycle - between old and new; clean and dirty forms of transport.<br>
<li><b><a href="../news/partner_news/newbury.html"><b>OneWorld News Service:</b> The Newbury Bypass</a></b><br>
Reports from the conflict between developers and campaigners over the proposed route of the Newbury Bypass. </ul><p>
<a name="nation">

<center>[break][break][break]</center><br>
</BLOCKQUOTE>



<h1>The Nation State</h1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue277/facts.html">New Internationalist: Facts - The State of Nations</a></b><br>
What is a Nation State? What are the problems associated with them?<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue277/keynote.html#definitions">NU: Definitions </a></b><br>
Nation, state, nation state and nationalism - what do they mean?<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue277/simply.html">NI: Simply - a History of the Nation State</a></b><br>
Where are the origins of nations states and nationalism?<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue277/keynote.html">NI: Bullets and Borders</a></b><br>
Nikki van der Gaag looks at why the nation state is on its last legs - and why people are still prepared to die for it.<br>
<li><b><a href="../ni/issue277/africa.html">NI: In Search of a New Africa</a></b><br>
Ikaweba Bunting believes that the nation state in Africa has lost its way, and travels across the savannah in search of a new pan-African Nationalism.<br>
<font size=-1">©Copyright New Internationalist</font><p></ul>
<a name="conferences">


<center>[break][break][break]</center><br>
</BLOCKQUOTE>



<h1>International conferences</h1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<h2><li>Habitat II</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL961.html#interview">World Goodwill: Interview with Dr. N'Dow</a></b><br>
Dr. N'Dow, Secretary-General of the UN Conference on Human Settlements (Habitat II), talks about the importance of dealing with global settlement challenges.<br>
<li><b><a href="../worldgoodwill/WGNL961.html#habitat2">World Goodwill: Habitat II - The City Summit</a></b><br>
Almost one half of the world's population lives in cities and they are growing by around one million people each week.  The stress of this rapid urban population growth is overwhelming.  World Goodwill looks at the issues Habitat II hope to tackle in June and what has happened since the first conference twenty years ago.<br>
<b><li><a href="../patp/vol6/leader.html">People and the Planet: Habitat - Twenty Years on</a></b><br>
In 1976 Colombian Secretary General Enrique Penalosa announced that this first Habitat conference marked a turning point in improving human settlements.  But what has the reality really been since then?<br>
<p>

<ul><a href="../diary/youth_diary.html"><b>Youth Diary: Habitat II</a></b>
<p></ul></ul>




<h2><li>The World Summit for Social Development</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../unicef/unicef_wssd.html">UNICEF: Special Report on the WSSD</a></b><br>
Despite a seven-fold increase in the wealth of nations in the last 50 years, more than one billion people still live in absolute poverty. The WSSD sets out to address this problem.
</ul>
<p>


<h2><li>International Conference on Population and Development</h2>
<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../patp/pp_con_v3n4.html">
People and the Planet: A Victory for Women</a></b><br>
The International Conference on Population and Development, which took place in Cairo from September 5-14 1994, was a victory for enlightenment and for women, but left many questions unanswered on development, the environment and migration.  John Rowley looks at what the conference achieved.<br>

</ul>

<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../patp/pp_con1_v3n4.html">People and the Planet: Programme Expansion a 'Major Advance'.</a></b><br>
Dr Fred Sai shares his thoughts on the achievements and limitations of the ICPD.<br>
<li><b><a href="../patp/pp_con2_v3n4.html">People and the Planet: Women's Perspectives</a></b><br>
Bishakka Datta reports on the challenge facing women's advocacy groups on changing the mountain of talk from the ICPD into action.<br>
<li><b><a href="../patp/pp_con3_v3n4.html">People and the Planet: Action Should be put on Hold until Further Notice</a></b><br>
Many delegates can't find enough funds to implement what was agreed at the ICPD.  Ajoa Yeboah-Afari looks into it.<br>
<font size=-1>©ODA</font><br></ul>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<a name="labour">


<center>[break][break][break]</center><br>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<h1><li>Labour</h1>
<blockquote>
<ul type=square>
<b><li><a href="http://www.foe.co.uk:80/camps/susdev/future.html">FOE: Working Futures</a></b><br>
Friends of the Earth report on employment and sustainable development.<br>
<li type=square><b><a href="../ni/issue281/keynote.html">New Internationalist: Cancer of "Class" has Taken Over the World</a></b><br>
In 1991 the board of directors of the company General Dynamics met to consider their salaries.  They worked out a way to enrich themselves by $18 million by cutting the jobs of 500 workers.  In effect, says <b>New Internationalist</b> magazine, the board members had pocketed the wages, self-respect and aspirations of 500 people.  And the US class system let them do it.<br>
<li type=square><b><a href="../oxfam/news/home_june20.html">Oxfam: ILO members to sign convention protecting rights of homeworkers</a></b><br>
ILO's long-awaited decision to recognise and protect the rights of employees working from home worldwide is strongly welcomed.  At present many homeworkers have to endure extremely low pay and poor conditions.<br>
<li type=square><b><a href="http://www.oneworld.org/euforic/courier/156e_pet.htm">Euforic: The Changing Face of Trade Unionism in Africa</a></b><br>
Trade unionists took a front-seat role in dismantling one-party regimes in African countries.  Today they face the challenge of safeguarding political pluralism and improving conditions for workers in the face of wider economic forces.<br>
<li><b><a href="../vso/orbit60/trade.html">VSO: Exploitation and Poverty - the Truth about Free Trade</a></b><br>
'Free trade', 'globalisation' and 'liberalisation' are concepts promoted with great vigour by the international capitalist establishment.  With good reason.  Strong countries with big companies have much to gain from open access to other countries' markets and labour.<p>

<li><b><a href="../oxfam/press_20may.html">Oxfam launches worldwide campaign for clothes workers</a></b><br>
Estela has worked Dominican garments factories for several years.  "I was sacked from one factory just because I was ill for a few days," she reports.  Hundreds of thousands of other people all over the world - mainly women - are working long hours for low pay in appalling conditions.  Why?  To produce clothes for Western consumers. <br>
<font size=2>Photo ©Copyright: Oxfam UK</font><p>

<br><li><b><a href="../oxfam/clothes/index.html">Oxfam's Clothes Code Campaign</a></b><br clear=left><br>




<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk51_gemini_presents.html">Gemini News Service: No Christmas joy for exploited toy workers</a></b><br>
While Western children enjoy their fluffy toys, multinational companies rake in the profits.  But workers in Asian factories are the real losers.</b><br clear=all><br>


</ul></blockquote>






