<a name="african">
<hr><br>




[International African Institute]<br clear=left><br><br>


<b><li>Africa and the Africa Bibliography</b><br>
The Africa Bibliography has been published annually since 1985 and has established itself as an authoritative guide to the previous year's publications relating to African studies. Covering the whole of Africa and including works in many languages, the Bibliography regularly contains well over 5000 entries, categorised by region, country and discipline. Full author and subject indexes add to its value as an important work of reference. It can be bought as part of a subscription to Africa, or as a separate volume.<br><br><br>

<b><li>History and Underdevelopment in Morocco<br>
The Structural Roots of Conjuncture</b><br>
<i>Benson Akutse Mojuetan</i><br>
History and Underdevelopment in Morocco is a wide-ranging interpretation of the history of Morocco. Drawing not only on the relevant literature of the Maghrib, but also on the more extensive literature on ~pre-capitalist formations' elsewhere, the author attempts to link the ~micro-history' of Morocco with the ~macro-history' of Europe and the Middle East. Covering the mediaeval period through to the present, and using a Marxist approach, he seeks to explain the roots of Moroccan underdevelopment in terms of Morocco's internal and external relations. It is a worthwhile contribution to understanding of Moroccan history and serious analysis of some crucial issues in the theory of historical change.

<p>B. A. Mojuetan is a Senior Lecturer in the Department of History at the University of Ibadan, Nigeria.<br>
<b>£14.95<br>
(Monographs from the IAI 1) ix+231pp<br>
3 89473 697 6<br>
LIT Verlag</b><br><br><br>

<b><li>Savannah Nomads<br>
A Study of the Wodaabe Pastoral Fulani of Western Bornu Province Northern Region, Nigeria</b><br>
<i>Derrick J. Stenning [reprinted with a new introduction by Philip Burnham]</i><br>
This account of the Nomadic pastoral Fulani of Bornu, Northern Nigeria, begins with a brief historical sketch of the ancient kingdom of Bornu and its vicissitudes, of the Holy War of the nineteenth century and its repercussions on the Fulani pastoralists themselves. There follows a detailed analysis of the family structure of the pastoralists (or Wodaabe), their organization into lineage groups, their forms of marriage and of inheritance, the status and functions of leaders in the lineage group and the cattle camps, and the central place in the whole structure occupied by the herds. Part II is concerned with changes in the traditional structure and way of life consequent on the British administration, in particular the effects of the introduction of village headships and of new methods of taxation. A concluding chapter describes current plans for improving the general economy of the pastoralists, by developing various modifications of their methods of agricultural and animal husbandry, and by establishing forms of settlement. 

<p>Derrick Stenning (1927-1964), after teaching at University College London and Cambridge, was the Director of the East African Institute of Social Research in Uganda.<br>
<b>£14.95 <br>
(Classics in African Anthropology 2) xxvii+266pp<br>
3 89473 878 2<br>
LIT Verlag</b><br><br><br>
 


<b><li>Land, Labour and Diet in Northern Rhodesia<br>
An Economic Study of the Bemba Tribe</b><br>
<i>Audrey I. Richards [with a new introduction by Henrietta Moore</i><br>
In this study Dr Audrey Richards describes the living conditions of the Bemba of North-Eastern Rhodesia, with special reference to the effects of migrant labour on the social and economic life of a mainly agricultural society. Although primarily concerned with the production, distribution, and consumption of food, and with conditions of labour and standards of living, the book gives a vivid picture of the social structure of the Bemba - their political organisation and the functions of the chief, systems of land-tenure, kinship groupings, and the whole complex of economic, social, and magico-religious factors which arise in any community.

<p>The book has been widely recognised as an authoritative study particularly among economists and anthropologists. 

<p>Audrey Richards (1899-1984) studied under Malinowski at the London School of Economics before teaching at Cambridge for many years.<br>
<b>£14.95<br>
(Classics in African Anthropology 3)<br>
xlii+428pp<br>
3 89473 876 6
 <br>LIT Verlag</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Peoples of the Horn of Africa<br>
Somali, Afar and Saho</b><br>
<i>IM Lewis [new edition with supplementary appendices]</i><br>
The disintegration of the Somali Republic in the internal conflicts of the 1990s has added to the demand for this book, out of print for several years. First published in the Ethnographic Survey of Africa series, this new edition departs from previous editions (the first in 1955 and the revised edition of 1969) in including a report on the population, social organisation, and land holding situation in the Inter-Riverine Area of southern Somalia which was written for FAO in 1964 (Appendices I, II and III). This new material is based on the author's field research carried out in the region in 1957, 1962 and 1964. Although much has happened in Somalia since then, the groups described are still the main protagonists in the region and this account of their relationships and patterns of land use may help in planning the region's reconstruction when conditions permit. 

<p>IM Lewis has been Professor of Anthropology at the London School of Economics since 1969.<br>
<b>£25.00<br> 
228pp<br>
9 781874 209560<br>
Haan Associates</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>A Handbook of Tswana Law and Custom<br>
Compiled for the Bechuanaland Protectorate Administration</b><br>
<i>Isaac Schapera [reprinted with a new introduction by Simon Roberts]</i><br>
When Professor Schapera was asked in 1934 by the Protectorate Administration to compile a record of the traditional and modern laws of the Tswana tribes he had already been working since 1929 on a comprehensive ethnographic study of the Kgatla, and his investigation was therefore based on a thorough previous knowledge of the social structure as a whole. The author gives a picture of what Tswana law was like in former times, and shows that, contrary to expectation, modern European contact and the administration of tribes by the then Protectorate Governemtn ende the original uniformity of the system, and created considerable diversity. Schapera conscientiously kept within the original mandate of the Administration and produced and authoritative, straightforward compilation. Despite its modest title it has deservedly become a classic and far exceeds its primary object, which was to serve as a handbook for the information and guidance of governmentofficials and administrators of the law. This is a reprint of the first edition published in 1938. 

<p>Isaac Schapera is Emeritus Professor of Anthropology at the London School of Economics and Political Science. He has published widely, particularly on the subject of the Tswana.<br>
<b>£14.95 <br>
(Classics in African Anthropology 1)<br>
xviii+326pp<br>
3 89473 685 2<br>
LIT Verlag</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Rainforest Relations<br>
Gender and Resource Use among the Mende of Gola, Sierra Leone</b><br> 
<i>Melissa Leach</i><br>
With environmental change and conservation in West Africa's tropical rainforests becoming topics of increasing political and academic attention, Rainforest Relations brings a fresh set of perspectives to the debate: those of the forest dwellers themselves.

<p>Based on detailed research in the Mende communities around Gola North Forest Reserve in Sierra Leone, this innovative book examines the different relationships women and men have with their environment. Surveying the recent debates and literature concerning forest conservation in this area, as well as current analytical approaches to gender and the environment, Melissa Leach examines the importance of rainforest resources to the local economy and social relations, and shows that neither an understanding of forest use and change, nor adequate conservation policies, can be achieved without a concern for gender. 

<p>Melissa Leach is a social anthropologist and Fellow of the Institute of Development Studies at the University of Sussex. <br>
<b>£39.50 <br>
(International African Library 13)<br> 
xx+272pp<br>
0 74860493 6<br>
Edinburgh University Press</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Ranching and Enterprise in Eastern Botswana<br>
 A Case Study of Black and White Farmers</b><br>
<i>Isaac Ncube Mazonde</i><br>
Botswana's economic development has been extraordinary in Third World terms, yet little is known about how different social groups have adapted to the new economic opportunities. This comprehensive account studies a key group of the new entrepreneurs: the ranchers. It describes their changing life styles, their construction of personal and social space, and the way they have adapted to state-initiated political and economic change, showing through a series of case studies how ranching has grown from being the preserve of white settlers to include Botswana and other African farmers as well. The relationship between ranching and communal land tenure, and the effect of Botswana's Tribal Land Grazing Policy are analysed in detail, while the careers of non-elites, the practice of bordermanship, labour relations and the management of multiple enterprises and risks are also covered. This book will appeal to Africanists, development planners, historians and anthropologists. 

<p>Isaac Ncube Mazonde is a Senior Research Fellow at the University of Botswana.<br>
<b>£39.50 <br>
(International African Library 12)<br>
xii+164pp<br>
0 7486 0467 7<br>
Edinburgh University Press</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Strangers and Traders<br>
Yoruba Migrants, Markets and the State in Northern Ghana</b><br> 
<i>J S Eades</i><br>
In the inter-war years, groups of enterprising Yoruba traders from a few towns in Western Nigeria established a remarkably successful trading network throughout the Gold Coast (Ghana). Using information, skills and capital generated mainly within the family, what grew to become the largest group of immigrant traders in the country had spread to even the most remote areas, becoming a powerful force in the Ghanaian markets. Then, in 1969, they were abruptly ordered to leave the country. 

<p>At the time of the exodus, Jerry Eades was carrying out research on the Yoruba and was able to follow these traders back to Nigeria. There, on the basis of extensive interviews and archival sources, he reconstructed the history of the migration from four Yoruba towns to northern Ghana. The result is one of the fullest and most detailed accounts of chain migration and its implications for economic development ever written - of interest not only to anthropologists and historians, but more generally to anyone with an interest in trade and informal sector labour markets, and their relationship to ethnicity, economic development and state policies in Third World countries. 

<p>J S Eades is Senior Lecturer in Social Anthropology at the University of Kent, currently teaching as an Associate Professor in the Department of Cultural Anthropology at the University of Tokyo.<br>
<b>£39.50 <br>
(International African Library 11) <br>
xiv+234pp<br>
0 7486 0386 7<br>
Edinburgh University Press<br></b><br><br>


<b><li>Black Mountain<br>
Land, Class and Power in the Eastern Orange Free State, 1880s to 1990s</b><br>
<i>Colin Murray</i><br>
Black Mountain is a chronicle of the struggles of many of the people - black and white - whose lives have been rooted in one district of the South African highveld over the last hundred years. Thaba Nchu (Black Mountain) was the territory of an independent African chiefdom until it was annexed by the Orange Free State Republic in 1884. By 1977, one third of the original territory had emerged as part of ~independent' Bophuthatswana, giving rise to acute inter-ethnic antagonisms. As a result, on an adjoining piece of bare veld, there sprang up the largest rural slum in South Africa, Botshabelo - a massive concentration of poverty and unemployment. The stories told by inhabitants of the slum in 1980 led Colin Murray to ask the questions that ultimately shaped this book.

<p>Black Mountain is a vast and complex jigsaw' assembled out of many disparate parts. The author complements detailed archival evidence with contemporary oral history. In its rigorously limited focus on the experience of one district, the book illuminates all the important themes of the political economy of the rural highveld of South Africa from the mineral revolution of the late nineteenth century to the erosion of apartheid in the late twentieth century.

<p>Colin Murray is an anthropologist who teaches in the field of development studies. He is Director of the Centre of African Studies at the University of Liverpool.<br>
<b>£39.50 <br>
(International African Library 10) <br>
xiv+340pp<br>
0 7486 0344 1<br>
Edinburgh University Press<br></b><br><br>

<h2>To order IAI publications, <A href="../iai/iaipubs.html#order">click here.</a></h2>

<a name="international">

<hr>
<br>



[International Institute for Environment and Development]<br clear=left><br><br>


<b><li>Urban Poverty and the Environment in the South Pacific</b><br>
<i>Jenny Bryant</i><br>
This book examines urban poverty issues and the changing nature of the urban environment in the South Pacific.  The author begins by discussing the nature of the relationship between poverty and the environment, and between development and sustainability objectives within the South Pacific in general, and places the urban issue within a broader context.  <p>

The discussion examines both the objectives of economic development
and "new" development institutions such as NGOs and community based organizations.  The book focuses mainly on "...the linkages between changing environments and increasing poverty in the urban centres of the South Pacific nations" (page 5) with a bias away from Papua New Guinea and towards the smaller islands.<p>

The main text starts with an introductory chapter on changing environmental management and urbanization trends in the South Pacific.  In the second half of this chapter, the author considers definitions of poverty and measures of poverty within the localities being
considered.  The following chapter examines a number of aspects of the urban environment including waste disposal and water supply facilities, solid and industrial waste disposal, hazardous wastes and atmospheric pollution, and impacts on health.  <p>

Separate sections consider economic strategies relevant to the environment, the specific role of the South Pacific Regional Environment Programme and environmental legislation and management. <p>

Chapter four focuses on urban poverty and examines the scale of poverty in the South Pacific, and related factors such as health, education and economic change; poverty issues related to the urban habitat are considered separately.  The chapter ends with a discussion
on policy related issues including the role of government and poverty alleviation strategies.<p>
 
Chapter five consists of a case study on poverty and urban environments in Fiji, and the final chapter considers "positive approaches" to the problems associated with urban poverty and environmental degradation.<p>

  The author concludes that, while the problems are complex
"...there are .... countless ways of improving the lot of the poor, but only if there is the political will , and only if the poor have the opportunities and capacity to participate" (page 94). 
<br>
<b>1993<br>
105 pages<br>
ISBN 1 86389 017 3  <br>
Published by and available from:<br>
the Department of Geography and Planning, University of New England, Armidale<br>
NSW 2351, Australia.</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>The Latin American City</b><br>
<i>Alan Gilbert</i><br>
This book consists of eight chapters, each considering different aspects of the Latin American city.  Chapter one presents short descriptions of Bogot , Caracas, Guadalajara, Rio de Janeiro and La Paz to highlight the diversity of Latin American cities but also to point to commonalities - for instance the common language (except for Brazil) and cultural roots laid
during almost 300 years of rule by Spain and Portugal.  Chapter two describes the growth of the Latin American city from its pre-Columbian and colonial heritage to the present.  This includes the rapid expansion from the 1930s or 1940s to around 1980 that coincided with
large increases in national populations, sustained economic growth and industrial development, and the slower growth in the 1980s with stagnant economies and falling birth
 <p>
Chapter three describes "the move to the city", including what fuelled rural to urban migration, the different forms it takes (and how these have changed over time), and the impact of the economic recession of the 1980s.<p>

Chapter four reviews employment and work, especially
the changes evident in the 1980s.  Special attention is also given to the situation of women
and to child labour.<p>
 
Chapter five, on housing strategies, describes the major changes in recent decades including the large increases in the proportion of people living in owner-occupied dwellings (even if most developed illegally) and the large expansion of city areas. <p>

Chapter six, on urban management, notes that often too much emphasis is given to "horror stories" and that, in general, infrastructure and service provision have expanded greatly. It also gives examples of how poorer groups are generally the worst served.  <p>

There are sub-sections on transport, pollution and disasters.  The current fashion for privatization of services is also critically
reviewed. Chapter seven describes the different protests that have taken place and discusses why protest in the form of conflict has not been more common,  given the scale of poverty and inequality.  It also describes different measures by which governments have dampened
protest - including repression, clientalism and the cooption of leaders.<p>

Chapter eight considers what the author suggests are the rather poor prospects for "The Future of the City."  He notes that "...in general, Latin America's cities face a much more optimistic future than do cities in most parts of Africa or those in many parts of Asia.  But much depends on the rate of economic growth, without which it is difficult to improve most
people's lives, and much on better and fairer government" (page 169).   In each chapter, boxes are used to give examples - for instance in the chapter on urban protest are there are boxes on a description of Superbarrio in Mexico City, a portrait of a community leader in Bogota, a description of the protest in Caracas in February 1989, and "How to fend off
protest; the Solidarity Programme in Mexico".
<br>
<b>1994<br>
 190 pages<br>
ISBN 0 906156 82 3<br>
Published by and available
from:<br>
the Latin American Bureau, 1 Amwell Street, London EC1R 1UL, UK. <br>
In North America, available from:<br>
Monthly Review Press, 122
West 27th Street, New York, NY 10001, USA. </b><br><br><br>


<b><li>El Futuro de la Capital<br> 
(The Future of Bogota, Colombia's Capital City)</b><br>
<i>Various authors</i><br>
These are the first four published volumes to have come out of a two-year programme involving Colombian specialists in a major research exercise designed to provide "a vision of the desirable future for Colombia's capital city for the first decade of the twenty-first century."  More publications are planned, but nearly 30 are already available in unpublished
form covering five major areas of the city's present and future development: social and economic issues; housing, infrastructure, utilities and social services; physical development and the environment; local government; and culture.<p>

The studies were prepared by specialist teams and their conclusions were discussed at public meetings with government officials and non-governmental organizations.  The four volumes have a common format and range in length from 110 to 210 pages.  In all cases, past and future population trends, and spatially and socially disaggregated data on income and employment are used as the basis to understand the present situation and to forecast developments to the year 2010.  The studies include a diagnosis of the key issues relating to
the sector, present institutional arrangements, possible future scenarios, and concrete proposals for implementation by present and future administrations.  The conclusions suggest that multi-disciplinary approaches are the more effective way of dealing with such issues.<p>

Particular attention is given to existing social inequalities.  Although the city's inhabitants have benefited from very real improvements in living standards since population growth peaked in the early 1970s, in 1985 nearly 15 per cent of the city's households still lived in overcrowded conditions, and 6.5 per cent lacked connection to one or more of three basic services: drinking water, sewage, or electricity.  A UNICEF-UNDP funded study, in
the same year, found that the basic needs of 23 per cent of the population were still unmet.<p>

Although run independently as a non-profit organization, until December 1992, Mision Siglo XXI had the financial backing of the mayor's office and the results of these studies were to have been incorporated in a medium-term metropolitan development plan.  If maintained, this scheme would have allowed the staff of the Mision to regularly monitor changes in some key areas of the city's development.  Such a scheme did not materialize,
but the city's future mayors and, indeed, its citizens, now have a set of documents which should help them identify the most pressing issues in building a more desirable future for the city. <br> 
<b>1993<br>
All four volumes (housing; health; education; and supply and
distribution of food) published by and available from :<br>
Mision Siglo XXI, A.A. 93597, Santafe
de Bogota, DC, Colombia</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Nairobi's Informal Settlements: an inventory</b><br>
<i>by Matrix Development Consultants</i><br>
This report aims to "...provide accurate information on the location and characteristics of informal settlements in Nairobi... to be used as a basis for formulating policies and strategies for the city... in particular for informal settlements."  The settlements were grouped into seven areas corresponding to the city's administrative divisions and, using aerial
photography, ground visits and a literature survey, information was gathered for each division and is presented in this inventory.<p>


The first section introduces the objective, organization of the report and the methodology, followed by a short overview of the city of Nairobi.  This is followed by a definition of "informal settlements" and an analysis of various characteristics including: population growth; economic survival including income levels and generation; the provision of basic urban services including water supply, sanitation, drainage and garbage collection; education; and the implications for health of life in the informal settlements.<p>

The next section is the actual inventory.  For each of the seven divisions information is given on the following: location and history; population; housing conditions; infrastructure and services including water, sanitation, electricity, refuse disposal; access roads and transportation; health, education, church and social facilities; economic activities and sources of income; and community based organizations and NGOs which operate in the area.<p>

Annex one gives a list of references; annex two outlines the aerial photography and mapping procedure, and explains how population estimates were arrived at; and annex three gives a long list of voluntary organizations which operate in Nairobi, and includes details of the activities they undertake.  A final section consists of a map showing all informalsettlements in Nairobi, and larger scale maps of five typical settlements with greater detail.<br>
<b>44 pages<br>
 1993<br>
Available from:<br>
Matrix, P O Box 59343, Nairobi, Kenya. </b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Towards a Sustainable Urban Environment: the Rio de Janeiro Study</b><br>
<i>Edited by; Alcira Kreimer, Thereza Lobo, Braz Menezes, Mohan Munasinghe and Ronald Parker</i><br>
This study provides a broad and detailed description of environmental problems and their underlying causes in Rio de Janeiro.  It is one of a series of studies of metropolitan areas in Brazil, Turkey and the Philippines being undertaken by the World Bank, the United
Nations Development Programme and the United Nations Centre for Human Settlements (Habitat); and is based on ten papers that were presented at a seminar in November 1992 organized by the Brazilian Institute for Municipal Administration.  The papers are presented
in four sections. <p>
 
Section I has an introductory paper that summarizes the most serious environmental problems in Rio de Janeiro and their underlying causes - and why the different levels of government have been unable to address these problems. This includes a description of environmental change within the wider region and of the historic roots of contemporary
social and environmental problems.  Section II, entitled "the conceptual framework", consists of two papers.  The first describes how Rio de Janeiro's real comparative advantages are its natural beauty and its potential for higher living standards, at a lower cost than other
Brazilian cities.  It also describes how public policy has failed to protect and promote these comparative advantages.  The second paper describes the concepts and tools used in coastal zone management and their use within the metropolitan region.<p>
  
Section III consists of four papers which consider different aspects of the institutional and financial framework.  The first describes the legal and institutional framework for environmental policy and the inadequacy of its implementation.  The second paper describes the development of the institutional framework for urban policy and some of its past and
current failings.  The third reviews government financing and expenditure on the environment in Brazil and Rio de Janeiro.  The fourth paper reviews recent research on urban environmental issues undertaken in Rio de Janeiro.  Section IV has three papers on "operational experience and technological issues".  The first describes the initial two years
of the "Rio reconstruction project" that was a response to the floods and landslides in 1988.<p>
 
The second describes how the relationship developed between the World Bank and the different government institutions in Brazil for World Bank funded work in Rio.  The final paper considers the issue of appropriate technologies for urban services in Rio de Janeiro. The report includes text boxes throughout, covering such subjects as the views of
NGOs, the basic sanitation programme for Guanabara Bay and an overview of emergency planning in industrial installations.<br>
<b>162 pages<br>
1993<br>
World Bank Discussion Paper No. 195. <br>
Published by and available from: <br>
Publications Department, the World Bank, 1818 H Street NW, Washington DC 20433, USA. </b><br><br><br>

<b><li>The Struggle for Nairobi</b><br>
<i>Terry Hirst assisted by Davinder Lamba</i><br>
This is a large format book that tells the history of Nairobi and its population and the city's changing relationship with its wider environment, in words and pictures in the form of a
"documentary comic book."  Although the information is presented, as illustrated above, in the form of a comic book,  it contains a level of detail and analysis both on the city's history and on its contemporary problems and underlying causes that will surprise many readers, including those who are familiar with Nairobi.  <p>

The text includes many maps that show how Nairobi developed over time - starting with maps showing the geological and ecological context and moving onto different maps showing how the city developed 1899-1905, 1906-1926, 1927-46, the 1948 masterplan, 1964-1983 and what the city is like in the early 1990s.<p>
 
Its coverage extends up to the Nairobi City Convention organized in July 1993, attended by 800 people, which was the first public consultation on Nairobi's future.  It was initiated by the former Mayor, Steve Mwangi and a committee of Nairobi citizens. 
<br>
<b>190 pages<br>
ISBN 9966-9876-1-4  <br>
Published by and available from:<br>
Mazingira Institute, PO Box 14550, Nairobi, Kenya.</b><br><br>


