<h2>Channel Africa to close</h2>

Channel Africa, South Africa's external shortwave broadcaster under threat of closure by the government, has launched a national and international campaign for its continuance with the backing of SABC management, staff and unions. <p>

At a special meeting held on June 6th to address the concerns of staff, Mr Govin Reddy, Radio Chief Executive, pledged the SABC's support for the campaign. The overwhelming majority of staff favoured the continuation of the station and also gave their backing to the campaign as Channel Africa was viewed as a national asset. One staffer said it was ironical that just when South Africa needed a voice on the airwaves in Africa and the world there were moves to silence Channel Africa.<p>

At present the station broadcasts in three Southern African languages (Chinyanja, Silozi and Xitsonga), one East African language (Kiswahili), as well as in English, French and Portuguese.<p>

The service was first established in 1966 as Radio RSA but repositioned itself as Channel Africa in 1992 and then embarked on  a transformation process which resulted in a  new mission statement which pledged to make the station &quot;a comprehensive and authentically African communications forum which serves Africa from Africa, is totally objective and credible and reliable, is dedicated to the promotion of positive development in Africa, is committed to the enhancement of dialogue, understanding and co-operation between all African people as their 'Channel of Goodwill'...&quot'.<p>

With more than 15 million regular listeners, Channel Africa is also extremely cost effective. According to recent estimates the station is able to broadcast at less then half a cent a day per listener.<p>


The Commonwealth Broadcasting Association notes with concern the announcement of plans to close the external service of SABC, Channel Africa, and has pledged support to the SABC to keep the station open. As the CBA Secretary-General, Elizabeth Smith, put it:<p>
<ul>
&quot;This would be a major loss to its regular audience of 15 million listeners. South Africa could not have a more cost-effective means of reaching and influencing its neighbours. It seems extraordinary that at a time when other African countries are looking to South Africa for leadership that a voice of this kind should be silenced.&quot;</ul><p>

All local support for the campaign should be faxed to Channel Africa (011) 714-2546 or 674-4325. International support to (+2711) 714-2546 or 674-4325.<p>

<h3>More Information and Internet Links</h3>

<blockquote><br><li><b><a href="http://www.sabc.co.za/units/chanafr/index.html">Channel Africa Home Page</a></b>
<li><b><a href="http://www.wrn.org/stations/africa.html">Channel Africa on the Internet in RealAudio</a></b>
<li><b><a href="http://www.sabc.co.za/">The South African Broadcasting Corporation</a></b>
</blockquote><br clear=left><br>
