<head>
<title>Situation in Sierra Leone worsens - press release</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000">

<hr><br>
<h4>For Immediate Release,10th October 1995</h4>

<h2>SITUATION IN SIERRA LEONE WORSENS</h2>


Over the last three months the inaccessibility of the hundreds of thousands of displaced people  in Sierra Leone  has greatly increased due to continued rebel attacks on the Freetown-Bo-Kenema Highways. This has resulted in serious shortages of food and other essential commodities, leading to widespread hunger, starvation and increased malnutrition in the districts. This horrendous situation has been aggravated by the recent outbreak of cholera. Children and women have been the worst affected.


<h4>Surveys have found -</h4>
  An estimated 20 - 30 children dying every day and that the incidence of acute global malnutrition was as high as 22%.  The causes of death are mainly lack of food, cholera/diarrhoea, acute respiratory infections, measles and malaria.
  An outbreak of cholera in the affected districts, propagated by the overcrowding and insanitary conditions in the camps and most homes, has had a serious impact on the population. To date, 1,248 cases have been reported in Kenema alone, 98 have died.
  The present population of Kenema is estimated to be 400,000, of whom 100,000 are displaced from the surrounding districts. The majority of the displaced are staying with relatives and friends in overcrowded conditions. The average size of a household has increased from 8 before the war to 38.
<p>

As an immediate response, UNICEF has airlifted emergency supplies, including basic health items, drugs, vaccines and other essentials to the area. Many of the airlifts don't manage to get through. Project teams have visited Bo, Kenema, Segbwema and Makeni to assess the situation. Health clinics are being established in all camps to provide free treatment to displaced persons, while support is being given to MSF and Action Internationale Contre la Faim (AICF) in their screening and therapeutic feeding programmes for children. To ensure continuation of schooling for displaced children, UNICEF has provided "school in a box" kits for 28,000 children between 6 and 14 years.
<p>

UNICEF is also concerned by the dramatic increase in the number of street children, with over 3,000 in Kenema and Bo, some as young as 4 years old, and another 3,000 in Freetown.  UNICEF
supports local NGOs in identifying and registering street children and placing them in transitory homes, providing blankets, clothing and cooking utensils.
<p>

Note to Editors: UNICEF's field staff are available for interview by phone.
<p>
<b>For further information, please contact: Stacey Adams, UK Committee for UNICEF, on 0171 430 0162.</b>
<hr>
©Copyright: UNICEF August 1995
<hr>
