<html><head><title>Rwanda: Special Report - Children in prison</title><!!keys: ></head><body><h2>Children in prison</h2>This segment includes interviews with child prisoners in Rwanda accused of involvement in the killings. Some of the imprisoned children are only five years old.<p>These children, who have lived through horrifying experiences over the past year, are housed in filthy prisons, with dirty water and poor nutrition. Their physical health continues to be at serious risk, not to speak of their emotional health.  <p>Estimates of the number of children in prison vary from 350 to as many as 1,000. Crammed into Kigali prison are over 7,000 men, women and children. Unicef has been trying to re-house the children in special centres - and to provide them with a team of ten lawyers to represent them.<p><p><ul><img src="../unicef/unicef_pix/rw_prisonboy.gif"></ul><p><i>Seven year old Musa has no idea why he's here or when he was arrested. He knows that he is accused of genocide, but doesn't know what that means. </i><p><br><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><img src="../unicef/unicef_pix/rw_prison.gif"></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul><p><i> Hundreds of children wait for justice behind barbed wire and prison walls. </i><p><br>©Copyright: Stills extracted from video by Unicef.</body></html>
