<head>
<title>Gemini - Classes under the mango tree fail teaching test</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<br><i> The material that follows has been provided by </i> <b><a href="../gemini_info.html">  Gemini News Service</a></b>
<hr>


<h3>CLASSES UNDER THE MANGO TREE FAIL TEACHING TEST</h3>
<i>
Education is often touted as the answer to every problem. But the presence of 
schools does not guarantee education. After spending several weeks in a 
Ghanaian village on assignment for <b>Gemini News Service, Isabella Gyau</b> reports 
on class conflict.<p>


By <b>ISABELLA GYAU</b>,
21 May 1996,<br>
Offuman village, Ghana  </i><hr><p>


Theresa Boateng is regarded as educated, but she cannot read letters or write 
correspondence for the old women whose children have travelled abroad. <p>

Nor can she write the names of people who donate money during funerals, or 
fill in funeral announcement and invitation forms.<p>

Theresa, a senior secondary school graduate in Offuman village, Ghana, is 
unperturbed. "I am not the only person like that," she says.<p>

She is right. About 70 per cent of the 2,000 villagers are illiterate and most 
of the young people who have been to school are, at best, semi-literate.<p>

One teacher attributes the low level of literacy to a general lack of interest 
in education: "Their interest lies in fufu  [a universally popular dish made 
from cassava] and garden eggs [a vegetable used in stews and soups] and nothing 
else." <p>

He says the children have no contact with the outside world, and so nothing 
challenges them to study and improve their lot. <p>

Girls face particularly difficult barriers. Some parents believe that however 
educated a women is, she will end up in a man's kitchen. So they are not keen 
on educating their daughters.<p>

"Because of this, whenever a female child threatens to drop out of school, the 
parents welcome the idea," says the teacher.<p>

"I have tried my best to educate them about women who have achieved high 
academic laurels as a result of interest in education," he says, "but it seems 
the girls are only interested in marriage.  For them, marrying at 20 is too 
late." <p>

As a result, about 95 per cent of adult women in Offuman are illiterate.
There are many other problems. Nursery school teacher Docia says: "It all 
begins at the pre-school level, where the child's interest in education could 
be developed." <p>

She says most parents refuse to send their children to nursery school, saying 
they cannot afford the fees. <p>

She also blames parents who fail to dress their children properly for school: <p>

"Some come in tattered clothes and sometimes their friends tease them." 
Consequently, the youngsters do not feel happy in school.<p>

Parents blame the poor facilities. One says: "The Methodist school classroom 
floors are not cemented and children face all sort of insect bites which 
sometimes make them cry their lungs out." <p>

Headmaster Ahima Boateng admits that a shortage of classrooms and teachers 
poses a big problem.<p>

There are no classrooms for the three final primary classes, although they are 
now under construction: "The children have been studying under the mango trees, 
and they will have to stay there until we finish the new building."<p>

He says that about 1.2 million cedis have been spent so far, with assistance 
coming from the parent-teachers' association and the local Methodist Church. <p>

The Methodist junior secondary school is reddening with age, and has no 
staffroom. A teacher says: "We have to sit around a big table on the verandah 
outside the school because the school hasn't got enough rooms for us." <p>

The junior secondary school run by the local authority also lacks classrooms. <p>

It is situated in a building used for tobacco  processing. Windows have been 
added to give light.<p>

"Accommodation for teachers has been a keen factor in the poor educational 
standard in the village," says Esther, a primary school teacher. "My landlady 
is ejecting me because I cannot afford to pay a 60,000 cedis advance for the 
room I am living in."<p>

Esther says that "since I am teaching their children, I think I deserve some 
kind of mercy from the village. I don't come from this place and if they don't 
want me to stay, I am prepared to leave for my village." <p>

The children themselves are aware of their plight and complain about 
conditions.  <p>

"When I was in primary four, for a whole term we had no teacher. We would go 
to school and come back home," recalls Mensah, a school-leaver. 
Books are scarce.<p>

Says Martha: "When I was in primary school, our teacher would always come in 
with the English textbook neatly covered to prevent it from getting dirty. We 
never saw the cover of the primary four English book."<p>

The junior secondary schools have been given a number of books under the 
government's library scheme. But a teacher moans: "Even the few children who 
are able to read are not interested in the books. No children borrow the 
books." <p>

<br><li><b><a href="../gemini_pix/may96_ghana.jpg">Gemini Graphic: Ghana</a> (24K)</b>
<li><b><a href="../gemini_pix/may96_offuman.jpg">Street plan: Offuman village in Ghana</a> (70K)</b><br clear=left><br>
<b>

Exchange rate: $1 = 1,608 cedis</b><p>
<hr>

About the Author: ISABELLA GYAU is a reporter with The Independent, Accra.


