<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - Ken Saro-Wiwa Sentenced to Death</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="#d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">[OneWorld News Service]<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>

<center><h2>Ken Saro-Wiwa and other leaders get death sentence</h2></center>
<p>

Nigerian activist Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other human rights campaigners have been sentenced to death.<p>

Five other defendants were acquitted of the murder charges.  The sentences are mandatory and carry no right of appeal.  Before executions can be carried out, however, the sentences must by approved by the Provisional Ruling Council.<p>

Saro-Wiwa is president of the Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni Peoples, which campaigned to protect the rights of the indigenous inhabitants of the oil-rich Ogoni region of south-eastern Nigeria.  The deputy president, Ledum Mitee, was acquitted.<p>

The Ogoni claim to be facing oppression both from Nigeria's military government and by multinational oil companies - including the Anglo-Dutch Shell Oil company.<p>

Saro-Wiwa and the other Ogoni were charged with murder after a mob riot left four moderate Ogoni leaders dead.  Saro-Wiwa and his fellow defendants were denied access to their families, doctors and legal counsel for eight months before being charged with the crimes.<p>

Supporters of Saro-Wiwa worldwide claim that the trial was flawed, and that the defendants were framed to suit the political aims of the military dictatorship.   Saro-Wiwa and the other accused were tried by a Special Military Tribunal.  <p>

The defence produced strong evidence that key prosecution witnesses were bribed to testify against Saro-Wiwa, but this was rejected by the judge.  The defence subsequently resigned, protesting that the outcome of the trial was clearly pre-determined.<p>

Ken Saro-Wiwa has proclaimed his innocence, and said that in life or death his ideas - about peaceful resistance and human rights - would remain.<p>

The British Government has condemned the trial as flawed and objected to the sentences.  Nigeria will also face strong criticism of its human rights record at the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in Auckland on November 10 - 13.<p>

<ul><li><b>For further information see <a href="../owbt/drilling_video.html">Transcript of The Drilling Fields documentary including background and interview with Saro-Wiwa</a>
<li>Press release from the <a href="partner_news/wk44_ogoni.html">Ogoni Community Association UK</a><b>

<li><a href="news_top_africa.html#nigeria">OneWorld Online's News Features on Nigeria</a></b></ul>
<hr><p>



