<html>
<head>
<title>Newsflash 1995 - Ken Saro-Wiwa Verdict Expected</title> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">OneWorld News Service

<p><b><font size=-1>This material has been provided by the Ogoni Community Association UK</font></b>
<center><h2>Ken Saro-Wiwa verdict <br>expected Tuesday 31 October</h2></center>
<p>

<br><b>The verdict in the murder trials of Ogoni leaders, including writer, environmentalist and 1996 Nobel Peace prize nominee Ken Saro-Wiwa, is expected by Tuesday the 31st of October 1995.  If found guilty they will be sentenced to death.  The sentences are mandatory and there is no right of appeal.</b><br><br><font size=-1>Photo ©Copyright:
 Catma Films.  Still taken from <a href="../../owbt/drilling_video.html">The Drilling Fields.</a></font><br clear=left><p>

Ken Wiwa, son of Ken Saro-Wiwa stated in London that: "We have every reason to expect that they will be found guilty and sentenced to death.  But we have long known that this trial is a politically motivated prosecution with very little basis in fact.  The verdict will be a judgement on the Nigerian regime and their contempt for justice, the rule of law, democracy and human rights.  The world is watching to see what will happen."<p>

Ken Saro-Wiwa and 15 other Ogonis were arrested in May 1994 following the deaths of four Ogoni chiefs during a mob riot.  Saro-Wiwa, who has been declared an <a href="../../amnesty/index.html">Amnesty International</a> Prisoner of Conscience along with Ledum Mitee and Dr Barinem Kiobel, were held in leg irons, denied access to their families, doctors and legal counsel for eight months before being charged and brought before a special Civil Disturbances Tribunal in February of 1995.<p>

The 500,000 strong Ogoni people of Nigeria are fighting for their survival under growing pressure from multinational oil companies and the Nigerian government.  An indigenous ethnic group, the Ogoni people reside on 400 square miles of oil-rich and fertile land in the Niger River Delta of southeastern Nigeria.<p>

Operating in partnership with the Nigerian authorities, several multinational oil companies, including the Anglo-Dutch Shell Oil company, have exported an estimated $30 billion worth of oil and gas from Ogoniland in the past 35 years.  In return the Ogonis have not seen any of the benefits of this oilfall, instead their environment has been destroyed - forever.<p>

In 1990 the Ogonis formed the Movement for the Survival of Ogoni People (MOSOP) to fight their economic and environmental exploitation in Nigeria.  In January 1993, 300,000 Ogonis came out in support of the movement and its ideals.  MOSOP declared Shell persona non grata until they regained the confidence of the community.  Soon after Shell claimed that they had withdrawn from Ogoni lands.<p>

In reaction to the peaceful Ogoni protests, the Nigerian military dictatorship sent a Military Task Force into Ogoni in April 1994 to "pacify and sanitise Ogoniland of the MOSOP virus" and to "allow Shell to return to the community".  Since the arrest of Saro-Wiwa in May 1994, many villages have been razed, women and children have been raped, more than 80,000 Ogonis displaced and more than 2000 people killed by the Task Force.<p>

The oppression in Ogonilands has been well documented in reports by Greenpeace, <a href="../../amnesty/index.html">Amnesty International,</a> the Commonwealth Human Rights Initiative, the Washington based <a href="gopher://gopher.humanrights.org:5000/11/int/hrw">Human Rights Watch</a> and the Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organisation (UNPO) at the Hague.<p>

Independent observers have found that the Special Military Tribunal falls short of internationally acceptable legal standards.  British lawyer Michael Birnbaum QC, who attended court proceedings and has compiled a comprehensive report for Article XIX, reported that "there were grave doubts as to the legality and fairness of the proposed trial".<p>

After Justice Auta, the Chairman of the Tribunal, rejected defence evidence of the bribing of two former prosecution witnesses to testify against Saro-Wiwa, the defence resigned.  They felt that the outcome of the trial was obviously pre-determined.<p>

Saro-Wiwa declined any further legal assistance in his defence and instead read a final statement to the Tribunal last week:<p>

"I predict a denoument of the riddle of the Niger delta will soon come.  The agenda is being set at this trial.  Whether the peaceful ways I have favoured will prevail depends on what the oppressor decides, what signals it sends out  to the waiting public.<p>

<b>In my innocence of the false charges I face here, in my utter conviction, I call upon the Ogoni people, the peoples of the Niger delta, and the oppressed ethnic minorities of Nigeria to stand up now and fight fearlessly and peacefully for their rights.  History is on their side, God is on their side."</b><p>

<ul><br><b><a href="../../owbt/drilling_video.html">Transcript of The Drilling Fields documentary<br> including background and interview with Saro-Wiwa</a><br clear=left><p> </b></ul><i> Catma Films have produced a sequel to The Drilling Fields, also using footage shot in secret by the Ogoni people.  It was screened on Channel 4, 4 May 1995.  An updated version will be shown on Thursday 1 November<p></i><b><ul>

<li>See also: <a href="../africa/nigeria.html">OneWorld Online's News Features on Nigeria</a></b></ul>
<hr><p>


For further information, please contact:<p>

<b>Lazarus Tamana, President of the Ogoni Community Association UK<br>
or Ken Wiwa<p>

at Tel: + 44 (0) 181 563 8614<br>
Mobile: + 44 (0) 956 425972<br>
Fax: + 44 (0) 181 563 8615<p>

