<head>

<title>ALGERIA: AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL CONDEMNS MASSACRES OF

CIVILIANS</title> 

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff"> 

<img src="../amnesty_pix/amnesty_logo.gif">

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a

href="../amnesty.html">Amnesty International</a></i>

<hr>

<p>

<h3>ALGERIA: AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL CONDEMNS MASSACRES OF

CIVILIANS</h3>

<p>

<h4>12 FEBRUARY 1997</h4>

<p>

Amnesty International condemns in the strongest terms the massacres of 
civilians which continue

to

be committed daily in Algeria.  The organisation calls on all those 
involved in the conflict to put

an

immediate end to the targeting of civilians.

<p>

     In the past weeks, hundreds of people have been shot dead, 
slaughtered, decapitated or

mutilated in targeted attacks.  Others have been killed and blown to 
pieces in bomb explosions

in

public places.  Among the victims were men, women and children, including 
relatives of

members

of the security forces and of government-backed militias, as well as 
relatives of members of

armed

groups defined as &quot;Islamic&quot; groups.

<p>

     Armed groups such as the <I>Groupe Islamique Arm&eacute;</I> (Armed 
Islamic

Group), GIA, or the <I>Front Islamique pour le Djihad Arm­</I> (Islamic 
Front for the Armed

Jihad), FIDA, which have claimed murders and attacks, continue to issue 
death threats against

civilians.

<p>

     &quot;Such atrocities cannot be justified under any circumstances.  
Those responsible for

such crimes continue to show their utmost contempt for the respect for 
human life,&quot;

Amnesty

International said. 

<p>

     The murders and bloody attacks of these past few weeks have taken 
place in the context of

the increased level of violence of the last three months.  However, while 
massacres and

explosions

form part of a terrifying daily reality, the Algerian authorities 
continue to claim that there is only

&quot;residual violence&quot;.

<p>

     The civilian population, especially in rural and isolated areas, 
often does not benefit from

any protection from the security services, who have been replaced in 
several regions by civilian

militias armed by the state.  Thus, it is often left to the civilian 
population, which is more and

more

vulnerable to attacks by armed groups, to find ways of protecting 
themselves and to take the law

into their own hands.

<p>

     The censorship of information defined as 
&quot;security-related&quot; and the restrictions

imposed on the media makes it impossible for the Algerian and 
international press to investigate

and freely inform the public.   Therefore, massacres go unreported and 
figures given by official

sources for the number of victims are often much lower than in reality.

<p>

     &quot;Concrete measures must urgently be taken to protect the 
civilian population.  

Thorough and transparent investigations must be carried out so as to 
ensure that those

responsible

for these atrocities are brought to justice,&quot; Amnesty International 
said.

<p>

     &quot;This is the responsibility and the duty of the Algerian 
authorities, but also of the

international community, which to date continues to ignore the plight of 
the civilian population in

Algeria,&quot; added the organisation.

<P><HR>

If you are a UK based journalist and require further information please 
call the AIUK Press

Office on 0171 814 6248 or e-mail 

<br>

<a href="mailto:abarnes@amnesty.org.uk">abarnes@amnesty.org.uk</a>

<br>

<a href="mailto:skobrin@amnesty.org.uk">skobrin@amnesty.org.uk</a>

<P>

If you are reading this page within the UK and require further 
information or more information 

about AIUK contact the AIUK Information Office on 0171 814 6200 or 
e-mail<BR>

<a href="mailto:info@amnesty.org.uk">info@amnesty.org.uk</a>

<P>

If you are reading this page outside of the UK and require further 
information about Amnesty,

please contact your <a 
href="http://www.amnesty.org/aisect/index.html">local section</a> or

the <a href="http://www.amnesty.org/">International Secretariat </a> of

Amnesty International.



<p>



