<html>
<head>
<title>OXFAM UK/I BRIEFING PAPER ON THE PROPOSED NEW ILO CONVENTION ON HOME-WORKING</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../oxfam.html">  Oxfam</a></i>
<hr>

<center>
<h1>Oxfam UK/I Briefing paper on the proposed new ILO convention on home-working</h1></center>

<li>See also Oxfam Press Release on June 20 - <b><a href="../news/home_june20.html">ILO Members Take Historic Decision to Benefit the World's Homeworkers.</a></b><p>



<h3>Introduction</h3>

According to the ILO, the International Labour Organisation, <i>homeworking is a primary growing source of income for a great number of workers throughout the world, and is on the increase in many countries.  </i>home working can offer new sources of employment and provide an opportunity for workers to balance employment and family responsibilities. It gives employers greater flexibility to meet rapidly changing markets and can make an important contribution to a country's export earnings and GNP. <br><p>

However, it also brings serious problems. The ambivalent employment status of homeworkers, their isolation, and weak bargaining position often leads to abuse. Homeworkers are often unprotected by employment legislation or collective bargaining agreements and therefore denied many of the most basic employment rights enjoyed by other workers. In Oxfam's experience they rank among some of the least protected, most vulnerable, and badly paid groups of workers. For example, according to an ILO study, "in Latin America piece-rates paid to homeworkers in urban areas are less than those paid in factories... and those doing homework in rural areas fall to the very bottom of the wage scale".  Not only do these conditions cause great personal suffering they also incur wider social and economic costs which are examined in this briefing. <br><p>

The low pay and poor conditions of homeworkers is of immediate concern to Oxfam UK/I's Clothes Campaign, which is aimed at improving working conditions in the garment industry, where homeworking is widespread. Homeworking is also an important focus of Oxfam's advocacy work with governments, the IMF, and World Bank to improve employment protection for vulnerable and marginalised groups of low paid workers. Oxfam UK/I supports homeworking groups in various sectors and countries around the world:  SEWA (The Self Employed Women's Association) in India; a recently formed organisation in South Africa called SEWU (the Self-Employed Women's Union); the National Homework Group in the UK; sweat-shop workers and homeworkers in the garment and shoe sector in Chile; NGOs working on the issue in Peru. Other members of the Oxfam International family also have contacts with organisations working with these groups in their own countries.<br><p>

Oxfam UK/I is urging government and employer delegations to support the proposal for a new ILO Convention and Recommendation on Homework at the next ILO Conference (General Assembly) in June 1996.  It believes that the proposed Convention offers a useful middle way between regulating homeworkers out of existence, or leaving them at the mercy of a global economy which confines them to low pay and poor conditions. A vote in favour would have a positive impact on the living and working conditions of millions of homeworkers in countries all over the world. <br><p>
<h3>Who are homeworkers ? </h3>

There are many different definitions of the term homework.  The new Convention is aimed at those who carry out paid work in their own home and who are dependent on an outside employer or sub-contractor for the supply of their work; rather than the genuinely self-employed, independent workers or small businesses who are largely in control of their own work.<br><p>
The definition of homework in the proposed ILO Convention is: work carried out by a person for remuneration in his or her home or in other premises of his or her own choice, other than the workplace of the employer, which results in a product or service as specified by the employer, irrespective of who provides the equipment, materials or other inputs used, as long as this person does not have the degree of autonomy and of economic independence necessary to be considered an independent worker under national laws, regulations or court decisions. <br><p>
According to HomeNet International, an International Network of Homeworkers, it is often groups who face discrimination in the wider labour market - women, people with disabilities, people from ethnic minorities, or migrant workers - who end up working from home. The vast majority of homeworkers globally are women - at least 80 percent according to the ILO - many of whom are caught between the urgent need for work and the need to be at home to look after their children. Contrary to common perception, most surveys reveal that the majority choose homeworking because of their urgent need for money, and generally use the income for essential items rather than 'pin' money.<br><p>
According to HomeNet International, homework is found in many different forms,  in northern and southern countries, in urban and rural areas, and in traditional and modern sectors. It is widespread in some industrial sectors especially in textiles and garments. It is also found in the electronic, leather, and car industries.  Homework in the rural sector is also common and may involve processing agricultural or forest produce; packing and cleaning fruit and vegetables; and processing fish products. It is also increasingly common in the service sector, and the rapidly evolving forms of new technology has also increased teleworking from home.<br><p>
<h3>Homeworking - a growing phenomena</h3>

Official government statistics seldom include data on sub-contracting, home-based workers, or businesses which are not legally registered. They also often fail to distinguish between the genuinely self-employed and those dependent on others for their work. However, evidence from household surveys conducted by the ILO, homeworking groups, academics and others, suggest that homeworking is widespread, and growing, in parts of Asia, Latin America, Europe (including the UK), North America, Australia, and parts of Africa. From Oxfam's own contacts with homeworking groups it is apparent that some have a detailed analysis of the prevalence and conditions of homework.<br><p>
This increase in homework, should be understood in the context of a rapidly changing world economy and the wider growth of flexible working practices, such as sub-contracting (whether from small businesses, workshops or homeworkers), temporary, part-time and casual work. Sub-contracting - either at home or overseas - has become an important way for companies to maintain competitiveness, ensure flexibility and cut labour costs in the face of intensified international competition arising from trade and investment liberalisation and rapidly changing patterns of consumer demand. <br><p>
According to the ILO's 1995 World Employment Report there was a pronounced growth in sub-contracting by large firms to small firms in both the formal and informal sectors during the 1980s in Latin America. Sub-contracting is particularly common in labour-intensive industries such as the garment industry, which has traditionally employed the greatest number of homeworkers. <br><p>
Many homeworkers are now found at the end of a long sub-contracting chain through which retailers or large manufacturers sub-contract to a myriad of smaller factories, businesses, and homeworkers either at home or overseas. Although the retailers may make the biggest profits, each contractor in the chain receives a commission, however small. This means that the homeworker may receive only a fraction of the final price.   A baby's dress, for example, might sell for around $15 in a department store in North America, or Western Europe, but the local producer who made it may get less than 10 cents. <br><p>
As many businesses and home-based workers are classed as self-employed or are not registered at all, sub-contracting allows companies to cut labour costs by bypassing existing labour regulations and collective bargaining agreements. It means they can pay lower wages, avoid paying employers contributions, benefits and taxes. Employers can also reduce overheads as workers bear many of the costs of heating or equipment  Sub-contracting also allows companies to maintain flexibility in the face of fast-changing global markets, as homeworkers can be 'hired and fired' easily. Workers who complain about conditions can be easily laid off. In sum, it passes many of the risks of production onto the homeworkers.<br><p>
Developments in transport, new technology, and communications have also facilitated the spread of sub-contracting. In the garment industry in Europe, for example, some companies have been able to combine the latest technology at the retail or final assembly stage, with a cheap and flexible work-force further down the production chain to assemble, process, and pack products. The new technology is especially important in monitoring sales and offers companies the "advantage" of rapid response to fast-changing life-style and niche markets. The adoption of modern satellite communications means that design can be carried out near the market and instructions for cutting can be sent anywhere in the world in minutes. Despite this, sub-contracting from their home countries has become increasingly attractive to some Northern based companies because it combines the advantage of "Third World" wage rates and shorter delivery runs.<br><p>
<h3>4.	The Case for a new ILO Convention on Homework </h3>

<h3>What is the Convention ?</h3>

The proposed Convention is based on a broad definition of homework which includes many homeworkers who have an indirect or disguised employment relationship. It aims at promoting :<br><p>
equality of treatment with wage-earners, in particular in relation to the right to organise, protection against discrimination in employment, occupational health and safety provisions, in remuneration, in statutory social security protection, access to training, minimum age for admission to employment, and maternity benefits<br><p>

<ul type=circle>
<li>the inclusion of homeworkers in the collection of basic labour statistics

<li>the regulation of intermediaries 

<li>the establishment of systems of inspection
</ul>
The proposed complementary Recommendation examines each of the above points in greater detail, gives advice to employers and intermediaries on employment practice, registration, and supervision of workers,  and also includes guidelines on programmes to support and train homeworkers, which would aid their organisation.  <br><p>


The Convention is highly unusual for the ILO, and particularly important, as conventions for  the protection of unorganised sector workers have rarely been seen in the ILO.  It is an important achievement for the invisible workforce of homeworkers and their organisations that the question of international regulation has finally been put on the agenda. This in large part reflects the efforts of SEWA and HomeNet, with the support of many trade unions. At SEWA's urging, the International Confederation of Trade Unions (ICFTU) adopted a resolution asking the ILO to pass a convention for the protection of homeworkers.  The ICFTU has consistently followed up the issue with the ILO and in 1995 the Governing Body of the ILO finally agreed that 'Homework' should be the subject of a new Convention, backed up by a more detailed Recommendation. (If a Convention is approved, it then has to be ratified by individual governments and converted into national laws. It is stronger than a Recommendation, which is voluntary and merely provides policy guidelines.)<br><p>


Last year the ILO tripartite Committee on Homework voted in favour of a Convention and by a narrow majority. Most employers were against a Convention and a Recommendation, preferring a recommendation only. Trade unions were and are solidly in favour of both the Convention and Recommendation. Government opinions were mixed.<br><p>


The proposed text of the Convention and Recommendation will be discussed and amended in detail in the Homework Committee in the ILO Conference in June 1996, and then voted on in the plenary  (where all members of the ILO vote). A two-thirds majority will be needed in the plenary session to approve the Convention. Given the voting pattern in the Homework committee last year, Governments which have two votes each will play the deciding role. <br><p>


<h3>Employment status of homeworkers</h3>

The proponents of the new convention argue that many homeworkers are not in fact self-employed or independent, but are dependent workers like employees, and should therefore be entitled to employment and social protection similar to that of normal wage-earners. For example, a survey published by the UK National Group on Homework in 1994, Home Truths,  discovered that 47 percent of the homeworkers interviewed thought that their employers considered them as self-employed and yet 63 percent would have preferred to be treated as employees. Supporters of the Convention argue that homeworkers should be treated as employees unless they genuinely want to be considered as self-employed and fit the relevant criteria for independent workers defined by national law, regulations or court decisions.<br><p>


According to the representative of the ILO Director General to the 1995 Homework committee, very few ILO instruments make any specific reference to homework. While some instruments cover all workers without exception, thereby including homeworkers, others permit the exclusion of certain categories of workers or limit their scope to workers in enterprises or establishments. Similarly, national legislation may fail to adequately protect homeworkers - either remaining silent or excluding them from some or all of its provisions. An ILO survey of 150 countries found that only 18 had specific homework legislation, though another 17 had a section on homework in their labour codes.   <br><p>


The main problem arising from these omissions is that unless homeworkers are specifically mentioned in legislation, they are usually excluded from protection in practice. Employers often do not put anything in writing to homeworkers and in the minority of cases where they do, they specify that the homeworker is self-employed. The onus therefore rests on the homeworker to prove his or her status as an employee, which often results in loss of employment. Their ambiguous employment status leaves them highly vulnerable to exploitation and abuse, and effectively denies them the rights enjoyed by other workers. This results in low pay, lack of basic employment rights, insecurity, and health and safety problems.  <br><p>


The Conventions' proponents argue that it is important to address this problem explicitly and systematically by setting minimum standards for the protection of dependent homeworkers which take account of  their special characteristics. The importance of standard-setting for homeworkers has been echoed in recent declarations from the Social Summit and Beijing Conference on Women. For example, the Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action of November 1995 asked governments to: Adopt policies to ensure the appropriate protection of labour laws and social security benefits for part-time, temporary, seasonal and homebased workers.<br><p>


(It is important to remember, however, that in the South, own-account or independent producers are often little better off than dependent homeworkers having limited access to credit, training and markets. Often as a small producer loses control over his or her market or raw material she becomes a piece rate worker.  Food processing and weaving are two examples of own-account workers whose status as small independent producers is being undermined and who are gradually losing control over their markets. However, not all of them will wish to be considered as workers and may prefer to try and maintain their status as self-employed. It is equally important that appropriate government measures are adopted to help these groups for example by assistance with credit, training, and marketing).<br><p>


<h3>The social costs of homework</h3>


Although the home-based nature of the work may offer some advantages to women, it also exacts a high human and social cost. Whether they sew garments in England, make toys in New York, weave silk in Thailand or roll bidis (cigarettes) in India, their problems remain in many ways similar. An ILO report states that: 'surveys in industrialised and developing countries have revealed a surprisingly similar catalogue of problems associated with homeworking. They include very low wages, often below legal minima where they exist; anti-social working hours; health and safety problems, often affecting the whole family of the homeworker; delays in payment, and on occasion, non-payment of wages; misinformation from employers about homeworkers "legal rights and status, and evasion of such regulations as may exist; and the threat of withdrawal of work used as a means to intimidate homeworkers and prevent them claiming their rights " .<br><p>


Ela Bhatt, the General Secretary of SEWA, sums up the situation: " Homeworkers are particularly vulnerable to unfair terms of employment and working conditions. Usually they are not considered as regular employees and have no job security, have irregular incomes and no career prospects. Their wages are far lower than those of other workers doing comparable work within the undertaking. The piece-rate method of remuneration commonly applied to homeworkers obliges many of them to work very long hours in order to gain a decent income. Often homeworkers have to work under conditions that present health and safety risks or dangers for themselves and their families and are not fully informed of possible consequences. Almost invariably they have no access to health benefits or social security".<br><p>


Studies also report that although not directly employed, children may be forced to work to help their parents because of low wages and the high pressure of tight deadlines. A recent survey of homebased workers in the incense industry in India showed that 43% of children in the surveyed families were involved in producing incense sticks due to economic necessity.<br><p>


The unreasonably low wages and benefits resulting from the unregulated use of homeworking exerts downward pressure on the wages and conditions of other workers in the industry and other countries.<p>


<h3>The economic costs of homework</h3>


One of the main concerns of employers delegations opposed to the convention, is that regulation of homework will reduce growth, cost jobs and drive workers into the black economy. In Oxfam's view the evidence does not support this overly negative view of regulation.<br><p>

For example, recent research on OECD countries suggests that lower employment protection increases hiring thereby reducing long-term unemployment, but also increases firing and thereby increases short-term unemployment - the first (good effect) is almost offset by the second (bad) one so that the national gains from flexibility are small. The research also indicates that employment taxes do not appear to have any long-term effect on unemployment and are borne entirely by labour (ie increases in non-wage costs are offset by lower wages), although there may be substantial short-run effects. <br><p>


Similarly, recent research on minimum wage legislation does not show significant long term job losses. Recent increases in the minimum wage in Chile in the early 1990s played an important role in reducing poverty alongside rapid growth and low levels of official unemployment. Evidence from the US suggests that the minimum wage has not had a significant effect on employment.  Countries such as Colombia and Costa Rica, which maintained minimum wage levels in the 1980s, in contrast to many other countries in Latin America where minimum wages fell significantly, achieved some of the fastest levels of growth in Latin America. <br><p>

The fact that many home-based workers and small businesses are in fact linked to large successful formal-sector companies and multinationals by sub-contracting relations, would imply that labour rights can be effectively extended to these groups without incurring the kind of enforcement difficulties or jobs losses which is feared in genuinely independent small or informal businesses . In so far as there is a short-term trade-off between improved employment standards and jobs because of company relocation this could be lessened by the introduction of core labour standards into international trading agreements.<br><p>

Furthermore, in Oxfam's view, measures to promote cheap and flexible labour markets can be economically inefficient and potentially self-defeating. While it is true that homework can create important new sources of  jobs in the short term, if it remains unregulated it can actually hinder a country's long-term economic expansion<br><p>

The ILO has pointed out that productivity will be impaired if wages and conditions fall below 'efficiency levels' due to high turnover, low commitment and poor health. Oxfam research on Chile shows how legislation which facilitates flexible labour markets, including sub-contracting, reduces the incentives for companies to train workers, to invest in new technologies or to improve products. Without such measure countries may not be able to move to a second phase of export based on higher value added products, rather than cheap labour. <br><p>

Low wages can also depress domestic demand, undermining growth prospects and deepening recession. The World Bank has acknowledged that wage reductions were one of the reasons for the failure of Bolivia's adjustment programme in the 1980s. <br><p>
Unregulated homework may also reduce tax government revenue either because their earnings are below the tax threshold or because they are unregistered. Growing inequality and social unrest associated with poorly regulated labour markets is also bad for growth.<br><p>

<h3>Oxfam's recommendations</h3>

Along with homeworkers, trade unions and other groups around the world Oxfam is urging governments, and employers' delegations, to vote in favour of the both the proposed new ILO Convention and Recommendation on Homeworking in their current form at the ILO Conference in June 1996. <br><p>

Oxfam UK/I believes that the rapid spread of homeworking, inadequate coverage in existing conventions and national legislation, the appalling employment conditions of many homeworkers, and the associated wider social and economic costs, point to the need for the establishment of an international core of minimum labour standards. This is not a case of introducing new onerous regulation but rather ensuring that employment rights enshrined in existing international conventions, cover all categories of workers as originally intended.<br><p>


Oxfam believes that such measures would help to reduce the human, social and economic costs associated with homework. The Convention is sufficiently broad and flexible to allow signatory countries to develop policies appropriate to the types and specific characteristics of homework within that country. It provides a basic definition of homeworking but allows countries sufficient flexibility to take account of criteria under national law which would distinguish homeworkers from truly independent workers. Rather than driving homework further underground, Oxfam believes that it will provide homeworkers with the confidence to register and become legal.<br><p>


The setting of minimum standards is only one means among others to improve conditions for homeworkers.  The complementary Recommendation provides important policy guidance on other ways for governments to help homeworkers, whether dependent or own account workers. The generation of alternative employment and the provision of child care is also important to help increase the choices available to women and to reduce their dependence on poor employers.<br><p>


Approving the convention is, of course, only the first step. It will then need to be ratified by governments and translated into national legislation, according to local social and economic conditions. Oxfam believes that the Convention will offer an important lever for homeworkers to exert pressure on Governments and employers to ensure that they receive a living wage and just employment conditions.<br><p>


Ruth Mayne, Oxfam UK/I Policy Department.<br>


HomeNet produces a regular newsletter and has contact addresses in South Asia, South East Asia, Africa, Americas, Europe. The European address is HomeNet, Office 26, 30-38 Dock Street, Leeds LS10 1JF, UK Tel 44 112 270 1119. Fax 44 113 2277 3296. The UK National Group on Homework can also be contacted at this address.<br><p>







PAGE  <br>
<p>


PAGE  8<br><p>




The ILO,  a specialist agency of the United Nations, is the most significant multilateral mechanism for improving and monitoring labour standards.  There are now 170 countries who are members  of the ILO, each entitled to send four delegates to its annual decision-making conference; two government representatives, one representative of employers, and one of employees, reflecting it's unique tripartite structure. <br><p>

 Provisional Record, 82nd Session, Geneva 1995, Fifth Item on Homework, Report of the Committee on Homework, ILO, Geneva, 1995<br>

