<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

The Week in Europe, 19 December 1996</h2>

<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>

<p>

Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>

</center>

<hr>

<P>

A week ago the President of the European Commission, Jacques Santer and the

Irish Prime Minister, John Bruton, in his capacity as the current President

of the European Union, met with US President, Bill Clinton in Washington.

The meeting was the most recent of a semi-annual series of summits between

the EU and US on matters of common concern.

<p>

The content of the meeting ranged from the problems of genetically modified

maize, NATO enlargement and Cuba, to the humanitarian crisis in Zaire. The

wide range of issues discussed and some of the differences that emerged

indicated clearly the significant changes that have taken place in the

EU/US relationship over the past ten years. As a meeting between equals it

was a far cry from previous bilateral discussions with certain EU member

states that characterised the post war special relationship.

<p>

This same process of change has been observable in the ways in which Europe

and the US now relate to the Caribbean. Traditionally the UK, the US and

Canada sought to co-ordinate their interests in the Caribbean through

regular discussions on matters of mutual interest. More recently this

dialogue has taken place in a North Atlantic framework and in the context

of economic development, within the Caribbean Group of Economic

Co-operation and Development (CGCED) of the World Bank.

<p>

But as the trans-Atlantic debate on the Caribbean has widened to embrace an

increasingly powerful European Union, achieving the consensus of the past

has become more difficult. Today the EU/US debate on the Caribbean is

increasingly characterised by a growing number of differences.

<p>

To a large extent the fundamental difference arises because the US Congress

- while paying some heed to an administration that has genuinely sought

multilateral solutions to international problems - is more inclined to the

belief that its role is to insist on unilateral action that puts America

and American interests first.

<p>

At their most obvious present EU/US differences over the Caribbean are over

Cuba and how to encourage change there. While the EU and US both seek a

transition to democracy and a market oriented economy in that nation, the

EU visualises that this can be encouraged through progressive engagement

while the US seeks change through isolation and coercion.

<p>

But beyond this singular issue and beneath the surface there are much

broader matters which have the capacity to create divisions between the US

and Europe which should worry the Caribbean.

<p>

Earlier this year in Europe at the preparatory meetings for the CGCED

meetings in Washington at which aid donors sought to co-ordinate policy

towards the region, new tensions began to emerge. At that meeting EC

officials were angered by the insistence of US officials on introducing new

political conditionalities. In particular they objected to US attempts to

determine the regional development agenda noting that, Haiti apart, the US

had virtually ceased to be a significant aid donor in the Caribbean. EC

officials observed that the US approach ignored the fact that the EU was

the single largest regional donor or had constructed its regional

relationships on the basis of partnership and consensus.

<p>

Further tensions are now in the making as the US pursues its hemispheric

agenda through the creation of a Free Trade Area of the Americas by 2005.

While this date is probably unrealistic, the underlying US policy of "our

hemisphere" ignores the fact that multilateral and bi-lateral ties between

the EU and the Caribbean and Latin America have become increasingly

significant.

<p>

These differences in approach and style may come to a head in the next four

years over the question of trade reciprocity. The EU is likely to pursue an

approach post Lom&#233; that results in a gradual phase out of preference and

the introduction over time of full reciprocity along lines similar to those

being negotiated at present with South Africa. The US, for its part,

appears from the steps it has already taken, to be arguing for full

reciprocity within the Americas, by 2005 on its terms alone. The difference

in approach is at its most stark in relation to small island states such as

those in the OECS. The concept of special and differential treatment is

well understood in Europe but not it would seem on Capitol Hill.

<p>

Many of these issues will become public in a Caribbean context as the

negotiations for a post Lom&#233; agreement proceed and the US makes its views

known on a special EU/Caribbean relationship. Other matters such as

different EU and US approaches on narcotics related issues are already

apparent.

<p>

In this latter context, Caricom heads of government agreed last week to

seek an early meeting with the US President to discuss their concern about

the ways in which "unacceptable methods of persuasion" were being used by

the US to prosecute the war on the narcotics traffickers. Thankfully this

important but narrow agenda was widened in the final communiqui to include

a desire for discussions with Mr Clinton and his new team on trade,

economic development and problems of security.

<p>

How the US reacts, the level at which such a meeting takes place and the

time allotted will all indicate whether the US takes seriously the region's

concerns. The response, or lack of it, may well turn the present

anti-American sentiment common throughout the region into a desire for a

deeper relationship with Europe. 

<p>

But this may be misplaced as few European nations let alone the EU as a

body would be prepared to engage further with a region regarded by most

member states as marginal. Rather there is a real need to understand what

Europe can and cannot do and where and why its approach is different to the

US. Many Caribbean economies are still underwritten by European preference,

aid or concessional funding because of an enduring sense of partnership.

But this interest is not reciprocated in levels of Caribbean contact other

than in Brussels or London. This column will look next year at how

individual EU member states and the Commission regard the Caribbean region.

But this is a matter that should have been addressed long ago in the region

if partnership is not to turn into self interest or benign indifference on

the part of Europe and come to parallel the attitude of the US.

<p>

But Europe apart, the real long term answer must be a change in US policy.

As Barbados's Prime Minister, Owen Arthur, said at the Miami Conference on

the Caribbean "The way forward is to build a new partnership grounded in

the new realities.... The end of the cold war offers an unprecedented

opportunity to forge a special relationship with the Caribbean...... based

on a coherent strategy..... designed to facilitate the Caribbean's own

efforts at building prosperous and stable societies...".

<p>

A new partnership is a message that is good for both Europe and the United

States.

<p>

<HR>

