<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

The Week in Europe, 12 December 1996</h2>

<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>

<p>

Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>

</center>

<hr>

<P>

No one in the Caribbean should under-estimate the turmoil that will arise

in the coming months in Europe over the agreement presently being sought to

achieve an EU single currency and monetary union.

<p>

Although there are some signs that an agreement might be reached at the

Dublin summit of EU heads of government, it is not clear what shape this

will take or whether it will be endorsed by all member states. The

divisions are so wide-ranging that it is suggested that if Britain, for

electoral reasons, rejects present proposals being advocated by Germany,

that nation, together with France, may seek to establish a "two speed"

Europe. This scenario would involve a group consisting of perhaps half the

EU' s member states, attempting to force the pace of integration by

establishing an inner core of nations that leaves out countries, such as

Britain, that are reluctant to join the monetary union in 1998.

<p>

Although the issues associated with this process are complex and technical

they are already impacting in a very political way. In Spain and Greece

there have been widespread demonstrations from workers not prepared to

accept the cuts in subsidies and pay required if those nations are to

reduce deficits to meet the criteria necessary for monetary union. In

Britain and Denmark there is growing public alarm over the implied threat

to sovereignty posed by the likelihood that the most economically powerful

members of the EU will be able, once monetary union is in place, to

determine economic policy without reference to individual parliaments. In

Belgium and France there is concern that the proposed fines for any nation

that runs up excessive deficits after monetary union might be too punitive

and worsen economic problems. And beyond all of this there is a fear that

it would be Germany that would dictate future EU economic policy through a

European central bank, leaving national governments powerless to tackle

very key issues such as unemployment.

<p>

In short, the debate is really about whether old concepts of nation states

and sovereignty can endure in a world moving to ever larger trading blocs,

reciprocity, and globalisation.

<p>

What is being seen in the parliaments and streets of Europe' s capitals are

perhaps the first developed world protests against this process. Readers in

the Caribbean may smile wryly at this as the former colonial powers come to

understand what much of the region has learnt the hard way through the IMF

or changes in, for example, the removal of Commonwealth preference. The

message is the same: economic or political influence exercised by

relatively few powerful nations can impact adversely and alarmingly quickly

on the economic, social and political stability of nations sometimes not

consulted and often remote from the decision-making body.

<p>

This lesson has again been made clear in the Caribbean context of rice. Two

weeks ago it seemed that the Irish Presidency of the EU had established a

compromise acceptable to all member states bar one on the much-debated

trade aspects of the EU and the Overseas Countries and Territories (OCT)

agreement which covers in part the Netherlands Antilles and the British

Dependent Territories in the Caribbean. Under this OCT/EU relationship,

which forms part of the Lom&#233; Convention, products from the ACP which

undergo certain transformation in the OCT enter Europe quota- and

duty-free. This facility was first used by Guyana and Suriname for rice

and, just as intended, it has had a developmental effect in the OCT and in

the ACP nations concerned. However, more recently this route has begun to

be used for sugar from the Dominican Republic, dairy products, and a range

of other sensitive items.

<p>

Faced with this - and subject to a discussion on numbers - the EC, all but

one member state, and the ACP rice producers accepted a system would have

to be established that set quotas on specific products exported to Europe

in this manner. But the solution required unanimity and the Dutch, for

reasons that are no longer clear, were not prepared to work with other

member states on an acceptable compromise. To the anger of all other EU

nations, Dutch intransigence in the General Affairs Council meeting led to

the issue remaining unresolved. 

<p>

If this had simply resulted in the status quo prevailing., ACP producers

could have slept, if not easily, then without too much discomfort. But

what, this time around, has materially changed the circumstances is a

parallel action by Italy to introduce safeguard measures to halt rice

shipments from the ACP via the OCT. Although the Italian position was

probably tactical initially with the objective of encouraging Dutch

agreement in the General Affairs Council, the absence of a compromise now

means that in a matter of weeks ACP rice may no longer be able to use the

OCT route.

<p>

No doubt the Dutch will appeal to the European Court, but that is of little

help to the rice farmers and millers in the ACP or those involved in

processing in those OCTs that only process rice. The ACP producers are

mobilising to defend their interests and the issue is far from over.

<p>

Whether it is in Europe or the Caribbean, it appears that economic

independence will become ever-less possible as globalisation accelerates.

As I suggested some weeks ago, the  questions this raises for governments

and for sovereignty need to be answered soon if the Caribbean is to find a

stable place for itself in an independent world. 

<p>

<HR>

<H6><i>Updated on December 18, 1996</i><p>

