<html>

<header>

<title>Uncertainty Surrounds Future of the Lom&#233; Convention</title>

</header>

<hr>

<H2><center><A HREF = "../index.html"></a><p>

Uncertainty Surrounds Future of the Lom&#233; Convention</h2>

<p>

<h4>Full text of an article from the <i>ECDPM Programme Highlights 1996</i>: pages 4-5</h4>

</center>

<hr>

<p>

Slowly the machinery to evaluate the Lom&#233; Convention has begun to roll. The burning questions

are whether there is a future for the Convention, and what shape it will take.

<p>

The European Commission is working on a new policy paper and developing countries are worried.

Despite all the debate however, there is a suspicion that the post 1999 scenario may change very  little.

To some observers, re-designing European development cooperation may be far more difficult than leaving

it more or less as it is.

<p>

The Lom&#233; Convention - a partnership between 70 countries in Africa, the Caribbean

and the Pacific (ACP), and the European Union - encompasses trade and aid. Created in

1975, no-one is certain whether it will be around after its 25th birthday in the year 2000.

<p>

When ECDPM began calling on  ACP states to begin preparations for a follow-up to the

Lom&#233; Convention, the Centre received irritated and sometimes even angry reactions.

Officials were tired after the tough negotiations on the Lom&#233; IV mid-term review and

did not want to hear the bad news that their task was far from over. In recent months

however, the climate has changed.

<p>

During the past year, ECDPM has been raising awareness among ACP interest groups,

encouraging them to critically evaluate and discuss the future of the Lom&#233;

Convention. According to Louk de la Rive Box, ECDPM Director, the "main conclusion is

a paradox. ACP states worry about their relationship with Europe but there is a complete

ignorance about Lom&#233;."

<p>

<h3>A mystery for most people</h3>



This conclusion is  based on extensive consultations by ECDPM staff with people in all the

ACP regions. ECDPM's Geert Laporte feels that, apart from a tiny circle of government

officials, the Convention remains an "absolute mystery" in ACP countries.

<p>

This lack of awareness is partly due to the way in which Lom&#233; resources are managed

at the country level -- a national authorising officer in each ACP country, usually a senior

government official, oversees and manages Lom&#233; activities. It is also due to the view,

in Brussels and in ACP capitals, that Lom&#233; is a matter for governments.

<p>

In this regard, Box suggests that a "criticism of the Commission could be that it did not

engage other interest groups, like Chambers of Commerce, soon enough into the process."

He is also critical of ACP governments that have done little to create a supportive

constituency for Lom&#233; in their countries. With such a small group involved in the

Convention, it is hardly surprising that public awareness is so low.

<p>

Awareness of the Convention is one thing, its utilisation is another. The convention is very

complex and contains more than 369 articles and a series of protocols written in a very

officialese style. "It is already difficult for a bureaucrat, working with it daily, to understand

Lom&#233;. Let alone ACP officials who are underpaid and not motivated," explains

Laporte.

<p>

The Centre hopes to "feed the debate by providing information, so when in 1998 the

negotiations on the future of Lom&#233; start, the parties know what the difficulties are.

Our aim is to create a real debate about the future of Lom&#233;." says de la Rive Box. "It

is a unique convention and was very progressive when it was developed in the seventies. But

it is not used adequately."

<p>

<h3>An effective instrument?</h3>



Much of the debate in Europe is on the supposed ineffectiveness of EU development aid.

While complete evaluations have not yet taken place, studies show that EU aid performs no

worse than other donors, says Laporte. 

<p>

The Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs doesn't yet have a complete picture of the results from

Lom&#233;. Government official Ernst Noorman, working on EC affairs at the department

of international cooperation, points to a decision last year by European ministers of

development cooperation to evaluate EU aid programmes. "That's a big point. Though there

was a lot of resistance by the top of the Commission, which felt threatened", explains

Noorman. He expects the evaluation to be ready within two or three years. "So at the

moment we can't say whether European aid was effective or not." Nevertheless, experience

shows, according to Noorman, that the EU is strong on structural adjustment, regional

integration, and food security projects, but weaker on the environment.

<p>

Paul Hoebink, senior lecturer at the Third World Centre of the Catholic University of

Nijmegen notes that a positive element of Lom&#233; is the way in which fund distribution

is tied to clear criteria of poverty and needs. According to Hoebink, political and economic

interests are less dominant than in other forms of international cooperation.The other side

of the Lom&#233; "aid and trade" pillar has been the provision of preferential access for

ACP exports to European markets. Despite these preferences however, most ACP countries

have not been able to advance in economic terms. Their market share has actually declined

from 6.7% in 1976 to 3.4% in 1993. 

<p>

"You might say that without Lom&#233; these countries would have lost even more, but

that is not very satisfying," comments Hoebink.

<p>

The picture is not all bleak. A few countries have benefited from the arrangement. Barbados

and especially Mauritius are the Convention's show-pieces, but they however are the

exceptions.

<p>

Critics of the preferences point to the experiences of some non-ACP countries which, with

fewer trade preferences, have strengthened their position in the European market. 

<p>

"ACP countries have not used the trade possibilities partly because of the rather complex

procedures," acknowledges Noorman. "Moreover we pretend that the trade preferences are

very ample. But in fact they are very restricted and are not interesting for bigger companies."

<p>

Noorman quotes Dutch Member of the European Parliament, Maartje van Putten, who said

that the amount of onions which can be exported preferentially to the EU is as high as the

annual onion production of two Dutch farmers.

<p>

Since ACP countries tend to have weak industrial bases, some argue that agricultural exports

should be one of their strengths. "It is important that their agricultural products get as much

access [to Europe's markets] as possible. But that is exactly a sensitive sector which Europe

keeps closed as much as it can", says Noorman.



<p>

<h3>Changed interests</h3>



When negotiations were held last year on the second part of Lom&#233; IV, it became clear

that interest from the European side had faded. The United Kingdom reduced its contribution

by one third; Germany has never been a strong supporter; and only the driving force of

France brought the mid-term review to a successful conclusion.

<p>

Part of the European reluctance can be explained by the history of the Lom&#233;

Convention. ACP countries are mainly former French and British colonies. France, especially

is very much attached to its former colonial ties. "In principle, Lom&#233; was a neo-

colonial treaty in which the old colonies of the Union were involved. That was a bad start,"

comments Hoebink. 

<p>

These ties have been diluted over time by the addition of new members to the European

Union. Newer members have different colonial histories, or none at all (Austria). Spain, for

instance has traditionally focused on Latin America, which like Asia, is excluded from the

Lom&#233; Convention.

<p>

Other motivations are tighter aid budgets, and a fear that five-year commitments to

Lom&#233; will put too great a squeeze on bilateral funds. Particularly where national

budgets are being reduced, Lom&#233; takes up an increasing proportion of the total

national aid budget. This motivation was particularly strong in the United Kingdom where aid

officials, facing a significant decline in bilateral funds, insisted on a reduction in their

commitments to the multilateral Lom&#233; framework.  

<p>

<h3>More discrimination in the future?</h3>

Internal and external forces have created the current stormy climate for the debate on the

Lom&#233; Convention. While it is too early for complete scenarios to emerge, the debate

is heating up as the issues become clearer.

<p>

One major problem to tackle is discrimination. In two ways. First, how to discriminate among

ACP countries so that differences are reflected in their relations with Europe. Second, how

to avoid discriminating against very poor countries like Bangladesh which are currently

excluded from the agreements.

<p>

Though he does not want to draw conclusions yet, ECDPM's Geert Laporte identifies a more

differentiated approach as one of the options under consideration. Laporte "gets the

impression that a kind of regionalisation is being worked on. The basic idea is that it is

unmanageable to keep seventy countries together, because they are too different." Since it

is clear that ACP countries face different problems, he can see Lom&#233; possibly evolving

into an "umbrella agreement covering all developing countries, with sub-agreements for

specific countries and regions."

<p>

This could lead to a Southern African region supported in different ways than Central Africa,

the Pacific or the Caribbean. Hoebink notes that while "everybody is talking about

regionalisation," he pleads for a treaty that also incorporates Asian developing countries.

"The crux for a new cooperation will be [to include] a country like India," he warns,

"because that is a large potential force on the European market."

<p>

But Dutch official Noorman does not exclude that Lom&#233; will remain intact:

<p>

"What we have laid down in Brussels is the result of years-long negotiations between Member

States, which all have different interests. A balance is found and it will not be easy to find a

new balance."

<p>

Noorman continues: "When you say no Lom&#233; no more you have to come up with

alternatives." 

<p>

This is the challenge for the next four years.

<p>

</h5>

<hr>

