<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#ft6106" vlink="#1f85d5" alink="f8c424"><a href="../../index.html">OneWorld</a>Feedback<br clear=left><br>


<b>Saturday 8 June</b><br>
<i>From Philip Bishop, USA</i><p>
<p>

<h3>China adoptions</h3>



I read somewhere in your WWW literature that adopting from China is very 
difficult. Working through an agency here in the States - called Wide 
Horizons for Children - we have found the process pretty straightforward. My 
wife returned home June 1st with our child on what was the 30th trip Wide 
Horizons has made to the country (usually in groups of 10-15 couples). Adopting 
from China <b>can</b> be very difficult if you attempt it without the support of 
people who have been there and established ties. With a competent agency, it 
need not be difficult (although there is plenty of red tape - most of it 
necessary - to deal with). My concern is that your warning will stop people 
from trying to adopt from China when the need is clearly urgent.<p>
<b>

Philip Bishop<br>
CDROM@msn.com</b><p>
<a href="../index.html">
