<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

The Week in Europe, 28 November 1996</h2>

<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>

<p>

Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>

</center>

<hr>

<P>

A little over a week ago the Green Paper produced by the EC's Development

Commissioner, Professor de Deus Pinheiro, on relations between the EU and

the ACP in the 21st century, was considered by the EC's College of

Commissioners and then presented to the EU ministers attending a

Development Council meeting.

<P>

Despite this, the much talked-about discussion document is still not widely

available.  While it is a veritable gold mine of ideas on options for a

future relationship, it is far from user-friendly. Its discursive style ranges from 

philosophic observations on the future relationship between the EU and

developing nations, through the implications of globalisation, to

indications of very specific ideas in respect of the political, economic,

trade and aid options under consideration by the EC.

<P>

Notwithstanding these reservations, it has to be essential reading for all

in Caribbean politics, government, the private sector, NGOs, trades unions

and others who seek to maintain a future relationship with Europe, whether

for political or economic reasons.

<p>

At its heart the Green Paper is not about a European prescription for a

future relationship, but the presentation of a series of options for

debate, although it is apparent from the drafting that the EC favours some

more than others.

<p>

While it is not easy to do justice to the broad sweep of the document in a

column such as this, let me try to provide a flavour of those sections that

are of most immediate concern and interest to the Caribbean.

<p>

Three aspects of the document are particularly relevant to the region.

These are those dealing with the 'political' relationship, the options for

future trade ties and the role of decentralised partners such as the

private sector.

<p>

The Green Paper recognises that there is now a widening economic divergence

between all developing countries, and within the ACP in particular. This

gap between the richest and poorest in the ACP, it argues, is likely to

widen as a result of rapidly changing global and regional environment,

unless - through partnership with the EU and others - new frameworks of

co-operation can be created. In the case of more advanced regions (such as

the Caribbean) this means assistance with economic transition and the

development of new instruments (regulations and aid mechanisms) that

embrace economic, scientific, technological and environmental co-operation.

<p>

This, it suggests, all points to an EU approach based on differentiation by

region. "The ACP Group is, in reality, neither a political group nor an

economic entity," the Green Paper states. "The geographical coverage of the

co-operation agreement might be changed to take on board factors such as

diversity within the ACP Group". In this context,  it then proposes four

options as a possible basis on which a future EU/ACP arrangement might be

constructed:

<UL>

<li>the maintenance of the status quo of the existing Convention but with

different arrangements and priorities;

 

<li>an overall agreement for the ACP supplemented by regional agreements;

 

<li>a division of the Convention into regional agreements; and

 

<li>a specific agreement for the least developed ACP States, possibly open to

other least developed nations outside the ACP.

</ul><p>

For the Caribbean, the Green Paper then puts forward its first 'heretical'

thought and what one assumes is its preferred choice: "There are a number

of options in the Caribbean, notably the idea of an enlarged co-operation

agreement for the whole of the Caribbean area leading ultimately to

integration of co-operation within these countries into the framework of

relations with Latin America." Much later in the document, in an annex, it

becomes clear that Professor Pinheiro's advisers envisage such a process

might be enhanced by the use of EU support for integration via the

Association of Caribbean States, thereby embracing Cuba, Central America

and all of the OCTs (the French DOMs and the British and Dutch Dependent

Territories).

<p>

Later still, the document addresses the question of the need for new trade

arrangements "consistent with the strategic choices made by the ACP

countries in their bid to integrate into the world economy". This

carefully-chosen expression reflects further new thinking, for it suggests

implicitly that the Caribbean, the Pacific, the ACP in the Indian Ocean,

southern Africa and other regions will, by their location, have to seek

different trade relationships.

<p>

The Green Paper then offers four trade options which it recognises are not

mutually exclusive:

<UL>

<li>that the status quo of non-reciprocal trade preferences be maintained but

be supplemented by co-operation in trade related fields;

 

<li>application of the Generalised Scheme of Preferences on a bilateral or

multilateral basis. This approach, it admits, would involve removing trade

from any post-Lom&#233; co-operation agreement;

 

<li>uniform reciprocity entailing all ACP States, after a transitional

period, extending reciprocity in line with World Trade Organisation rules

with new areas of co-operation in trade-related fields; and

 

<li>differential reciprocity between the EU and different groups of nations

or single countries. This option (which implies the creation of free trade

areas), the Green Paper suggests, might be supplemented by co-operation in

new areas covered by the WTO agenda.

</ul>

<P>

Beyond these critical choices, which warrant much more extensive coverage

and analysis than this column can possibly provide, the Green Paper deals

with the delivery of programmes, the need for efficiency and changing

European perspectives. It also dwells at length on the role of the private

sector and other social partners, and suggests ways forward.

<P>

Much more will be written on all these issues in future columns and, no

doubt, by many others. But, above all, the Green Paper provides a

much-needed focus for the region about the types of options the EC believes

are viable. If the document suggests any one theme, it is that, if the

successor to the Lom&#233; Convention is to have real value in a changed world,

more successful regions such as the Caribbean must look ahead to future

objectives rather than seek to defend the status quo. 

<p>

<HR>

