<html>
<head>
<title>DEA Journal: The drama that crossed 'The Line'.</title>
<!!keys: DEA+drama+South Africa+television></head>
<body>

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by the </i> <a href="dea_info.html"> Development Education Association</a>
<hr>
<h2>The drama that crossed 'The Line'</h2>
<ul><b><i>SABC crosses The Line</i></b><br>
<b><i>Laying down the line on the harsh realities in SA</i></b><br>
<b><i>For many The Line was the last straw</i></b><br>
<b><i>Are we ready to go on The Line?</i></b><br>
<b><i>Bravely CCV lays it all on The Line</i></b></ul>
<p>
<i>These are just a few of the headlines from dozens of articles in the South African press reacting to the controversial screening of the IBT-Afravision co-production 'In a Time of Violence', screened in South Africa with the original title, 'The Line'. They were accompanied by a letter from producer Jeremy Nathan in which he says: 'I believe this series has changed the shape of television in South Africa forever.'</i>
<hr>
In Britain the series was shown on three consecutive Sunday evenings as part of a Channel 4 mini-series during the run-up to the South African elections in April. Originally the South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) had scheduled the screening on their CCV channel at the same time but, due to the volatility of the pre-election period, they decided not to screen it until after the elections. 
<p>
After screening the first episode, SABC withdrew the drama because of protests from the certain vocal factions, but when this action provoked even more protests, and accusations of censorship, SABC decided to go ahead and screen all three programmes together on the evening of Saturday 30 July. This caused a national debate in the press, radio and television that lasted for weeks. Producer Jeremy Nathan gives his account of what happened:
<p>
"The first episode was screened on Wednesday 20 July, having received fairly extensive publicity and good reviews. That evening, the SABC's lines were jammed with viewers calling to complain about the portrayal of Inkatha and Zulu-speaking South Africans. The main complaint was the querying of whether this was the right time to screen such a dramatic portrayal of recent events, and did this constitute a reconciliation?
<p>
"After a meeting with Inkatha's Transvaal head Temba Khosa, the SABC suspended the screening of the further two episodes. Another, larger volley of complaints was then received by the SABC demanding it be put back on and that they were breaching the newly established Bill of Rights. 
<p>
"The issue hit front page and leading news reports. After discussions between SABC management, producer, director, cast and crew, it was unanimously agreed to push ahead with the screenings. All the Sunday newspapers carried large front page articles and an announcement from the SABC explaining why it was going ahead with all three episodes. 
<p>
"Dawn on Monday broke with the press and radio coverage becoming even more extensive. For the entire week, the whole country was caught up with debating the merits and demerits of the forthcoming screening, with people of all political persuasions getting involved in the freedom of information and expression debate. 
<p>
"On Thursday evening, a week after the series was suspended, the Inkatha-linked National Hostel Residents Association went public on national press, radio and television placing a Ôfatwah' on the lives of the producer, cast and crew of the series. Some of the more visible cast and crew went into hiding, as Inkatha threatened to march on and occupy the SABC offices. On the Saturday morning the march and occupation took place. Although small, it was vocal and the police were a constant presence.
<p>
"Saturday 30 July was truly the most bizarre day and night in the lives of the cast and crew. About twenty of us were holed up in a hotel room, preparing to watch our series screened to the nation, not knowing how ordinary people would react. The moment finally came, with the SABC screening a peace song before the series, and a lengthy introduction by a top SABC management person. Cut off from the rest of the world, protected by anonymity and the hotel's discretion, we hotly debated whether we had done the right thing. Without doubt, and to a person, whatever the cost to ourselves, we all felt that we had. 
<p>
"Sunday morning found us at breakfast, all a little drained by the experience of the last few days. Four elderly white women were breakfasting at the hotel. One of them recognised one of the actors, came over to the table and suddenly, the entire breakfast room knew who we were. They all loved the series and told us how they never knew how things were in the townships, and thanked us all for a brilliantly entertaining and informative show. 
<p>
"For the next two weeks the debate raged in the newspapers and on the radio. Most viewers were of the opinion that it was all true, and that it was a great start for new South African television. What was all the fuss about? Some did not, and felt it was one-sided and pro-ANC. All forgot that it was a drama and not a documentary. Pure opinion, and entertainment.
<p>
"The audience figures a few weeks later proved that it was the second most viewed programme ever in South Africa, second only to the news during the elections, and higher than the World Cup soccer finals. After a traumatic few weeks, the debate quietened down. The cast and crew felt exhausted on the one hand, pleased that freedom of broadcasting had been placed on the agenda, and that their work had been seen by many millions, but also aware of the distance that the country still has to go to create a culture of tolerance and debate.
<p>
"All the broadcasters and people involved in the series can feel pleased that in some small way we have contributed to challenging the monolith of power that has historically controlled broadcasting in South Africa, and for the first time given the audience, the people, a choice in the matter. Those people who complained when it was taken off ensured that it was rescreened, and to them we are indebted." 
<hr>
This article first appeared in the December 1994 issue of the Development Education Journal. <br>
©Copyright Development Education Association 1994
