<head>
<title>Middle East peace process in tatters as fifth suicide bomb hits Israel</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#823308" alink="d9d919" vlink="ff7f00">OneWorld News Service<p><b><font size=-1>This report has been researched and written by the OneWorld News Team</font></b>



<h2>Middle East peace process in tatters as fifth suicide bomb hits Israel</h2>



<b>5 March 1996</b><p>

Thousands of grief-stricken Israelis called for an end to Prime Minister Shimon Peres' peace process last night, as  a fifth suicide bomb attack killed 12 people and wounded over 100 in Tel Aviv.<p>

In the past 8 days more than 60 people have been killed in suicide bomb blasts, detonated by the military wing of the Palestinian Muslim fundamentalist group, Hamas.<p>

Hamas' stated aim is to wreck what is left of the Arab-Israeli peace process by proving to Israelis and Arabs alike that their leaders are ineffectual, and that the two communities cannot live together.<p>

Judging by the reaction of some Israelis to the latest terrorist atrocity, the bombers are achieving their aim.  "Peres, you're next," shouted some, in an apparent reference to the fate of the assassinated prime minister Yitzak Rabin.  Mr Peres has seen his lead in the polls over the hardline Jewish Likud opposition party slashed in the last several days.  <p>

In response to this latest series of blasts, Peres has himself been forced to take a stronger stance towards the Palestinian threat.  After an emergency cabinet meeting yesterday, he told reporters: "We will go to any corner where this twisted terror has begun to take root."<p>

Israel will now give priority to a military campaign against Hamas, and its fellow fundamentalist organisation Islamic Jihad.  Security services will be given a free hand to enter even the parts of the former Occupied Territories now controlled by Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority.<p>

This is a reversal of previous Israeli policy, which has seen the withdrawal of troops from the occupied territories of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip after the 1993 peace deal with the Yasser Arafat's PLO.   <p>

However, the Palestinian authorities condemned the decision, saying that they were in charge of countering the threat from Muslim militants.  Over the past few weeks 350 known Hamas members have been detained by Mr Arafat's police.<p>

A further long-term threat to peace is the emnity that the bombing campaign is continuing to sow between Palestinians and Israelis.  Many Israelis feel there has been a distinct lack of sympathy among the Palestinians for their plight.  "Where are the peace rallies?" many are asking.<p>

Palestinians are in turn angry at Israel's response, which has been to close indefinitely the border between Israel and the former Occupied Territories.  Thousands of Palestinians depend on jobs in Israel for their income, and preventing them from working will deepen despair and poverty in Muslim communities.<p>

It is from this crushing poverty that fundamentalism and extremist politics derive their strength, say many observers.  Unless there is a long term strategy to tackle this problem, Arab-Israeli peace may still be a long way off.<p>

<br><li><b><a href="../mideast/index.html">OneWorld News Service reports on the Middle East</a></b>


<br clear=left><br>
<p>



