<html>
<head>
<title>World Conference on Women - Beijing</title>
</head>
<body>

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="oxfam.html">  Oxfam</i></a>
<hr>

<center><h2>Briefing paper for the IV World Conference on Women<br>

Beijing - 4th-15th September 1995</h2></center>

The IV World Conference on Women scheduled to take place in September this 
year is the
latest in a series of Conferences scheduled to coincide with the United 
Nations' 50th
Anniversary. As such, it will build on the work already done by the World 
Summit on
Children (1990), the Earth Summit 1992), the Vienna Human Rights Conference 
(1993), the
International Conference on Population and Development (1994) and the World 
Summit on
Social Development (1995). Coming at the end of such a long list, the charge 
of "conference-
itis" is perhaps inevitable. So why is Beijing important and what can it 
achieve ?
<p>

The Declaration and the Platform of Action which will be agreed at the 
Beijing Conference
will mark the latest stage in a process which began twenty years ago in 
1975, declared
International Women's Year by the UN's General Assembly. The year was a 
turning point
in putting women's issues on the agenda in the development process. The UN 
Decade for
Women (1976-1985) was a worldwide effort to examine the status and rights of 
women and
to bring them into the decision-making process at all levels. In 1979, the 
UN General
Assembly adopted the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of 
Discrimination against
Women which entered into force in 1981 and set an international standard for 
what was
meant by equality between women and men.<p>


In 1985, the World Conference to Review and Appraise the Achievements of the 
UN Decade
for Women in Nairobi adopted the Forward-looking Strategies for Women to be 
implemented
by the year 2000. These marked a turning point for women, securing agreement 
by
governments to update their legislative frameworks, incorporating women's 
rights and
building awareness of gender into planning processes. The Nairobi Conference 
also gave a
boost to women's organisations and NGOs campaigning on gender issues. While 
the
intervening years have undoubtedly brought many positive changes for women, 
ten years on,
many of the commitments made at Nairobi have still to be met.<p>


Oxfam believes that the Beijing Women's Conference is important firstly 
because it presents
an opportunity to remind governments of their previous commitments and put 
them under
pressure to implement them; secondly, it will highlight the enormous gender 
gap which still
exists; thirdly, it will allow women from all over the world to seek new 
commitments from
national governments and international institutions, linked to concrete 
proposals which can
bring about real changes in their daily lives. The NGO Forum will complement 
this by
providing an opportunity for women's groups to share ideas and experience 
across the world.<p>


In summary, we hope that the Beijing Conference will lead to:

<ul><li>   Re-affirmation that women's rights are fundamental human rights.

<li>   Action to halt the increasingly female face of poverty.

<li>   Generation of additional resources for women in the development process
     through enhanced debt relief and acceptance of the 20:20 compact.</ul><p>

The Conference is taking place against a background of controversy, with the 
most recent
focus of dissent being over the siting of the NGO Forum. The Chinese 
Government has
proposed that this should be moved from the centre of Beijing to Huairou in 
the suburbs,
giving rise to fears that NGOs' access to official delegations will be 
limited. While lobbying
by NGOs has resulted in some important concessions including agreement on 
visas, transport
between Beijing and Huairou and a satellite base for NGOs in Beijing itself, 
concerns over
accreditation of NGOs and censorship of publications remain.<p>


While Oxfam shares these concerns, we are keen to ensure that they do not 
detract from the
overall purpose of the Conference - the promotion of women's rights and 
equality.<p>


<h3>The scale of the problem</h3>

Oxfam works in over 70 countries around the world and witnesses the results 
of
discrimination against women on a daily basis. Women provide most of the 
food consumed
by poor households and perform more than three-quarters of the agricultural 
work in many
countries. They manage common resources and are responsible for collecting 
water and
firewood as well as bringing up children. Female labour also accounts for a 
growing
proportion of employment in commercial agriculture and industry.<p>


But despite this contribution, women face a bewildering array of social, 
economic, cultural
and religious barriers to their equal participation in society. 
While the 
true cost of this
systematic discrimination cannot be measured, the results can be seen in a 
few revealing
statistics:<p>


<ul><li>  Out of 130 million primary school children not attending school, 70% 
are girls.

<li>  Out of 960 million illiterate adults in the world, two-thirds are 
women.

<li>  In many countries, especially in Asia, the malnutrition rate for girls 
is much
     higher than for boys. In Bangladesh, for example, the malnutrition rate 
for girls
     is three times that for boys.

<li>  Women are typically paid 30-40% less than men for doing the same jobs.
<li>  One third of wives in developing countries are physically abused. In 
Peru, 70%
     of all crimes reported to the police concern women beaten by their 
partners.

<li>  Worldwide, one woman in 2,000 has been reported as raped.

<li>    Women's share of the seats in the world's parliaments has fallen from 
15% in
     1988 to 11% in 1994. Only around 6% of cabinet posts are held by women 
and
     in 1994, only ten women were heads of state or government. At the UN, 
only six
     of the 184 member countries have a female permanent representative.</ul><p>


Given the scale of the problem and the all encompassing nature of the 
Beijing Platform of
Action, there are many issues which could be raised at the Conference. In 
its lobbying at
Beijing, Oxfam will concentrate on the following points.<p>


<h3>Women's Human Rights</h3>

Among the agreements on women's rights made at previous UN conferences, one 
of the most
significant is the explicit recognition in the Vienna Declaration that the 
human rights
of women and the girl child are an inalienable, integral and indivisible 
part of universal
human rights. Against a background of rising religious fundamentalism and 
growing
economic and political conservatism, such basic principles are once again 
under attack from
some quarters. In particular, it seems likely that those who champion the 
nuclear family will
attempt to scapegoat women for the social breakdown which is occurring in 
many societies.
Throughout our overseas programme, Oxfam's experience of the diversity of 
families leads
us to believe that diversity should be recognised and valued.<p>


As a starting point for its lobbying, Oxfam will seek to ensure that the 
principle that
women's rights are fundamental human rights is upheld and that there is no 
backsliding on
previous agreements. As a means of holding governments accountable for 
ending
discriminatory practices, we will be calling for:


<ul><li>  Universal ratification and implementation of all UN human rights 
instruments,
     including ratification without reservation of the Convention against 
All Forms of
     Discrimination Against Women.</ul><p>


<h3>Women in Poverty</h3>

Of the 1.2 billion people living in absolute poverty, a disproportionate and 
growing number
are women, leading to what commentators have dubbed "the feminization of 
poverty". The
causes of poverty in general and women's poverty in particular are many, 
complex and
varied. One fundamental problem is that in many societies, women continue to 
be denied
access to land, property and other resources and are discriminated against 
in terms of
inheritance, credit and banking services. In Bangladesh, daughters inherit 
land at half their
brothers' entitlement while in much of Africa, women have no rights to 
resources such as
the land they cultivate. Overall, it is estimated that women obtain only 10% 
of all rural
credit. <br>At Beijing, Oxfam will be lobbying for:

<ul><li>  Equal access to land, property, inheritance, credit and banking 
services for
     women.</ul><p>


Given that women do around two-thirds of the world's work in return for less 
than 5% of
the world's income, measuring and valuing unwaged work is an important 
aspect of
recognising women's economic and legal rights. Quantifying and valuing 
unwaged work
would provide official information on how much work women do in the home, on 
the land,
in family business and in the community. <br>
At Beijing, Oxfam will be calling 
for:


<ul><li>   Governments, financial institutions and the UN to measure and value 
women's
     unwaged work and include this in satellite accounts of GDP.</ul><p>


The deregulation of labour markets has led to an increase in the number of 
women joining
the work force. While some have done so on a voluntary basis, seizing newly 
gained rights
and opportunities, others have been forced to take paid employment to make 
ends meet.<p>


All too often, the latter category of women join the informal sector, 
working long hours in
poor conditions for inadequate remuneration.<p>


In Chile, an "economic success story", Oxfam partners are working in the 
Patronato district
of Santiago, centre of the country's textile industry. Here, an estimated 
6,000 small
workshops do outwork for large manufacturers and provide employment to over 
12,000
mainly female workers. Few of these workshops meet even the minimum 
specifications of
Chile's weak health and safety laws and accidents are regular occurrences. 
Most women do
not have contracts so can be made redundant without compensation. Piecework 
rates are so
low that most women have to work shifts in excess of twelve hours, including 
night work.
Even the most basic trade union rights are denied.<p>


Elsewhere in the formal sector, national labour laws often fail to give 
women adequate
protection against discrimination or protect their rights to employment and 
social security
during illness and pregnancy. <br>At Beijing, Oxfam will be calling for:<p>


<ul><li>   Implementation of all International Labour Organisation (ILO) 
conventions
     relevant to the protection of women's employment rights including those 
relating
     to equal pay for women, maternity rights, rights of association and 
rights of
     part-time workers.</ul><p>


Despite calls at the World Summit for Social Development in Copenhagen for 
the
International Financial Institutions to ensure that social development goals 
are fully integrated
into macro-economic policies, Oxfam remains concerned at the impact of 
structural
adjustment programmes on poor and marginalised groups, including women.<p>


In Zimbabwe, for example, the simultaneous reduction of food subsidies 
combined with the
decline in wages which accompanied adjustment dramatically reduced household 
incomes.
One study of a low income urban settlement in Harare estimates that the 
proportion of
families living below the poverty line doubled to 43% under adjustment. The 
poorest families
cut their meals from two to one a day, with women bearing the brunt of this 
household level
adjustment, foregoing meals themselves in order to feed their children.<p>


Whereas there is now a strong international consensus on the importance of 
investing in basic
health and education services, as illustrated by World Bank statements at 
the Copenhagen
Summit, the reality that Oxfam sees on the ground is government cut-backs 
which hit women
and girls hardest.<p>


Burdened by debt as they attempt to meet IMF-World Bank targets, many 
governments have
responded by cutting social welfare budgets. During the 1980s, real per 
capita spending on
education in Africa fell by one-third while two-thirds of the countries in 
the region also
reduced expenditure on health. Uganda, one of the most severely indebted 
countries, is
currently obliged to spend more on servicing its debt than it is able to 
invest in health and
education combined.<p>


In an attempt to bridge the gap, some countries have resorted to the 
introduction of user fees
for health and education. Such measures have predictably hit the poor 
hardest and poor
women the hardest of all.<p>


An Oxfam study in Zimbabwe found that women's attendance at ante-natal 
clinics was
particularly sensitive to increased health fees. The Government of Zimbabwe 
has
subsequently withdrawn fees in rural health clinics but they continue to be 
standard policy
in many other countries. While exemption schemes have been introduced, these 
have
generally proved to be inadequate. Moreover the user charge schemes have 
proved to be
economically inefficient - in Zimbabwe, the scheme cost more to run than it 
raised in
government revenue. <br>At Beijing, Oxfam will be lobbying for:<p>

<ul><li>  The withdrawal of user fees for basic health services and primary 
education
     under structural adjustment programmes.<br>

<li> Greater participation from civil society in the formulation of World 
Bank/IMF
     policies and in particular, agreement that community based 
organisations,
     women's groups and NGOs should be involved in the design of economic 
reform
     programmes.

<li> Agreement that all future structural adjustment programmes will be 
designed to
     take account of their impact on women's labour and access to services.

<li>  International Financial Institutions to introduce effective social 
conditionality so
     that the disbursement of structural adjustment loans is made 
conditional on
     government action to improve basic services and ensure access to them 
by women
     and girls.</ul><p>


<h3>Women's Health and Reproductive Rights</h3>

Last year's International Conference on Population and Development 
successfully reached
new agreements on women's health and reproductive rights. Oxfam understands 
the
concerns
which are often expressed in relation to the population question, but 
believes that rapid
population growth is both a cause and a consequence of poverty and of 
control. It is vital that
women are empowered to make choices about family size within the couple, 
within the
family and within the community. We support agreements reached in Cairo for 
a
comprehensive strategy to reduce rapid population growth through a wider 
anti-poverty
strategy and specific measures to improve the education and status of women 
and ensure
that
women have access to quality reproductive health care services.  There are 
many reasons
why people elect to have large families but one of the most obvious is 
poverty. Tackling
poverty, followed by providing education and freely available reproductive 
health care for
women is, in our view, the best strategy for reducing family size.<p>


However, a coalition of the Holy See and some Roman Catholic countries plus 
Muslim
countries in the Middle East are seeking to use the Beijing Conference to 
re-open the debate
they lost in Cairo regarding women's reproductive rights. <br>Oxfam will be 
lobbying for:


<ul><li>    Full implementation of the Cairo commitments on women's sexual and
     reproductive health.

<li>   A holistic approach to women's health which recognises their needs from 
early
     childhood to old age, including needs for high quality reproductive 
health care.</ul><p>


<h3>Violence Against Women</h3>

Violence against women in the home continues to be endemic in many 
societies. One study
covering 35 countries found that an average of one-fifth to one-half of 
women have suffered
domestic violence from a male partner, on average three times a year. In 
Egypt and Zambia,
injuries resulting from domestic assaults are the most common reason for 
female visits to
casualty units while in Latin America, domestic and sexual violence against 
women claims
more lives than political violence. <p>
Oxfam will be lobbying to:<ul>

<li>  Ensure that national legislation specifically recognises and 
establishes sanctions
     against all forms of violence against women.

<li>   Ensure that police forces and judiciaries are trained to take domestic 
violence
     seriously and deal with it appropriately.

<li> Ensure that the Special Rapporteur on Violence Against Women has all 
necessary
     assistance from national governments and UN agencies in fulfilling her 
task and
     in promoting the renewal, updating and strengthening of her mandate.</ul><p>


<h3>Women and Conflict</h3>

While the end of the Cold War initially heralded a new spirit of optimism 
about the prospects
for world peace, this has quickly dissolved in the myriad of intra-state 
conflicts which have
erupted across the globe. As the nature of conflict has changed, so have its 
victims - four out
of every five casualties in contemporary conflicts are civilians. The 
outbreak of conflict has
led to refugee movements on an unprecedented scale. The 82 major armed 
conflicts which
took place between 1989 and 1993 have left 40 million people as refugees or 
internally
displaced and of these, around 80% are women and children.<p>


Refugee women form a particularly vulnerable group, frequently dependent on 
others to meet
even their most basic needs for food, water, shelter and clothing. They are 
also vulnerable
to gender specific forms of violence such as rape, forced prostitution and 
forced pregnancy.
In former Yugoslavia, it is estimated that between 50,000 and 80,000 women 
have been
raped, while in Rwanda, countless thousands have been forced to bear the 
children of those
who massacred their families. <br>Against this background, Oxfam is lobbying 
for:

<ul><li>  Adequate resources to guarantee the rights to protection and relief of 
refugee and
     displaced women.

<li>   Explicit recognition that rape and other forms of sexual assault in the 
conduct
     of armed conflict constitute a war crime under the terms of the Geneva
     Convention and its Protocols.

<li>  The establishment of a permanent International Tribunal for genocide, 
war
     crimes and other serious violations of human rights.</ul><p>


All too often, intra-state conflicts are fuelled by weapons sold by the 
former super-powers
to governments only too willing to sacrifice social development for military 
hardware.<p>


Pakistan, with some of the worst social indicators in the world, continues 
to allocate a greater
proportion of its annual budget to military expenditure than to health and 
education
combined. Developing countries now account for 15% of global military 
expenditure,
an annual total of $118bn. While excessive military expenditure remains 
primarily a matter
for the governments concerned, those who sell the weapons must bear their 
share of
responsibility. Four-fifths of the world's weapons are supplied by the 
Permanent Five
members of the UN Security Council.<p>


Perhaps the most sinister aspect of "modern" conflicts is that long after 
peace has been
declared, the weapons of death can go on claiming innocent victims, killed 
or maimed by
anti-personnel mines. There are an estimated 100 million mines in the world 
laid in 64
countries. They kill or injure 2,000 people each month - every 15 minutes, 
someone,
somewhere in the world will step on a landmine - and a large proportion of 
victims will be
women and children. Oxfam remains unconvinced that the various export 
moratoria imposed
on anti-personnel mines will prove adequate to deal with the scale and 
seriousness of the
problem.<br> Oxfam is therefore calling for:

<ul><li>  A total ban on the production, sale, transfer, export, stockpiling or 
use of all
     anti-personnel mines.</ul><p>


<h3>Implementation, follow-up and resources</h3>

No matter what governments agree to at Beijing, there is a danger that 
commitments will turn
into empty rhetoric unless the Conference addresses the central issues of 
implementation,
follow-up and resources.<p>


Coming in the wake of various other UN Conferences which have sought to 
establish new
bodies to oversee implementation, Oxfam believes that the responsibility for 
implementing
the Beijing Platform of Action should be integrated with existing 
structures.<br> We will argue
the case for:

<ul><li>  Responsibility for co-ordinating implementation to rest with ECOSOC, 
which
     should be strengthened. Specific strategies must be developed to ensure 
that
     gender perspectives are incorporated in all UN programmes.

<li>   Introduction of an integrated mechanism for reporting back on Beijing 
and all
     other recent UN conferences.

<li>  Creation of a new post of Under Secretary General to oversee UN
     implementation of the Agenda for Equality.</ul><p>


With regard to follow-up, we believe the key to success lies in ensuring 
that governments
give commitments to measurable, time-bound objectives for progress.<p>


Given that the Beijing Conference takes place against a background of 
falling aid budgets,
it seems unlikely that governments will agree to finding additional 
resources for
implementation of its proposals.<br> Nevertheless, Oxfam believes that 
considerable progress
could be made by reallocating existing resources more wisely and by adopting 
more
imaginative schemes to release funds for women in development.
In particular, we will be arguing the case for:

<ul><li>  A co-ordinated strategy and improved terms for debt relief, including 
80-100%
     reductions in Paris Club debt and agreement on new measures to tackle 
the
     growing crisis of multilateral debt, financed  from within the 
multilateral
     institutions.

<li>   Commitment to the 20:20 compact, agreed on a voluntary basis at the
     Copenhagen Summit, whereby 20% of donor countries' development 
assistance
     and 20% of recipient countries' national budgets will be spent on basic 
health
     care and basic education.
<li> A reduction in military expenditure with the proceeds invested in 
social
     development priorities such as health and education. Reducing military 
spending
     in developing countries by 25% would be sufficient to double social 
spending.</ul><p>


In relation to Beijing, we believe that priority expenditure for funds 
released in this way
should include:

<ul><li>  Increased financial and human resources for the Committee on the 
Elimination
     of Discrimination Against Women which monitors compliance with the
     Convention on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women.

<li>   Strengthening the capacity of the Division for the Advancement of Women
     to service CEDAW and CSW.

<li> Adequate resources to be directed toward UNIFEM (United Nations 
Development
     Fund for Women) to strengthen its programmes and implement its mandate.</ul><p><hr>
 
<i>For further information please contact Oxfam on +44 1865 311311.</i>
<hr>

Oxfam Policy Department : July 1995

<hr>
<a href="index.html"> Oxfam Home Page</a>
<hr>
</body>
