<Html><Head><Title>AUTISM AWARENESS WEEK 1996

</title></head>

<Body  bgcolor="#CCFFCC" link="#336633" vlink="#669966">

<i>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">The National Autistic
Society</a></b></i>

[nas logo]
<hr>

<h2>AWARENESS WEEK - 2 - 8 DECEMBER 1996</h2>



Autism Awareness Week (AAW) is a week dedicated to raising awareness of autism and Asperger syndrome. 
Each year we hope to further raise the general level of awareness of autism but specific audiences
are also targetted. This year’s theme for the week is “Beyond Rainman” - a look at how carers of
people with autism cope with the stresses and strains they experience as a result of caring.
<p>

To find out more about these issues, we commissioned a survey which looked at the way in which the
general public perceive autism - what they understand about it and what it involves.  The majority of
the general public did not feel that people with autism receive enough services and support. Many who
had heard of autism were unaware of the main characteristics of the condition  etc  The survey also
contains extracts from interviews with people who have autism. 
<p>

The survey highlights many of the issues that families affected by autism experience.   In addition
there are many events which are being organised around the country which will help to heighten
awareness of autism.
<p>

<b><a href="events.htm">Events list</a></b>

<Hr>

<Address>The National Autistic Society, 276 Willesden Lane, London NW2 5RB <br>
Tel: 0181 451 1114<br>
Email: <b><A href="mailto:nas@clus1.ulcc.ac.uk"> 

nas@clus1.ulcc.ac.uk</a></b></adDRESS><p>

