<h1>CAMPAIGN UPDATE:</h1>

<b>Progress with retailers as of June 22:</b><br> 
<b>M&S:</b> has acknowledged contact with Oxfam, but no meeting has been arranged. An M&S spokeswoman said that a meeting would 'depend on how things developed in the future.'<br>
<b>C&A:</b> Oxfam met with John Greene, head of corporate communications, in May. According to Clothes Code campaign co-ordinator, Shelagh Young, the meeting with C&A was 'positive' and that C&S's new code of conduct initiative for suppliers was 'a step in the right direction.' Gail Pilling, C&A’s UK corporate communications manager, said all buyers were responsible for ensuring suppliers met required standards and added: 'the meeting was amicable and we spoke about the concerns that Oxfam has.'<p>


Very constructive meetings with Sears and Burtons have taken place, and Gail now will have follow-up meetings.  Oxfam will meet with the Club Executive at Next in August.<p>


<b>It is now more important than ever for you to hand in <a href="coupon.html">coupons</a> and write <a href="letter.html">letters</a>. Your letters and coupons will help convince all retailers to carry on talking to Oxfam. Thanks for all the letters sent and coupons handed in so far. You are the power behind the campaign!</b><p>

<p>
