<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> 7 : Welcome Page of the Section for Philosophy of the GHProject</TITLE></HEAD><body>

<center><h2><a name="top">Towards a multi- & meta-cultural  Philosophy ?</a></h2><h5><center><a href="welcome.htm">Global Help Project</a></center></h5></center><center></a></center><h5><center><a href="7einfo.htm">Info about the Editor</a></center></h5><p><hr width= 75% noshade><p><a href= "#cri"></a><a href="#mod"></a><a href="#log"></a><a href="#philo"></a>

1.  <a href="#def">A Definition of Philosophy : Unity through Variety.</a><br>

2.  <a href="#sys">A Mild Postmodern System* of Philosophy ?</a><br>

3.  <a href="#cor">Corpus Equiaeon.</a><br>

4.  <a href= "#pneu">Pneuma Equiaeon.</a><br>

5.  <a href= "#self">Self Equiaeon.</a><br>

6.  <a href= "#spira">Spira Equiaeon.</a><br>

7.   <a href="#link">Links.</a><br>

8.  <a href="7nfilo.htm">De Nederlandstalige Afdeling.</a></h4> 

<a name="def"><hr><h3>One and Many Definitions ?</a></h3><hr><br>

<FONT size="+2">N</FONT>umerous definitions of philosophy exist. According to some philosophy can not be defined without the use of dialectics involving one or more contradictions, for Man himself IS the longing for wisdom. Being the soul of culture & science, the heart of religions & churches and the core of morality & ethics, philosophy <b>can not be described from one particular outside perspective</b>. Philosophy should be compared, in this Hegelian scheme, with her own specialized utterances in science, art, morality & religion.<br>

<br> 

The distinction between philosophy and <b>the logistics of philosophy</b> or 'academical philosophy' is interesting. Although according to Hume academical philosophical knowledge may be useful, we understand authentic philosophy to serve a more vital purpose, i.e. the leap from certain living (natural) knowledge to a revealed (intuitive) wisdom. What German philosophy calls "Wissen" is indeed a non-verbal, unknowing knowledge conjuring <b>the presence of a sense of being within consciousness.</b><br><br> For rationalists like Wolff this special intuitive knowledge is the result of an <b>intellectual perception</b>, i.e. a direct insight into the operations of thought, devoid of sensoric and conceptual input (a Western prototype of "method of union", cfr. Eastern "yoga" ?). In this way a panoramic view may be acquired. However, this non-verbal insight is rooted in <b>a systematical & methodical natural knowledge</b> (cfr. Maimonides) which tried to explain Being as-such (immanent & transcendent metaphysics). Without this natural knowledge our intuitions stand alone and are not serving the ultimate extension & unity of our minds (cfr. Kant). So although we accept the possibility of intuition we do not accept its autonomy. This is certainly the case when the philosophical investigation of Being reveals continuous change to be the core of existence.<br>

<br>

<a name="philo">In</a> the Introduction of the <a href="7etltc.htm">Tractatus Logico Tragi-Comicus</a> the following ideas appears : <br><br><I>"Philosophy (or love of wisdom) aims to attain a pure intuition & an authentic understanding built upon multi-rational knowledge. Philosophical insight (its wisdom) results from a recurrent & multiple transference between reason (logos) & intuition (arché, eidos)."</I><br>

<br>A pure intuition, the beginning of wisdom, is the goal of philosophy. The parameters of purity are defined by understanding, So authentic understanding (longing for wisdom through purity) is the rock upon which philosophy is built. The laws of purity are not to be found outside consciousness. They derive from the perception of consciousness of its own mental, emotional & actional operations. In infancy the mirror-image of 'my' physical body caused this sense of 'me', which I called 'I' or 'ego' (cfr. Lacan). Of the circular space of early semiotic functions this 'I' is the center. Likewise, when thought learns how to consider itself by itself, a <b>transcendental 'I'</b> emerges in consciousness. The circular ego-consciousness is transformed into an elliptic consciousness oscillating between 'I' & the 'transcendental I', finally encompassing both (transfiguration). Authentic understanding or philosophical insight is always reaching towards wisdom by allowing <b>all possible interactions between both approaches of our physical brain</b>, i.e. digital, linear, sequential & verbal versus analogous, chaotic, parallel & non-verbal.<br><br> Philosophy starts with natural rational knowledge  and -when optimalized- results from the stern training of a rational mind focussed on <bthe global, universal, cosmic 'meaning' of humanity. </b>Its method & system is the first object of epistemology.<br><br> Wisdom is what happens after glimpses of the first & final causal  scheme of things emerged in consciousness as the totality (Gestalt, mandala) of Being. Our natural talents will not suffice to allow consciousness to contemplate All long enough to leave conscious operational traces in the best trained minds. Sometimes a total loss of unity is the reaction-form created to compensate for awesome monadic experiences. Surely 'academical' philosophers should be made conscious of this. Fieldwork remains necessary.<br><br> Wisdom is the free state arrived at when the monad is permanently present in the 'now' of consciousness. When -in Husserl's words- the 'natural state' has been completely, through <b>the method of bracketing</b>, put out of action, i.e. <b>all concerns for spatio-temporal existence (Dasein) have been eliminated</b>, then and only then 'a new region of Being' (Sosein) may by won. Wisdom implies abstention. For what can remain over when the world, we & our thinking have been bracketed ? <br><br>

<a name="sys"><hr><h3>A Mild Postmodern System* of Philosophy ? </a></h3><hr><br>

Postmodernism is the name given to a mutli-cultural movement which for the moment  <b>has not been completely understood nor implemented</b>. It was Joseph Hudnut who, at Harvard with modernist Walter Gropius, introduced it into architecture. In an article published in 1945 he spoke of 'the post-modern house'. Lyotard, introducing this notion in contemporary philosophical discourse with his book 'The Postmodern Condition : A Report on Knowledge' (1979), proposed that his own commitment to this new and emergent movement be grasped as a reaffirmation of the authentic modernism (to be found in Adorno's philosophy). So in fact he is pro-modernist !  Some claim postmodernism to be the 'avant-garde' of the modernism of the XXIth century (Eco), others say that by depending too much upon a 'subjectivist' non-social conception of rationality it moves towards irrationalism (Habermas). For the latter the Enlightenment is indispensable. <br><br>'Postmodernism' is still in the process of being born. Its truths are culture-dependent and grow in time. At present is it a hybrid philosophy and world view <b>dialectically involved with modernism</b>. But, most parameters of postmodernism have not as yet been established. Nevertheless, here we do not grasp it as a intermediary phase towards a new type of modernism. Like Wolfe, Jencks and others, <b>we understand postmodernism to be basically anti-modernist</b>, which does not imply a regression into pre-modernism for the whole of modernism should not be rejected. However, the rhetorical tropes celebrated by modernism like 'logical consistency', 'analytical reason', 'straightforwardness', 'simplicity', 'justification', 'system', 'proof' with the exclusion of 'holism', 'interdisciplinary approaches' & the 'interconnectivity of knowledge' are rejected as such. The sterile division between 'human sciences' and 'natural sciences' is questioned and replaced by the triad <a href = "consc.htm">consciousness</a>, <a href= "informat.htm">information</a> & <a href="matter.htm">matter</a>. Jenck's definition of postmodernism as "double coding" is interesting (cfr. 'The Language of Post-Modern Architecture', 1984). The combination of modern techniques with "something else" which does take into account history and which is able to communicate with its users is indeed typical for the postmodern approach (cfr. Cahoone, L. (edit) : 'From Modernism to Postmodernism', Blackwell - Oxford, 1996). <br><br>The distinction between 'radical postmodernism' and 'mild postmodernism' is justified on the grounds of <b>the argumentative weakness of both Lyotard's 'paralogy' or Derrida's 'deconstruction'</b>. Habermas & others are right in pointing out that Lyotard's view on rationality is defunct. For some logical rules are necessary a priori. Transcendental object & subject can not be eliminated from thought and so constitute <b>the groundless ground of knowledge, i.e. a continuity</b>. Stressing discontinuity does not desolve continuity. Nor is continuity interesting & revealing without discontinuity. In the same spirit, let us ask : Who will deconstruct deconstruction ? How did deconstruction emerge ? From Derrida's mind ? Is -like Feyerabend's "anything goes"- <b>deconstruction not a metaphore for the last outpost of a philosophy of language -initiated by Wittgenstein- unable to shape a plausible theory on language</b>? A mild postmodernist is aware of the necessities implied by transcendental logic, without however falling into the trap of either metaphysical realism or idealism. Nor is s/he inclined to deny the rules of logic, i.e. the same rules needed to negate its unconditional importance.<br><br>    

Nor do we claim (as Jameson did) postmodernism to be the 'cultural logic of late capitalism'. The logic of late capitalism (or late socialism) and classical modernism are one and the same. Is 'classical modernism' not a destructive & necrophilic expression of defunct modern ideals and fundamentalistic 'big stories' articulated a couple of centuries ago ? The  XXth century has seen the offspring of these illusions, resulting in massive destruction, misery & death (although our technology enables us to reshape Earth into a paradise for all of humanity). It is time to use modern technology without mechanizing or digitalizing our humanity (which modernism did by placing technological materialism on the altar of our souls). A technology <b>which does not pollute, serving the whole of humanity, is a workable postmodern standard of mechanization</b>. For modern technology walked hand in hand with <b>an erroneous belief in permanent growth.</b> As in our postmodernism a global <b>sustainable dynamical equilibrium</b> is the goal, technological science should be demystified and secularized. In Western philosophy today, a theory on sustainable dynamical equilibria (authoring different objective & subjective conditions) is the main issue. So the first phase of postmodernism is <b>an open & polite deconstrucion of most 'classical' modern standards of approach.</b> In this way the original features of postmodernism may slowly be apprehended. In the following phases <b>the true name</b> of this new cultural movement will ensue. Tantamount however to an agreement on the fundamental nature of some decisive break between the modern and the postmodern is  a general acceptance of this new term. <br><br> 

Some of the difficult ramifications of postmodernism are discussed in volume I, 'Knowledge' (1995) of the book 'Knowledge, Chaos & Metaphysics' and the 'Prolegomena' (1994) to that book. Readers able to understand Dutch are referred to our <a href="7nfilo.htm">Dutch Section</a>. For the moment the following conclusions will help our English readers understand what is meant by 'mild' postmodernism.<br>

<h3><a name ="mod">How did modernism evolve ?</a></h3>Is it not very important to know that modernism, taken as a historical phenomenon, has itself gone through several stages ? In 'Knowledge, Chaos & Metaphysics' six stages were characterized as follows : <br><br>The <b>rise</b> of the Modern Ideal :<br><br><li>

1.<b>Humanism</b> (starting with the Renaissance) : <br>

a) a non-radical, nominalistic denial of the conceptual realism of scholasticism;<br>

b) observation, experiment & a 'bricoleur'-mentality which derive from the individual ; <br>c) focussed on solving practical problems ;</li><br><br><li>

2.<b>Rationalism</b> of Nature in the XVIIthe century : <br>

a) mathematical quest for the final foundation of knowledge in a clear, distinct, continuous, certain & absolute sufficient ground ;<br>

b) systematic observation & formalization of facts ; <br>

c) focussed on a closed, knowledge-founding & dualistic worldview & antropology ; </li><br><br><li>

3.<b>Empirism</b> of Nature in the XVIIIthe century :<br>

a) mathematical certainty & impressions are the foundation of knowledge (phenomenism) ; <br>b) systematic observation & its formalization ;<br>

c) sceptic agnosticism which undermines positive science, scholastic & natural philosophical metaphysics ;</li><br><br><li>

4.<b>Criticism</b> at the end of the XVIIIthe century :<br>

a) transcendental quest for the objective boundaries of intellect (Verstand) & reason (Vernunft) in the subject of knowledge ;<br>

b) 'Copernican Revolution' : Man imposes Nature his own a priori-categories ;<br>

c) focussed on a new, scientific metaphysics which does not move beyond the boundaries necessary for our intellect to function properly ;</li><br><br>

The <b>fall </b>of the Modern Ideal :<br><br>

<li>5.<b>Technologicism</b> from 1850 till Worldwar I :<br>

a) metaphysics & theology are negative values, facts are positive (Comte) ;<br>

b) 'sense-data' are the foundation of knowledge & emergent materialism ;<br>

c) a definite movement towards a new 'scientific' class & its logical-postivist monolith ;<br></li><br>

<li>6.<b>Institutionalism</b> from 1945 till early '70 :<br>

a) rapid global divulgation of the 'black box'-model ; <br>

b) valid knowledge is tested & consensual : scientific elitarism ; <br>

c) focussed on the metaphysics of permanent scientific discovery & material growth !

<br><br><h3><a name="log">Has postmodernism a particular logic ?</a></h3>

<li>The 'logic' of postmodernism can be found in the texts of Lyotard, Rorty, Foucault, Derrida, although the latter (often called a poststructuralist) does not use the term to define his views. This 'logic' is very unformal but analytically sharp. It is refined & grotesk. Derrida introduced so-called 'deconstruction' into Western philosophical thought. For Derrida, <b>Western thought as a whole is a philosophy of presence</b>. Socrates, who inspired Plato when the latter wrote the first Western philosophical texts did not write. However, because Plato listened to Socrates and textualized his words, Socrates is said to be present in our minds when we read Plato's text (we, not present when Socrates was uttering his own words !). The text refers to something outside the text itself. This presence is summoned up by the text to sustain a mental mechanism through which a certain conscious unity of the text and the presence outside the text is realized. Spoken words are considered as symbols of mental experiences and written words are the symbols of spoken words (cfr. Aristotle). This logocentrism is also a phonocentrism : absolute proximity of voice and being, of voice and meaning of being, of voice and the ideality of meaning. Derrida does not reject this philosophy of presence. Because his deconstruction takes place 'in the margin' of its mayor texts, it seems that presence & absence form a pair. Deconstruction takes place in a consciousness aware of the pair, of this formidable difference between the so-called presence of being in texts and the absence of the being of the man Plato knew, Socrates. Derrida answers : there is nothing outside the text.

<br><br>(In our view modernism is an example of an exclusivism of presence.)<br><br>

Logocentricm is a determination of the being of an object as presence. In this way linguistics remains completely enclosed within a classical conceptuality in which false exits occur, i.e. a transcendental signified. By marking these in a text (for example by adding an asterix*) one menaces the history and the life of the spirit of self-presence, one menaces substantiality. For by allowing the text to summon a presence outside the text we delude ourselves by creating a fiction through the medium of that book, programme or film. So although deconstruction does not interfere with the summoning of the spirit of identity, it adds little notes in the margin of the text. In these a remark is made which shows how a hidden passage was taken in this or that passage of the text. These passages taken together suggest a meta-level of meaning delimitation, unnoticed strands of hidden variables which -after analysis- prove to contain infinite reiterations, with unexpected & unparallelled complexities. Otherwise these remain absent. Has Heidegger's conception of thruth after "die Kehre" as "a-lethèia", i.e. both unhidden & hidden inspired Derrida ? Two conclusion at the close of modernism are really consensual : most questions remain open & the human kingdom is still ignorant. <br><br>

By understanding the importance of the difference between presence and absence one may become aware of the word-ontology characterizing Western philosophy. Perhaps the real thing is not made present by words ?<br><br>

For more information on deconstruction see our two <b>Dutch texts </b>on epistemology (for which translators are sought) : <a href="7nproleg.htm">Prolegomena (1994)</a> & <a href= "7nkennis.htm"> Knowledge, Chaos & Metaphysics, volume 1 : Knowledge (1995).</a></li><br><br>

<li><a name= "crit">The criticism of our mild postmodern position :</a><br><br>

a) discarts a discourse in which knowledge is eternalized ;<br>

b) stresses a pluralistic, faillibilistic & multidisciplinary approach of rationality instead of a one-dimensional model ; <br> 

c) avoids a vision of science in which the uniqueness of scientific knowledge -when considering the different ways to organize society- is stressed ;<br>

d) replaces the confrontational dialectics between science & metaphysics with the idea that metaphysics can not be eliminated without hurting the scientific ideal, i.e. information of which one can say that is 'true' knowledge ;<br>

e) avoids the foundational approach in which all 'true' knowledge has a sufficient ground (in experimental data and/or in theoretical constructs) ;<br>

f) confirms the Piagetian theory that cognitive growth is the result of conceptual conflict (between an individual & his intellectual peers) rather than conceptual similarity (between individuals).</li><br><br>

<li>In our opinion scientific knowledge is related to 2 of 3 approaches to the one reality :</li><br><br>

a) <b>reality-for-me</b> (the personal approach) : can be known by experiencing & conceptualizing the constituants of my own personal experience ; <br>

b) <b>reality-for-us</b> (the intersubjective approach) : can be known by conceptualizing the constituants of the experience of reality shared with others through facts (experiment) hand in hand with dialogue (and if necessary argumentation) ;<br>

c) <b>reality-as-such</b> (the transcendent approach) : has to be postulated as 'knowable' without us being able to encompass it with our minds, implying that the facts (considered as revealing this absolute, one reality) have always to be thought off as open to further corrections. Reality-as-such is the object of a transcent metaphysics*, moving beyond the limits imposed upon our intellects (or scientific minds). Science is not equipped to enter this realm of the absolute order of things. Transcent metaphysics* implies a non-verbal & unknowing intuitive insight* into the order of things-as-such. <br> 

<br>

<h3>How to structure our Mild Postmodern Philosophy ?</h3>   

<li>HISTORICAL Philosophy : 'logistics' of philosophy on the basis

of past facts.</li><br><br>

<li>SYSTEMATIC Philosophy : 'topology' of philosophy on the basis

of different objects of investigation :</li><br><br>

- <I>Normative Philosophy </I> : the rules Man should Mind in following

disciplines :<br><br>

* logic : order, meaning & symbolization (true/false)<br>

* epistemology : theory on knowledge & method (corroborated/falsified)</li><br>       

* esthetics : the exemplaric & emancipation (beauty/ugliness)</li><br>

* ethics : theory on just change & geo-politics (good/evil)</li><br><br>

- <I>Descriptive Philosophy </I> : philosophical investigations into psychology, economics, sociology, politicology, religion, mysticism & other areas.<br><br>

<li>THEORETICO-PRACTICAL Philosophy : meta-nominal speculations on Nature

(natural philosophy), Man (philosophical antropology), Being (ontology), God (theology), Language, History, Religion ... and their practical applications.</li><br><br> 

<a name="cor"><hr><h3>Corpus Equiaeon</a></h3>

<h5>During 1996 <I>all texts & musical compositions</I> will be made available in WP51-format op CD-rom. Texts marked with # will be offered in this departement soon.</h5><br>

<li><h4><a href= "#philo">Philosophy</a></li><br>

<li><a href= "#text">Texts & Comments</a></li><br>

</h4><hr><br>

<FONT size="+2">T</FONT>he Corpus Equiaeon is the body of a moderate postmodern philosophical system*. Its method is open & flexible without negating the reasonable. Example : as in

the case of a catalyst, the influence of this rigidly sustained philosophical

discipline should not be discernable in the final product, i.e. solved problems.<br>

<br>

So to its readers, the Corpus offers cognitive instruments which they can &

must use in order to build up their own new insights. In spite of this rather

mysterious way to bestow knowledge, the Corpus do holds totalizing rational

claims, seemingly fulfilled through a large body of texts (on epistemology,

cosmology, anthropology, aesthetics, ethics, metaphysics, hermetics, ...).

These texts contain the knowledge necessary to allow its readers to deal in a

creative way with the fact that our rational knowledge is incomplete.<br><br>

<li><h3><a name="philo">Philosophy</a></h3> </li>

Basic text :<br>

<a href= "7etltc.htm">1.Tractatus Logico Tragi-Comicus</a> (TLTC, 1992, 245p)<br><br>

The TLTC is an English lexicon (cornerstone or keystone) in which all ideas which are to be elaborated later are loosely defined. In 1996 this book will be revised and  supplemented with comments.<br><br>

Core : an 8-dimensional model of the Universe ruled by 3 independent, irreducible but centralizing meta-entropic operators, namely Consciousness (C), Information (I) and Matter (M). Study of the axioms of its 4 divisions : 'prima materia', logic, aesthetics and ethics. Basic definitions and premises. Keys for a comparative philosophy.<br><br>

<a href= "7nstuurk.htm">2) Towards a Cybernetic Anthropology (1993, 113p, Dutch)</a><br><br>

Conventional but eclectic study of man, examining -through a functionalistic approach- the cognitive genesis of the 4 'nominal' dimensions of consciousness, taking into account the ideas of S.Freud, L.Kohlberg & A.Maslow.<br><br>

3) Codex Eroticus (1993, 41p, English) #<br><br>

Logic of love. The 'codices' are texts that are linked up with the TLTC (numbers of concordance can be found on every page).<br><br>

4) Codex Diabolicus (1993, 11p, English) #<br><br>

Logic of hate. Unlike the Roman Catholic dogma, this infernal metaphysics argues in favour of the complete and irreversible end of the Devil, who -mythically spoken- at the end of time (when the 'Jubilee of Jubilees' or the 'apokatastasis' is celebrated) is totally consumed by God.<br><br>

<a href="7nesthet.htm">5) Towards an Aesthetic of the Excellent Exemplaric & the Sublime Beyond </a>(1993, 72p, Dutch) <br><br>

Aesthetical theory inspired by Kantian exemplarism borne upon a sublime integration of harmonization (order) and disharmonization (chaos).<br><br>

<a href = "7nmystic.htm">6) Knowledge and Love-Mysticism </a> (1994, 416p, Dutch)<br><br>

On love in the work of Beatrix of Nazareth, the mystical knowledge-manipulation and its strictly negative & symbolic theology. Provided are : a general and contextual study of Flemish mysticism, a commentary on and critique of Beatrix's treatise and a study of the totalizing mental operators supporting contemplation and the yearning for God contemplation of God through God).<br><br>

7) The Royal Formula (1994, 34p, English) #<br><br>

Practical layout of Patañjali's path to liberation and method of meta-nominal inquiry.<br><br>

<a href= "7nproleg.htm">8) Prolegomena or the Rules of the Game of 'True' Knowledge</a> (1994, 216p, Dutch)<br><br> 

Epistemological inquiry into the unfounded foundation of all thinking in the light of a critical, strictly nominalistic & moderate postmodern view on science and rationality. Preliminary to 'Knowledge, Chaos & Metaphysics' (1995).<br><br>

<a href="7ededeo.htm">9) De Deo </a>(1995, 10p, English)<br><br>

Short summary of the axioms of our apofatic & qabalistic theology. The difference made between the unknowable God (uncreated & creating) and the knowable Creator (created & creating) showing Himself as a Trinity of Father, Son & Holy Spirit, is essential.<br><br>

10) Knowledge, Chaos & Metaphysics (volume 1 : 1995, 456p, Dutch) <br><br>

Volume 1 : <a href= "7nkennis.htm">Knowledge</a><br>

Complete epistemology (theory & practice of knowledge) preceded by a study of transcendental logic. A mild, postmodern epistemology is offered, resulting in the methodology of a refined participative observation. Study of Western metaphysics & criteria for a valid immanent metaphysical project (volume 3). This work was introduced by the Prolegomena of 1994.<br><br>

11) Remarks about Death & Resurrection (1994 & 1996, 49p, English) #<br><br>

Short remarks from a revised Christian perspective about the afterlife, the role of Jesus Christ, reincarnation, resurrection & the spiritual task of Satan.<br><br>

<li><h3><a name="text">Basic Texts with Comments</a></h3> </li>

<a href= "7nzevenm.htm">1) On Seven Ways of Holy Love </a>(1993, 41p, Dutch)<br><br>

Translation from Middle Dutch into contemporary Dutch of the mystic text of Beatrix of Nazareth (1200 - 1268), prefaced by a short introduction.<br><br>

2) Sepher Yetzirah (1993, 72p, Dutch) #<br><br>

Translation of and commentary on the first chapter of the 'Book of Creation'.<br><br>

3) Yoga-sûtra, Book 1 : the Samâdhi-Pâda (1993, 88p, Dutch) #<br><br>

Translation of and commentary on the first book of Patañjali's Yoga-sûtra.<br><br>

<a href= "7nzeven.htm">4) On Seven Ways of Holy Love : an Interpretation</a> (1995, 214p, Dutch) <br><br>

Complete revised interpretation of the text of Beatrix of Nazareth, preceded by all the philological & biographical data.<br><br>

<a name="pneu"><hr><h3>Pneuma Equiaeon</a></h3><hr><br>

<FONT size="+2">A</FONT>s soon as this body of texts is large enough, a hermeneutical metalevel is introduced. A critical deconstruction (false exits being marked with an asterix) counters the claims expressed by the texts. Among others, the author -in his autobiographical critique- uncovers the hidden motives of some of his choices. This metalevel, called 'Pneuma', will also be co-responsible for the further development of the system*. Its main aim is to undermine in a radical & stern way any dogmatic inclination manifesting itself in the indexed textual auditorium. The Pneuma is part of a Know Tree i.e. a multi-accessible systematic hypertext with a maximum of 10.000 categories. This Know Tree is build or customized in accordance to a thesaurus or any chosen library classification system. Moreover, there are also hyperlinking possibilities and a general indexing feature indexing all words of all texts.<br><br>

<a name="self"><hr><h3>Self Equiaeon</a></h3><hr><br>

<FONT size="+2">O</FONT>ffering this philosophy to the worldcommunity via the Internet is the Self-level of this system. For no human creative work starts off "ex nihilo". An author has to communicate continuously if s/he wants to interact with the problems at hand. In that respect the Internet offers unseen possibilities. We invite everyone to <a href="mailto:siberti@innet.be">react to our texts</a>. The further development of our system will thus be influenced by, with and in the worldcommunity of sign-interpreters. <br><br>In the commercial 'new age'-movement emphasis is placed upon individual growth, meaning that the Self of each person is understood to be essential. This is a narrow view, for <b> it is a fact that we receive most and that intersubjective interaction is essential when emancipating</b> <b>consciousness.</b> So this Self-level of our system is of a christian denomination. It grows as a result of the reactions we get from others and the interactions we trigger. No philosophy aiming at giving meaning to life is devoid of the co-creative input from others.<br><br>  

<a name="spira"><hr><h3>Spira Equiaeon</a></h3><hr><br>

<FONT size="+2">T</FONT>he 'spira' of this system is its inner twist, i.e. its growth-symbols & conclusions, guiding people to solve their questions about <I> the origin, meaning & finality of human existence</I>. It's evident that the information presented in the  2.300 pages of the Corpus (anno 1995) <b>are most surely unable to convey all the arguments in favour of the conclusions reached</b>. More work has to be done. However, these conclusions constitute a first frame-work acting as a floodgate between levels of critical introspection ('pneumatic' in the first degree, 'Selfmatic' in the second, 'spiramatic' in the third). Because of auto-critical considerations the network of each conclusion is liable to change when more Corpus-texts materialize. The frame-work itself is an abstract & formal formulation of the basic tenets or options found in the body of texts.<br><br>

The categories of these conclusions are :<br><br>

<li>10. Holism :</li> the World (nature, cosmos, universe & Man) is an absolute & continuous continuum in which members have their proper explicate fields of manifested  existence & mutual, fruitful, dynamical & intelligent operations, whereas all members of it are united through an implicate superfield, permanently negating the idea of the world as a collection of 'disjecta membra' (the World as 'nature morte').<br><br>

<li>9. Hylic pluralism :</li> the World is a continuum in which material processes take place in a multi-dimensional way, i.e. <a href="matter.htm">matter</a> (M) embraces both ordinary, 'nominal' or four-dimensional M, and its finer, more subtle manifestations. As meta-nominal M has less inertia than nominal M, our state of consciousness interacts more vividly in every real encounter with the former. Our knowledge about meta-nominal M is -to our own peril- diminishing.<br><br>

<li>8. Organicism :</li> the parts of the World are like the organs of a body. The universe is limited & temporal. To understand a part of the World one should make sure that all possible connection with the other parts of the World are not artificially reduced to that number figuring in one's own theory. The logic of organicism does not exclude chaotic functions from the discription of life, nor is it necessarily linked with a pyramidal <a href="informat.htm">information</a>-format, as networking & so-called 'stochastic coincidental events' are part of the opportunistic logic of life's evolution. <br><br>

<li>7. Agapism & Erotism :</li> spiritual love hand in hand with passions bridled in every way, are the only valid means to achieve a permanent & evergrowing state of  happiness.<br><br>

<li>6. Creationism :</li> the World has been created, is permanently recreated and will eventually end. Creationism values creativity as a very important intellectual property as such, both for the individual as in society.<br><br>

<li>5. Auto-criticism :</li> no philosophy, science or common sense regarding the World is completely without unsolved paradoxes, flagrant incompletenesses or shameful contradictions. Moreover, a philosopher should construe his (her) system* in such a way as to make sure his (her) messages comes across while the means to do so (the texts) hopefullly auto-deconstruct themselves by uncovering their proper absurdities.<br><br>

<li>4. Unicism :</li> a mayor regulating idea in science is the unity of all possible knowledge. Without variety the generalizing power of unity is eclipsed. Without unity no order is possible and anarchy ensues. To have both variety & unity is possible if unity is always reached at but never gained (never possessed).<br><br>

<li>3. Symbolism :</li> cognitive growth beyond the nominal level of formal-operational conditioning necessitates (besides signs) the use of totalizing visual matrices (symbols) enabling the emotional hemisphere to form an understream of <a href= "consc.htm">conscious</a> emotions triggering new processes of thought (cfr. action, meta-action = emotion, meta-emotion = thought, meta-thought = intuition).<br><br>

<li>2. Apophatism :</li> God (in the qabalah 'ain soph aur') can not be known or experienced. In a possible negative theology we arrive at the formula : God equals 'all possibilities' (potential reality). As this virtual reality -from our perspective 'sub specie temporis'- does 'not exist', God is not. However, this so-called 'nothingness' of God created, so does tradition claim, the cosmoi. Clearly it differs from the void visualized as the terminal of so-called thermodynamical death. Here the possibility of regeneration is totally absent. From intuïtive gatherings the idea emerges that God (unknown, creating, uncreated) created the first of the Elohîm (Kether, creating, created) and the World (2, 3, ... 10).  So through Kether God is living (in this cosmos).<br><br>

<li>1. Pan-en-theïsm :</li><br>(objective) : God is one absolute one-fold potential creating "ex nihilo" a manifested Creator (first Elohîm, demiurg). How can we know whether God cares for the World created by God's Creator ? The Creator (alternating between virtuality & manifestation) is paradoxical. He is equal to His creation (pantheïsm) but is not 'causa sui'.<br>

(subjective) : Man is unable to know God (cfr.deïsm). He is however able to move back to the First Cause (cfr.theïsm), experience & know his Creator through Jesus the Christ (christianity).<br> 

<br>

