</a><br clear=all><br>
<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>

<h1 align=center>Back to the roots<br>
Sugar cane</h1>


<font size=4>Sugar cane, a giant grass from the same family as sorghum and maize, thrives in the heat and damp of tropical climates - so most of it comes from the Third World<p>

<center></center><br clear=all>

<hr width=71%><p>


<br><br>

Growing up to five metres high, with stalks 5cm thick, canes can be propagated from cut stems. Once the cane has been cut, the stubble sprouts again for the following year. This process, called ratooning, can get a yearly harvests from cane for up to seven years<p>

<br clear=all><p>
<hr width=71%><p>




Sugar can be converted into ethanol for use as motor fuel. Brazil started 'gasahol' production in an attempt to use up sugar stocks, but the rise in oil prices in the late 70s made sugar-fuel an attractive alternative for many Brazilians. Now almost half Brazil's sugar output goes to make fuel<br clear=all><p><hr width=71%><p>

<br><br>

Sugar cane is tough enough to survive floods, cyclones, and hurricanes, but in many places it is still cut by hand. Controlled burning removes the leaves: this reduces the sucrose content, but makes the crop easier to harvest<br clear=all>
<p>
<hr width=71%><p>



<center></center><br>

Although most sugar cane is grown for commercial use, some is grown by small farmers for their own consumption<p><hr width=71%><p>



<br>


Cane has to be processed soon after cutting. It is washed, shredded, and crushed, then the extract soaked in water. The mixture is heated until the water evaporates, leaving concentrated sucrose which crystallises into 'raw' sugar. By-products are molasses (used to make rum), baker's yeast, and cattle feed, and fibrous bagasse, used to fuel the sugar factory
<p>
<br clear=all>


</font>
<p><hr>
<center><h3>[<a href="index.html">Oxfam news contents</a>] [<a href="../index.html">Oxfam Home Page</a>]</h3><p>
<hr></center>

</body>
