<html>
<head>
<title>Family planning: the male point of view</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="../ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i>
<br clear=left>

<hr>



<h1>Family planning: the male point of view</h1>

<b>by Malcolm Potts</b><p>








<b>All reasonable people subscribe to the ideal of a loving human family, where the man shares in all levels of bringing up his children.  At the same time, when it comes to mating and parenting, men and women have different needs and expectations.  Here, <i>Malcolm Potts, President of International Family Health and Bixby Professor of Population and International Health at the University of California at Berkeley</i>, looks at male attitudes to family planning methods and services.</b><p>




In the animal world the sex that makes the greatest investment in reproduction tends to adopt the most cautious mating behaviour and the one that makes least investment tends to be more competitive and risk taking.  Birds such as penguins and swans are monogamous because both sexes are able to incubate the eggs and bring food to the fledglings.  In mammals, however, biology forces the females to make a disproportionate investment in pregnancy and breast-feeding, and therefore most male mammalian species are polygamous.  The males compete for access to females but they make no investment whatsoever in their offspring other than to supply the fertilizing sperm.<p>






Human beings are unusual in that all societies recognize a male interest in his children and men naturally nurture, protect and educate their children.  However, parenting remains an asymmetrical investment.  In practically every known society men are more likely than women to have extra-marital affairs, but when divorce occurs the women nearly always end up caring for the children.<p>




Overall, women have good reasons to be more concerned and careful over family planning because they have more to lose.  But men have an equally strong desire to separate the pleasures of sex from the cost of bringing up children.  For both sexes family planning providers must make services accessible and take the perceptions of users into account.  Are men more interested in the erotic aspects of contraception?  Do they sometimes seek group solidarity?  Do they want to be assured of their partner's faithfulness?  Family planning is listening to what people want, not telling them what to do.<p>



<h4>Male orientated services</h4>
In Iran in the 1960s an alert psychologist called Siassi noted only 12 per cent of women who began taking oral contraceptives were still using them six months later.  Instead of blaming the consumer for this disappointing result, he changed the distribution system. He gathered together the husbands of the same group of women and told them how Pills worked and distributed the contraceptives to the men to pass on to their wives.  The continuation rate at six months jumped to over 80 per cent.  No change in pharmacology ever led to such a dramatic change in use as this alteration to the distribution system.  Clearly, Iranian men were comfortable seeing their wives use contraception if they could be directly involved, but threatened if the women appeared to act unilaterally.  Outsiders may hope Iranian society will evolve to give women greater autonomy, but in the real world helping couples avoid unintended pregnancies is an immediate and real liberation of women.<p>


<h4>Many men accept vasectomy</h4>

Male attitudes have not proved a barrier to the adoption of vasectomy.  The problem is creating commonsense services that men can attend.  Vasectomies outnumber tubal ligations (female sterilization) in Ireland because some family doctors provide them, while tubal ligation is not performed in Catholic hospitals.  In South Korea in the 1960s vasectomy exceeded tubal ligation because government policy made it available.  Most family planning services around the world are orientated towards women and it is a fairly simple rule that men, particularly from a traditional society, are not going to wait in a clinic crowded with women.  Dr Marcus de Castro of PROPATER showed this brilliantly in Brazil in the 1970s:  men who chose vasectomy tended to be those who divided their marital roles.  They were firemen, policemen, members of the armed services, who on the whole did not help with the washing up or volunteer to change the baby's nappies.<p>




The art of family planning is to provide a service the provider might not choose for him or herself, but which responds to the perceptions of the user.  In Bombay in the 1960s Dr Datta Pai<br> 

<pre>
</pre>
<ul><blockquote>
<font size=5><i>&quot;For both sexes we must make services accessible and respond to the perceptions of the users.&quot;</i></font><br></blockquote></ul>
<pre>
</pre>


noted that poor, illiterate men in India who wanted a vasectomy perceived a hospital to be somewhere where "you we nt to die".  Hence when he offered vasectomy in a hospital setting few men came.  When he offered the same operation on railway stations more vasectomies were performed in one month than had been done in hospitals in the previous year - if the operation could be done on platform 9 it must be safe!  In Bangkok thousands of vasectomies have been offered in a "camp" setting as part of the celebrations of the King of Thailand's birthday.  Unfortunately, ethnocentric Western advisers have browbeaten the Indian Government to stop promoting such events.<p>


<h4>Male unmet need for contraception</h4>

Many couples are happy with coitus interruptus (withdrawal) as a method of preventing pregnancy.  Withdrawal averts many more births than new methods like sub-dermal hormonal implants ever will, yet it receives almost no scientific attention and it is commonly dismissed as ineffective or as damaging to a sexual partnership.  The little objective data available, however, suggest that the failure rate for the method overlaps with that for condoms.  If a couple love each other they can achieve satisfaction when using coitus interruptus, and if they do not, then the best technology will not repair absent affection or lack of a wish to share in sexual pleasures.<p>




Easy availability and a sensitive ability to respond to the client's perceptions is the key to most family planning provision . The most useful and important male method remains the condom.  It is also the first line of defence against infection with a sexually transmitted disease and HIV transmission. In many countries (for example Ethiopia and Pakistan) condom sales in social marketing programmes are held back not by lack of demand, but by lack of supplies.  Given the appropriate promotion of correctly priced brands, sales will go up, and as some men use the method more will want to.<p>




Men will willingly become involved in family planning decisions if service providers try to see the world through their eyes, and focus resources on helping those with the greatest need.<p>








 
<hr><p>

