<HTML>

<HEAD>

<title>The Development Policy of the Federal Republic of Germany</title>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<hr>

<H3><CENTER></H3>

<h3>The Development Policy of the Federal Republic of Germany

<P>

<i>Guido Ashoff</i></h3>

<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>

</I>No. 5, September-October 1996: pages 26 - 31</h4>

<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>



<hr><br> D+C is published

by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.

Subscriptions and further information are available from: The

Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,

D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69

7501-4855. </H5>

<HR>

<P>

<b>German development cooperation is in a difficult phase. The Federal

government claims its aid is contributing to securing the global

future. But this is confronted by declining financial commitments

and a growing scepticism among the German public about the success

of development cooperation as a whole. So Bonn's development policy

is facing several challenges. It needs more money, sustainable

improvement of its effectiveness and efficiency, more influence

on other policies, intensive public relations, a more realistic

portrayal of the impacts development cooperation can achieve,

and a more precise determination of its role in Germany's relations

with developing countries.</b>

<P>

Germany's Official Development Assistance (ODA) began in 1952

with a financial contribution to a UN programme to support the

economic development of Third World countries. In 1956, the Foreign

Ministry set up a DM 50 million fund for bilateral aid. And at

the end of the 1950s the Bonn Parliament came out for an active

North south policy. The growing volume of aid, handled by various

federal ministries, as well as party politics within the conservative liberal

coalition government of the day, led to the establishment of the

Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation (BMZ) in 1961. Liberal

Free Democrat Walter Scheel was its first minister. In 1993, the

words &quot;and Development&quot; were added to its name.

<P>

Initially, the BMZ was a coordinating ministry. In 1964, it was

given competence for development cooperation principles and programmes,

as well as for Technical Cooperation (TC). In 1972, under minister

Erhard Eppler, its remit was expanded to cover bilateral and multilateral

Financial Cooperation (FC). It was only then that development

policy was established de facto as a separate policy.

<P>

<B>Quantitative aspects</B>

<P>

Measured against absolute ODA volumes, Germany is one of the world's

largest donors (1993: DM 11.5 billion, or US$ 6.95 billion). It

ranks fourth after Japan, the USA and France. But Germany's ODA-GNP

ratio positions it midfield among the 21 donor country members

of the OECD's Development Assistance Committee (DAC). In 1993,

with an ODA-GNP share of 0.36 per cent, it came ninth.

<P>

Assessment of the ODA volume depends upon the frame of reference.

Germany's ODA appears marginal when compared, for example, with

its trade with developing countries (1993: exports plus imports

totalled about DM 200 billion). This is also the case when Bonn's

ODA is measured against its transfers to Germany's new eastern

Lander (states) of about DM 150 billion a year. These have recently

often been used as a yardstick. But on the other hand, German

ODA has to date exceeded private flows to developing countries

at market conditions.

<P>

No-one disputes that Germany has not yet achieved the UN's 0.7

per cent ODA GNP target, to which the Federal government again gave the nod

at the 1992 Rio Earth Summit. Nor that Bonn has in recent years

dropped further away from it. The German ODA-GNP ratio reached

its high water mark in 1982/83 with 0.48 per cent. But since 1990

(0.42 per cent), its ODA share has fallen steadily. In 1993 it

was 0.36 per cent, and it dropped to 0.33 per cent in 1994.

<P>

True, Germany is not the only DAC donor with declining ODA-GNP

ratios. The ODA budgets of numerous other countries have been

squeezed for some years, justifying talk of a financial crisis

in international development assistance. But the drop in Germany's

ODA-GNP ratio is disproportionately large when measured against

the DAC average (1990: 0.33 per cent; 1993: 0.30 per cent). Bonn

blames public spending constraints for the fall. But development

cooperation's diminished political status in the Federal budget

must not be overlooked. BMZ's share of the budget, which covers

most of German ODA (see Table 1), dropped from 2.4 per cent in

1989 to 1.7 per cent in 1995 (its top share was 2.6 per cent),

and will probably hardly increase to 1998.

<P>

German development cooperation includes not only ODA, but also

development assistance by NGOs, such as churches, foundations

and associations, from their own funds and donations. Over the

years, they have accounted for an amazingly constant equivalent

of 11-12 per cent of ODA, which should be differentiated from

the subsidies these organizations receive from the government.



<P>

<table border=1 cellpadding=8>

<caption><b>Table 1: Quantitative trends (Net disbursements in DM mill.)</b></caption>

<tr><td><td>1960<td>1970<td>1980<td>1990<td>1993<td>1950-93

<tr><td>1. ODA<td>938.8<td>2202.8<td>6476.1<td>10213.2<td>11504.6<td>182393.5

<tr><td>% of GNP<td>0.31<td>0.33<td>0.44<td>0.42<td>0.36<td>-

<tr><td>-BMZ budget<td>2018.0<td>5401.8<td>7864.7<td>8279.9<td>135471.8<td>a)

<tr><td>% of federal budget<td>2.5<td>2.6<td>2.0<td>1.8<td>-

<tr><td>bilateral<td>690.8<td>1705.9<td>4219.0<td>7238.3<td>7472.9<td>127076.2

<tr><td>multilateral<td>248.0<td>496.6<td>2257.1<td>2975.0<td>4031.7<td>55317.3

<tr><td>2. Private development aid b)<td>284.6<td>763.9<td>1222.7<td>1434.1<td>20700.5

<tr><td>3. Other official inputs<td>539.0<td>483.5<td>1144.1<td>3410.0<td>3033.6<td>36202.6

<tr><td>a) 1964-93, b) Subsidies from NGOs from own funds and donations<br>

Source: BMZ

</tr></table>

<p>



<B>Who provides aid?</B>

<P>

German ODA's actors are very diverse. This applies to the financing

(provision of funds), as well as the implementation of projects

and programmes. The German ODA reported to the DAC embraces:

<P>

<ul>

<li>BMZ development assistance totalling more than 70 per cent of ODA, making it the most important actor;

<P>

<li>development assistance of other Federal ministries, above all the Foreign Ministry (humanitarian aid,

materials and equipment assistance, cultural cooperation, contributions

to UN organizations); the Ministry of Education, Science, Research

and Technology; and the Ministry of Economics; and

<P>

<li>development assistance of the federal states (Lander) (study

place costs for students from developing countries, and own cooperation

measures).</ul>

<P>

In addition, there are Germany's contributions to the EU's development

budget, debt servicing relief, and part of the expenditure on

political refugees in Germany. The involvement of several ministries

in development cooperation is more

marked in some other donor countries than in Germany, for example,

in France and Japan.

<P>

A peculiarity of German development cooperation is the developmental

commitment of the L&#228;nder. They are involved primarily in the education

sector, but for some years have also promoted their own projects.

German municipalities also engage in developmental activities

in the context of partnerships and local government cooperation.

<P>

<B>Bilateral and multilateral aid</B>

<P>

Germany perceives itself first and foremost as a bilateral donor.

Its bilateral ODA

accounted for 70 per cent of its overall development assistance

to 1993 (see Table 1). Bonn bases this above all on its claim,

as one of the major donors, to operate its own development policy.

It says it has specialised and differentiated instruments for

implementing this policy. But it has also in recent years increasingly

criticized the lack of efficiency of multilateral cooperation.

Its unwritten guideline could read: &quot;As much bilateral aid

as possible, as much multilateral aid as necessary.&quot;

<P>

After Japan and the USA, Germany is the third largest financial

supporter of multilateral cooperation (as at 1993), and ranks

first on the EU development aid league table. Over the years,

Bonn has fulfilled its intention, declared in the 1970s, to earmark

about 30 per cent of its ODA for multilateral cooperation. This

is despite fluctuations which were due primarily to the payment

cycle. Germany has also collaborated steadfastly in multilateral

organizations and pressed for reforms. And it has renounced spectacular

steps such as the withdrawal of the USA and Britain from UNESCO.

From 1950 to 1993, 41.6 per cent of Germany's multilateral ODA

went to the European Community or Union, 39.6 per cent to the

World Bank and the regional development banks, 14.7 per cent to

UN organizations and funds, and 4.1 per cent to others.

<P>

Germany has always supported EC or EU development cooperation

(strictly speaking, the EU is a supranational, and not a multilateral,

institution), which above all had its roots in French and British

self interests, as well as European Parliament ventures. Not least,

Bonn has been the main financial contributor. But it has never

played a leading role as an initiator. In contrast to France and

Britain, whose colonial legacy has strongly influenced the regional

alignment of EC/EU development cooperation, Germany has from the

start preferred a more global approach to it. Bonn has also criticized the European Development Fund's

disproportionately low level of procurement orders to German contractors

compared with French companies, and the inefficiencies of EU aid.

<P>

The federal government has for a long time advocated better coordination

of EU development cooperation, although not a stronger communalising

of the member countries' individual aid programmes. Germany therefore

appears to be more reserved in the development cooperation field

than might be expected because of its intensive efforts for political

union. In that respect, the Maastricht Treaty, which lays down

that EU and bilateral development cooperation should be complementary,

corresponds completely with the Federal government's intentions.



<P>

<table border=1 cellpadding=8>

<caption><b>Table 2: Regional distribution of bilateral ODA<br>(Gross disbursements in %)</b></caption>

<tr><td><td>1970/71<td>1980/81<td>1992/93

<tr><td>Europe<td>8.7<td>15.5<td>15.4

<tr><td>Sub-Saharan Africa<td>15.8<td>29.2<td>24.8

<tr><td>America<td>16.0<td>11.6<td>11.5

<tr><td>North Africa, Near and Middle East<td>18.8<td>14.1<td>20.9

<tr><td>Asia and Oceania<td>40.5<td>29.7<td>27.5

<tr><td>Share of LDCs<td>13.8<td>39.4<td>21.7

<tr><td>Source: DAC Report 1994

</tr></table>



<P>

<B>Regional focal points</B>

<P>

The development cooperation of France and Britain reflects their

ties to their former colonies. US aid is concentrated on Israel

and Egypt for security policy reasons. In contrast, Germany's

assistance was from the beginning guided by the principle that

it was open to the world. This was in line

with Bonn's foreign policy interests; a striving for worldwide

recognition and preventing international acceptance of the GDR.

But it also stuck the then West Germany's aid with the label of

being based on the principle of &quot;something for everyone&quot;.

<P>

This type-casting hits the mark in terms of the great number of

countries with which the Federal Republic fosters developmental

relations. In 1992, German Technical Cooperation (TC) projects

were either being appraised, prepared or implemented in 150 countries.

And new TC commitments had been made to 130 countries. The corresponding

figures for Financial Cooperation (FC) were 105 and 66 countries.

<P>

However, German development cooperation is clearly concentrated.

During the period 195093, 26 per cent of Germany's net bilateral

ODA disbursements were made to the five most important recipient

countries (India, Israel, Egypt, Turkey and Indonesia), and 37

per cent to the 10 most important countries. This reflects foreign

policy and geopolitical interests.

<P>

Table 2 shows the regional distribution of German aid. It makes

clear that sub saharan Africa's share has increased, while Asia's has declined. The share of least developed countries (LDCs)

fluctuates considerably, and in 1993 equalled about the DAC average.

Other donors such as the EU or some Scandinavian countries have

greater LDC disbursements.

<P>

The BMZ (not least due to pressure from the Parliamentary Budget

Committee) has for some years been trying to reduce the number

of recipient countries and achieve a stronger regional concentration

of German aid. The main motive is to improve the effectiveness

and efficiency of cooperation by bundling it. The BMZ also intends

to foster development cooperation only with partner countries

whose political and economic general conditions favour successful

cooperation. The effort to downsize the number of recipient countries

is in line with the &quot;graduation&quot; of threshold countries

who &quot;grow out&quot; of development aid. On the other hand,

other countries have become new German development cooperation

partners (Albania, the Central Asian and Caucasian developing

countries, and South Africa).

<P>

<B>Aid for the East at the cost of the South?</B>

<P>

Since the beginning of the 1990s, Germany has been the leading

western donor in financially supporting the transformation process

of the Central and East European countries and the successor states

of the former Soviet Union. In 1993, it accounted for about one third

of the official aid of all DAC member countries. German official

aid to those countries, without the Central Asian and Caucasian

states which the DAC has meanwhile recognised as developing countries,

as well as Albania, totalled about US$ 8.4 billion in 1991 93.

The disbursements thereby accounted for almost 40 per cent of

Bonn's total ODA to developing countries. But they were not made

at the cost of the South. Most of the money did not come from

the BMZ's budget, but of course it increased the general spending

burden of the Federal budget.



<P>

<table border=1 cellpadding=8>

<caption><b>Table 3: Sectoral distribution of bilateral commitments in %</b></caption>

<tr><td><td>1989<td>1990<td>1991<td>1992<td>1993

<tr><td>Social/admin. infrastructure<td>27.0<td>24.7<td>22.3<td>23.8<td>25.3

<tr><td>Education<td>(16.4)<td>(14.2)<td>(11.6)<td>(11.6)<td>(13.4)

<tr><td>Economic infrastructure<td>31.6<td>22.8<td>21.5<td>13.3<td>20.9

<tr><td>Productive sectors<td>18.4<td>15.8<td>8.8<td>14.0<td>12.6

<tr><td>Agriculture<td>(6.5)<td>(7.3)<td>(5.4)<td>(5.1)<td>(8.2)

<tr><td>Programme aid (goods)<td>4.7<td>13.0<td>9.6<td>6.7<td>2.2

<tr><td>Debt remission/relief<td>3.0<td>8.1<td>12.5<td>14.1<td>10.3

<tr><td>Food aid<td>2.7<td>2.4<td>1.9<td>2.7<td>2.1

<tr><td>Humanitarian aid<td>0.7<td>0.8<td>6.9<td>10.2<td>9.2

<tr><td>Subsidies to NROs<td>4.3<td>3.7<td>3.7<td>3.6<td>3.5

<tr><td>Others<td>7.6<td>8.7<td>12.8<td>11.6<td>13.9

<tr><td>Source: BMZ

</tr></table>



<P>

<B>Sectoral focal points</B>

<P>

Table 3 shows that social and administrative infrastructure and

economic infrastructure are the two main promotion sectors of

German bilateral development cooperation. Three things are noteworthy

in the period covered (1989-93). These are the more or less constant

weighting of social infrastructure, the distinct decrease of economic

infrastructure and the productive sectors, and the sharp increase in the share of debt relief

and humanitarian aid. The latter was above all aid for refugees,

which has also risen markedly in some other donor countries.

<P>

But while Table 3 presents a picture of sectoral focal points,

German aid, or more precisely its TC, is involved in a great number

of individual areas. This is a result of the growing differentiation

of development policy goals since the 1970s. But it bears the

inherent risk of over fragmentation, or becoming a sectoral &quot;wateringcan&quot;.

<P>

Since the beginning of the 1990s, the BMZ has defined as priorities

of bilateral cooperation the three &quot;key areas&quot; of alleviating

poverty, protection of the environment and resources, and education,

supplemented by the promotion of women. Developmental measures

in the various sectors and areas are to concentrate on these priorities

which, except perhaps for education, are cross-sectoral tasks.

<P>

According to the BMZ, 4050 per cent of the government's recent

commitments relate to projects of satisfying basic needs (these

include 13 per cent for alleviating poverty by help for self help),

about 30 per cent relate to environmental and resources projects

(1988: 15 per cent), and 13 per cent to the educational sector.

Gathering statistics on alleviating poverty is not easy, and it

has therefore, not surprisingly, also given rise to controversy.

<P>

<B>Instruments and conditions of bilateral cooperation</B>

<P>

Germany's bilateral development cooperation has essentially the following instruments (space limits

preclude a more precise breakdown):

<P>

<ul>

<li>Financial Cooperation (FC): favourable credits (depending

on the development level of the partner country, interest rates

of 0.75 per cent or 2 per cent and 40or 30year terms of maturity

with 10year periods of grace), or grants (LDCs) for investment

projects and programmes, as well as aid in kind and structural

adjustment aid. Implementation: Reconstruction Loan Corporation

(KfW);

<P>

<li>Technical Cooperation (TC): strictly speaking, the provision

of experts and materials and equipment assistance on behalf of

the federal government, primarily by the GTZ (cost-free). In the

broader sense, subsidies for the developmental activities of private

project executing organizations;

<P>

<li>Personnel Cooperation (PC): in particular, advanced training

programmes for specialists and executives from developing countries

(cost free), organized mainly by the German Foundation for International

Development (DSE) and the Carl Duisberg Society (CDG); and

<P>

<li>Other forms: food aid, promotion of the cooperation of German

industry with developing countries, and promotion of the latter's

exports.</ul>

<P>

<B>Development cooperation and German unification</B>

<P>

Unification of the two German states meant for Bonn's overall

development policy less of a task of adjustment than in other

political sectors. Most of the former GDR's development programmes

and projects implemented as part of its last Five year Plan had

ended in 1989/90, or had not survived the dissolution of the GDR

structures. After examining former East Germany's 106 projects,

the BMZ continued 64 of them. Moreover, numerous scholarship-holders

from developing countries who were studying in the GDR continued

to be promoted in the new L&#228;nder in eastern Germany.

<P>

<B>Organizational structure</B>

<P>

In contrast to those of most other DAC donor countries, the organizational

structure of German development cooperation has, among other things,

the following characteristics:

<P>

<ul>

<li>Germany has its own development cooperation ministry which

has competence for: laying down the principles, and the financing,

planning, controlling, steering and coordination of all development

policy measures; government negotiations with recipient countries;

and coordination with other donors;

<P>

<li>implementation of development cooperation is assigned to

two central, parastatal organizations (KfW, GTZ), as well as to

numerous other parastatal, semigovernmental and private organizations;

<P>

<li>implementation of FC and TC is institutionally separated

for historical reasons;

<P>

<li>not least due to the traditional reservations of the Foreign Ministry,

the local representation of German development cooperation in

developing countries is weaker than that of a number of other donors.

The latter have to a great extent delegated the planning, implementation

and management of their projects to on site development cooperation

offices. German representation has only in recent years taken

on a more marked form. At present, it encompasses 26 officers

of development cooperation seconded by the BMZ to German embassies,

24 project administration offices and 30 small project service

offices of the GTZ. The KfW has had two local project representatives

(in Cairo and New Delhi) since only recently.</ul>

<P>

<B>Strengths and weaknesses of organizational structure</B>

<P>

The organization of German development cooperation has advantages

and disadvantages. The advantages include:

<P>

<ul>

<li>the existence of strong project implementing organizations

such as the KfW and GTZ. The other donors, where implementation

is incumbent upon development cooperation authorities or agencies,

either do not have such organizations or only to a limited extent.

The KfW and GTZ can work more flexibly than a cooperation authority.

They have also accumulated a great deal of regional and sectoral

professional knowledge, and in this respect enjoy international

repute; and

<P>

<li>the very differentiated organizational structure of implementation,

involving the participation of numerous NGOs and organizations

of German industry and commerce. Despite coordination problems,

these structures deliver pluralism, offer possibilities for specialization,

and tend to increase the public's acceptance of development cooperation.

The five foundations of the political parties are a German peculiarity.</ul>

<P>

On the other hand, the organization of German development cooperation

also has several disadvantages:

<P>

<ul>

<li>the inadequate division of labour between the BMZ on one side

and the KfW and GTZ on the other. This results in the BMZ's competence

ranging from decisions on principles to the levels of developmental (in contrast to specialist-technical) planning and management

of every individual project. It also leads to overlapping of work

between the institutions and cramps the BMZ's capacity for conceptional

work;

<P>

<li>the institutional separation of FC and TC, which is unknown

to most other donors. In view of the trend to more comprehensive

forms of aid (programme assistance, support of structural adjustment

programmes, capacity building), the split is also causing increasing

difficulties; and

<P>

<li>the relatively weak local representation of German development

cooperation in developing countries. The DAC has repeatedly criticized

it, and it also hampers the adequate planning and management of

activities in close contact with partner countries.</ul>

<P>

<B>Developmental concept, paramount goals, self-interests</B>

<P>

In order to characterize the intents of German development cooperation,

it is useful to differentiate between the developmental concept,

paramount goals and &quot;self interests&quot; (nondevelopment

cooperation objectives) linked with it:

<P>

<ul>

<li>Developmental concept: the declared goal of German development

policy  to support economic and social development in the recipient

countries by help for self help, and thereby contribute to improving

living conditions  has basically not changed since it began. What

has changed are the concepts in pursuit of that goal. German development

cooperation has in principle gone all the way with the changes in

international developmental concepts over the years. Expressed

in very simple terms, these saw strong emphasis on economic infrastructure

and education in the 1960s; on satisfying basic needs in the 1970s;

on structural adjustment, policy dialogue and strengthening the

private sector in the 1980s; and concentration on poverty alleviation,

the environment and education since the beginning of the 1990s.

Germany assumed a certain role of initiative giver among the donors

when the BMZ introduced its new allocation criteria in October

1991. These identified human rights, participation of the people,

rule of law, a market friendly and social economic order, and government

action oriented on development as priorities, of which the first

three are explicitly political benchmarks. The change in the concepts

(which in the view of the administration is sometimes too rapid)

does not in the nature of things lead every time to fundamental

changes in developmental practice, but rather to gradual adjustments.

<P>

<li>Paramount goals: Traditionally, German development cooperation

has always been perceived in Bonn as part of a global peace policy

(which is still enshrined in the Federal Government's &quot;Basic

Principles of Development Policy&quot; of 1986). Since the end

of the East west conflict, the motive of securing the future of

humankind has come increasingly to the fore. That reflects growing

awareness of the new global threats posed by environmental degradation,

population growth, international refugee flows or regional and

ethnic conflicts with cross-border impacts.

<P>

<li>Self interests: German development cooperation has always been

integrated in the network of overall foreign relations. Like every

other political sector, it is subject to the Constitutional imperative

to benefit the German people and avert danger to them, and therefore

also has to serve German interests.</ul>

<P>

The definition of German interests is thereby decisive. They can

relate either to such basic goals as securing peace or the 

 future, or to quite specific foreign policy, 

foreign trade or domestic political interests. In the second case, conflicts of objectives can arise in development cooperation. In fact, concrete self interests have

always influenced and partly also impaired

the practice of German development cooperation. Such as the Hallstein Doctrine

(the rundown of diplomatic relations with countries which recognized former East

Germany), the checking of Communism, securing exports and raw

materials, creation of domestic employment by securing procurement

orders from ODA, and improving German industry's competitive position

in important export markets.

<P>

Compared with other donors, when it comes to the relationship

between development policy and self interests Germany stands midfield.

It has never subordinated its development cooperation policy to

foreign and security interests so blatantly as the USA has done,

or, like Japan in the past, to foreign trade interests. But on

the other hand, Germany has also never sought such a distinct

developmental profile as various &quot;likeminded countries&quot;,

for example some Scandinavian countries and the Netherlands, have

done in the past.

<P>

<B>Development policy among political parties, parliament and public</B>

<P>

Germany's development policy enjoys a positive consensus among

all the main political parties, parliament and the public, despite

many differences (which are also partly a matter of style for

political &quot;show business&quot; reasons) and some scepticism

over the practice of cooperation. This is a great developmental

asset, even if development policy has naturally less importance

in political and public minds than domestic and economic topics.

<P>

Development policy is an agenda for all parties represented in

the Bundestag. Not only for their manifestos and election campaigns,

but also for parliamentary debates, question times and, not least,

in consultations and decision taking on the BMZ budget. Parliament's

development policy debate is carried out intensively in the Development

Policy Committee, whose influence on the practice of cooperation

is, however, less than that of the Budget Committee.

<P>

According to opinion polls, the great majority of Germans (in

both the old and the new L&#228;nder) endorses development cooperation,

even in hard economic times. This positive basic attitude is also

reflected in their great readiness to make donations, which they

have shown for decades. Furthermore, the polls show:

<P>

<ul>

<li>an increase in awareness of the interdependence of the developments in the

North and South;

<P>

<li>overestimation of not only the quantitative significance but also the possible impacts of development cooperation;

<P>

<li>low awareness of government development cooperation compared with the work of NGOs; and

<P>

<li>growing scepticism over the practice of government development

cooperation, which is based on reports of failures, doubts about

the &quot;feasibility&quot; of the aid, and suspicion that it

is only an &quot;alibi&quot; to camouflage the pursuit of economic

selfinterests.</ul>

<P>

<B>Challenges</B>

<P>

A development policy that claims to contribute to global securing

of the future needs the following to remain credible at home

and abroad:

<P>

a) in the medium term, an increase again in funds;

<P>

b) more political influence in the sense of political coherence.

Many policies play a role in relations with developing countries

(e.g. in the areas of foreign policy, agriculture, trade, direct

investment, indebtedness, environment, refugees) which are not

part of the domain of development policy, but which touch upon

it strongly and in part counteract it. These policies must be

reviewed more intensively for their global impacts and developmental

soundness. In the Maastricht Treaty, Germany acknowledged the

imperative of coherence.

<P>

c) a sustainable improvement of effectiveness and efficiency.

This applies not only to the general conditions in the

partner countries, as important as they are, but also the aid

delivery on the German side.

<P>

Lines of approach, besides greater political coherence, are: relieving

the BMZ of responsibility for projects (except for the evaluation

of results which, rather, must be intensified); strengthening

its capacity for politicalconceptual work (which will also enable

it to &quot;occupy&quot; the agenda of global securing of the

future even more intensively among the Bonn ministries); concentrating

development cooperation on fewer countries (perhaps in agreement

with other EU donors) and also fewer sectors in bilateral cooperation;

consistent fostering of the country strategy papers as an important

developmental management instrument; closer cooperation (and finally

merging) of FC and TC; and strengthening of foreign representation.

<P>

d) a more precise definition of the role of development cooperation

in the overall network of relations with developing countries.

Development policy is undisputedly part of German cooperation

relations with developing countries and regions, and with its

special terms of reference and instruments can make an important

contribution to shaping them.

<P>

The criticism that a development policy which feels itself obliged

to alleviate poverty is only something for the LDCs and cannot

cope with the cooperation needs of advanced developing countries

misses the point in many respects. On the one hand, poverty is

also a relevant problem in many of the latter countries. And on

the other, it is precisely development cooperation that can make

them interesting offers (e.g. advisory services in fields such

as social, labour market, education, environment or urban development

policies). These offers have a great deal to do with alleviating

poverty, and are ones with which development cooperation, compared

with other German cooperation policies, have advantages. A social

and environmentally sound development of the partner countries

is in Germany's including in the economic sense.

<P>

But although active promotion of German exports is a legitimate

concern, it is not a task of development cooperation. It should

therefore be represented vigorously in parliament and among the

public as a policy in itself, if necessary also with a view to

appropriate funds.

<p>

<HR>

