<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="unicef_info.html">  UNICEF</a></i>
<hr>
<h2>Scouts Around World Promote ORT</h2>
<p>
In  Latin America, North and southern Africa Scouts are following up on a World Scout pledge to increase the use of oral rehydration therapy and reduce deaths from diarrhoeal dehydration.  The President of the World Scout Movement and UNICEF's late Executive Director, James P. Grant, signed their agreement on ORT last summer.<P>
In September, 5,000 Scouts representing over 1 million  throughout southern Africa took an oath to disseminate information on ORT to individuals, families and communities in a region which accounts for 40% of the 3 million annual child deaths from diarrhoeal disease.<p>  
In late December, diarrhoea and ORT became the central theme of the Panamerican Scout Jamboree in Cochabamba, Bolivia, attended by 7,000 Scouts.<p>  
In Cairo, 20 Scout and Girl Guide leaders from the Middle East and North Africa attended a 3-day training workshop on ORT sponsored by the Arab Scout Organisation and UNICEF.  Back home, participants will train 175,000 Scouts to promote ORT.
<p>
At the World Summit for Children in 1990, world leaders resolved to halve child deaths from diarrhoeal disease by the year 2000.  To achieve this target, it was further agreed that 80% of families should be empowered to use ORT by  the end of 1995.  By the end of 1994, UNICEF calculated that 44 developing nations are on track to achieve the 80% target within one year, while 46 could do so with some extra effort.
<hr>
