<head>
<title>Programme Update 19: Zaire</title>
</head>
<body>
<h3>PROGRAMME UPDATE 19</h3>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by</i> <a href="oxfam.html">Oxfam</a>
<hr>
<h2> ZAIRE - GOMA</h2>
<h3>Key developments</h3>
<p>
<ul><li>As reported previously, phase I of the registration
     operation in the camps took place on Sunday 29 January
     1995 without major security incidents although NGO's
     did observe some instances of fraud (estimated to be
     about 10%).  During phase II temporary ration cards
     were handed out.  In Kibumba camp refugees refused to
     dip their fingers in ink, resulting in security
     incidents and a one day delay. This process is to be
     continued in Kubumba but has been abandoned in other
     camps.  Some other security incidents were reported
     and MSF-Belgique, after speaking out about instances
     of fraud they had observed, then received threats from
     refugee leaders.  Feeling that the situation had
     become untenable, MSF-Belgique subsequently announced
     their intention to pull out of Kibumba camp. A
     communique signed by all the NGO's in the coalition
     and supported by UNHCR was issued on Monday 6
     February.  Following this announcement IRC also
     expressed their intention to withdraw their staff from
     the Kibumba camp.
<p>
<li>UNHCR continue with their policy of facilitation of
     voluntary repatriation. Information centres are still
     operating in the camps.  UNHCR have agreed to pay œ8.6
     million for 1,500 Zairean troops to protect more than
     a million refugees (1,000 in Goma and 500 in Bukavu)
     as part of a 'Zairean contingency for Security in the
     Camps.'  A special 30-50 member UNHCR liaison
     committee made up of international military 'experts'
     will work with the Zairean High Command on all aspects
     of the planning and implementation of the agreement. 
     Security posts will be set up in each refugee camp and
     the UN will fund all operational costs.
<p>
<li>Figures reported for monitored repatriation show a
     significant decrease of returnees.  In November 1994
     an average of 1,000 refugees per day were returning,
     decreasing to 500 a day in December and to only a few
     hundred a day at the current time. (These figures were
     obtained in a transit centre in Gisenyi but interviews
     with the returning refugees have been cancelled after
     criticism from the Rwandese authorities.  However,
     counting continues in Gisenyi).
<p>
<li>The latest information on the situation with the two
     volcanoes in the region is more hopeful but the
     situation remains unsure. 
</ul><p>
<h3>Oxfam's response</h3>
<p>
<ul><li>The water distribution system in Kahindo camp has been
     closed for short periods during the day to allow tanks
     to refill.  Investigations are being carried out to
     find out why the tanks have been running empty -
     whether it is due to increased consumption or reduced
     flow from the source.
<p>
<li>Oxfam is to consider its long term plans/strategy in
     the camps in the light of UNHCR's proposed intention
     to dismantle the camps in North Kivu by the end of
     1995 by a process of voluntary repatriation to Rwanda
     or a transferral of a significant proportion of the
     current camp population to alternative camps in the
     interior of Zaire.  A site has been proposed for the
     latter suggestion but it is over 200 km into the
     interior of Zaire with no available access. 
     Clarification is needed on this proposal as this has
     direct bearing on current programme decisions.
<p>
<li>Oxfam is considering its own contingency plans in
     light of the predicted volcanic eruption as well as
     participating in an information campaign for local
     leaders and the Zairean population.  A grant for
     œ73,000 has been approved to provide emergency water
     equipment for 200,000 people.
<p>
<li>Oxfam is to set up contingency stocks of non-food
     items in the Masisi area where we have been working
     since 1993 with victims of civil war to be distributed
     to up to 50,000 displaced people.  
</ul><p>
<h4>TOTAL NO. OF REFUGEES IN GOMA</h4>
<p>
<ul><ul><li>Kibumba
    233,000
<li>Kahindo
    100,000
<li>Mugunga
    155,000
<li>Katale
    200,000   
</ul><p>
TOTAL NO. in N. Kivu 725,000<br>
*UNHCR estimates.
<p>
N.B.  Preliminary figures from UNHCR registration put the refugee
figure at between 725,000 - 730,000. 
</ul>
<hr>
This article first appeared in Oxfam's Programme Update No.19 - Great Lakes Region: Rwanda Crisis.<br>
