<a name="albania">

<br>

<h2>Albania </h2>


<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../index_oc/news/albania6feb.html">Opposition press and politicians under fire in Albania:</b></a><br>
Albania's democratically-elected government has come under attack for passing repressive legislation to silence its critics.<p>

</ul>

<a name="bosnia"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Bosnia </h2>


<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../oda/publications/bod47/elderly.html">Elderly abandoned in Balkan post-war wreckage:</a></b><br>
Manda Rodic is a 73-year-old Serb living in the Krajina.  She is one of the few non-Croats who stayed when the Croatian army retook the province from Serb rebels.  Alone and afraid for her life, she hides outside during the hours of darkness.<br>
<font size=2><b>From the ODA, featured on the OneWorld News Service 9 August 1996</b></font><br>
<p>



<li><b><a href="../index_oc/issue496/williams.html">War and democracy in Bosnia:</a></b><br>
Sarajevo in June 1996 is crowded and vibrant - the pavement cafes have returned and trams and buses are running again.  But peace has confirmed the ethnic divisions forged by war, and September's elections are likely to legitimate them further.<br> 
<font size=2><b>From Index on Censorship, featured on OneWorld News Service 25 July 1996</b><br>
Children playing war games in Bosnia ©Copyright: Dario Mitidieri</font>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="../amnesty/press/bosnia_july3.html">Amnesty demands truth about Srebrenica on massacre anniversary:</a></b><br>
Many relatives of the 6,000 people who were feared killed after the Serb seizure of Srebrenica last year still have no news of their loved ones.  <b>Amnesty International</b> is calling on governments and agencies to ensure that the truth is told about the mass graves of Bosnia.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Amnesty International, featured on OneWorld News Service 3 July 1996</b></font>
<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/tribunals_may6.html">Justice in Rwanda and Bosnia undermined by lack of international support:</a></b><br>
Amnesty International is strongly critical of UN member states, who are not providing adequate long-term support to ensure for the International Criminal Tribunals for the former Yugoslavia and Rwanda.<p>

<li><b><a href="../oda/press/mar20_2.html">Britain will show peace pays in Bosnia, says Lady Chalker:</a></b><br>
The British Government's overseas aid arm, the ODA, has announced a package of aid for Bosnia worth up to £17 million.<p>

<li><b><a href="../afpic/update/130196.html">AfPiC: Successful Bosnia aid convoy</a></b><br>
Update from <b>Action for Peoples in Conflict</b> who have successfully sent a convoy to the devastated Bosnian town of Bosanska Krupa.<p>



<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_bosnia_jan23.html">Step up search for Bosnian war criminals, urges Amnesty:</a></b><br>
Concerns have been raised by </b>Amnesty International</b> that the multinational peace Implementation Force in Bosnia is failing to search for and arrest indicted war criminals.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk3_bosnia.html">Bosnian children learn to live with scars of war</a></b><br>
The Dayton agreement has brought peace to Bosnia, but many children are still trapped in memories of the traumas they suffered.  <b>Gemini News Service</b> reports on efforts to help them.<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_bosnia_jan16.html">Don't rush return of Bosnian refugees, warns Amnesty:</a></b><br>
Following the recent detention of 16 people by Bosnian Serb forces near Sarajevo, <b>Amnesty International</b> is warning the international peace force 'I-FOR' that returning refugees may still be in danger.<p>




<li><b><a href="wk50_bosnia.html">Bosnia: Peace or just plaster?</a></b><br>
Will peace now come to former Yugoslavia, after nearly four years of bloodshed - or is the peace treaty negotiated in Dayton and signed in Paris yesterday merely plastering over unmended cracks? 
<p>

<li><b><a href="bosnia.html">Bosnian peace deal signed - is the war over?</a></b><br>

The peace treaty for the Balkans has at last been concluded.  But the Bosnian Serbs have already rejected it.  Will it end the war? <font size=-1>Photo of Tuzla ©Copyright: <a href="../oxfam/index.html">Oxfam</a></font>

<p>

<li><b><a href="../realaudio/palmer_bosnia/index.html">RealAudio interview with Oxfam's John Palmer:</a></b><br>
John Palmer helped Oxfam handle the refugee crisis in Tuzla during the summer.  Here he speaks to OneWorld Online - in realtime audio format - about Oxfam's work in Bosnia.  <b><a href="news_realaudio.html">More about RealAudio...</a></b><p>



<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk46_gemini_bosnia.html">Declining religious freedom in Bosnia:</a></b><br>
Sarajevo was once and ethnic and religious melting pot with a vibrant cultural scene.  While some of this atmosphere remains, government policies are resented by many non-Muslims.<p>



<b><li><a href="../amnesty/ai_yugoslavia.html">International community should address plight of "disappeared" and "missing":<br></b></a><b>Amnesty International</b> demands that the people who are missing or disappeared - and their families - should not be forgotten in the wake of recent human rights disasters.<p>

<b><li><a href="../index_oc/rieff_595.html">Emblems fo failure:<br></b></a><b>Index on Censorship</b> reports on the UN's successes and failures in the Balkans<p>

<b><li><a href="../index_oc/warsawski_595.html">Interview with Tadeusz Mazowiecki:<br></b></a>The former prime minister of Poland talks frankly to <b>Index on Censorship</b> about his recent resignation as Special Rapporteur on Human Rights in the former Yugoslavia<p>

<li>The<b><a href="bosnia.html"> latest update</a></b> in the Bosnian war from the <b>OneWorld</b> news team.<p>

<li><b><a href="bosnia_updates.html">Previous updates from OneWorld Online</a></b> on the Balkan situation.<p>


 <br><br><b>See OneWorld Online's<br> <a href="../bosnia_sp/bosniasp_top.html">Special Report on Bosnia</a></b>

</ul>
<a name="bulgaria"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Bulgaria</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li type=square><b><a href="../amnesty/press/bulgaria_june13.html">Amnesty concerned about proposals to resume executions:</a></b><br>
A Bulgarian government minister has asked parliament to lift the country's moratorium on executions, apparently justifying his request with a reference to a rising crime rate.<br>
<b><font size=2>From Amnesty International, featured on OneWorld News Service 21 June 1996</font></b>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="../amnesty/press/bulgaria_june6.html">Violence and illegal acts by police officers common in Bulgaria:</a></b><br>
Despite big improvements in Bulgaria's human rights situation since 1989, police shootings, torture and deaths in custody persist on a large scale.<br>
<b>From Amnesty International, 17 June 1996</b>
<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_bulgaria_oct3.html">Police racism leads to beatings and killings:</a> </b><br>
<b>Amnesty International</b> expresses its concern that the beatings and killings of Roma by Bulgarian police are not being thoroughly investigated.</ul>

<a name="cyprus"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Cyprus</h2>

<ul type=square>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/april/cyprus.html">Rich legacy of shared culture withers in Cyprus:</a></b><br>
The Green Line has divided the island of Cyprus since the Turkish invasion of 1974.  Greek Orthodox churches in the Turkish areas have been left to decay or converted into mosques.<br>
<b><font size=2>From Gemini News Service, featured on OneWorld News Service 3 October 1995</font></b><p>

</ul>

<a name="europeanunion"><hr width=40%>

<h2>European Union</h2>

<ul type=square>



<li><b><a href="partner_news/jun96_statewatch.html">European governments split over EU secrecy:</a></b><br>
Tony Bunyan, UK journalist and editor of the Statewatch bulletin, has been highlighting the issue of secrecy in European institutions.  Now his applications to view important documents - relating to policing, immigration and refugees - are causing disagreements between member governments.<br>
<font size=2><b>From Statewatch, featured on OneWorld News Service 17 June 1996</b><br>
Image ©Copyright: Statewatch</font><p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/april/refugees.html">New iron curtain keeps migrants out of 'Fortress Europe':</a></b><br>
The European Union has been pushing Eastern European countries to erect new barriers against poor migrants seeking a better life in the West.<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/chinaeurope_mar27.html">Amnesty - European Union gagged by China with offers of trade deals:</a><br>
Amnesty</b> reports that the European Union has been caving in to trade pressure from the Chinese Government, and is backtracking on promises to press for human rights reforms in the country.<p>

</ul>

<a name="france"><hr width=40%>

<h2>France</h2>

<ul type=square>


<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press/france_apr4.html">Amnesty voices concerns over French police killings:</a></b><br>
Incidents of deaths and beatings in custody in France are increasingly worrying <b>Amnesty International</b>.  The victims are often juveniles and many were of non-European ethnic origin. <br><b><font size=2>April 15 1996</font></b><p>


</ul>

<a name="germany"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Germany</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/may/germany.html">German angst over post-Berlin wall identity crisis:</a></b><br>
Six years after the fall of the Berlin wall, Germans are still undergoing a profound soul-searching about what it means to be German.  For some, this very national passion for self-analysis is in fact the essense of Germanness.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk2_gemini_heroine.html">East German women pioneer economic recovery:</a><br>
Gemini News Service</b> reports from the town of Marwitz in eastern Germany, where 88-year-old Hedwig Bollhagen's ceramic factory has made her a national heroine.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_germany.html">Churches become home from home:</a> </b><br>
German churches are offering sanctuary to refugees the government wants to deport.  Gemini News Service reports.</ul>


<a name="luxembourg"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Luxembourg</h2>

<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../amnesty/ai_Luxembourg_oct3.html">Amnesty criticises prolonged isolation of prisoners:</a> </b><br>
<b>Amnesty International</b> is concerned that the long-term isolation imposed on some convicts in Schrassig prison may constitute cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment.</ul>

<a name="macedonia"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Macedonia</h2>

<ul type=square>
<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_macedonia.html">Balkan fruit salad continues to sour the atmosphere</a> </b><br>
In Italy and France 'Macedonia' means 'fruit salad'.  Greece and the 'Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia' may at last be reaching agreement on the word too.<p>
</ul>

<a name="netherlands"><hr width=40%>

<h2>The Netherlands</h2>

<ul type=square>



<li><b><a href="partner_news/teakwood.html">Teakwood exploitation and insurance scandal engulfs WWF:</a></b><br>
In the Netherlands, the World Wide Fund for Nature has given its name to a financial scheme for teakwood exploitation which others denounce as "fraud".  The implications for global forest management could be huge.<p>

</ul>

<a name="sweden"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Sweden</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk4_sweden.html">Swedish refugee haven begins to close its doors:</a></b><br>
Many Swedish citizens, used to their country's strong moral stance abroad, were shocked to see frightened Kurdish women and children being forcibly deported to Turkey by Swedish police.<p>
</ul>
<a name="ukraine"><hr width=40%>

<h2>Ukraine</h2>

<ul type=square>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/april/chernobyl.html">Hand of help for the children of Chernobyl:</a></b><br>
The explosion of the Chernobyl nuclear reactor in April 1986 is now thought to rank as the world's worst man-made disaster.  <b>Gemini News Service</b> looks at the continuing efforts to help those affected.<p>

<li><b><a href="../amnesty/press_ukraine19oct.html">Ukraine abolishes the death penalty:</a> </b><br>
<b>Amnesty International</b> welcomes Ukraine's declaration of an end to state killing as part of its preparation to join the Council of Europe.</ul>

<a name="uk"><hr width=40%>

<h2>United Kingdom</h2>

<ul type=square>


Picture

<li type=square><b><a href="../outthere/ot_danger.html">Danger for peace looms in Londonderry:</a></b><br>
This is a dangerous weekend for the failing peace process in Northern Ireland.  Long negotiations have failed to defuse a crisis over a planned march by the Protestant Apprentice Boys, which commemorates a crucial Protestant victory over Irish Catholics 300 years ago.<br>
<b>See the <a href="../outthere/index.html">OutThere site</a> for more updates</b><br>
<font size=2><b>From OutThere World News, featured on the OneWorld News Service 9 August 1996</b><br>
Miltown Cemetary in Belfast ©Copyright: John West</font><p>


<li><b><a href="reports/jul96_refugees.html">Refugees get 'kick in the teeth' from UK government:</a></b><br>
On 15 July, the British government passed new laws  re-introducing "unlawful" social security regulations, which will stop asylum-seekers from claiming welfare benefits. The Refugee Council's Chief Executive,<b> Nick Hardwick</b> has described the laws as "a kick in the teeth to some of the world's most vulnerable people". <br>
<font size=2><b>By the  OneWorld News Service 17 July 1996</b></font>
<p>


<h3>Special News Feature: Northern Ireland's Troubles</h3>	


<li><b><a href="reports/ulster/trunk.htm">Ulster's Orangemen beat police at five-day stand-off in Drumcree:</a></b><br>
Police in Northern Ireland have reversed a five-day ban and allowed Protestant Orange marchers to pass through a Catholic area in the town of Portadown.  The decision sparked the worst civil unrest the province has seen for decades. <br>
<font size=2><b>From John West, featured on OneWorld News Service 12 July 1996</b></font>
<p>




<li type=square><b><a href="reports/ulster/marching.htm">Eyewitness report from the Whiterock Parade, Belfast:</a></b><br>
Why do Protestants in Northern Ireland march, and why do Catholics hate it so much?  <b>John West</b> looks at the thorny issues of Protestant tradition - and Catholic memories of centuries of domination.<br>
<font size=2><b>From John West, featured on OneWorld News Service 12 July 1996</b><br>
Photo: Catholic boys prepare to stone Ulster police at a march last week ©Copyright: John West</font>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="reports/ulster/ceasefire.htm">The death of a ceasefire:</a></b><br>
Two years of relative calm followed the IRA's declaration of a ceasefire in September 1994.  But little real progress was made towards finding a permanent settlement, and now the IRA has gone back to war with a vengeance.<br>
<font size=2><b>From John West, featured on OneWorld News Service 12 July 1996</b></font>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="reports/ulster/orange.htm">A short chronology of the Orange Order:</a></b><br>
Bowler hats and pipe bands - familiar scenes during the Northern Ireland 'marching season' which commemorates Protestant King William of Orange's victory over the Catholic King James in the Battle of the Boyne. <b>John West</b> tells the story of the Orange Order.<br>
<font size=2><b>From John West, featured on OneWorld News Service 12 July 1996</b></font>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="reports/ulster/troubles.htm">The thirty-year history of Ulster's Troubles:</a></b><br>
'The Troubles' in Ulster began in 1969, and to date have resulted in the deaths of over 3,500 people.  What are the roots of the present-day conflict?  <b>John West</b> traces 30 years of hopes and failures.<br>
<font size=2><b>From John West, featured on OneWorld News Service 12 July 1996</b></font>
<p>



<li><b><a href="reports/jun96_bbc.html">BBC World Service staff campaign against corporate axe:</a></b><br>
Staff at the London headquarters of the BBC World Service are launching a vigorous campaign to protect it from corporate restructuring plans, which they say will split up the service and compromise its editorial freedom.  The World Service has 140 million listeners worldwide.  Are their English services under threat?<br>
<font size=2><b>Report by the OneWorld News Service, 24 June 1996</b></font><p>


<li><b><a href="reports/jun96_ira.html">Peace on the rocks as IRA bombers strike again:</a></b><br>
Last weekend's IRA bomb in Manchester may have shattered the 'peace process' as well as the city's Arndale Shopping Centre.  Why did they do it?  Have the IRA 'hard men' won out over the faction that favours a negotiated settlement?  Peace can still be achieved, reports the <b>OneWorld News Service</b>, but time is running out. <br>
<font size=2><b>Report by the OneWorld News Service, 21 June 1996</b><br>
Image ©Copyright: Sinn Fein</font><p>


<li type=square><b><a href="../amnesty/press/uk_june17.html">Amnesty condemns IRA and loyalist human rights violations:</a></b><br>
As well killing and injuring people by placing bombs in crowded British city centres, the IRA is blamed by <b>Amnesty</b> for punishment beatings and killings within Northern Ireland.  Similarly, loyalist paramilitaries have  been carrying out their own violent forms of arbitrary justice.<br>
<b><font size=2>From Amnesty International, featured on OneWorld News Service 21 June 1996</font></b>
<p>

<li type=square><b><a href="../gemini/june/companies.html">Protesters take direct action to company shareholder meetings:</a></b><br>
Buy just one share in a company, and under UK law you have to be admitted to its Annual General Meeting.  Then you can strip naked, rush to the Chief Executive's seat and handcuff yourself to his microphone. All in the name of exposing environmental exploitation, mining and the arms trade.<br>
<b><font size=2>From Gemini News Service, featured on OneWorld News Service  19 June 1996</font></b>
<p>




<li><b><a href="reports/jun96_criticalmass.html">Fuming cyclists take to the streets in protest at pollution:</a></b><br>
Cyclists the world over say they are sick of being treated as second-class road users.  As cheap, non-polluting transport, many feel that the future belongs to them.  Critical Mass - when cyclists club together to show cars who's boss - has become a world-wide expression of pedal-power.<br>
<font size=2>Critical Mass comes down the Cowley Road in Oxford, UK  ©Copyright: Helena Earnshaw</font><p>



<li><b><a href="partner_news/jun96_rowntree.html">Report reveals harsh reality of life for Britain's poor:</a></b><br>
Millions of people in Britain - one of the world's richer countries - are facing a constant battle to make ends meet.  Life for Britain's 14 million poor often means living without adequate heating, good food and housing.  Most find living below the poverty line a stressful and demeaning experience, which they are powerless to change.<br>

<font size=2>Underprivileged children in the 1920s are given free milk.  Has anything changed in Britain? ©Copyright: Unicef</font><p>


<li><b><a href="../index_oc/holland.html">Why we should have known the IRA would lift its ceasefire:</a></b><br>
<b>Mary Holland</b> warns journalists against falling for the trap of self-censorship when covering sensitive issues.  It is this, she says, that blinded reporters to the impending end of the ceasefire.<p>

<li><b><a href="../oda/press/apr23.html">Britain's response to the crisis in Lebanon:</a></b><br>
As a response to the humanitarian crisis caused by the Israeli blitz on Southern Lebanon, the British Government is to give £250,000 to assist aid efforts.<p>



<li><b><a href="../gemini/april/ulster.html">Northern Ireland's tightrope walk between war and peace:</a></b><br>
As police and Protestant marchers clash on the streets of Ulster, a <b>Gemini News Service</b> correspondent gives a frank account of the current state of the Irish peace process. <br><b><font size=2>April 15 1996</font></b><p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/apr96_newbury.html">Eviction of protesters finally ends at Newbury:</a></b><br>
The first stage of the British government's long-running battle with environmentalist anti-road campaigners at Newbury has ended, with the last protest camps being evicted by bailiffs.<p>



<li><b><a href="reports/apr96_bse.html">Special OneWorld Science Report - Mad Cows and Englishmen:</a></b><br>
The British beef industry is reeling from an overseas ban on its exports and a sharp drop in sales.  Consumers are showing a critical lack of trust in government assurances that beef products are safe.  What does this mean, and why did it happen?  Will thousands or even millions of people die because of the food industry's relentless search for profits?<p>

<li><b><a href="reports/apr96_realworld.html">New movement for change launched in UK:</a></b><br>
In the run up to the next election, a coalition of campaigning and voluntary sector organisations is aiming to push social justice and sustainability onto the British political agenda.<p>


<li><b><a href="news_bse.html">Cattle crises - Britain's BurgerGate and Yaks in Yushu:</a></b><br>
Britain has been trying to avoid killing its cows - while in Tibet, nomadic farmers are watching their yaks die. <p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/mar96_oil.html">Welsh oil spill - flags of convenience signal safety alert:</a></b><br>
A huge oil spill off the Welsh coast is killing sea wildlife in some of Britain's most protected nature reserves.  The disaster has focused debate on the deregulation of the shipping industry.<p>



<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk1.9_ira.html">Northern Ireland - why the IRA went back to war</a></b><br>
Expert IRA observer Kevin Toolis looks at the reasons for the republican hardliners' return to violence, and argues that a lasting peace can still be achieved.<p>

<li><b><a href="reports/mcspotlight_launch.html">McDonald's vow to continue McLibel fight after McSpotlight launch:</a></b><br>
The McDonald's watchdog Internet site, McSpotlight, was launched from a laptop and mobile phone outside a McDonald's in London by the McLibel Two yesterday.<p>



<li><b><a href="reports/mcspotlight.html">McSpotlight Web site targets "arrogant" corporation McDonald's:</a></b><br>
Today sees the launch of a campaigning site by people determined to win "the fight against McDonald's global domination".  Dealing with issues ranging from animal welfare to tropical deforestation, this site intends to use the Internet to keep one step ahead of the corporation's lawyers.<p>

<li><b><a href="../news/reports/ira.html">IRA bomb in London shatters 18-month ceasefire:</b></a><br>
A huge bomb in London's Docklands has killed two people and destroyed several buildings.  This could be a fatal blow to the Northern Irish peace process.<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/foe_press.html">Environmentalists protest to rainforest countries over loss of UK wildlife:</a></b><br>
This Friends of the Earth press release details an ironic twist in the anti-roads campaign in the UK.  The UK has criticised deforestation in other countries, but now its own policies are in the spotlight.<p>



<li><b><a href="partner_news/newbury.html">One World News Service Multimedia Report: Newbury, UK</a></b><br>
The campaign against the new road at Newbury has been much  in the UK media recently. <b>OneWorld Online </b>visited the site of protest to find out why.<p>

<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk3_ireland.html">Northern Ireland's ceasefire in danger:</a></b><br>
Hopes for a break in the deadlocked peace negotiations over Northern Ireland rest with the 'Three Wise Men' - international mediators discussing the decommissioning of arms.<p>

<li><b><a href="wk2_newbury.html">End of the road for British transport policy?</a></b><br>
The English town of Newbury is today the scene of a conflict which reaches to the heart of modern Britain's development.  Should a new road be built to ease the town's choking traffic problem, or should rare species and wildlife habitats be protected from the bulldozers?<p>

<li><b>See also: <a href="partner_news/wk2_newbury_background.html">Friends of the Earth's 'Ten Reasons why the Newbury Bypass is Unacceptable'.</a></b><p>

<li><b><a href="../cafod/pr100196.htm">New campaign launched on refugees:</a></b><br>
Two leading British charities, CAFOD and the Refugee Council, warn of the dangers of "stoking up fears" about the numbers of refugees in Britain.<p>

<li><b><a href="wk46_refugees.html">British Government accused of playing 'race card':</a></b><br>
Over 2300 people fled from Nigeria to Britain last year, claiming that they feared for their safety and their lives.  Only one was granted asylum.  New legislation will restrict entry even further.
<p>

<li><b><a href="partner_news/wk46_refugee.html">Statement from the Refugee Council:</a></b><br>
"It would be a tragedy if matters of life and death for individual asylum seekers are decided
with one eye on the forthcoming general election..."<p>


<b><li><a href="../feedback/wk44_foe.html">Finding the pollution in the UK's backyard:</a></b><br>Friends of the Earth have launched possibly the world's first interactive mapping system, aiming to give people in England and Wales local information about toxic emissions.<p>

<b><li><a href="../gemini/wk40_gemini_laugh.html">Three parties fight for the centre ground:</a></b><br> With the British Labour party throwing away its old socialist beliefs, the political centre ground has become disputed territory<p>

<b><li><a href="../index_oc/fisher.html">Is liberty alive in Britain? </a></b><br> Or do the British live in a state of virtual liberty, all appearance but little substance?  <b>Index on Censorship</b> assesses the situation.<p>


<li><b><a href="../gemini/wk39_gemini_oda.html">Weasel words usher in British aid cuts:</a> </b><br>
In order to stave off a near-certain election defeat, the British government is casting about for more money to use in tax cuts.  The overseas aid budget may be the first to get the chop...<p>

<li><b><a href="../cafod/aid-pr.htm">Opinion poll shows strong support for aid:</a> </b><br>
Eight out of ten people in Britain do not want the overseas aid budget to be cut, according to a poll commissioned by <b>CAFOD</b>.
</ul>



