<HTML>

<HEADER>

<TITLE>Information, Capacity Development and Environmental Policy-making</TITLE>

</HEADER>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<HR>

<center><A HREF = "../index.html"></a>

<h3>Information, Capacity Development and Environmental Policy-making<p>

</h5>Report prepared by Peter Ballantyne and dated October 1995<br>(ECDPM Working Paper

No. 7)</h5>

</center>

<hr>

<h3>Policy-making on the Environment and Sustainable Development</h3>

<p>

The first part of the meeting concentrated on the policy process. This section elaborates on some

particular features of environmental policy-making, and it briefly looks at the policy process and

associated information dimensions.

<p>



<i>      Managing natural resources and the environment</i>

<p>

The environment is often discussed as if it is a homogenous concept or group of problems somehow

separated from other sectors. In his opening presentation, Michael Carley was at pains to emphasise

that we would be better to think of the "environment" as a set of complex socioeconomic problems

spread across and involving all of the sectors in which we work. Instead of confining it to an

isolated box, it needs to be treated as a cross-cutting theme requiring attention at all levels of

government and society. He argued that we almost never solve an environmental problem in the

sense that it goes away. Instead, problems evolve, change, and reappear elsewhere. We can

conclude therefore that environmental management is a process to manage change.

<p>

According to Leonard Nurse, decision-making on the use of coastal resources is essentially about

tradeoffs between and among competing uses. And, since many of the uses are not mutually

exclusive, decision-makers are often looking for compromises that minimise conflict and maximise

the benefits to the people and organisations most involved. In their decisions, small-country policy-

makers seek to facilitate economic development by maximising the benefits to be gained from

natural resources, while also limiting the negative impacts of development on what is usually

natureþs fragile and limited resources. We can conclude that environmental management is a process

to manage conflicting interests and competing demands for resource use. 

<p>

Some other characteristics of environmental management are identified in a recent report of the

Organisation of Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD, 1995). They talk of cross-sectoral

and multi-disciplinary linkages, managed interdependence, the adoption of long-term and "system"

perspectives, participation in decision-making and implementation by a broad spectrum of

organisations, communities and institutions, and the need for disparate organisations to engage in

new inter-organisational relationships that emphasise cooperation and collaboration. We can

conclude that environmental management is about the search for institutional arrangements adapted

to complex inter-sectoral and inter-organisational demands.

<p>

In their efforts to adapt to the specific needs of environmental management, governments have been

trying out various organisational forms and approaches. At the consultation, Anthony Bartholomew

showed how responsibility for the environment in Trinidad and Tobago has shuttled between several

ministries over the years, and led to a situation where the environment was not managed in a

coherent and coordinated manner (see <a href = "conbox2.htm">Box 2</a>). <a name="box2"></a>In response to

some of these problems, he presented current plans by the government for an Environmental

Management Authority (EMA) to be responsible for overall environmental coordination in Trinidad

and Tobago. A high priority for the new agency is to develop a national environmental information

system that will link and integrate the many different national institutions that have environmental

interests.

<p>

Many of the worldþs small states are islands that can expect to benefit from efforts to improve the

management of their coastlines. At a major international conference on coastal zones organised by

the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) in 1993, coastal problems were identified

as "almost always rooted in resource use conflicts" (IPCC, 1994: p. 25). This was confirmed by

Leonard Nurse during the consultation when he singled out conflict between incompatible uses of

coastal resources as the major coastal management problem in Barbados.

<p>

Accordingly, a major objective of coastal policies is to encourage changes in human behaviour. At

the 1993 conference, the Panel recommended that this could be achieved if countries adopt an

integrated coastal zone management (ICZM) approach based on wide participation, inter-sectoral

collaboration and coordination, and horizontal as well as vertical integration.

<p>

Barbados has been using such an integrated approach to coastal zone management for several

years. There, as in other small islands, coastal zones vital to the economy are under great pressure,

mainly from human demands. The management of coastal zones provides a good example of the

complexities faced in environmental management. Coastal problems, as Carley indicated above for

the environment, can rarely be conveniently "boxed" and considered as uniquely "coastal." Trees

growing away from a coast may, for example, be implicated in coastal problems when downstream

water flows and quality are adversely affected by logging. Solving such a "technical" problem is

greatly complicated by institutional factors, not the least of these being the difficulties encountered

by a coastal zone scientist operating outside strictly "coastal" jurisdictions. In these situations, some

mechanisms are needed to bring diverse groups together. As an example of this organisational

diversity, <a href = "conbox3.htm">Box 3</a> <a name="box3"></a> shows some of the institutions that are involved in

coastal zone management in Barbados.

<p>

The example above, as well as illustrating the organisational issues, highlights the need for different

types of data to be brought together and used in problem-solving. Elaborating on this theme, Nurse

suggested that the ultimate task of coastal zone management is to fuse information and data from

different sources. He highlighted good inter-agency links as essential in carrying out this task, and

the value of a formal coastal zone management plan that identifies all of the actors and their

responsibilities. Looking again at Box 3, and assuming that each organisation is both a source and

a consumer of data and information, we can begin to appreciate the potential scope (and

complexity!) of an integrated information system on coastal zone management.

<p>

The IPCC also sees information playing a major role in this integrated approach. They found that

coastal managers are "increasingly basing their decisions on analytical and scientific information"

(IPCC, 1994: p. 48), and that "technical capacities, encompassing hardware, practices and human

skills, appear to be crucial for organizing information" (IPCC, 1994: p. 35). They also recognised

that data collection is difficult and costly, and they suggested that it is still necessary to identify the

most relevant information that is needed for the ICZM process.

<p>

In this section, we have tried to elaborate on the nature of environmental management, emphasizing

the processes, the changes, and the institutional frameworks that underlie and influence

environmental decisions. Looking at the situations in Barbados and in Trinidad and Tobago in a little

more detail, we see that the development of inter-sectoral linkages and inter-organisational

collaboration get high priority in the search for effective national decision-making on environmental

issues. We also see that data and information collection and sharing are regarded as essential tools

for better linkages and collaboration. We can conclude therefore that environmental management

is largely concerned with the effective integration and use of information and data from diverse

sources.

<p>



<i>      Information dimensions of the policy process</i>

<p>

If we accept that information is indeed at the centre of environmental management, and by

extension environmental policy-making, then what do we know about the policy process itself, and

specifically the role of information in it?

<p>

These were the key questions posed to the meeting by Michael Carley. In earlier work, he

emphasises that the policy cycle is an information-intensive process (Carley, 1994). He describes

a cycle in which problems and challenges are identified, and information on the problem is gathered

and analysed to create a knowledge base from which strategies, policies, programmes and projects

can de developed and implemented. In this cycle, decision-makers and their advisers

interact with one another to exchange information and knowledge, and they each rely on several

complex information "systems", both formal and informal, that provide specialised data, advice, and

opinions.

<p>

According to Carley, an effective policy cycle has four key ingredients: First, political commitment,

second, institutional capacity, third, stakeholder participation that integrates both bottom-up and

top-down ideas, and fourth, knowledge capacity (Carley, 1995). In his view, the last has an enabling

role that helps to ensure the effectiveness and long-term viability of the other three. Enhancing

knowledge capacity leads to enhancements in the others. The question of how we enhance this

knowledge capacity is addressed in the second part of this paper.

<p>



<i>      Whose knowledge capacity?</i>

<p>

In the discussions, there were several views about whose knowledge capacity needs to be enhanced.

A recurring concern in the meeting was the need for precision in identifying the people whom we call

"policy-makers" as well as the processes in which they are engaged. Being concrete about specific

policies and the decision-makers involved in each was considered to be essential if we are to better

understand policy processes.

<p>

According to one of the working groups, information for policy-making is ultimately directed towards

the Cabinet of Government as the ultimate body who approves or disapproves of a policy decision or

choice. Since this is normally a small group of people, policy "advisers" or "technocrats" were also

identified as a policy-making group closely connected to Cabinet, and in fact mandated to inform and

advise it. This of course reflects a view of policy-making in which information and choices flow

upwards to Cabinet through well-established official channels that also provide opportunities for

consultation. In this view, policy-makers are surrounded by a plethora of advisers, researchers,

lobbyists, campaigners, information specialists, media, and the general public who direct opinions,

advice, data and information at the policy-making groups. The impact of these groups is measured in

terms of their access to the policy-making groups and presumed influence on subsequent decisions.

<p>

In such a scenario, it could be argued that the "knowledge capacity" of most concern to us is that of

the Cabinet and its supporting policy advisers, usually, but not always, in government. Bombarded

with vast quantities of information and advice, these policy-makers seek acceptable solutions that,

according to Louk Box, reduce risk but do not necessarily optimise decisions. Weighing the arguments

requires that decision-makers have access to a wide range of sources and opinions as well as hard

data, and sufficient analytical capacity to make sense of it all. One way to do this is to provide policy-

makers with the necessary skills and access to information resources to become information specialists

themselves. However, while they can become more skilled and can increase their access to

information, it is doubtful if they will ever have sufficient time for the required scanning and analysis.

<p>

An alternative that emerged in the discussions was for policy-makers to benefit from some kind of

"distillery" where ideas and information are sorted and processed for easier consumption. The precise

nature of this distillery was not defined. It might be seen as a function that needs to be performed;

or it could be seen as a specialised unit attached to a policy cluster. It might be staffed by some kind

of policy information manager (or information "broker") who, from within the policy-making

community, clearly articulates and interprets policy information requirements and plays an active role

in seeking out information that is needed. The essence of the idea is that someone focuses on gaining

a better understanding of the specific policy process and its information dimensions, and is thus in a

strong position to acquire the information that is really needed, to make sure it is analysed, and then

to make sure that it is used.

<p>

Another argument is that the "knowledge capacity" of the outside communities and organisations that

try to influence policy-makers is equally a candidate for enhancing. In particular, these groups are

constrained by lack of information and data itself, sometimes by their inability to transform and

present what data they have got, and also by an inadequate understanding of the policy process,

including how decisions are made and who by. For groups or organisations that target policy-makers

or are supposed to serve them, this last constraint was felt to be critical.

<p>

In this section, we have emphasised the view of the participants that policy-making is not a single

process, but a number of interlocking and simultaneous processes that involve a wide range of actors.

Understanding policy-making means looking not only at the top where decisions are taken, but at all

of the levels that contribute to policy preparation, formulation, and also implementation.

<p>

While Michael Carleyþs focus on "knowledge capacity" set the scene for later discussions on capacity-

building, it also led participants to discuss who actually makes policy (and therefore needs knowledge

capacity) and what role information plays in the decisions. He implied that the knowledge absorption

"capacity" of policy-makers was still quite limited and that information providers would do well to

concentrate on issues of information quality, content, and presentation. A "distilling" function closely

linked to the policy-makers was suggested as a possible way that knowledge could be brought into

policy-making and managed in a coherent manner.

<p>



<a name="reach"><h3>Reaching the Policy-makers</h3></a>

<p>

Moving from a discussion of the policy process, this section presents some experiences from

organisations located "outside" of policy-making, but eager to inform and influence policy decisions. 

<p>

<i>      . . . through advocacy and awareness</i>

<p>

Using recent debates on the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) as her principal example, Ruth

Raymond talked about the experiences of the International Plant Genetic Resources Institute (IPGRI)

in supporting national decision-making on biodiversity issues. The institute recognises that policy and

management decisions of this kind are the responsibility of national governments and she emphasised

that IPGRI, as an international organisation, aims to work in partnership with national organisations

in developing countries. IPGRI relies to a large degree on the abilities and capacity of their national

partners to inform local decision-makers, and thus it recognises the need to support strong national

organisations working on biodiversity issues. In its dealings with national decision-makers, IPGRI sees

its principal role as giving advice and providing options; it tries to avoid providing "prescriptions." 

<p>

In addition to this advisory role which is based on technical and scientific analysis, a major aim of

IPGRI is to generate public awareness of the need for effective management of plant genetic

resources. This public awareness and advocacy is intended to generate a climate of support that will

help to create the necessary political will to make decisions that favour the best management of genetic

resources. In this, the media plays a crucial role (as at the UNCED conference where huge media

attention helped to create a positive political climate for biodiversity). IPGRI also makes substantial

use of conferences and dialogues as a way to inform policy-makers. 

<p>

As an international agency keen to see countries adopting international conventions that benefit them,

Raymond emphasised that people who disseminate information need to better understand local policy

needs and local processes. This, she argued, was necessary to ensure that suitable information reaches

decision-makers and that it persuades them of the likely benefits from a certain course of action.

<p>

As well as calling for more attention to the policy process, Raymond was concerned with how

information can be better evaluated in order for it to be used more effectively. She suggested that

paying closer attention to improving the information "package" (including its content and presentation)

would result in national decision-makers being in a better position to know and understand the

consequences of their decisions.

<p>



<i>      . . . through structured data systems</i>

<p>

A contrasting approach was presented by Guy Engelen from the Research Institute for Knowledge

Systems in the Netherlands. His emphasis was on data, stored and manipulated through computer-

based simulation models, and graphically displayed using geographic information systems. The aim

of such policy information systems is to help decision-makers and planners to understand very

complex natural and socioeconomic systems and then to make informed decisions.

<p>

Engelen raised three main questions: What level of abstraction of information do decision-makers

need? What information systems are needed? And what information tools are needed?

<p>

In dealing with these questions, he identified three levels at which information systems generally

operate. In the lowest, the emphasis is on data and the principal tool is the database management

system. At the second level, the focus (and the data) is transformed into information -- a geographic

information system is a typical tool at this level. Above all of these, he identified a third level which

he called intelligence, and where a decision support system would typically be found. He suggested

that decision-makers can be considered as needing "intelligence" more than either information or data.

<p>

Regarding the specific needs of small states, he demonstrated a model to simulate the effects of

climate change and other environmental policy decisions on the island of Saint Lucia. Designed as a

policy support system (PSS), it is intended to facilitate the design and evaluation of alternative policy

options. It allows users to analyse long-term trends and the impacts of policy interventions using

"what-if" scenarios to visualise the likely results of decisions. He said that they had encountered

several problems in collecting the data that the model required, the most critical being their

dependence on the goodwill and collaboration of officials on the island. He emphasised that for a

model like this to be useful in environmental decisions, it needs to have access to location-specific data

that is not always easily-accessible or even collected. Finally, on the issue of data sources, he

indicated that although such modelling tends to rely on more formal data systems, future efforts must

also find ways to incorporate "traditional" knowledge.

<p>



<a name="some"><h3>Some Conclusions on Information and the Policy

Process</h3></a>

<p>

<ul>

<li>There is no single policy process involving a well-defined group of people. Instead, several processes

are in progress at the same time, with various participants depending on the problem or issue in question.

<p>

<li>There are many different actors in policy-making, each with different roles and contributions, and

different information needs.

<p>

<li>Knowledge capacity is both a pre-requisite for policy-making itself, and an "enabler" for three other

pre-requisites (political commitment, institutional capacity, and stakeholder participation).

<p>

<li>Knowledge capacity is a pre-requisite for decision-makers, and also for those who seek to advise,

inform and influence them.

<p>

<li>The nature of the information needed is influenced by the main purpose of the decision, for example,

to manage change, to resolve conflict, or to facilitate inter-organisational coordination and linkages. The

information will be different, it will come from different sources, and it will be presented and used in

different ways.

<p>

<li>Distinctions can be made between data used to prepare policy decisions, and intelligence that is

actually used by policy-makers.

<p>

<li>Policy-makers may benefit more from information that has been "distilled" and is presented in

accessible ways.

<p>

<li>Better understanding of specific decision-making processes, and the actors involved, can help those

outside the decision group to support the processes more effectively.

<p>

<li>Improving the content and presentation of an information "package" will help to reach the right

decisions.

<p>

<li>Environmental decisions need to draw on traditional, indigenous, and local knowledge sources as well

as more formal data-based tools of science.

<p>

</ul>

<a name="cap"><h3><hr>Approaches to Capacity Development</h3></a>

<p>

The second part of the consultation took the idea of "knowledge capacity" a little further and looked

at the information elements of the environmental policy process. The aims were to identify what

kinds of capacities need to be developed, and how. Recognising that our knowledge of the role of

information in policy-making is rather weak, participants drew on other experiences where it was

hoped insights might be gained. Thus, several agencies briefly presented their approaches to

information capacity-building and identified some of the lessons that they had learned. As in the first

part, working groups discussed the issues in more detail.

<p>



<i>      What is capacity?</i>

<p>

Tony Land opened the discussion by emphasising that capacity-building is not a new concept --

under various names and guises, it has been around for some time. What is new is the current

widespread use of the term in relation to many different situations, projects, and levels of activity.

According to some observers, this indiscriminate use of the concept is a danger. Instead of being

a well-defined set of tools and approaches, capacity-building looks like becoming a fashionable

catch-all, sufficiently vague and all-embracing to be applied in almost any situation (Bossuyt, 1995).

The danger is that capacity-building becomes a slogan that few people really understand and an

approach that is difficult to make operational and to measure.

<p>

Land pointed out that capacity is applied at various levels -- of a country, of the state (or public

sector), of an organisation or one of its components, in civil society, or even at the level of the

individual. This diversity makes the concept very difficult to encapsulate, and very difficult to

discuss in concrete terms. In the meeting, it was suggested that an additional nuance - capacity

utilisation - might also be considered. It is not a question only to build capacity, but also to ensure

that there is an enabling environment that allows capacity to be used meaningfully.

<p>

In conclusion, he emphasised that when we talk about an entity having "capacity," we mean that

it has reached a desirable condition in which it can perform its functions in a satisfactory manner.

But, how do we move from this still rather general definition of capacity, and how do we develop

it? While a single definition is hard to come by, we can identify some general characteristics that

may help us.

<p>

First, capacity is task and context-dependent. Capacity is not a goal in itself; the goal is what can

be done with capacity. Referring in a rather abstract way to national capacity or capacity

development without a qualifier is often not helpful. It is more useful to link capacity to the tasks

to be performed or the goals to be reached; thus we can talk of capacity to collect data, to

cooperate effectively, to use advice, or to make policy.

<p>

Second, capacity is often seen as a set of skills or resources or expertise that is considered

necessary to do a task. For example, organisations may define what they consider to be the optimal

skill set that their staff need in order to implement the organisationþs mandate. Information

managers need to be literate and numerate, proficient in the use of computers, and well-informed

about the activities of the organisation in which they work. However, this approach is rather limiting

in that it excludes more contextual or institutional capacities that are also necessary, but much more

difficult to define.

<p>

Third, it is difficult to measure capacity. Definitions tend to be qualitative and refer to capacity as

"sufficient" or "adequate" to carry out a task or to reach a goal. In the absence of quantifiable

measures of capacity, it is very difficult to define exactly what capacity is needed to reach a goal,

and to know when sufficient capacity has been reached. When for example, does an organisation

know that it has sufficient information technology capacity? Of course, not all capacities are so

difficult to measure. If sufficient capacity is specified as certain levels of staffing, equipment, and

financial support provided to an activity, then it can quite easily be defined and measured. However,

such precision is only really possible when tasks have been clearly defined and when the inputs are

mainly financial or technical. It is much more of a challenge to adequately define and assess human

capacity requirements or an "enabling institutional environment."

<p>



<i>      How is capacity developed?</i>

<p>

Moving away from what we are trying to enhance (capacity to use and organise information)

towards how we enhance it (capacity development) we face a multiplicity of options. In many

organisations, capacity development is about training. Increasingly however, this is not seen as

sufficient, and organisations like ECDPM aim to enhance institutional capacity and especially the

organisational structures, linkages, and systems that allow people to function effectively. This

entails a broader focus and also a concern for the institutional and governance contexts in which

organisations operate.

<p>

A useful framework for thinking about capacity development is presented in a recent report by the

OECD (1995). They argue that the central concerns of environmental management - to manage

change, to resolve conflict, to manage institutional pluralism, to enhance coordination, to foster

communication, and to ensure that information and data are shared - require a broad and holistic

view of capacity development.

<p>

The report goes on to discuss some approaches to developing environmental management

capacities. Better environmental legislation, incentives for improved management, the development

of environmental strategies, enhanced horizontal coordination among organisations, organisational

restructuring, and support for local organisations are all mentioned. The authors emphasise that

countries must be able to carry out certain key environmental management functions in an effective

way. While information management is not identified as a core function in the sample list,

"networking and collaborating" is highlighted as a way to bring environmental actors together to

jointly address environmental issues. To do this, the report suggests that donors can support local

networks, information exchange opportunities such as workshops and publications, and the

activities of local environmental NGOþs. 

<p>

Experiences of donor agencies suggest that the way in which capacity is developed is critical.

Capacities that are developed in a participatory way, over time, and in response to real local needs

are more desirable than those identified in a top-down way with relatively little local involvement.

Capacities developed in a participatory way will be more relevant to local realities, will create a

greater sense of ownership in subsequent activities, and the tasks carried out will have a far greater

chance of being sustainable.

<p>

Who develops them is also important. Indigenous, home-grown capacities that deal effectively with

local challenges are what most countries and organisations seek, although they may import specific

capacities at certain times. In the environment, local expertise is especially critical and environmental

capacity development gives more emphasis to local knowledge and experience and places less

importance on outside expert knowledge (OECD, 1995).

<p>

A final strong message in the OECD report (and others) is that a capacity development orientation

also poses significant challenges to donor agencies. It requires that they re-think how they support

development cooperation and the nature of their relationships with aid recipients. The whole project

cycle may need to be modified to give greater roles to recipients. And, as both the OECD Task Force

and Bossuyt emphasise, capacity development implies a greater emphasis on partnership in which

all the actors are involved, are committed, and have clear roles to play.

<p>

The notion that donors and other technical assistance agencies commit themselves to a recipient-

driven process received strong support at the meeting. Paul OþNolan was emphatic that his

organisation seeks to avoid contributing, however unknowingly, to local capacity problems.

Operationally, this means engaging in dialogue, involving local actors in decisions and ensuring that

interventions emerge from and reflect the needs and requirements of local organisations. It also

means that assistance organisations need to take a closer and more critical look at themselves to

ensure that their efforts are consistent, internally, with each other, and with the requirements of the

local organisation. He cited cases where this consistency was not present and where incompatible

computer hardware was provided by different assistance agencies to local organisations. This

incompatibility then holds back local plans to create a common platform for staff to exchange data

and information. 

<p>

While assistance agencies can do a lot to improve things, through coordination and cooperation,

participants agreed that local agencies have a major role to play in managing the relationship with

donors. They argued that the ability of local organisations to "say no" to inappropriate or unsuitable

assistance was one of the most important capacities that they need, but currently lack. In this

context, the ability to say "no" was understood to result from a process in which local actors

identify their own needs and priorities, develop their own vision, set their own standards, and clearly

articulate these to assistance agencies.

<p>

In summary, capacity is something that individuals, organisations, and countries need, in sufficient

amounts, to do a task in the most effective manner. It is possible to identify the elements or

components that comprise capacity, but it is difficult to quantify (and therefore to measure) how

much or how many of each are needed. The way in which capacity is developed has a major

influence on its subsequent usefulness and sustainability. According to Tony Land, capacity

development should be people-centred, based on local ownership and agendas, and reliant on

participation and the use of local resources and expertise. Finally, implementing capacity

development approaches in development cooperation needs changes in the orientations and

procedures of both assistance and recipient agencies. In this, the latter can be more proactive in

defining their own requirements and communicating them to prospective donors.

<p>

<a name="do"><h3><hr>Doing Capacity Development in Practice</h3></a>

<p>

The OECD report is valuable in identifying promising approaches to capacity development. But, as

Bossuyt (1995) has noted, there is frequently a large gap between what we say we should do about

capacity development, and what is actually done in the field. In an effort to overcome this, the next

section shows how some organisations are actually trying to develop information capacities, in

different ways and in different places.

<p>



<i>      Developing information management capacities in an environmental NGO</i>

<p>

Maritza Hee Houng introduced the work of the Caribbean Conservation Association (CCA) and its

information activities. She emphasised that it has individual, organisational and governmental

members and it is therefore a bit different from other NGOþs. Its mission is to "promote and

coordinate policies, programmes and practices which contribute to the conservation, protection and

judicious use of the region's natural and cultural resources in order to enhance the quality of life for

present and future generations." In the early years, the cultural heritage was most important; recent

years have seen an emphasis on natural resources and their management.

<p>

While the provision of information has been a major part of most CCA activities, the information

function has tended to be subsumed under other activities, especially education. There have been

no conscious attempts to set policies on information, nor to systematically plan how it interacts with

other CCA activities and its membership. Despite this, CCA has developed a solid information base

and it provides a variety of information services to its members. This "evolutionary" approach has

served CCA well. However, in recent years, driven by some of the day-to-day problems encountered

in managing documents, CCA has taken a closer look at its information management. With

assistance from the Commonwealth Secretariat, a specialist has been recruited to reorganise internal

services and to develop a programme to enhance the dissemination of information to CCA members.



<p>

Good progress has been made with the internal reorganisation and the focus is now on how CCA

can more effectively support the activities of its members through its information programme. The

current CCA strategic plan emphasises coordination and linkages with member governments and

NGOs (rather than implementation) and information management. Thus, CCA will have more of a

facilitating and, with regard to information, clearinghouse role. Despite this, it is not yet clear

whether CCA will be (or will try to be) the main source of information for its members, or whether

members will themselves maintain information units that CCA supports and works through. Most

member governments already have some kind of environmental information system that CCA can

work with. However, member NGOþs tend to have less-developed information capacities requiring

that CCA adopt different roles.

<p>

In working with both groups, CCA aims to better understand the information needs of its member

organisations, to identify the information capacities that members are likely to need and to have,

and to implement concrete activities that respond to the needs expressed, including the provision

of training. 

<p>

In initiating this programme, CCA has accepted some responsibility to provide or facilitate training

in information management for its members. By doing this, CCA is shifting its focus from efforts

to enhance its own information capacities towards initiatives that also strengthen the information

capacities of its members. This training is being developed with support from the British Council and

others, and in collaboration with UNEPþs INFOTERRA programme. The first phase in late 1995 is a

seminar where environmental organisations in the region will review and discuss efforts to enhance

their cooperation. It will be an occasion also where government and NGOþs can come together. In

early 1996, a training workshop will help CCA members to develop some of the information

capacities identified at the earlier meeting.

<p>



         <i>Information technologies in the service of sustainable development</i>

<p>

According to Chuck Lankester, non-governmental organisations also play a major role in the

activities of the Sustainable Development Networking Programme (SDNP). Set up by UNDP in 1991

and now active in more than twenty developing countries, the SDNP aims to build capacity and

linkages between those who have information, and those that want it. Lankester sees a "hunger for

information" in the participating countries but an unwillingness among policy-makers to pay for

information until they are converted to its value in their own decisions. Making the "conversions"

requires that information providers adopt a proactive and marketing approach in which user needs

are more clearly understood that at present, and in which the benefits of information access are

demonstrated. 

<p>

He likened the process to one in which policy-makers and others become "addicted" to

information.In the Programme, sustainable development networks (SDN's) in each of the

participating countries are the main vehicles used to satisfy this hunger and, at the same time, to

spread the information addiction. Intended as a concrete mechanism to help build capacity to

implement agenda 21, each SDN is a national effort launched by coalitions of local stakeholders in

sustainable development and supported by UNDP. The underlying rationale is that efforts to build

the capacities needed to implement Agenda 21 can be helped by a network that facilitates access

to information on sustainable development.

<p>

Among its formal objectives, the SDNP aims to: facilitate access to information for users in

developing countries; to encourage increased communication about sustainable development; to

enhance the capacity of national institutions to meet their own needs for information on sustainable

development; and to help increase participatory decision making by elements of civil society. Their

approach is to involve civil society as well as government; to provide relatively short-term

assistance; to use participatory approaches; to complement the efforts of others (such as UNEP)

rather than to compete; and to support local networks (national initiatives) by providing guidance

and a little money.

<p>

The SDNP seeks to use computer-mediated technology to facilitate a wider process of sustainable

development (see Zambrano and Daudpota, 1995). In many such projects, the technologies can

come to dominate the discussions and the activities. Participants in the SDNP have been aware of

this and in their meetings they repeatedly emphasise that an SDN is a people-centred network that

uses information technologies to reach wider objectives.

<p>

De-emphasising the technology was also at the centre of a presentation by Paul OþNolan from the

International Service for National Agricultural Research (ISNAR). His experience suggests that

information technology has a great potential as an integrating mechanism that can bring different

parts and levels of an organisation together, and to bring different organisations together. He argued

that much of this integration can be done without major investments in technologies, but it does

need changes in organisation and policy. His comments reinforce an UNCTAD study on information

technology use in small states in which the author suggests that non-technical barriers are the main

factors that prevent the development of well-functioning information technology applications in small

islands (Romer, 1990).

<p>

OþNolan suggests that the institutionalisation and management of information technology, including

the development of policies and standards, while often overlooked, is as important as its installation

and maintenance. Capacities are needed to plan information technologies as well as to use them.

Investing in capacities to plan, to coordinate, and to think strategically about information

technologies provides the self-knowledge that allows an organisation to define its own priorities and

standards, and ultimately it empowers an organisation to say "no" or "yes" to offers of technical

assistance.

<p>



<i>      Strengthening national information networks</i>

<p>

The SDNP is an example where information networking on the very broad theme of sustainable

development is promoted. The consultation also heard about more specific network building

experiences -- in the environmental, and water and sanitation sectors.

<p>

Cor Dietvorst reviewed the experiences of the International Water and Sanitation Centre (IRC) with

information capacity building. Effective information management in the water and sanitation sector

is constrained by the organisational diversity of the sector as well as by its multi-disciplinary nature.

The environment, health, public works, and community development are all involved. The basic

information management challenge is therefore to facilitate inter-institutional communication.

<p>

In a recent report, Stephen Parker (1993) looks at several years of IRC experience in Asia and Africa

and he identifies three major lessons. First, that the users of information and their needs are

relatively unknown and poorly described. Descriptions of target groups that do exist tend to be

exhaustive or rather vague, and little effort is made to prioritise the groups according to needs.

Second, while policy-makers seem to be aware of the need to provide information, they do not

know how to go about it. There also seem to be few information systems that target policy-makers

as users of information. Third, information services on water and sanitation tend to be fragmented

and incompatible. Top-down approaches to information network design have not managed to

overcome this.

<p>

In dealing with these constraints, IRC has concentrated on some specific activities. First, it assists

national organisations to establish an information management unit (IMU) that brings various

information functions together under one "roof." Second, it facilitates the establishment of national

networks of IMU's to cooperate in providing integrated and targeted services to the various user

groups. Third, it supports training activities for information staff to acquire the skills and

qualifications necessary to provide a demand-driven service. Dietvorst summarised their overall

capacity development objectives as to help national organisations get back to basics regarding the

aims and activities of an information system, and to use and develop local capacity.

<p>

Nanny Kempers from INFOTERRA described a different approach. Where IRC is supporting "stand-

alone" national networks of local organisations, INFOTERRA is a global environmental information

and referral system with national focal points (NFP's) in most countries. Thus, it has activities to

build the capacities of the national focal points as well as the capacity of the network as a whole.

<p>

Concern for the overall operation of the network includes a commitment to support efforts of the

national focal points in their own countries. According to Kempers, the work of the focal points has

been held back by a variety of constraints including staff turnover, slow communication, language

barriers, limited funds, and the poor institutional locations of some NFP's. In addressing these

constraints, INFOTERRA employs a variety of approaches -- "twinning" of focal points in developed

and developed countries, allowing the sharing of skills and resources; the development of common

tools, methodologies, and products; the organisation of training courses; and access to expertise

and skills in the people that make up the network. A recent development has been the signing of

a memorandum of understanding between INFOTERRA and the SDNP to collaborate in strengthening

the capacities of national SDN's/NFP's.

<p>

Finally, although not represented at the meeting, the World Conservation Monitoring Centre (WCMC)

circulated a draft note on their approach to biodiversity information management. Set up by UNEP,

the World Conservation Union and the World Wide Fund for Nature, the Centre provides information

services on the conservation and sustainable use of species and ecosystems, and supports others

in the development of their own information management systems. The WCMC is currently

developing the concept of a biodiversity information network which, in each country, would

consolidate scattered information resources and provide integrated access to them. At the heart of

the network approach is a capacity-building process that seeks to involve key local actors in

developing a country-specific system to manage biodiversity information (<a href

="conbox6.htm">see Box 6</a>.). The approach is still being

developed and it will be "tested" in several countries during 1995 and 1996.<a name="box6"></a>

<p>

<a name="def"><h3><hr>Defining the Capacities to be Developed</h3></a>

<p>

Moving beyond the presentations which talked mainly of how capacities are being developed,

participants were asked to identify which management capacities are needed to deliver the

information that policy-makers need. As an aid to presentation, the many suggestions and

recommendations on capacity development have been clustered in three areas: First, the capacities

necessary to manage the "capacity" agenda itself. Second, the capacities needed to define a vision

and purpose of information activities. And third, the capacities needed to manage information flows

between information providers and policy-makers (see box 7 for a summary).

<p>



<i>      Thinking about capacities</i>

<p>

Although the meeting was focused on capacity-building and capacity development, participants

identified other kinds of capacity-related tasks that are just as important to an organisation. Since

some capacities may not be permanent and not all institutions have the same needs, it was argued

that organisations could also look at how capacity can be obtained for shorter periods, through out

sourcing, local consultants, or borrowing. In addition, organisations need to think about how they

keep the capacities that they have. This requires extra effort to create opportunities for people to

grow and develop in their organisations. Critical organisational capacities are to be able to identify

the various kinds of information capacity that are needed, to locate them, and then to keep and

develop those that are considered essential to the operation of the organisation.

<p>

<i>      Defining a vision for information</i>

<p>

According to participants, a first step is to look at the policy processes and the people engaged in

them. Capacities cannot be determined without knowing the intended purpose of the information

and the context in which it will be used. This understanding of policy processes is greatly facilitated

by a "systems view" that accommodates the full breadth of the policy issue in question. Mapping

information resources, information sources, institutional strengths and weaknesses, and likely

participants in specific policy areas may help to define the scale and scope of the intended policy

information system. 

<p>

Linked to this quest for greater understanding of the purpose, participants suggested that capacities

to develop a "vision" of the information function in relation to environmental policy-making are

necessary. Developing such a vision or strategy can be a participatory process by which the policy

and information communities are brought together. It brings coherence to scattered or dispersed

resources, reduces duplication and overlap and builds complementarities among contributing

agencies. Finally, it is the basis for organisations to say "no" to systems or approaches that are not

based on local requirements. 

<p>

Discussions in the meeting suggested that although all participants recognised the value of a clear

vision that defined the objectives and tasks of an information activity or function, there was little

experience in actually going through a process to develop this vision.

<p>

Based on experience with coastal zone management (CZM) in Barbados, developing "vision" is a

process in which a problem is recognised, agreement is reached that it should be tackled, decisions

are taken on how to tackle the problem, and then the problem is tackled. In this approach, problems

are clearly identified and a strategy is set out to deal with them. However, in discussing the CZM

process in Barbados, it became clear that a vision was not developed for information resources.

Instead, Leonard Nurse argued that the CZM process provided participating organisations with

sufficient knowledge about the locations of different data and so a specific process for information

was not needed. Thus, the resulting information "system" on coastal zones emerged over time in

a bottom-up fashion with decisions taken as and when required, and without any up-front strategic

vision. 

<p>

Such an evolutionary approach is what happened at CCA and it probably reflects the real

development of most information systems. In light of this, the question was raised as to whether

information systems actually need to go through the process of developing a vision and whether

such capacities are indeed necessary. Perhaps evolution is a sufficient approach for information

systems. The general feeling of participants was that a strategic vision for information should be

developed, but that they had too little empirical experience to say exactly how and in what

circumstances it was better than a more evolutionary process.

<p>

Having an understanding of environmental systems and insight into policy processes, and being able

to develop a local "vision" for the information function are the critical capacities identified here.

<p>



<i>      Managing information flows</i>

<p>

Participants were concerned that while there is already plenty of information and data on the

environment, much remains under-used. As Ian King from Barbados suggested at a UNEP meeting

in 1994, the basic issue is "not necessarily the question of the existence of the information, or

rather the data, as much as the access [to] the information or the analysis of the data" (King, 1995:

p. 26).  He picked on two of the key issues that concerned participants at the Maastricht meeting.

Namely, that capacities are needed to enhance the access of policy-makers to information, and to

ensure that data is digested for easy consumption.

<p>

Participants felt that increasing the access of policy-makers to information required more attention

to what their actual information needs are. The capacity to define information needs is one that

information consumers themselves need if they are to clearly and effectively articulate their needs

to information sources and providers. At the same time, skills in tracking environmental policy

demands and in identifying associated information needs are at the core of effective information

provision. Thus, participants emphasised that information providers focus on developing capacities

needed to understand what users are doing, the tasks they are involved in, and their needs for

information. Also, they need to look closely at how this understanding of users can be used to

target information more effectively. Critical capacities are to be able to define information needs and

to target information.

<p>

In improving access to information, one of the most important capacities identified is to be able to

transform and adapt information to the needs of different target groups. Particularly where data are

present in a non-processed form, what is often needed are the specialised capacities to convert data

into information or even "intelligence." In this, participants emphasised the need for scientific

capacity to analyse data and turn it into knowledge, and for "packaging" skills to spread the results

both down to the public and up to the policy-makers. Linked to the issue of analysis, it was

suggested that technical or scientific capacity can also be used to determine the usefulness and

usability of information and to exert some quality control on the data and information. Critical

capacities are to be able to distil and package information.

<p>

While most of the discussion was about using and disseminating information, there was an

underlying concern that countries and organisations also ensure that data and information is stored

and preserved in accessible ways. Valerie Isaac talked about information and data in the smaller

eastern Caribbean states being lost and inaccessible for want of adequate basic storing and filing

systems. And Leonard Nurse referred to aerial photographs of beaches on the islands being

overlooked in reviews of coastal systems, simply because almost nobody knew of their existence.

The capacity to collect, store and to preserve local information is especially critical in environmental

management, and exciting new developments should not shade out one of the basic reasons why

we manage information -- to preserve it for future generations.

<p>

Moving from rather static storage and preservation, a strong plea was made for information to be

properly marketed to policy consumers. As Chuck Lankester had emphasised, making information

available is not sufficient, people have to become addicts with an information habit. Doing this in

practice is difficult. Nevertheless, participants felt that a critical capacity is to be able to sell

information to consumers and to convince them that investment in information brings benefits to

their policy decisions. 

<p>

And finally, as in all discussions of development issues, information activities need to be monitored

and evaluated. This is a capacity that is lacking, in both the information suppliers and the

consumers. Policy-makers tend, for a variety of reasons, to have only slight acquaintance with their

own information needs and especially with the possible sources of information that are open to

them. Education is needed to make them intelligent consumers of the information they already pay

for. Among the information providers also, not very much is known about performance of

information systems and services, and how it can be assessed. This is an area where organisations

like IDRC have been active in trying to identify promising ways to measure information activities.

Individual information managers need to learn from this and to develop performance indicators that

allow them to evaluate how information is used and to show how it improves the policy process.

<p>



<a name="some"><h3>Some Information Capacities Required in Environmental Policy-making</h3></a>

<p>

Organisations and individuals who provide or use information require capacities in three main areas. First, they

need the capacity to think about capacity, to know what information capacities are needed, and how they can

be obtained, developed and kept.

<p>

Second, identifying the purpose and direction for the information function requires vision in which policy-

making and information systems are well-understood. In doing this, some useful capacities are to:

<ul>

<li>adopt "systems" approaches;

<li>understand the policy process;

<li>"map" institutional and informational resources;

<li>formulate strategies and plans for the information function;

<li>say "no."

</ul>

Third, transforming data and information into something that can be used in policy-making requires distillation

where the essence of an idea is disentangled and directed towards key audiences. In doing this, some useful

capacities are to:

<ul>

<li>formulate and articulate information needs;

<li>identify target groups of users;

<li>track demands;

<li>market information products and services;

<li>scan, analyse, and distil useful information;

<li>transform and adapt information to the needs of different target groups;

<li>preserve information and data for future use;

<li>monitor and evaluate the information function.

</ul><p>



<p>

<a name="next"><h3>Next Steps -- Identifying a Programme of Work</h3></a>

<p>

The final aim of the meeting was to identify some areas where activities and projects can be developed

to address the issues and problems identified in the discussions.

<p>

First of all, however, participants supported the initial hypothesis of the meeting that "policy-making

can benefit from access to appropriate information and data and well-managed information systems."

Furthermore, they agreed that this requires, at the least, that we have a good understanding of policy

processes and associated information needs, as well as sufficient information capacities to manage,

deliver, and use information and data. Next steps should address these concerns.

<p>

So what concrete activities emerged from the discussions? In his summary of the working group

presentations, Louk Box identified five main areas of activity:

<p>

<ol>

<li>Understand the policy process. Carry out case studies to analyse the policy cycle, paths and

processes of a specific issue in a country to show how things happen, who the real and unexpected

players in policy-making are, and how key policy players interact with each other;

<p>

<li>Look at the information dimension in policy-making. Do case studies on the role of information

in policy management situations, exploring how information is organised, managed, and used in

different types of organisations, the nature of an information "distillery," and how information and

data are transformed and interpreted for use in policy-making;

<p>

<li>Examine how information capacities are organised. Carry out exercises to "map" environmental

information systems to show where specific capacities are located, and who the audiences, products,

players, fundamental objectives, and beneficiaries are;

<p>

<li>Review the performance of information. Assess the impact of specific information initiatives on

policy-making, such as awareness campaigns;

<p>

<li>Mobilise interest. Organise activities to raise awareness of the role of information in policy-

making -- workshops, presentations, training, and publications.

</ol>

<p>

In discussing these activities, participants identified some guiding principles. First, every effort should

be made to link this initiative with others in the same general area - through collaboration and

information exchange - and to make certain that each initiative finds common actions and activities

and thus can learn from one-another. Second, that a region like the Caribbean is very diverse and any

follow-up should emphasise the specific policy concerns and context in each country. Third, that

comparative data (from a region) is useful and new activities should allow countries to learn from their

neighbours. Finally, that case studies should try to learn from mistakes as well as from successes.

<p>









</DOC>
