<head>
<title>Gemini - Liberation struggle continues in the classroom</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<br><i> The material that follows has been provided by </i> <b><a href="../gemini_info.html">  Gemini News Service</a></b>
<hr>
<h3>LIBERATION STRUGGLE CONTINUES IN THE CLASSROOM</h3>
<i>
Some Eritrean parents oppose having their children schooled in their minority 
tongue for fear of denying the youngsters knowledge of more widely spoken 
languages. However, three years after independence, reports <b>Gemini News 
Service</b>, the government is pushing ahead with such education, saying national 
culture must not perish.<p>


By <b>JENNIE STREET</b>,<br>
12 April 1996,<br>
Asmara </i><hr><p>


Eritrean authorities are determined to provide primary education in minority 
languages - even when parents oppose it. Some parents demonstrated in Adi Kaieh 
against the policy on the grounds that mother-tongue teaching in their own 
language, Saho, would marginalise their children.<p>

They demanded Arabic as the medium of instruction, although it is not widely 
spoken in their area. In reply to such fears, Kebede Gebregazabiher, head of 
the curriculum department in the Ministry of Education, points out that the 
government "is not going to hire those who passed elementary school - they have 
to go higher".<p>

After the fifth year of education, English is the medium of instruction in 
schools across the country, and knowledge of English will well-equip a child to 
land a good government job.<p>

"We tell the parents, 'Your language is your culture, your heritage, your 
identity. It has to be developed, or it will perish.'"<p>

Emphasising that "we are very much convinced of the need for this policy", he 
explains: "Its roots lie in the independence struggle." After a long war, 
Eritrea broke free of direct Ethiopian control in 1991 and an independent 
republic was founded in 1993. During the fighting, a Revolution School was set 
up in a liberated area by the Eritrean People's Liberation Front (EPLF).<p>

"When we opened the Revolution School in 1976, there were children who spoke 
neither Tigrinya nor Arabic (the two most widely spoken languages), and we 
realised we needed to give them education in their own tongue first."<p>

All of Eritrea's nine ethnic groups have their own language. Yet 354 of the 
510 elementary schools teach in Tigrinya and 96 in Arabic, compared with 25 in 
Tigre, 13 in Kunama and 14 in Saho.<p>

Teaching in Tigrinya and Arabic in areas where neither is a second language 
contributes to poor attendance and high drop-out rates - which in turn 
contribute to widespread illiteracy.<p>

Only about 20 per cent of the population is literate. In remote rural areas, 
and among women, the percentage of literates drops even lower, in some areas to 
below five per cent.<p>

"Imposing Tigrinya was practically not fruitful," says Kebede of the period 
before liberation. "They could learn nothing in a language they didn't 
understand. Children learn quicker in their own tongue."<p>

At that time, he recalls, there was no problem getting teachers from minority 
language areas, "as there were many in the army from all parts of Eritrea, and 
we developed the curriculum in minority languages for grades one to three. But 
now, we have a desperate shortage of mother-tongue teachers." <p>

He explains: "We cannot find the personnel because now people have more choice 
as to their work." <p>

Last year, 360 students graduated as elementary teachers, but only nine were 
from minority ethnic groups. They have been assigned to work in their mother 
tongues. <p>

"Nine is a tiny number compared with the needs for 52 minority language 
schools," admits Kebede.<p>

The nine graduates are from the Kunama, Saho, Afar and Nara nationalities, and 
have known each other and experienced much hardship over many years. <p>
As 
children of the independence struggle, they lost their families or were the 
children of fighters.<p>

They received their early education in the Revolution School, in classrooms 
carved into hillsides or camouflaged against Ethiopian bombing. In 1984, six of 
their classmates were killed in a bombing raid.<p>

As part of the mother-tongue teaching policy, the Education Ministry is 
writing the curriculum in the Saho, Kunama, Afar, Nara and Bilen languages - 
which is resulting in the languages being written down for the first time, 
using Romanisation.<p>

"We cannot find anyone, though, for the Hadendowa (Beja) language," says 
Kebede.<p>

As with the protesting Saho-speaking parents, some Hadendowa speakers advocate 
the use of Arabic for political and religious reasons. But Kebede says: "it is 
not practical for the children, who do not know it." <p>

Kebede says that one of the difficulties in convincing parents of the 
importance of mother-tongue teaching is that whereas during the liberation 
struggle EPLF fighters lived among the people, now government is more remote 
and less directly involved with people. <p>

Elementary education for rural children is, therefore, seen as being of great 
importance - not simply as providing some literacy and numeracy, but mainly as 
a way of delivering basic knowledge on hygiene, nutrition and health.<p>

Elementary enrolment has risen by 49 per cent since liberation, but 31 per 
cent of all students drop out or repeat classes. <p>

"We don't expect these rates to improve for some time, because living 
standards are so low," says Kebede. "In some communities girls are married 
before puberty, and children everywhere are needed to work. But we may consider 
giving food to counter poverty, and perhaps legislate against early marriages." 
<p>
<hr>

About the Author: JENNY STREET is a freelance journalist living in Eritrea.<p>
 Copyright: News-Scan International Ltd. (1996)    12/4

<hr>
