<HTML>



<HEAD>



<TITLE>Institutional and Managerial Requirements at the National Level</TITLE>



<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jacques van Laar">

</HEAD>



<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<HR>



<H3><CENTER></H3>



<H3>Institutional and Managerial Requirements at the National

Level<BR> for Effective Regional Cooperation: Editorial</H3>



<P>

by <I>Stanley Please</I> 

<P>

Full text of an article from <I>DPMN Bulletin, 2(1) April 1994:

page 2</I> </CENTER><HR>



<P>

Development policy management as a subject of study has been established

over the past decade to address the question of <I>how</I> policies

are formulated and implemented as opposed to the question of <I>what

</I>policies should be pursued. The subject of regional cooperation

and integration in Africa certainly cries out for study in this

context.

<P>

There is now little controversy about the desirability of greater

regional cooperation and integration as an objective of policy.

Even the World Bank has moved from an attitude of scepticism,

or even of hostility, to one of support. Yet the most persistent

and enthusiastic proponents of greater cooperation as both a political

goal and as a means for stimulating economic growth, are despondent

over the achievements since independence. So the critical question

becomes not <I>what </I>to achieve but <I>how </I>to achieve the

objective.

<P>

The broad message which emerges from the contributions to this

issue of the Bulletin is that <I>top-down </I>decisions emerging

from regional institutions will represent little more than the

posturing of politicians and the pious hopes of regional bureaucrats

unless national institutions and administrative processes are

adapted to ensure that regional policies and programmes are integrated

into national decision-making -- i.e. unless it also becomes a

<I>bottom-up </I>process.

<P>

But the contributors do not add to the tale of woe on regional

cooperation. On the contrary, limited and qualified success stories

are reported on from Southern Africa (Goodison and Nee), from

West Africa (Deme), and from the Cross Border Initiative in Eastern

and Southern Africa and the Indian Ocean (Mansoor). All these

have required the effective involvement of <I>bottom-up </I>actors

-- national ministries, public agencies, the private sector. This

is also the lesson which is provided by non-African experience,

represented in this Bulletin by Stronck's account of Luxembourg's

experience as a member of European regional bodies.

<P>

However, beyond their importance to the discussion of regional

cooperation and integration on which the contributions speak for

themselves, these contributions also raise wider issues relating

to the content and methodology of development policy management

as a subject of study. Two issues are of particular importance.

<P>

First is the point made strongly by Senghor that institutional

development as part of development policy management, must be

seen as a 'process'. It has to be recognised that governments

only have a limited political capacity in any period of time to

address major policy issues, that administrative structures and

processes can only be changed progressively over time, and that

society more generally has only a limited capacity or willingness

to adapt to changes in the policy and institutional environment

in which firms, farmers, workers, consumers, and others have to

live and operate. Thus because everything cannot be done at once,

the critical policy issue is the 'sequencing' of actions.

<P>

The emphasis on sequencing in the study of institutional development

parallels what has taken place in the study of economic policy

reform. This now concentrates less on the objectives and content

of reform programmes. No longer is there much questioning of the

importance of disciplined macro financial policies, of markets

and prices of an active private sector and a more efficient public

sector, of programmes to help the poor and to develop human resources.

We are all structural adjusters now!

<P>

Instead the emphasis of scholars and policy-makers is on the speed

and sequencing of reform measures. Can expenditure on human resource

services be modified before the production underpinnings of the

economy have been reformed and stimulated? Should uneconomic public

enterprises be wound up or sold off before the conditions are

in place for private sector enterprises being established. And

a host of other questions of sequencing.

<P>

Senghor's paper invites the question of whether the subject of

public administration has generated any comparable conceptual

framework upon which the emerging subject of development policy

management can be built. Or has it tended to concentrate on 'ideal'

or 'optimal' institutional structures and administrative processes

at the expense of the process through which these objectives can

be achieved?

<P>

The second conceptual issue which is important for the advance

of development policy management as a separate subject within

the social sciences is the need for tentative hypotheses to be

derived from historical and descriptive studies and for these

hypotheses in their turn to be tested against further studies

of experience. For instance: 

<UL>

<LI>No changes in institutional arrangements will effectively

advance regional cooperation without the participation of civil

society. 

</UL>



<P>



<UL>

<LI>In the pervasive African situation of crisis-management of

economic policy, no institutional or policy changes to achieve

the longer term objectives of regional cooperation are possible

in the absence of donor willingness to bear the short-run costs

and to supplement local administrative capacity.

</UL>



<P>



<UL>

<LI>Any major new and qualitatively significant addition to government

objectives (e.g. regional cooperation, environmental objectives,

role of women) cannot be immediately absorbed as part of the existing

policy-making and implementation bureaucracy, but requires a separate

and high profile addition to this bureaucracy.

</UL>



<P>



<P>

Maybe these and other similar hypotheses and questions should

be the subject of further and differently focussed papers. However

it must be said in all frankness, that unless the experiences

of scholars and practitioners can be brought to test hypotheses

and to raise new hypotheses, then the emerging subject of development

policy management will be in danger of failing to generate any

credibility as a scientific discipline. The subject does not have

to become prescriptive -- and certainly not arrogantly prescriptive

as is so widely true of economics. But it must move beyond description

and beyond treating each case as a unique problem-solving exercise.

<HR>



