<HTML>

<HEAD>

<title>Colonial Legacy and Tied Aid: The Development Policy of Italy</title>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<HR>

<H3><CENTER></H3>

<H3>Colonial Legacy and Tied Aid:<br> The Development Policy of Italy<p>

<I>Antonio Giarra-Zimmermann</I></H3>

<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>

</I>No. 1, January-February 1996: pages 24-26</h4>

<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>



<Hr><h5> D+C is published

by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.

Subscriptions and further information are available from: The

Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,

D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69

7501-4855. </H5>

<HR>



<B>Italy's development aid reached the level of other industrial countries only in the 1980s. It serves as

an instrument of foreign policy, suffers from a hardly efficient

bureaucracy and is tied strongly to procurement. Italy's

former colonies in the Horn of Africa are given priority in

regional distribution.</B>

<P>

Italy's development policy was very limited until 1979. Its ODA

share of GNP in that year was only 0.08 per cent. There was almost

no bilateral cooperation. In 1978, multilateral cooperation reached

a highwater mark of 94 per cent of ODA. Private transfers far

outweighed ODA inputs. And in 1979, the multilateral sector, in

which mostly private export credits predominated, accounted for

more than 81 per cent of Italy's total disbursements to the developing

countries. In the 1950s and 1960s, the only bilateral cooperation

with systematic approaches was with Somalia.

<P>

<B>Extent of aid</B>

<P>

Starting from last place in a 1979 comparison of the industrial

countries' aid (DAC statistics), Italy had by 1986 achieved in

several steps an ODA-GNP share of 0.40 per cent, and thus exceeded

the DAC average. In 1989, in the context of the G7 leading industrial

countries' aid, Italy posted an 0.42 per cent ODA-GNP share to

take third place after France and Canada and ahead of Germany.

In 1990 and 1991, however, Italy's aid dropped sharply to ODA-GNP

shares of 0.31 per cent and 0.30 per cent respectively. The latter

percentage was also recorded in 1993. In general, Italy has since

1986 made efforts to position its development aid disbursements

in the middle of the G7 countries, while by OECD comparison it

has come only in 15th place.

<P>

Tables 1 and 2 make clear the growth in Italy's cooperation with

the developing countries since the mid1980s. Budget appropriations

have increased continually since then prom 3,629 billion Lire

in 1985 to 5,210 billion Lire in 1992, a plus of 43 per cent).

It was not until 1993 that appropriations dropped sharply by 47

per cent to only 2,775 billion Lire. While forward commitments

were immediately slashed by 40 per cent, the disbursement volume

covering those of the previous years was still maintained at a

relatively stable level (minus 11 per cent to 4,155 billion Lire).

<P>

Noticeable in the tables are the in part strong fluctuations which

point to certain weaknesses. The multilateral payments increased

from US$ 317 million in 1985 to US$ 1,424 million in 1989, dropped

distinctly in 1990/91, then rose again. Italy's 1993 Budget, which

made sharp inroads into development cooperation funds, led in

particular to a disastrous cutback in bilateral commitments. They

were slashed from 1,504 billion Lire to 339 billion Lire, and

resulted in a clear reduction of Italy's bilateral cooperation

with the paesi <I>in via di sviluppo </I>(lit.: countries on the

way to development).



<P>

<table border=1 cellpadding=8>

<caption><b>Table 1: Quantitative trends</b> (in billion Lire)</caption>

<tr><td><td>1985<td>1986<td>1987<td>1988<td>1989<td>1990<td>1991<td>1992<td>1993

<tr><td>Budget appropriations<td>3,629<td>3,745<td>3,998<td>4,291<td>4,398<td>5,098<td>5,153<td>5,210<td>2,775

<tr><td>Commitments<td>3,182<td>4,774<td>4,898<td>5,455<td>4,919<td>4,267<td>5,060<td>4,763<td>2,893

<tr><td>Disbursements<td>2,189<td>3,638<td>3,304<td>3,896<td>4,945<td>3,665<td>3,648<td>4,656<td>4,155

<tr><td>Source: Relazione annuale (various years), and Cooperazione, No. 110, January 1992, p. 49.

</tr></table>

<p>





<table border=1 cellpadding=8>

<caption><b>Table 2: Bilateral and multilateral ODA</b> (in $US mil.)</caption>

<tr><td><td>1985<td>1986<td>1987<td>1988<td>1989<td>1990<td>1991<td>1992<td>1993

<tr><td>Bilateral ODA<td>781<td>1487<td>1878<td>2408<td>2189<td>2112<td>2245<td>2430<td>1930

<tr><td>in %<td>71,1<td>61,9<td>71,8<td>75,4<td>60,5<td>62,2<td>67,00

<tr><td>Multilateral ODA<td>317<td>917<td>737<td>785<td>1424<td>1283<td>1102<td>1691<td>1113

<tr><td>in %<td>28,9<td>38,1<td>28,2<td>24,6<td>39,5<td>37,8<td>33

<tr><td>ODA total<td>1098<td>2403<td>2615<td>3193<td>3613<td>3395<td>3347<td>4122<td>3043

<tr><td>ODA-GNP %<td>0,31<td>0,41<td>0,35<td>0,39<td>0,42<td>0,31<td>0,30<td>0,34<td>0,31

<tr><td>Source: OECD annual audits, 1987-93; Relazione annuale, various years; own calculations.

</tr></table>

<p>





<P>

<B>Legal bases and organizational structures</B>

<P>

Italy's Law No.49 of 1987, which still applies, created the base

for modern development cooperation according to international

standards.

<P>

The law's most important standards include the guidelines on the

<I>Fondo rotativo </I>(Fund for credit allocation) and the <I>Fondo

di cooperazione, </I>the central financing fund of Italy's development

policy (allocation of subsidies). According to these terms of

reference, the country's development policy is a <i>parte integrante</i>

(integral part) of its foreign policy, serves the realization

of human rights, and observes the principles of the UN as well

as the EU's Lom&eacute; Agreement. The development cooperation

goals include satisfying basic needs, as well as food security,

which are to be achieved by drawing up multi sector programmes

with a time frame of several years.

<P>

Besides studies, planning and integrated development projects,

Italy's development cooperation consists of all forms of FC, training

and qualification of staff, and cooperation with NGOs. The law

also identified possible sectors of cooperation: agriculture,

education, trade, appropriate technologies, and information. The

<I>interventi straordinari </I>(extraordinary measures) provided

for cover above all aid missions in regions of need, i.e. food

supplies to famine areas and the provision of basic infrastructure

in rural areas.

<P>

<I>The Direzione generale per la cooperazione allo sviluppo,

DGCS </I>(the Head Office in the MAE, the foreign office) is responsible

for the practical implementation of development cooperation. It

has a certain financial autonomy as it has its own auditing office,

and non tied budget funds of one fiscal year can be carried forward

to the next. 

<P>

The Ministry of Finance also has development policy competences,

as it is responsible for looking after relations with international

banks and development funds.

<P>

<B>Regional focal points</B>

<P>

In 1992, the CICS gave a total of 20 countries tries the status of

<I>prima priorit&agrave;, </I>which meant they were to receive

a total of up to 75 per cent of available funds. They were  Angola,

Ethiopia, Mozambique, Somalia and Tanzania in Black Africa; Algeria,

Egypt, Morocco and Tunisia in North Africa; China and the Philippines

in Asia; and Argentina, Bolivia, Chile, Colombia and Peru in Latin

America.

<P>

A second category of countries (<I>seconda priorit&agrave;</i>), which

with Italy cooperates in key areas, is made up of Turkey, Djibouti,

Kenya, Senegal, Sudan, Zimbabwe, Jordan, Yemen, India, Pakistan,

Vietnam, Brazil, Costa Rica, Ecuador, Jamaica, Guatemala, Nicaragua,

the Dominican Republic, Uruguay and Venezuela.

<P>

Italy continues to concentrate strongly on selected LDCs with

which it has traditional, good, historic and cultural links (<i>vincoli

storici</i>). Above all, this means Eritrea, Ethiopia and Somalia

in the Horn of Africa. But over the years the intensifying of

cooperation with Latin American countries (&quot;young democracies&quot;

in Argentina and Chile) and, on account of security interests,

the Mediterranean region, has gained in importance.

<P>

Table 3 shows the geographical distribution of Italy s disbursements

(subsidies and credits) in recent years. While payments to African

and Latin American countries dropped, and cooperation with European

and Mediterranean region countries remained relatively stable

at a low and high level respectively, development cooperation

with countries in the Asian-Pacific region was expanded strongly.

The latter are above all China, Indonesia, Pakistan and the Philippines.

<P>

<B>Sectoral focal points</B>

<P>

The sectoral distribution of Italian development cooperation is

made in a very differentiated way, depending on the financing

mechanisms used. While agriculture and, correspondingly, food

production in the developing countries is the most important sector

for subsidies (<i>Fondo di cooperazione</I>), energy is the priority

sector for credit allocation (<i>Fondo di rotazione</i>). In the

agricultural sector, the concept of <I>sviluppo rurale integrale

 </I>(integrated rural development) plays a leading role. In the

energy sector, the focal point is the development of energy plans

aimed at the optimal use of existing regional and local resources.

<P>

Other priority sectors include industrial projects to support

infrastructure, and education and public health. The education

sector was given a <I>priorit&agrave; a taglio orrizonta</I>

(horizontal priority) early on. For Italy saw the available potential

of human capital as a basis for the development of the respective

country. Cooperation with the universities in the developing countries

thereby plays an important role. The most significant example

of that was the establishment of the National University in Somalia

in 1969.

<P>

Environmental protection and participation of women in development

cooperation are among the more recent fields of Italian development

policy. The former was also assigned a horizontal priority, with

concentration on agriculture, infrastructure and industry.

<P>

Right from the start, another important area of Italian sectoral

development assistance was food security and disaster aid. The

<I>Fondo aiuti italiani</I> (FAI) was created by Law No. 73 of

March 1985 and was initially to function for only 18 months. It's

a special instrument for <I>interventi straordinari </I>in a limited

number of countries (above all in Africa). Its goal is to implement

integrated programmes for self sufficiency in agricultural produce

(<i>agroalimentare</i>), and improve hygiene and sanitation conditions

in the public health sector. Criticism of Italy's development

policy was sparked by its tied aid and duplication of administrative

structures. Reintegration into normal development cooperation

work did not take place until Law 49/87 was passed. In 1993, Italy

spent almost 200 billion Lire on food production and disaster

aid. The key areas were in Africa (Somalia and Eritrea) and South-East

Europe (Bosnia and Croatia).

<P>



<table border=1 cellpadding=8>

<caption><b>Table 3: Regional distribution</b> (payments in $US mil.)</caption>

<tr><td><td>1991<td>%<td>1992<td>%<td>1993<td>%

<tr><td>Africa<td>680<td>36,4<td>626<td>27,6<td>611<td>28

<tr><td>Mediterranean and Middle East<td>379<td>20,3<td>549<td>24,2<td>416<td>19

<tr><td>Latin America<td>537<td>28,8<td>452<td>20<td>467<td>21,4

<tr><td>Asia and Oceania<td>155<td>8,3<td>383<td>17<td>568<td>26

<tr><td>Europe<td>116<td>6,2<td>260<td>11,5<td>121<td>5,5

<tr><td>Total<td>2.452<td>100<td>2.826<td>100<td>2.528<td>100

<tr><td>Source: Relazione annuale 1993, p. 30. The differences with the absolute amount are due to non-classifiable payments.

</tr></table>

<p>



<B>Peculiarities of allocation policy</B>

<P>

A reason for the unsatisfactory development of the bilateral cooperation

instrument lies in the insufficient building up of the so called

<I>Unit&agrave; tecniche centrale </I>(UTC) in the MAE. It is

true that under Law 49/87 the unit was a main object of the reform

carried out at that time and was to be the implementation level

within the DGCS. But it was not operational until the beginning

of the 1990s. The patronage system hindered the filling of the

120 planned positions (The newspaper <I>La Repubblica</i>, April

16, 1988). The Head Office also had to award the supervision and

monitoring of TC which, according to Law 49/87 (Art.12 and 13),

were actually the task of the UTC in the ministry and on site,

to the private company <I>Societ&agrave; italiana di monitoraggio

(SiM) </I>.

<P>

When it comes to tying bilateral ODA to procurement, Italy is

among the leaders on the DAC league table. It's been first or

second since 1985. In 1989, the tied element of Italy's bilateral

ODA was 58.4 per cent. The tying is determined by the CICS. It

rules that goods and services may be bought in other developing

countries (South-South trade) or other industrial countries (possible

advantages due to absence of transport costs), only when they

are not available in Italy (CICS decision of September 8, 1987).

<P>

Italy's multilateral aid stands out for its high share of payments

to the European Union, which often account for more than one third

of its total multilateral disbursements. Among the international

banks and funds, a clear preference for the International Development

Association can be noted. The IDA share accounts for an average

of about one fifth of the multilateral inputs, posting in 1989

a top value of 35.7 per cent. A more important aspect of multilateral

aid is the continual increase in payments to other UN organizations

(about one sixth of total disbursements), and other international

development banks (about one eighth). With these mostly voluntary

multilateral contributions, Italy has developed into a kind of

leader that is more and more frequently called in to carry out

coordination functions in international development policy.

<P>

In Italy, this form of cooperation is highly regarded, and because

of its particular importance has been adopted in developmental

terminology as <I>multibilateral development aid</I>. The multibilateral

development policy, whose basic structure is to be seen as multilateral

in realization and implementation (through an international development

aid agency), and bilateral in alignment (benefiting one developing

country), features a coupling and mixing of several developmental

processes.

<P>

The multibilateral cooperation arose through Italian offers to

multilateral organizations and the latter's requests for co financing.

That boosted the organizations' liquidity and capacities for development

cooperation. For the Italian side, the voluntary financial inputs

enable it to assert not only its own sectoral and geographical

priorities, but also to tie aid strongly to procurement.

<P>

In assessing this form of development cooperation, it must be

noted that some positive aspects can be seen. In a comprehensive

study, Sergio Marchiso proved that the crisis of international

organizations engaged in multilateral cooperation had compelled

them to seek new sources of finance. But this doesn't mean their

autonomy is encroached upon, because it's a matter of additional,

voluntary inputs of the donor countries. Another plus point is

that many projects and programmes which a country could not perhaps

have implemented alone can be realized by co financing.

<P>

However, a critical argument must focus first of all on the motivation

for this particular form of development cooperation. The starting

point was the possibility, also in multilateral terms, of &quot;controlling&quot;

financial contributions in a certain way, and thereby ensuring

that national economic interests as well as developmental considerations

were taken into account. In this respect, a conflict of interests

is not inevitable, but certainly entirely possible. Moreover,

and Italy uses these opportunities intensively, bilateral cooperation

enables aid to be tied to procurement.

<P>

<B>More recent developments</B>

<P>

Since the passing of Law 49/87 which created the legislative base

for modern development cooperation, a number of measures have

addressed inefficiencies in Italy's development policy. On the

one hand, the latter are due to deplorably low staffing (in 1993

the Head Office of development cooperation in the MAE had a staff

of about 550). And on the other, there is heavy criticism of a

lack of economic expertise in assessing the profitability of individual

projects and drawing up country programmes. More than half of

all administrative proceedings must still be handled by external

experts.

<P>

A report in 1993 by a special commission headed by the then Foreign

Minister, Emilio Colombo, used harsh words in criticizing the

deficiencies in Italy's development cooperation. The body slammed

the lack of country programmes, misuse of funds for extraordinary

measures, insufficient use of the competitive tender system, the

shortage of administrative staff, insufficient monitoring and

evaluation mechanisms, and inadequate decision making structures

due to insufficient competences and responsibilities. Corrective

measures being taken in the meantime are focusing on improving

technical assessment within the DGCS, gradually adapting the tender

procedure to that of the EU, and new end-of-project evaluation processes.

<P>

At the end of 1993 the organizational structure was radically

changed. Law 537/93 scrapped the CICS, and its competences were

transferred to the Inter ministerial Committee for Economic Planning

(CIPE) and the MAE. That was a far reaching move to dismantle duplicate

administrative structures. 

<P>

1. Sergio Marchiso: <I>Il financially multibilaterale. La terza

via de la cooperazione al sviluppo</I>, Milan 1986.

<p>

