<html><head><title>Womankind Worldwide - Newsletter</title></head><body bgcolor="bdfbc0" text="000000" link="9306a9" vlink="502c88"><h1 align=center><img width=589 height=77 src="newsletter_logo.jpg" ></h1><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../wk_info.html">Womankind Worldwide</a></i><hr><h1 align=center>The National Lottery</h1>Many of our supporters ask us if WOMANKIND gets any money from the National Lottery. The answer is no, not yet anyway.  As there seems to be some confusion, we thought you might be interested to hear just how much money does go to charity from the lottery.<p>Lottery money is divided between the winners, the government (12% tax take), Camelot who are the organisers, and five 'Good Causes'.  These five good causes are Arts, Sports, Heritage, The Millenium Fund and Charities. In fact, 'charities' is not entirely accurate since this category includes any group doing philanthropic or benevolent work, whether or not they are registered as a charity.<p>From your £1 ticket, an average of 28p goes to the five good causes. Of this, only 5.6p actually goes to the charities sector.  It is not yet clear how much of this take will go to charities doing work overseas but it is unlikely to be more than 10%. So charities like WOMANKIND will have to compete for their share of the halfpence of every pound of Lottery money allocated to the overseas charities sector.  The lottery board is not even looking at applications for overseas work yet so we do not expect they will start making grants until well into 1996.<p>Charities are being hurt by the public's belief that their lottery money is going to charity. A recent survey showed that just under 60% of people thought that buying lottery tickets was a good way to help charities and that charities got at least 20p from each £1 ticket, which is clearly not the case. As a result people are contributing less to charities.<p>The National Council of Voluntary Organisations' recent research showed a fall in those donating to charity from 81% (February) to 61% (March) and a 4% fall in the value of the donation.  They project an alarming loss of £161 million in charitable income over the first 12 months of the National Lottery.<p>So when you are thinking about making a donation to support our very special work, please remember WOMANKIND does not receive anything from the National Lottery and we are unlikely to do so for quite some time to come!<p><b><a href="index.html">Contents Page</a></b><p><hr><p>©Copyright:1996 Womankind Worldwide<hr></body></html>
