<h1>What the Papers Say:<br>
UK Press Coverage:</h1>

<center>
	<b>Oxfam challenges high street on exploitation</b><br>
	'Oxfam is introducing a new concept of 'serious shopping' today. Everyone is being asked to ensure that their latest little extravagance 	or essential was not made with the sweat and blood of exploited workers around the world.' - <b>The Independent</b> May 20 1996<p>


	<b>Shops pressed on Third World firms</b><br>
	'Oxfam's Clothes Code campaign, launched today, urges retailers to ensure that staff in Third World factories are not exploited through excessive hours, intimidation or breadline wages.' - <b>The Guardian</b> Monday May 20 1996<p>


	<b>Oxfam targets rag trade</b><br>
	'Oxfam wants retailers to take responsibility for the actions of subcontractors. The code includes a 48-hour  working week, no employment for children under 14 and no forced labour.' <b>The Times</b> Monday May 20 1996<p>


	<b>Oxfam in High Street crusade to curb world's 	sweatshops</b><br>
	'As you agonise over whether you should fork out a small fortune on a new summer dress or suit, it might be well to remember who made it.
	This is the message from Oxfam today as it launches a new campaign aimed at improving life for the millions of clothes workers world-wide who work in appalling conditions.' - <b>The Standard</b> Monday May 20 1996<p>


	<b>Oxfam calls on firms to adopt labour codes</b><br>
	'Oxfam has received a mixed response retailers after issuing a call for businesses to sign up to a code of practice on third-world labour standards. C&A and Sears have reacted positively, but Oxfam is still looking for encouraging signs from Next and the Burton Group.' - <b>People Management</b> June 13 1996<p>


	<b>£45 buys this pretty summer dress. The woman who made it earned £1 an hour. In Hong Kong or Bangladesh? No, in the East End of London. </b><br>
	' Sweating in the summer heat, cramped between bales of cloth, racks of patterns and finished designs, machinist Asiye Altun, 32, scores notches into a jackets central panel...Asiye works a 60-hour week. She is paid £100 in cash.
	Ruth Mayne, a quality adviser at Oxfam, says that 'governments and companies are engaged in a race to the bottom to cut labour costs in order to compete. Global economic integration is causing downward pressure on labour standards in the North as well as in the South and minimum standards need to be set.' - <b>The Observer</b> June 23 1996</center><p>


<b>Global Press Coverage:</b><p>
<center>

<b>	OXFAM launches move to improve conditions of garment workers</b><br>
	'Women working in the garment factories badly need their jobs to fight poverty  and countries like Bangladesh badly need the foreign exchange earnings that the industry can provide, an OXFAM release said in Dhaka on Sunday.
	But most of the garment factories world-wide by women's labour at the cheapest possible rate. Working long hours in appalling conditions the women workers get the smallest possible share of the huge amount of money that changes hands at different phases of the garment trade.' - <b>The Bangladesh Observer</b> May 20 1996<p>


	<b>OXFAM launches 'cloths code'</b><br>
	'Though OXFAM's new campaign is global in nature, it has relevance in the Indian context given the huge garment export industry here. 'The purpose of our initiative', according to Ashvin Dayal, OXFAM's public policy analyst in India, 'is not to undermine exports or boycott retailers...instead, through facilitating a dialogue with retailers we hope to encourage improvements in working conditions and wages which will ultimately promote sustainable and equitable export growth.' - <b>The Patriot</b> New Delhi May 27, 1996</center><p>


<b>Note: This is only a selection of the newspaper coverage that Oxfam's Clothes Code campaign has received during the last month and a half.  The campaign has been profiled in over 20 newspaper articles; has been featured on eight television programmes, including the BBC Breakfast News; and has been discussed on 18 radio programmes, including BBC Radio 1 'Newsbeat', and Voice of America.</b><p>

