<title>Programme Update 20: Zaire</title>
</head>
<body>
<h3>PROGRAMME UPDATE 20</h3>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by</i> <a href="oxfam.html">Oxfam</a>
<hr>
<h2> ZAIRE - GOMA</h2>
<h3>Key developments</h3>
<p>
<ul><li>The UNHCR registration exercise has continued and
     Phase 2 involving cutting of wrist bands has now been
     completed in most camps.  Limited food distribution
     took place in all the camps due to the registration
     exercise.
<p>
<li>UNHCR continue with their policy of facilitation of
     voluntary repatriation. Information centres are still
     operating in the camps.  UNHCR have agreed to pay œ8.6
     million for 1,500 Zairean troops to protect more than
     a million refugees (1,000 in Goma and 500 in Bukavu)
     as part of a 'Zairean contingency for Security in the
     Camps.'  A special 30-50 member UNHCR liaison
     committee made up of international military 'experts'
     will work with the Zairean High Command on all aspects
     of the planning and implementation of the agreement. 
     Security posts will be set up in each refugee camp and
     the UN will fund all operational costs.
<p>
<li>The latest information on the situation with the two
     volcanoes in the region remains unsure but the
     situation continues to pose a very real threat..
<p>
<li>Work has started on the Bunagana route providing an
     alternative route from Uganda into Goma and will be
     completed by the end of February.  The first convoy
     from that direction is expected this week. 
</ul><p>
<h3>Oxfam's response</h3>
<p>
<ul><li>The water distribution system in Kahindo camp has been
     closed for short periods during the day to allow tanks
     to refill.  Investigations are being carried out to
     find out why the tanks have been running empty -
     whether it is due to increased consumption or reduced
     flow from the source.
<p>
<li>Oxfam is considering its own contingency plans in
     light of the predicted volcanic eruption as well as
     participating in an information campaign for local
     leaders and the Zairean population.  A grant for
     œ73,000 has been approved to provide emergency water
     equipment for 200,000 people.
<p>
<li>Oxfam is to set up contingency stocks of non-food
     items in the Masisi area where we have been working
     since 1993 with victims of civil war to be distributed
     to up to 50,000 displaced people.  
</ul><p>
<h4>TOTAL NO. OF REFUGEES IN GOMA</h4>
<p>
<ul><ul><li>Kibumba
    233,000
<li>Kahindo
    100,000
<li>Mugunga
    155,000
<li>Katale
    200,000   
</ul><p>
TOTAL NO. in N. Kivu 725,000<br>
*UNHCR estimates.
<p>
N.B.  Preliminary figures from UNHCR registration put the refugee
figure at between 725,000 - 730,000. 
</ul>
