<DOCNO>WT17-B21-160</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA073-000473-B023-241</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://mickey.acri.fr:80/English/Society/profile.html 194.98.101.6 19970124214132 text/html 9844
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Date: Fri, 24 Jan 1997 21:43:13 GMT
Server: Apache/1.2b4
Connection: close
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>

  <HEAD>

    <TITLE>Company Profile</TITLE>
    <!-- Created by: Jean-Michel Augusto, 29-Jan-1996 -->
    <!-- Changed by: Jean-Michel Augusto, 29-Jan-1996 -->

  </HEAD>

  <BODY BGCOLOR="white">

      <TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%">
	<TR>
	  <TD>
	    <IMG WIDTH=102 SRC="/gifs/acri.gif" ALT="ACRI Logo">
	  <TD COLSPAN=2 ALIGN=CENTER>
	    <FONT SIZE="7">
	      Company Profile
	    </FONT>
	    <P>
	      <FONT SIZE="4">
	      </FONT>
	    <P>
	      <FONT SIZE="4">
		<A HREF="/French/Societe/profile.html">
		  <img alt="french flag" align=middle src="/gifs/frenchflag.gif">
		  Cliquer ici pour obtenir la version fran&ccedil;aise
		</A>
	      </FONT>
	  </TD>
	</TR>
	<!--an empty line-->
	<TR>
	  <TD>
	  <TD>
	  <TD>
	</TR>
	<!--The c-->
	<TR>
	  <TD COLSPAN=3>
	    <B>ACRI</B> functions under a unified management structure, with
	    operations located in Sophia Antipolis (France). It employs a matrix
	    organization, that is, a combination of functional or line sections,
	    and of a project team.

	    <P>

	      ACRI has a wide experience in remote sensing system requirements,
	      analysis and ground segment design, mission analysis and requirements.

	    <P>

	      ACRI has also a wide experience in a variety of space problems such as
	      overall mission performances, orbital properties generator, spacecraft
	      axes steering control, signal characteristics to be detected on top of
	      the atmosphere, geometrical and radiometric instrument features and
	      distortion, and on ground processing algorithms needed to retrieve
	      accurate Earth and environmental signal and geophysical parameters.

	    <P>

	      In particular, ACRI has been continuously involved in mission analysis
	      tasks such as identification of optimal and attitude parameters for
	      Earth observation; optimisation of instrument mission performance:
	      coverage, signal dynamics characterisation on top of the atmosphere,
	      sampling geometry and signal quality, pointing accuracy and on board
	      calibration procedure. For instance, ACRI has performed the mission
	      analysis and requirements for MERIS, MIMR, MIPAS,
	      GOMOS,... instruments during the POEM-1/ENVISAT-1 Pre-Phase-A, Phase-A
	      and Phase-B. All the scientific and technical reports have been issued
	      to the ESA Scientific Advisory Groups (SAGs) members.

	    <P>

	      Furthermore, ACRI is well acquainted with the Earth observation
	      science community. As such ACRI has co-operation agreements with
	      laboratories in France (such as Service d'A&eacute;ronomie: J-L. Bertaux,
	      Institut Laplace: G. Megie, Laboratoire de M&eacute;t&eacute;orologie
	      Dynamique:
	      N.A. Scott, P. Flament, Laboratoire de Physique et Chimie Marine:
	      A. Morel, Laboratoire d'Optique Atmosph&eacute;rique: 
	      D.Tanr&eacute;,....., Ecole
	      des Mines de Paris: L. Wald) and European laboratories such as Finnish
	      Meteorological Institute: G. Leppelmeier, Free University of Berlin:
	      J. Fischer, GKSS: H. Grassl, Plymouth Marine Laboratory: J. Aiken, UK
	      Meteorological Office: P.  Curtis, Institut d'A&eacute;ronomie Spatiale de
	      Bruxelles: P. Simon...

	    <P>

	      ACRI is leading the project "Integration of remote sensing, in-situ
	      observations and numerical modelling applied to the northeast
	      Atlantic" in the frame of the "Human capital and mobility" initiative
	      of the CEC. ACRI is participating in the OCEAN project of the CEC
	      Joint Research Centre.  ACRI experience can be summarised in six types
	      of activities:

	    <UL>
	      <LI>i. User requirements: ACRI is currently in charge for
		the EUMETSAT Ground Segment support of the coordination with the users
		community. ACRI is involved with JRC in pilot projects, part of the
		Centre for Earth Observation (CEO) project, in charge of the
		collection of user requirements from experimental community on coastal
		zones;

	      <LI>ii. Mission Analysis: ACRI has been continuously involved in
		mission analysis tasks such as identification of optimal orbit and
		attitude parameters for Earth observation (yaw steering, ESA study);
		optimisation of instrument mission and performance: coverage, signal
		dynamics characterisation, sampling geometry and signal quality,
		pointing accuracy,... for instruments studied during the POEM-1 phase
		B: MERIS, MIMR, MIPAS;

	      <LI>iii. Ground processing: ACRI has performed the
		definition study for engineering and scientific data products of MERIS
		and MIMR instruments in the frame of POEM Ground Segment Phase B study
		(ESA contract led by Logica, MDA). To satisfy the global requirements,
		the MERIS and MIMR instrument operation will be permanent. All
		corresponding data should be acquired, processed following various
		levels, and disseminated in due time to user point of contact.


		<P>

		  ACRI is currently in charge of the complete definition of the
		  data processing chain of the GOMOS and MERIS instruments; the
		  definition covers all necessary processing steps from the raw data to
		  the generation of the geophysical products. (e.g. the MERIS Ocean
		  Colour products such as chlorophyll concentration, chlorophyll
		  fluorescence, type and Optical depth of marine aerosols or the GOMOS
		  ozone or aerosols vertical profiles among others).

		<P>

		  It includes the MERIS and GOMOS overall ground processing
		  architecture, detailed design, development plan, products and
		  algorithms definition specifications. The documentation follows ESA
		  Software Engineering Standards and Product Assurance Quality.
		<P>

	      <LI>
		iv. Guidance and Control:
		<P>ACRI has performed studies on MIPAS
		  instrument pointing requirements in order to aim at a stable
		  tangential altitude. ACRI has also performed, with the Laboratoire
		  d'Automatique de Nantes, a study on Guidance Navigation and Control
		  for moderate lift/drag Re-entry, applied to aero-assisted orbit
		  transfer (ESA Contract March 1991).  v. Navigation: ACRI has modelised
		  6 D.O.F. trajectories applied to as various subjects as a spacecraft
		  attitude, ship precise positioning (French Navy contract), re-entry in
		  the atmosphere .  vi. System Software: ACRI has developed general
		  purpose software in the fluid dynamics and combustion (ANSWER), ground
		  water (PORFLOW), surface and marine waters (TIDAL), atmosphere (RADM),
		  guidance and control (ANACOM), and Earth Observation (EOSS)
		  fields. This activity includes software sells, users training and
		  maintenance.
		<P>
		  ACRI has specified the software requirements for the future
		  MIMR end to end system simulator during the Phase-B of the MIMR study
		  (ALENIA Contract, 1991-2);
		  ACRI has performed under contract with DORNIER :
		  MERIS mission performances and end to end system simulator
		  (including on ground processing until level 2) development .
		  GOMOS mission performances and end to end system simulator
		  (including on ground processing until level 2) development.

	    </UL>

	    <I> A common concept is being developed for remote sensing
	      instrument simulators. The objectives generally recognised are to
	      assess end-to-end performance of the remote sensing process in order
	      to:
	      verify instrument and ground processing performance against
	      the mission objectives
	      provide feedback to the instrument design and tuning
	      provide a reference and support tool for the validation of the
	      mission ground segment in development, delivery and in-orbit operation
	      phases The simulator includes mathematical models for 1) signal (raw
	      data) generated from various Earth, atmosphere, etc. targets emitting
	      signal including environmental conditions (sun illumination, satellite
	      orbit motion, satellite axes steering control, target environment,
	      signal propagation...).  2) instrument hardware and electronic chain
	      simulator (MTF) generating instrument outputs from given reference
	      inputs signal (incident flux at the top of the atmosphere).  3) ground
	      processing simulator generating from raw data the data product
	      processed and calibrated on ground. These processes require to inverse
	      the geometric, radiometric and instrument transfer function using
	      dedicated deconvolution methods.  The mathematical models are
	      supported by a common infrastructure of data management and user
	      interface, tools supporting simulation results analysis such as image
	      quality assessment.  </I>

	</TR>
      </TABLE>
      <P>

	<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
