<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>GOSS Simulator</TITLE>
    <!-- Created by: Jean-Michel Augusto, 29-Jan-1996 -->
    <!-- Changed by: Jean-Michel Augusto, 29-Jan-1996 -->


  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="/gifs/fond.jpg">

      <H1>GOSS Simulator</H1>
      <img src="/gifs/bar_marbre_noir2.gif">
      <BR><BR>

      <BIG>
	The GOMOS instrument has been designed to measure trace gas
	concentrations and other atmospheric parameters in the altitude range
	between 20 and 100 km. In addition to the main goal of monitoring
	ozone long term trends, the GOMOS near-IR spectrometers will measure
	O2 and H2O, from which density and temperature profiles can be
	obtained, which are of interest in atmospheric modelling, but will
	also improve the quality of the ozone retrieval. At the same time two
	fast photometer channels will produce information about atmospheric
	fluctuations, again of interest both for basic atmospheric modelling,
	but above all useful in the reduction of the ozone-related data.

      <p align=center>
	<img alt=GOMOS Satellit src="/gifs/GOMOS2.gif"><br><br>
	<b>Figure 1 </b>: GOMOS<BR>
      </P>
      <P>

	About 25 stars brighter than MV=2 can routinely be observed, at
	different longitudes from each orbit. With typically 14 orbits/day
	the GOMOS instrument will thus produce as much data as a global
	network of 360 ground stations. Depending on the mode and goals
	of observation, some 100-200 stars are candidates for GOMOS
	occultation observation.  

      <P>

	Because of interference from scattered sunlight, fewer stars can be
	observed in bright limb occultation than in dark limb.  In dark limb
	occultation the limiting considerations are quality of spectral
	information and the ability of the tracking system to maintain lock.
	Hotter stars give better spectral signal-to-noise ratio, and thus are
	better for ozone measurements.  At the same time, for a fixed
	brightness, such stars have fewer photons in the range used by the
	star tracker. Given the starting time of an occultation and the time
	required to move the input mirror from the end point of one
	occultation to the beginning of the next, it is not possible in
	practice to observe all possible stars in one occultation.  Therefore,
	selection is necessary.

      <P>

	This is accomplished by establishing selection criteria, such as 
	brightness, next available star, maximum intensity in a particular
	wavelength region, etc., which allow a list generator to create
	scenario of observations for one orbit. The instrument optical
	design is based on a single telescope concept : the telescope
	simultaneously feeds a Ultra violet-Visible medium resolution
	spectrometer, a near-infrared high resolution spectrometer,
	a fast photometer equipped with two spectral channels, and a
	CCD-based star tracker. The latter provides the tracking accuracy
	required to maintain the star image at the centre of the
	spectrometers entrance slit during the occultation observation.

      <P>

	The steering front assembly is made of one flat mirror mounted
	on a 2-stage mechanism. The first stage is an open loop orientator, 
	used to move the instrument line of sight from one star for which 
	the occultation is completed to the next star to be occulted. 
	The orientator is then blocked for the duration of the occultation. 
	The second phase is the tracking device, based on a closed control 
	loop using the star tracker data. It is operated during the 
	occultation phase, in a reduced window (7  in azimuth and 4 
	in elevation), and provides the fine centring of the star image
	within the spectrometers entrance slit. 

      <P>

	The thermally controlled optical bench and the telescope are mounted 
	on a fixed part on the instrument interface plate, used also to 
	support several electronic units for data handling, command and 
	control, and power distribution. An opto-mechanical cover is put 
	around both optical and steering front assemblies to provide the 
	adequate straylight and thermal baffling.

      <P>

	The scientific data are suitably filtered, digitised and multiplexed 
	into a single data stream of constant rate at the platform interface.
	The instrument operates largely autonomously and only requires once
	every 36 hours uploading of the instrument pointing and observation
	program.

      <P>

	The instrument measurement characteristics are listed in tables I.

	Finally, two features characterise the GOMOS instrument allowing to 
	reach its expected performance :

      <UL>
	<LI>The instrument is self-calibrating by measuring the star spectrum
	  outside and through the atmosphere.
	<LI>The stellar and background spectra are simultaneously recorded, 
	  allowing to correct for background or straylight as well as dark
	  current contributions.

      </UL>

      <TABLE BORDER=3>

	<TR>
	  <TD>
	    Channel
	  <TD>
	    Spectral Range
	  <TD>
	    Spectral Resolution
	  <TD>
	    Altitude Range
	  <TD>
	    Vertical Resolution
	  <TD>
	    Analysed Species

	<TR>
	  <TD>
	    UVIS
	  <TD>
	    250 - 675 nm
	  <TD>
	    0.6 nm
	  <TD>
	    20 to 100 km
	  <TD>
	    1.7km
	  <TD>
	    O<SUB>3</SUB>, NO<SUB>2</SUB>, NO<SUB>3</SUB>, aerosols

	<TR>
	  <TD>
	    IR 1
	  <TD>
	    756 - 773 nm
	  <TD>
	    0.12 nm
	  <TD>
	    20 to 100 km
	  <TD> 
	    1.7 km
	  <TD>
	    O<SUB>2</SUB> (temperature information)

	<TR>
	  <TD>
	    IR 2
	  <TD>
	    926 - 952 nm
	  <TD>
	    0.12 nm
	  <TD>
	    20 km to 100  km
	  <TD>
	    1.7 km
	  <TD>
	    H<SUB>2</SUB>O

	<TR>
	  <TD>
	    PHOT 1
	  <TD>
	    470 - 520 nm
	  <TD>
	    broadband
	  <TD>
	    20 to 100 km
	  <TD>
	    1.7 km
	  <TD>
	    scintillation

	<TR>
	  <TD>
	    PHOT 2
	  <TD>
	    650 - 700 nm
	  <TD>
	    broadband
	  <TD>
	    20 to 100 km
	  <TD>
	    1.7 km
	  <TD>
	    scintillation
      </TABLE>

      <CENTER>
	<BR><B>Table I</B> : GOMOS measurement characteristics
      </CENTER>

      <H1>GOMOS System Simulator</H1>

      The GOMOS system simulator provides support for end-to-end performance
      evaluation of the GOMOS instrument and on-ground processing.
      It does so by :
      <OL>

	<LI>managing a set of targets ;

	<LI>simulating the star and background spectrum formation process, as
	  well as the scintillation and depointing of the star image, within
	  the instrument ;

	<LI>performing the ground segment software functions which contribute
	  to product generation.

      </OL>

      Performance evaluation is based on qualitative and quantitative
      evaluation of the difference between the original target parameters
      set, and the results of processing by instrument and ground segment
      sub-models, as shown in following figure.
      

      Figure Performance Evaluation levels

      The modular structure of the simulator allows to perform such
      comparisons at several different stages of the data processing. This
      is intended to help evaluate the contribution of each stage :
      satellite, instrument, on-ground processing, to the overall system
      performance.

      <P>

	Intermediate results, in particular internal parameters of the
	instrument sub-model, are available as intermediate results to help
	trouble-shooting.

      <P>

	The selected targets provide a wide choice of stars and atmosphere
	configuration which may be observed by GOMOS, which is meaningful 
      <UL>

	<LI>from the point of view of performance evaluation ;

	<LI>from the point of view of instrument calibration and testing on
	  ground and in flight.

      </UL>

      The complete imaging process is simulated and includes the apparent
      movement of the star, the limb conditions where the star is viewed,
      the pointing perturbations resulting from the GOMOS pointing
      sub-system interaction with the external world, the collection of
      light by the sensors and the electrical processing on board, and the
      digital data processing on board and on ground.

      <P>

	Several modes of simulation are provided in order to support :
      <OL>

	<LI>realistic simulation of the various GOMOS instrument operations :
	  occultation, calibration

	<LI>investigation of local as well as global effects

	<LI>investigation of mission strategies by allowing to build and test
	  observation scenarios

      </OL>

      The GOMOS System Simulator is a software application capable of
      running in stand-alone mode and to manage interfaces to the external
      world. It runs and manages its data on a single host computer. Its
      user interface allows to prepare, operate simulations of the GOMOS
      system in various configurations, and to process and analyse the
      simulation results. Its data management allows to exchange data and
      results with other components of the GOMOS system environment
      (e.g. ground processing).

      <P>

	The GOMOS simulator does not operate in real time. Instead, the
	continuous processes which it models are broken into discrete,
	elementary operations. The simulation time is modelled by a set of
	counters, each linked to a pre-set time scale : spacecraft orbital
	movement, star image formation, CCD sensor cycle, etc.
      </FONT>

	<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
